          <aside>GF Fisher appointed Trustee.</aside>
          <p>
            A vacancy having occurred on the Board by the death of Henry L. Carter
            it was unanimously resolved that Mr. C.F. Fisher of Petersburg be
            appointed to substitute his place. Mr. Fisher being present was duly
            sworn according to the requisition of the Charter and took his seat.
          </p>
          <aside>Guillet to teach French at $150.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That Mr. Guillet be employed to give lessons in the
            French language three times each week to the students at the college, at
            a salary of one hundred and fifty dollars per annum, he not to be a
            member of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <aside style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: "center" }}>
            <div>
              Secretary<br />Treasurer
            </div>
            <div style={{ fontSize: '2em', lineHeight: 2 }}>{'}'}</div>
            <div>elected</div>

          </aside>
          <p>
            On motion the Board proceeded to the election of officers of the Board,
            which resulted as follows.
          </p>
          <dl>
            <dt>James B. Taylor</dt>
            <dd>Secretary</dd>
            <dt>James C. Crane</dt>
            <dd>Treasurer</dd>
          </dl>
          <aside>Steward's Act</aside>
          <p>
            The Steward presented his account, whereupon, on motion a committee
            consisting of Jessee Snead and James Thomas, was appointed to examine
            the account and report at the next meeting.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={39} />
          <p>
            On motion Resolved that when this Board adjourns, it adjourn to meet at
            this place on the 4th of July at 4 o'clock PM.
          </p>
          <aside>volunteary agt. continued</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the voluntary agents heretofore appointed be
            requested to continue their efforts in collecting funds in behalf of the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>The Board adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1844-07-04'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College held an adjourned meeting at the
            basement room of the 2nd Baptist Church on <time dateTime="1844-07-04">Thursday July 4th 1844</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, Daniel Witt, Eli Ball, A. Thomas, James Sizer,
            A.J. Crane, J.B. Jeter, and J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Daniel Witt</p>
          <p>The minutes were read.</p>
          <aside>D<sup>rs</sup> Metanaur's proposal rejected.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee to consider the application of Drs. J.P. Mettaner and F.I.
            Mettaner requesting to connect a private medical school in Prince Edward
            County with Richmond College for the purpose of securing the power of
            confering [sic] degrees hereby report that they consider the union
            inexpedient.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Report was adopted and the President directed to write to Dr.
            Mettaner.
          </p>
          <p>Mr. A. Snead appeared and took his seat.</p>
          <aside>Report of Committee to procure professor or tutors. See File No 20</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee to procure a Professor or two Tutors to supply the place
            of the President during his absence from the College in the agency of
            the Board, reported. The Report accepted, and the committee discharged.
          </p>
          <aside>R. Rylan's agency to collect funds judged inexpedient. to continue a volutary Agt with the Secy.</aside>
          <p>
            The following preamble and resolution were adopted - In view of the
            considerations stated in the report of the Committee, Resolved
            that it is inexpedient for the President to be wholly absent from the
            College during the next session, and that he be requested to spend as
            much time during the present year as he may deem appropriate in
            collecting funds <PageNumber num={40} />
            for the endowment of the College, and that the Secretary be also
            requested to devote as much time to the same agency as may be compatible
            with his other engagements in the present year.
          </p>
          <aside>If absent, to get a supply.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That should the President deem it proper to employ any
            part of the session in collecting funds he be empowered to secure the
            services of Mr. Tiberias G. Jones, or any other suitable individual to
            assist him in his duties at the college, at a salary not exceeding $40
            per month.
          </p>
          <aside>Resignation of Steward See Fille No 21.</aside>
          <p>
            The Steward of the College having tendered his resignation, it was
            Resolved that this subject be referred to a committee, to report as soon
            as convenient -
          </p>
          <p>Committee:  J.B. Jeter, J.B. Taylor, and A. Snead.</p>
          <p>
            On motion adjourned to meet at this place on Tuesday afternoon at 5
            o'clock
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1844-07-09'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met according to appointment at the
            basement room of the Second Baptist Church on <time dateTime="1844-07-09">
              Tuesday the 9th of July
              1844
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  Jno D. McGill, James Thomas, jun'r,
            A. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, A. Snead, A.J. Crane, and James B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read. J.B. Jeter and Eli Ball came
            in and took their seats.
          </p>
          <aside>C.L. Cock [sic] reappointed steward.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee to consider the subject of the stewardship of the College
            reported that they recommend the reappointment of Mr. Cocke as steward
            of the College for one year with permission to employ an assistant for
            one year at his own expense.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={41} />
          <p>The report of the committee was on motion adopted.</p>
          <aside>Lecturers?</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Faculty be a committee to inquire into the
            practicability and expediency of securing the services of individuals to
            lecture on other branches beside those which now engage the attention of
            the Professors.
          </p>
          <p>On motion Mr. A.J. Crane was added to the Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1844-09' className='noquorum'>
          <aside>no quorum.</aside>
          <p>
            Public notice having been given, several members of the Board of
            Trustees assembled at the regular quarterly meeting in <time dateTime="1844-09">September</time>, but a
            quorum not being present no business was transacted.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1844-12-03'>
          <p>
            The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was
            held <time dateTime="1844-12-03">Thursday afternoon Dec [3]rd 1844</time> at the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, Pres't.  J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, L.W. Allen,
            James Sizer, A. Snead, Jas. Thomas jun., and James B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by A.B. Smith</p>
          <aside>None obtained to lecture</aside>
          <p>
            The quarterly report of the President was presented and read, by which
            it appeared that no action had been taken by the committee to procure
            additional Lecturers.
          </p>
          <p>Mr. Richard Reins appeared and took his seat.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to consider the expediency of procuring a person or
            persons to deliver additional lectures were on motion discharged from
            the consideration of the subject.
          </p>
          <aside>Assistant teacher authorized</aside>
          <p>
            On motion Resolved That should the number of students offering to
            enter the Junior class at the beginning of the next session be
            sufficient to justify it that the <PageNumber num={42} />
            Faculty of the College be authorized to conduct their studies, and to
            employ an assistant, at a salary of $300 to aid in teaching ancient
            Languages.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section className='noquorum'>
          <p>
            Due notice having been given of the regular meeting of the Trustees of
            Richmond College the following members were present, VIZ
          </p>
          <aside>no quorum.</aside>
          <p>
            Robert Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, James C. Crane, Eli Ball, and
            James B. Taylor. A quorum not being present, the meeting adjourned to
            next Thursday afternoon at 4 o'clock.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-03-11'>
          <p>
            The adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held on
            <time dateTime="1845-03-11">Tuesday March 11th 1845</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  Eli Ball, James C. Crane, James
            Thomas, jun., Richard Reins, A.J. Crane, J.B. Jeter, and J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Mr. Walthall being present opened the meeting with prayer.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read. The quarterly report of the
            President of the College was read.
          </p>
          <aside>Ed. Socy give a $500 Portsmouth Bond on conditions.</aside>
          <p>
            Whereas the Education Society has proposed to give to the College a bond
            of the town of Portsmouth for five hundred dollars on condition that a
            proper refunding bond be executed for the same and that the interest be
            received by the Education Society when paid until its debts are
            liquidated.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the proposition be accepted, and the President and
            Secretary be a committee to make the necessary transfer and arrangement.
          </p>
          <aside>Jo. Walker Agt.</aside>
          <p>Resolved That Rev. Joseph Walker be appointed <PageNumber num={43} />
            an agent to collect funds for the College at a salary of $600 per
            annum, and his necessary travelling expenses, the appointment shall take
            effect from the first of June next.
          </p>
          <aside>Odenhall, French Teacher</aside>
          <p>
            Mr. I. Guillet having resigned the place of teacher of French at the
            College, therefore resolved that Mr. Odenhall be appointed to that place
            upon the terms upon which it was offered to Mr. Guillet.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned by benediction</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-06-03' className='annual'>
          <aside>5<sup>th An. Meetg.</sup></aside>
          <p>
            The Board of Trustees of Richmond College held a regular, annual meeting
            in the Baptist meeting house in Lynchburg <time dateTime="1845-06-03">June 3rd 1845</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  J.B. Jeter, Alex'r Fleet, A.M.
            Poindexter, Wm. Sands, A.G. Wortham, Daniel Witt, and Eli Ball.
          </p>
          <p>
            In the absence of the Secretary, Eli Ball was appointed Secretary pro
            tem.  C.F. Fisher came in and took his seat.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurers account See File 25 No.</aside>
          <p>
            The Treasurer's report having been presented, was examined, approved,
            and ordered to be filed.
          </p>
          <aside>Report of President See File 26 No</aside>
          <p>
            The President presented his quarterly report which was read and put upon
            file.
          </p>
          <aside>Entire Records to be read at each An. Meetg</aside>
          <p>
            The following was offered by A.M. Poindexter and adopted. Resolved
            That at each annual meeting of the Board the records of the preceding
            year shall be read.
          </p>
          <p>J.B. Jeter offered the following which was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Joint Agent of Col & Ed. Society</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That this Board will unite with the Board of the
            Virginia Baptist Education Society in the appointment of an agent to
            collect funds; and that this Board will allow the agent a compensation
            of $500, provided the Board of said Society will allow him the sum of
            $250, his travelling expenses to be paid in the same proportion; all
            funds collected by him, being divided in the ratio of two thirds of
            undesignated funds for Richmond College; and one third to the Education
            Society.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={44} />
          <aside>Jos Walker reappointed agent</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That Rev. Joseph Walker be appointed an agent for the
            Board, in accordance with the preceding resolution, to collect funds for
            the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That Alex'r Fleet and Daniel Witt be a committee to
            notify him of his appointment.
          </p>
          <aside>Declines at present</aside>
          <p>
            The committee after having an interview with Mr. Walker, reported that
            he declined accepting the appointment for the present, that he will
            however give the subject a careful examination, and communicate with the
            Board at a future period.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned</p>
          <p>Benediction by the Pres.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-07-26'>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held in the
            basement room of the Second Baptist Church the <time dateTime="1845-07-26">26th of July 1845</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  Henry Keeling, A.G. Wortham, J.B.
            Jeter, A. Snead, W. Sands, A.J. Crane, and James B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by the Secretary</p>
          <aside>The agency declined by Mr Walker finally</aside>
          <p>
            The President announced to the Board that Mr. Joseph Walker had
            signified his determination to decline the appointment of collecting
            agent conferred on him at the annual meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            A. Thomas, James C. Crane, and James Thomas, Jun., entered and took
            their seats.
          </p>
          <aside>M.T. Sumner proposed</aside>
          <p>
            A motion was made by Mr. Jeter that the Rev. Martin S. Sumner be
            appointed a collecting agent of the Board; after some discussion the
            motion was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <aside>Shall more professors be apptd?</aside>
          <p>
            On motion a committee was appointed to consider the expediency of
            enlarging the number of Professors at the College, and if deemed proper
            to nominate suitable individuals to report on <PageNumber num={45} />
            Tuesday evening at 1/2 past 4 o'clock.
          </p>
          <p>
            Committee:  R. Ryland, J.B. Jeter, Henry Keeling, A.J. Crane, and A.G.
            Wortham.
          </p>
          <aside>certain pupils to prepare lessons in the presense of Professor</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That each officer of the College be requested to cause
            those of his pupils whose age and other circumstances may require it to
            sit in his presence while preparing the lesson to be recited to him.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution was offered by A.J. Crane.</p>
          <aside>An. Meetings to be always in Richmond?</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Bye Law referring to the time and place of
            holding the annual meeting be altered by striking out the words &quot;at
            such time and place as the Board may appoint&quot; and substituting in
            lieu thereof the words &quot;in the City of Richmond&quot;.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the resolution was laid upon the table.</p>
          <p>Adjourned to meet next Tuesday afternoon at 1/2 past 4 o'clock</p>
          <p>Benediction by the President</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-07-29'>
          <p>
            Richmond <time dateTime="1845-07-29">July 29th 1845</time>.  The Trustees of Richmond College met according
            to previous appointment in the lecture room of the Second Baptist
            Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, Pres.  H. Keeling, J.B. Jeter, E.L. Magoon, Eli
            Ball, A.G. Wortham, A. Thomas, J. Thomas, jun., W. Sands, R.C. Wortham,
            J. C. Crane, and A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by E.L. Magoon</p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent A. Snead was appointed Secretary pro tem.
          </p>
          <aside>See File No 27.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee appointed at the last meeting to consider the propriety of
            electing other professors for the College reported as follows (see
            report):
          </p>
          <p>
            The report after being read was received and taken up for consideration
            and after some conversation thereon was laid for the present on the
            table.
          </p>
          <p>A.J. Crane appeared and took his seat as trustee.</p>
          <p>
            On motion The resolution offered at last meting to amend the bye laws
            was taken up, considered and <PageNumber num={46} />
            adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Agency</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the subject of appointing an agent to collect funds was taken
            up and while under consideration J. B. Taylor entered and took his seat.
            The name of Martin S. Sumner was presented for the office, but the board
            refused to appoint him; the subject was then laid on the table until the
            next meeting, and a committee consisting of J.B. Jeter, J.B. Taylor, and
            A. Snead appointed to consider the subject and recommend some suitable
            person for the office.
          </p>
          <aside>Election of JL Reynolds and Prof Ruggles</aside>
          <p>
            The report of the committee was again taken up, and on motion the board
            proceeded to the election of Professor J.L. Reynolds of S. Carolina, and
            Prof. Ruggles of D.C. to professorships in the College.
          </p>
          <aside>salary of Prof</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the salary of each professor in the College be one
            thousand dollars.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the consideration of the 3rd and 5th articles of the
            committee's report be postponed to the next meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the board adjourned to meet on Monday next at 5 o'clock PM at
            this place
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-08-04'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met according to adjournment on <time dateTime="1845-08-04">
              Monday
              the 4th of August 1845
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  Thomas Hume, J.B. Jeter, R.C.
            Wortham, H. Keeling, A.J. Crane, A. Thomas, A. Snead, A.G. Wortham, J.
            Thomas, jun., and James B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Thomas Hume</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to recommend some suitable person as collecting agent
            reported several names.
          </p>
          <aside>Saml Wait appointed Gen. Agent.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the Rev. Samuel Waite was appointed General agent to collect
            funds on behalf of Richmond College at a salary of $750 and the
            President directed to correspond with Mr. Waite on the subject.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={47} />
          <aside>Secy to advertize terms of board & tuition</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the secretary was directed to insert in the papers of the City
            at his own discretion, an advertisement of the course of study, terms of
            tuition, etc. for the coming session at the College.
          </p>
          <aside>Prof Ruggles declines appointment See File No 28</aside>
          <p>
            The President read a letter from Professor Ruggles declining the
            appointment conferred on him at the last meeting.
          </p>
          <p>H. Keeling and A. Thomas obtained leave of absence.</p>
          <aside>Hume to collect Portsmouth dividends</aside>
          <p>
            On motion Resolved That a power of attorney be conferred on Thomas
            Hume to receive the dividend from the Portsmouth scrip belonging to this
            Board.
          </p>
          <aside>Advertize for Professors</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That a committee be appointed to advertise for a
            Professor of mathematics and natural science, and should Mr. Reynolds
            decline the appointment tendered to him, for a Professor of languages -
            Committee:  J.B. Jeter and A.J. Crane.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the consideration of the 3rd and 5th articles of
            the report of the committee to procure additional Professors be
            postponed to the next meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>A.J. Crane's bill referred</aside>
          <p>
            A bill of A.J. Crane was referred to a committee consisting of J. Snead
            and A. Thomas to report at next meeting.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned by benediction</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-09-02'>
          <p>
            The quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at
            the basement room of the Second Church on <time dateTime="1845-09-02">Tuesday Sept'r 2nd 1845</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  J.B. Jeter, Richard Reins, A.J. Crane, A. Thomas, A.G.
            Wortham, W. Sands, Eli Ball, James Sizer, J. C. Crane, A. Snead, and
            J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President being absent J.B. Jeter was appointed President pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Eli Ball</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and <PageNumber num={48} />
            approved.</p>
          <aside>S Wait's Letter <span className='pencil'>Declining</span> See File No 29</aside>
          <p>
            A communication from Rev. Samuel Wait [sic] was read declining the
            appointment of General Agent conferred on him at the last meeting of the
            Board.
          </p>
          <aside>Geo F Adams appointed Gen Agent</aside>
          <p>
            On motion Rev. George F. Adams of Maryland was elected Gen. Agent
            of the Board to collect funds on behalf of the College at a salary of
            $750 per annum.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Secretary be directed to communicate with Mr.
            Adams on this subject.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion, the Trustees proceeded to the election of a Professor of
            Mathematics and natural science for Richmond College.
          </p>
          <aside>Testimonials See File No 30</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee to advertise for a suitable individual to fill this
            Professorship presented the names of several applicants with numerous
            testimonials.
          </p>
          <aside>GF Holmes appointed Professor of Mathematics</aside>
          <p>
            A motion was made that Mr. G.F. Holmes be appointed a professor of
            Richmond College, and after some conversation it was agreed to postpone
            the final decision of the question until Monday the 15th inst.
          </p>
          <p>
            The death of George Alderson one of the members of this Board being
            announced
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion Mr. James C. Spotts was appointed a Trustee of Richmond
            College.
          </p>
          <p>
            Adjourned to meet at this place on Monday the 15th at 8 o'clock P.M.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter, Pres. Pro tem</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-09-15'>
          <p>
            The adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held on
            <time dateTime="1845-09-15">Monday September 15th 1845</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.B. Jeter, J.C. Crane, James Sizer, A. Thomas, A. Snead, A.J.
            Crane, A.G. Wortham, Jos. Mosby, R. Reins, <PageNumber num={49} />
            W. Sands, E.L. Magoon, James Thomas, Jun., and J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            The President being absent, J.B. Jeter was elected President pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by E.L. Magoon</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            Mr. James C. Spotts, having become duly qualified as a trustee, appeared
            and took his seat.
          </p>
          <aside>GF Adams declines the Agency.</aside>
          <p>
            The Secretary presented a communication from Rev. Geo. F. Adams
            declining the agency to which he had been invited.
          </p>
          <aside>LW Allen appointed Agent.</aside>
          <p>
            The Rev. L.W. Allen of Gloucester County was elected Gen. agent of the
            Board to collect funds on behalf of Richmond College, and the Secretary
            was directed to inform him of the appointment.
          </p>
          <aside>G.F. Holmes</aside>
          <p>
            On motion, The Board proceeded to the appointment of a Professor of
            Mathematics and natural science. Whereupon Mr. G.F. Holmes recently of
            Charleston S.C. was duly elected.
          </p>
          <p>The Secretary was directed to notify Mr. Holmes of his election.</p>
          <p>On Motion, Mr. Reins was added to the committee on the premises.</p>
          <aside>A student received on bond & security</aside>
          <p>
            A communication was read from Mr. Lawrence Battaille, jun., desiring to
            be received as a student of Richmond College on condition that he give
            his note with good security payable in twelve months.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereupon it was Resolved that the Secretary be directed to inform Mr.
            Battaille that for room, rent and tuition fees, the trustees will accede
            to the terms proposed by him, leaving him to make arrangements with the
            Steward for board.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board adjourned to meet at this place tomorrow evening at
            7 o'clock.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter, Pres. Pro tem</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={50} />
        <section id='meeting-1845-09-16'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met according to adjournment on <time dateTime="1845-09-16">
              Tuesday
              evening Sept 16th, 1845
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Jessee Snead, J.B. Jeter, A.J. Crane, E.L. Magoon, James
            Sizer, R. Reins, James Thomas, jun., J.C. Crane, A. Thomas, A. Snead,
            A.G. Wortham, and J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President being absent, Jessee Snead was appointed President pro
            tem.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by R. Reins</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read, approved and duly certified
            by the President and Secretary.
          </p>
          <aside>Res in reference to Treas</aside>
          <p>
            On motion Resolved That the Treasurer be authorised to pay for any
            repairs on the College premises ordered by the committee on the premises
            duly certified from any money in his hands, not otherwise appropriated.
          </p>
          <p>Mr. Sands appeared and took his seat.</p>
          <aside>Crane's bill $5.50 paid.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Treasurer be directed to pay A.J. Crane's bill
            for bringing a suit against Joel B. Bragg, guardian, and tax, amounting
            to $5.50. -
          </p>
          <aside>Motion to annul the boardg Dept.</aside>
          <p>
            The following resolution was offered - That the future policy of the
            Board will be, so far as practicable, to disconnect from the College any
            establishment for board and lodging, and confine the duties of the
            College strictly to furnishing students with instruction. After some
            discussion the resolution was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That a committee be appointed to correspond with the
            Boards of other Colleges in the State soliciting them to unite with this
            Board in reviving before the Legislature the memorial of the Colleges
            presented at the session of 43 &amp; 44.
          </p>
          <p>Committee:  A.J. Crane and J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <aside>C.L. Cock [sic] tutor</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That Charles L. Cocke be appointed tutor of the
            College, at a salary of $600 -
          </p>
          <aside>appeal.</aside>
          <p>Resolved That a committee be appointed to prepare an <PageNumber num={51} />
            appeal presenting the claims of Richmond College to the support and
            patronage of the state and that the same be published in the
            <cite>Religious Herald</cite>.
          </p>
          <p>Committee:  J.B. Jeter, E.L. Magoon, and J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            On motion adjourned to meet the first Tuesday evening of next month at 7
            o'clock.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jessee Snead, Pres. Pro tem</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-10-07'>
          <div><time dateTime="1845-10-07">7th Oct. 1845</time></div>
          <p>
            The Board of Trustees met this evening according to previous adjournment
            at the 2nd Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Ro. Ryland, Pres.  J.B. Jeter, Jessee Snead, J.C. Crane, A.G.
            Wortham, James Sizer, J.C. Spotts, A. Thomas, R. Reins, James Thomas,
            jun., A.J. Crane, E.L. Magoon, A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>The Board being called to order, prayer was offered by J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent, A. Snead was chosen Sec. pro tem.</p>
          <aside>Com. on the memorial</aside>
          <p>
            The reports of committees being called for; the committee to correspond
            with the various Colleges on the subject of renewing the petition to the
            Legislature presented at the session of 43 &amp; 44 reported and was
            continued.
          </p>
          <aside>on the appeal</aside>
          <p>
            The committee appointed to address the friends of the College through
            the <cite>Herald</cite>reported they had performed the duty and on motion was
            discharged.
          </p>
          <aside>Acceptance of Prof Holmes</aside>
          <p>
            A letter from Mr. G.F. Holmes accepting the appointment of Professor in
            the College was read.
          </p>
          <aside>Lot of ground in Chicago</aside>
          <p>
            A letter was read from Mr. Freer of Chicago relative to a lot of ground
            in or near that town; in which lot this Board possess an interest, and
            on motion the letter was referred to the President, with instructions to
            correspond with Rev. Wm. Southwood in relation to the subject matter
            thereof, and report to this Board at the next meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>Steward's Report.</aside>
          <p>A communication from the Steward of the College <PageNumber num={52} />
            was read, and on motion a committee was appointed to consider the
            suggestions therein <aside>suggstion</aside> contained and report thereon at the next meeting of
            the Board. Committee to consist of Jessee Snead, James Sizer, and James
            C. Spotts.
          </p>
          <p>
            The resolution laid on the table at the last meeting relative to the
            future policy of this Board concerning the feeding and lodging of
            students was taken up and considered:  After remarks from several
            trustees, the following resolution was offered by Mr. James C. Crane and
            adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Removal of College referred to a Committee</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the resolution now under consideration be referred
            to a committee of three Trustees, with instructions to consider the
            expediency of removing the College within the limits of the City of
            Richmond, and at what pecuniary cost such change of location can be made
            and report at the next meeting of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>Committee:  Jessee Snead, A.J. Crane, and J. Thomas, jr.,</p>
          <p>
            Resolved That when this Board adjourn, it adjourn to meet at
            this place at 7 o'clock P.M. of the first Tuesday in Nov next; and that
            the Sec give notice of the same through such of the news papers as he
            may deem necessary.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A. Snead, Sec'y Pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={53} />
        <section id='meeting-1845-11-04'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1845-11-04">4th November 1845</time></div>
          <p>
            The Board of Trustees met this evening at 7 o'clock at the lecture room
            of the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, Pres't.  J.B. Jeter, Eli Ball, James C. Crane,
            A.G. Wortham, Jessee Snead, Joseph Mosby, J. Sizer, and A.
            Snead. <span style={{ marginLeft: 30 }}>Prayer by J.B. Jeter.</span>
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent, A. Snead was on motion appointed Secy. pro
            tem.
          </p>
          <aside>committees</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed to correspond with the representatives of other
            colleges, not being prepared to make any further report, was on motion
            <aside>continued</aside>continued.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed to consider and report on the steward's
            communication, not being prepared to report, was on motion continued.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed to consider and report on the expediency of
            removing the College to the City was continued.
          </p>
          <aside>Country Trustrees notified</aside>
          <p>
            On motion, the Secy. pro tem was directed to give notice through the
            <cite>Herrald </cite>[sic] that the next meeting of the Trustees will
            take place on the first Tuesday in Dcer. next at this place, <aside>✓</aside>at which
            time it is proposed to determine the question of propriety of changing
            the location of the College.
          </p>
          <aside>Reynolds declines</aside>
          <p>
            A letter was read from Prof. Reynolds declining the professorship
            confered [sic] on him by the trustees.
          </p>
          <aside>Professor Reynolds urged to accept.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the President be directed to write to Prof'r
            Reynolds urging him to reconsider his determination, and assure him, if
            he will accept, the expenses of his removal to the College from his home
            will be paid.
          </p>
          <aside>Bills for Repairs</aside>
          <p>
            Two bills, on of R.I. Clarke, amounting to $107.22, and one of Walter C.
            Freeman, amounting to $12.80, both for repairs done on the College
            premises, under the advice of the Comt'e. on the premises, were
            presented and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board adjourned to meet at this place at 7 o'clock P.M. on
            the first Tuesday in Decr. next.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A. Snead, Sec'y Pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={54} />
        <section id='meeting-1845-12-02'>
          <div><time dateTime="1845-12-02">December 2nd 1845</time></div>
          <p>
            The Board of Trustees met this evening at 7 o'clock at the lecture rom
            [sic] of the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  R. Ryland, Pres't.  Edmund Broad[d]us, L.W. Allen, A. Fleet,
            Jas. Thomas, E.L. Magoon, J.B. Jeter, A.G. Wortham, Jesse[e] Snead, A.J.
            Crane, A. Thomas, Eli Ball, J. Sizer, R. Reins, James C. Crane, and A.
            Snead. Prayer by L.W. Allen.
          </p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent, A. Snead was appointed Secy pro tem.</p>
          <p>A communication from the Pres't. was read.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to correspond with the colleges of the state reported. The
            report was received and committee discharged.
          </p>
          <aside>Delegates to the College Convention</aside>
          <p>The following resolution was adopted:</p>
          <p>
            Resolved That Robert Ryland, A.J. Crane, and J.B. Jeter be
            appointed to represent Richmond College in the convention of Colleges to
            be held in this city on the 8th Inst.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee on the Steward's communication reported, and the committee
            was discharged.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion, the report was laid on the table, after some conversation on
            its merits.
          </p>
          <aside>Indefinite postponement of question of <u>Removal</u></aside>
          <p>
            The Committee on the subject of removal stated they had not prepared a
            written report but submitted a verbal one. After discussion by members
            on the subject of removal, it was Resolved that the whole subject be
            indefinitely postponed.
          </p>
          <aside>Declinature of Mr Reynolds.</aside>
          <p>
            A letter was read from Mr. Reynolds in reply to the president's last
            communication made in complyance [sic] with and [sic] order of the
            board, declining the professorship to which he had been elected.
          </p>
          <aside>Designation of Prof Holmes</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That Professor Holmes be transfered [sic] to the
            professorship of Ancient Language.
          </p>
          <aside>Portsmouth scrip.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That Thomas Hume be authorized to draw the interest on
            the Portsmouth scrip held by this board.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board adjourned to meet at this place to-morrow at 7
            o'clock P.M.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A. Snead, Sec'y Pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1845-12-03'>
          <PageNumber num={55} />
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met according to adjournment <time dateTime="1845-12-03">
              Wednesday
              evening Dec 3rd, 1845
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  E.L. Magoon, Jessee Snead, Jas. C.
            Crane, L.W. Allen, Edmund Broaddus, Eli Ball, Jas. Thomas, Jun., Albert
            Snead, and Jas. B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Jas. B. Taylor</p>
          <p>The minutes of last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Ssecy and Treasurer appointed</aside>
          <p>
            The record containing no reference to the election of Secretary &amp;
            Treasurer at the last annual meeting &amp; doubts being expressed as to
            whether the election actually took place - Resolved That the
            acts of those officers who have continued to hold the offices since that
            period be declared legal, they being present and consenting thereto -
            and that the Trustees now proceed to elect to the next annual meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            The election resulted in the choice by ballot of Jas. C. Crane as
            Treasurer, and Jas. B. Taylor, Secretary.
          </p>
          <aside>BH Benton appointed Professor</aside>
          <p>
            The Board proceeded to the election of a Professor of Natural Science,
            whereupon after some conversation Mr. B.H. Benton of Loudon County was
            appointed.
          </p>
          <aside>Designation of funds</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That all funds collected by the Agent after deducting
            the expenses of the agent be appropriated exclusively to the permanent
            endowment until otherwise designated by the donors.
          </p>
          <aside>Com on agency</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That a standing committee on the agency be appointed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Committee:  Robert Ryland, Eli Ball, J. C. Crane, &amp; Jas. B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Sec</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={56} />
        <section id='meeting-1845-12-27'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met at the house of Richard C. Wortham
            on <time dateTime="1845-12-27">Dec 27th 1845</time>.  Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  A. Thomas, J.C.
            Crane, Edmund Broaddus, Richard C. Wortham, Wm. Sands, J.B. Jeter,
            Richard Reins, A.G. Wortham.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by J.B. Jeter</p>
          <p>
            A.J. Crane, Jas. B. Taylor, and Jas. Thomas, Jun., appeared and took
            their seats.
          </p>
          <aside>Bento declines</aside>
          <p>
            A letter from B.H. Benton declining for the present the appointment of
            Professor of Mathematics and Natural Science was read. Whereupon,
            Resolved  That a Committee consisting of the President, A.G.
            Wortham, &amp; <aside>Temporary supply</aside>A.J. Crane to secure an individual temporarily to supply
            this Professorship was appointed.
          </p>
          <aside>Stewards letter</aside>
          <p>
            A letter was read from the Steward in which he proposes to relieve
            himself from certain duties pertaining to this office, whereupon the
            following resolutions were adopted:
          </p>
          <aside>Duties insisted on</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Steward shall be required to perform such
            duties as he has heretofore rendered since the College went into
            operation.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Board will be much gratified if Mr. Cocke
            should find it consistent with his interest to retain the Stewardship -
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-01-25'>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at the
            First Baptist Church on <time dateTime="1846-01-25">Monday Jan 25, 1846</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  R. Ryland, President.  A.J. Crane, E.L. Magoon, J.B. Jeter, A.
            Snead, A.G. Wortham, L.W. Allen, J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by E.L. Magoon</p>
          <p>The minutes of last meeting were read.</p>
          <PageNumber num={57} />
          <p>Jas Thomas, Jun., Wm. Sands appeared and took their seats.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee to procure a temporary supply for the Professorship of
            Mathematics, etc. reported that they had been unsuccessful in their
            inquiry.
          </p>
          <aside>S.E. Brownell a temporary supply</aside>
          <p>
            Res'd. That a temporary appointment until the close of the present
            session be conferred on Mr. Stephen E. Brownell of New Bern, N.C., as
            Professor of Mathematics &amp; Natural Science, his salary to be at the
            rate of $600 per annum.
          </p>
          <aside>Joint agency of Ed. Society & College</aside>
          <p>
            Res'd.  That the agent of the College, Rev. L.W. Allen, be permitted, if
            he deems it proper, to accept a joint agency for the Baptist Education
            Society of Va., on the terms proposed by that society, viz., that the
            Trustees of the College defray two thirds, and the said society one
            third of the salary; all funds collected by the agent to be divided
            between the college and society in the same ratio, unless specially
            designated by the donors.
          </p>
          <aside>Stewards bill referred</aside>
          <p>
            A bill from the Steward for Incidental Expenses was presented, whereupon
            on motion it was referred to the Auditing Committee.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-05-29'>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held on the
            <time dateTime="1846-05-29">29th of May 1846</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  J.B. Jeter, A. Snead, E.L. Magoon,
            R. Reins, A.J. Crane, A.G. Wortham, and Jas B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by E.L. Magoon</p>
          <aside>C.L. Cock resigns as tutor & Steward</aside>
          <p>
            A letter was read from Charles L. Cocke resigning his place at the
            College as Tutor and Steward.
          </p>
          <p>A. Thomas and J.C. Crane appeared and took their seats.</p>
          <aside>accepted</aside>
          <p>
            Whereupon it was resolved that the resignation of Mr. Cocke be accepted
            and that he be allowed to leave the College as early as the 20th of
            June, provided that he make arrangements for the instruction of his
            classes to the close of the session.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={58} />
          <aside>Compliment to Mr. Cocke</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That in accepting the resignation of Mr. Cocke the
            Board take pleasure in bearing testimony to his good character,
            fidelity, and competence as a Teacher.
          </p>
          <aside>Plan of the Stewardship</aside>
          <p>
            A plan for the Stewardship was presented by the President &amp; after
            some conversation the whole subject was referred to the Committee on the
            premises.
          </p>
          <aside>Advertiz.g Bill $10.75</aside>
          <p>
            Two bills for advertising in the <cite>Whig</cite> amounting to $10.75 were
            paid by the Board.
          </p>
          <aside>Com. to Examine Treasur's account</aside>
          <p>
            That a Committee consisting of James Thomas, Jun., and Jas C. Spotts be
            appointed to examine the Treasurer's account.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-06-09' className='annual'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College held their annual meeting on <time dateTime="1846-06-09">
              Tuesday
              the 9th of June 1846
            </time> at the 2nd Baptist Church, Richmond.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  J.C. Crane, Daniel Witt, Addison
            Hall, James Sizer, Jos. B. Turner, Jno. D. McGill, A.M. Poindexter, Eli
            Ball, A. Snead, J.B. Jeter, A.J. Crane, L.W. Allen, A. Thomas, W.
            Southwood, Cumberland George, C.F. Fisher, T. Hume, Jas. Thomas, jr.,
            and James B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Mr. Simons of Burmah</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The quarterly report of the President was read.</p>
          <aside>Treasur's report read & approved</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer's report was read, having been audited by the
            appropriate committee, it was approved.
          </p>
          <aside>Agent's report</aside>
          <p>The General Agent presented a report of his labors.</p>
          <aside>Stewardship</aside>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was referred the subject of the stewardship
            reported, which report on motion was referred to a select committee
            consisting of A.J. Crane, Jno. D. McGill, Tho. Hume, Jos. B. Turner, and
            the President.
          </p>
          <aside>Steward's accounts.</aside>
          <p>
            The Steward presented a statement of his account whereupon Jas. Thomas,
            jr., and James Sizer were appointed to examine his books to report at
            the next quarterly meeting of the Board.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={59} />
          <aside>Two Tutors to be advertised for</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the President be authorised to advertise for two
            tutors, one to conduct the classes in mathematics and natural science in
            the College proper at a salary of $500 and the other to take charge of
            the academic department at a salary of $400.
          </p>
          <aside>Vacancies in Trustees to be ascertained</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That a committee be appointed to ascertain the
            vacancies which may have occurred in the Trustees of Richmond College
            and to nominate individuals to supply them. Committee:  L.W. Allen and
            Tho. Hume.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Trustees proceeded to the election of officers which
            resulted as follows:
          </p>
          <aside>Officers elected</aside>
          <dl>
            <dt>James B. Taylor</dt>
            <dd>Secretary</dd>
            <dt>James C. Crane</dt>
            <dd>Treasurer</dd>
          </dl>
          <aside>Public meeting</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the President be authorised to appoint a public
            meeting sometime during the present week, and that due arrangements be
            made to secure speakers to address the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution was proposed.</p>
          <aside>Property to be alienated by Trustees at the annual meetings only;</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That this Board of Trustees shall not have the right to
            alienate property or to enlarge the operations of the College, or
            otherwise materially to increase its liabilities, at any other than an
            annual meeting of the Board unless such change shall have been proposed
            and referred to a subsequent meeting, and a notice of such meeting,
            stating specifically the change proposed, shall have been sent to each
            trustee <span style={{ marginLeft: 30 }}>months</span> previous to its taking place.
          </p>
          <aside>Laid upon the table</aside>
          <p>The resolution was laid upon the table.</p>
          <aside>Endowment to be ascertained</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That a committee be appointed to ascertain and report
            the exact amount of our endowment and character of the funds in which it
            is invested to report tomorrow afternoon at 5 o'clock.
          </p>
          <p>James C. Crane and L.W. Allen, Committee.</p>
          <p>Adjourned by Benediction</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={60} />
        <section id='meeting-1846-06-10'>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College, according to adjournment, met at the
            First Baptist Church on <time dateTime="1846-06-10">Wednesday June the 10th 1846</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, President.  J. Snead, A.J. Crane, A.G. Wortham,
            L.W. Allen, Jno. D. McGill, Jos. B. Turner, Wm. Sands, Thos. Hume, &amp;
            J.B. Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by the Secretary</p>
          <aside>Stewardship</aside>
          <p>
            The committee on the Stewardship reported in favor of the plan
            recommended by the President. The minority of the committee presented a
            counter-report.
          </p>
          <p>The Trustees adjourned to meet at the call of the President.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland<br />Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-06-29'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1846-06-29">June 29th, 1846</time></div>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met this evening, in obedience to the
            call of the President, at the house of Archibald Thomas.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Robert Ryland, Pres't.  A.G. Wortham, Rich'd Reins, E.L.
            Magoon, A.J. Crane, Jessee Snead, James Thomas, Jun'r., J.B. Jeter, and
            A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent, A. Snead was appointed Secretary pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting being read, were corrected and approved.
          </p>
          <aside>Stewardship</aside>
          <p>
            The Trustees then proceeded to the consideration of the reports made at
            the last meeting on the subject <PageNumber num={61} />
            of the Stewardship; said reports having been read, on motion the report
            of the majority was adopted.  (See document &quot;A&quot;)
          </p>
          <aside>Steward, a Com. to engage</aside>
          <p>
            On motion it was &quot;resolved that a committee of three be appointed
            to engage a Steward for the next year, and that the committee consist of
            Ro. Ryland, A. Snead, and A.G. Wortham.
          </p>
          <aside>Seats of Trustees vacated.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion, Resolved  That the seats of the following Trustees be
            vacated, they not having attended the meetings as provided for by the
            charter, viz: Thomas Hudgins, Charles Hunton, Jno. B. Young, and Silas
            Wyatt, and to fill the seats thus vacated <aside>Trustees elected</aside> the following persons were
            elected, viz: Thomas J. Evans, Richard H. Toler, Charles T. Wortham, and
            William F. Ritchies. <span className='pencil'>Supp. 87 &amp; 90</span>
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurer to borrow money and pay Cock's salary.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Treasurer be authorized to &quot;borrow and
            pay to Charles L. Cocke, the amount of three hundred dollars, due for
            salary last year.&quot;
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board adjourned to meet on the 31st July at half past four
            o'clock P.M. at the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A. Snead, Secy pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={62} />
        <section id='meeting-1846-07-31'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1846-07-31">July 31st, 1846</time></div>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College, pursuant to adjournment, met this
            evening at half past four o'clock at the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex' }}>
            Present:
            <ul style={{ marginTop: 0, listStyle: 'none' }}>
              <li>Robert Ryland, President</li>
              <li>J.B. Jeter,</li>
              <li>A.G. Wortham,</li>
              <li>Rich'd Reins,</li>
              <li>A.J. Crane,</li>
              <li>James Thomas, Jr.,</li>
              <li>Wm. Sands,</li>
              <li>A. Snead,</li>
              <li>Thos. J. Evans.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by Robert Ryland</p>
          <aside>Secretary resigned</aside>
          <p>
            The resignation of James B. Taylor as secretary of the Board was offered
            and accepted.
          </p>
          <aside>Secy. elected</aside>
          <p>
            J.B. Jeter nominated Thomas J. Evans who was duly elected Secretary of
            the Board.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read, corrected and approved.</p>
          <aside>Aurelius S. Goff appointed Steward.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee appointed at the last meeting to engage a steward for the
            next year, reported that they engaged Aurelius L. Goff as the Steward
            for one year from and after the 1st day of August 1846 at the price and
            on the conditions contained in articles of agreement entered into by the
            said Goff on the one part and the President and Secretary of Richmond
            College on the other part. The report was adopted and the committee
            discharged.
          </p>
          <aside>School house ordered to be built on the College lot.</aside>
          <p>
            On the motion of Richard Reins, seconded by J.B. Jeter, the following
            resolution was adopted, to wit:
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the committee on the premises be instructed
            &quot;to have a suitable school-house built on the College lot.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Resignation of Jas. C. Crane Treasr. laed on the table</aside>
          <p>
            The resignation of James C. Crane as one of the trustees, and as
            Treasurer of Richmond College, was offered, and on the motion of Richard
            Reins, was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <aside>B Robertson appointed tutor of mathematics &<sup>c</sup>.</aside>
          <p>
            The Board then went into the election of Tutor or Professor of
            Mathematics and Natural Science, whereupon Mr. T.B. Roberson of
            Richmond, Va., was elected.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={63} />
          <aside>N.H. Massie elected academic Tutor.</aside>
          <p>
            Mr. N. Harden Massie was then unanimously elected Tutor of the
            academical department of Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>J.B. Jeter offered the following resolution, which was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Refusal to pay Steward, Cocke, for storeroom built without direction of the Board.</aside>
          <p>
            &quot;A communication having been received from the Steward of the
            College, Mr. C.L. Cocke, preferring a claim of $75 for a store-house
            built by him upon the premises, and this improvement having been made
            without the direction of the Board, therefore, Resolved, that this Board
            deem it inexpedient to allow the claim; and that Mr. Cocke be permitted
            to remove the said room, should he wish to do so, provided it can be
            done without injury to the property of the College.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Act. referred to committee.</aside>
          <p>
            The account of C.L. Cocke, former Steward, of <span style={{ marginRight: 20 }}>$</span> was referred to the
            auditing committee.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned by benediction.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-12-08'>
          <p>Richmond, <time dateTime="1846-12-08">Decem'r 8, 1846</time></p>
          <p>
            At a quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this
            evening at the Second Baptist Church, Present:  Ro. Ryland, Pres't.
            J.B. Jeter, L.W. Allen, A.G. Wortham, A. Thomas, Jas. Thomas, Jun'r., A.
            Snead, Charles T. Wortham, &amp; Thomas J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by L.W. Allen</p>
          <p>The minutes from the 9th of June last were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Quarterly report.</aside>
          <p>
            The quarterly report of the president was read &amp; approved and
            filed.  (See document &quot;K&quot;)
          </p>
          <aside>Cock's Salary</aside>
          <p>
            A communication was read from C.S. Cocke, late Steward of the College
            (see document &quot;L&quot;), whereupon the following resolution,
            offered by J.B. Jeter, was adopted.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={64} />
          <aside>Explanation of the permission to C.S. Cocke to leave the College</aside>
          <p>
            &quot;Whereas the resolution of the Trustees of Richmond College, dated
            the 29th of May 1846, permitting Mr. C.L. Cocke to leave the college
            after the 20th of June 1846 has been misunderstood, therefore,
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Trustees understood by the resolution that Mr.
            Cocke's salary should cease &quot;at the time that he left the
            institution.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Report of the Genl. Agent</aside>
          <p>
            L.W. Allen, the General Agent of the College, made a report of his
            proceedings, which was approved and referred to a committee consisting
            of James C. Crane and Charles T. Wortham.
          </p>
          <aside>Cabiness and Owens to be compensated.</aside>
          <p>The following resolution offered by Ro. Ryland was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved That A.B. Cabaniss and R.R. Owens be compensated, at
            the discretion of the President of the Board, for services rendered in
            teaching last session in consequence of Mr. Cocke's resignation.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Agency</aside>
          <p>
            The following resolution, offered by J.B. Jeter, was referred to the
            following com'ee:  Jeter, A.J. Crane, and A. Snead.
            &quot;Resolved That Rev. L.W. Allen be reappointed agent of the
            Trustees with a salary of <span style={{ marginRight: 20 }}>$</span> per annum, with his necessary travelling
            expenses.&quot;
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Trustees adjourned to meet at this place on Tuesday
            evening next at 7 o'clock.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1846-12-15' className='noquorum'>
