        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1949-03-13'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1849-03-13">March 13th 1849</time></div>
          <p>
            At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held,
            pursuant to adjournment, at the Second Baptist Church Present
          </p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols">
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, presdt.</li>
              <li>A. Snead</li>
              <li>A. Judson Crane</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>James Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>E. Wortham</li>
              <li>James B. Taylor</li>
              <li>J.S. Reynolds</li>
              <li>S.W. Allen</li>
              <li>James Sizer</li>
              <li>J.B. Jeter</li>
              <li>Thos. J. Evans</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. Mr. Pollard. </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent, A.J. Crane was appointed Secretary pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>The quarterly report of the President was then read.</p>
          <p>The Secretary appeared and took his seat.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last two meetings were read &amp; approved.</p>
          <aside>Salaries of the Professors, how to be paid.</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee on the subject of changing the mode of paying the Salaries
            of the Professors submitted a report in which contained the following
            suggestion which was adopted. &quot;Your Committee therefore recommend
            that from the commencement of the next session, the tuition fees, with
            the avails of the endowment fund, be divided between the Teachers, in
            proportion to the relative Salaries, they at present receive.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Mode of liquidating the debt by the College.</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee on the liquidation of the debt due by the College,
            submitted a report, in which was contained the following recommendation
            which was adopted. &quot;That the Treasurer be directed to give his bond
            to the President for the amount due to him, with the<PageNumber num={79} />
            understanding that so much of the interest as may accrue from the
            endowment fund yet to be collected shall be applied to the payment of
            interest and principal from year to year until the bond shall be
            cancelled.&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Scholarships.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee on the subject of scholarships offered the following
            report which was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            &quot;On the subject of scholarships, your committee report in favor of
            an entire change in the policy of the Board. They are satisfied that
            without ample endowment the College can never rise to its appropriate
            position among Sister institutions of the State.  They beleive [sic]
            also that it will be difficult, if not impossible within in a few years,
            to secure, as a gratuity, a sufficient sum to place it on a firm basis.
            It is therefore deemed expedient greatly to reduce the price of
            scholarships. Nor is this, in the history of Colleges, an untried
            experiment. Bethany College and Hampden Sidney of our own State have
            adopted the measure with success. The latter institution has already, in
            this way, secured about seventy thousand dollars. It is therefore
            recommended by your committee to reduce the price of scholarships, in
            Richmond College, so as to bring them within the reach of all classes in
            the community. The following scheme is proposed for the adoption of the
            Trustees.
          </p>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: "inside" }}>
            <li className='first'>That scholarships at $50, each, not exceeding 2000 in number be
              hereby offered to the friends of Education.</li>
            <li className='second'>Any person paying in cash to the President and Trustees of
              Richmond College, the sum of Fifty dollars shall be entitled to one
              scholarship, and for every additional $50, another share in the scheme
              shall be held.</li>
            <li className='third'>Each scholarship shall entitle one person &amp; only one to a full
              course of instruction in said Richmond College, and its preparatory
              departments.</li>
            <li className='fourth'>Any individual holding a scholarship may, by it, himself pass
              through a course of study or send his own son or the son of another, at
              any period within thirty years from the time when the operation of the
              scheme shall commence. Tuition being given to one person by virtue of a
              scholarship, the scholarship shall thus become null and void.  A
              scholarship may be transferred by will or otherwise.</li>
            <li className='fifth'><PageNumber num={80} />This scheme shall commence operation when 1000 scholarships shall
              have been secured.</li>
            <li className='sixth'>The foregoing scheme shall not be understood to invalidate any
              privilege or right secured by the system of scholarships heretofore
              adopted by the Trustees of the College.&quot;</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            The committee on the subject of the removal of the College to the City
            was allowed time to report.
          </p>
          <aside>Com. on agent</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of J.B. Jeter, the committee to nominate an agent, was
            continued and authorized to employ an agent or agents to carry out the
            scheme of scholarships and collect the subscriptions formerly made to
            the endowment. Mr. E. Wortham was added to the committee.
          </p>
          <aside>On chemical apparatus.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of A.J. Crane a committee was appointed to examine the
            chemical aparatus [sic] referred to in the president's report, and to
            report upon the subject at our next meeting. Com:  A.J. Crane, A. Snead
            &amp; A.G. Wortham.
          </p>
          <aside>on a Diploma.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of T.J. Evans a committee was appointed to prepare a form of
            diploma for graduates in Richmond College. Com: Reynolds, Ryland &amp;
            A.J. Crane.
          </p>
          <aside>on Agent's acts</aside>
          <p>The committee on the accounts of the agent was continued.</p>
          <p>Adjourned to meet at this place, this night two weeks.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={81} />
        <section id='meeting-1849-06-14'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1849-06-14">June 14th 1849</time></div>
          <aside>9th ann<sup>l</sup> Meeting.</aside>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the 2nd Baptist
            Church on the <time dateTime="1849-06-05">5th of June 1849</time>
          </p>
          <p>
            Present:  Ro. Ryland, Pres't.  James B. Taylor, Rich'd Reins, A. Thomas,
            C.T. Wortham, James Thomas, Jr., J.B. Jeter, J.L. Reynolds, E. Wortham
            &amp; T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Mr. Baynham.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting were read &amp; approved.</p>
          <aside>Removal</aside>
          <p>
            The committee on the removal of the College to the City of Richmond, not
            having made any report, was on motion discharged. Present: Wm. Sands.
          </p>
          <aside>Presidents Report.</aside>
          <p>
            The report of the President was read and ordered to be referred to the
            appropriate committee.
          </p>
          <aside>Robertson & Snead resign</aside>
          <p>
            The resignations of Professor Robertson and Tutor Snead were read and
            accepted.
          </p>
          <aside>W<sup>m</sup>. H. Pollard agent.<br />3 prct salary.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee on procuring an agent to obtain scholarships reported that
            they had obtained the services of Mr. Wm. Pollard at a salary of three
            per cent upon the amount secured by him for scholarships.
          </p>
          <aside>Funds to be returned</aside>
          <p>
            The report of the committee was amended so as to authorise the return of
            the money to subscribers in the event of the scheme of scholarships
            failing. The report as amended was adopted and the committee was
            continued and instructed to prepare a certificate and receipt of the
            money subscribed for scholarships.
          </p>
          <aside>Students petition to leave.</aside>
          <p>
            A memorial of the students requesting the immediate termination of the
            college session on account of the cholera was presented and respectfully
            declined.
          </p>
          <p>Present:  Mr. Herndon and A.G. Snead.</p>
          <aside>Apparatus purchased</aside>
          <p>
            The report of the committee confirming the purchase of the chemical
            apparatus by the President of Mr. Benton was adopted, on the condition
            that there be an abatement for articles not furnished according to the
            list.
          </p>
          <aside>Officers to be advertized for</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the President was authorised to advertize [sic] for officers
            to fill the vacancies occasioned by the resignations of Messrs.
            Robertson and Snead.
          </p>
          <aside>Nat. Science</aside>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that a Professor of Natural Science be
            appointed at a salary of $650 per annum to be paid in the same manner
            and in the same <PageNumber num={82} />
            proportion with the other professors, and the President was directed to
            advertize for such a professor.
          </p>
          <aside>Com. on College Finances</aside>
          <p>
            E. Wortham &amp; T.J. Evans were appointed a committee to examine the
            finances of the College since 1846.
          </p>
          <aside>on treasurer's accounts.</aside>
          <p>
            A. Thomas and J.B. Taylor were appointed a committee to examine the
            Treasurer's accounts.
          </p>
          <p>Committee on agency was continued.</p>
          <aside>Repairs.</aside>
          <p>
            The president was authorized to have the repairs to the College's
            premises alluded to in his report, done.
          </p>
          <aside>First graduates</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of J.B. Jeter the degree of A.B. was ordered to be conferred
            on P.S. Henson &amp; Josiah Ryland.
          </p>
          <aside>Secy & Treasr</aside>
          <p>T.J. Evans was elected Secretary &amp; E. Wortham Trs'r.</p>
          <aside>Agent</aside>
          <p>
            The President was authorized and requested to act as agent in obtaining
            scholarships.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned to meet on the <time dateTime="1849-07-14">14th July</time> next.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <aside>no quorum on <time dateTime="1849-07-14">14th July</time>.</aside>

        <section id='meeting-1849-07-16'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1849-07-16">July 16th 1849</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting adjourned because of there being no quorum on the 14th.
            Present:  Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Taylor, A. Thomas, E. Wortham,
            A.J. Crane, J.L. Reynolds, Wm. Sands, James Sizer, C.T. Wortham, and
            T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.L. Reynolds.</p>
          <p>Minutes read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Board then went into the election of a Tutor of Mathematics, and Mr.
            John Lawson was elected at a salary of $650 to be paid in the same
            proportion and in the same way as the other members of the faculty.
          </p>
          <aside>Tutor Lawson.<br />$650<br />Prof. Turner<br />$650<br />Tutor Puryear<br />$400</aside>
          <p>
            Mr. Lewis Turner was elected professor of Natural Science at a salary of
            $650, and Mr. Bennett Puryear was elected tutor in the academical
            department at a salary of $400 - each to be paid as the other members of
            the faculty are paid.
          </p>
          <aside>French teacher</aside>
          <p>
            Mr. Arthur Frieze was elected instructor of modern languages, to make
            his own contract with the students for his salary.
          </p>
          <p>The President was instructed to procure a steward.</p>
          <PageNumber num={83} />
          <aside>J.R. Scott as orator.</aside>
          <p>
            Mr. Jacob R. Scott was invited to deliver an address at the commencement
            of the College, and his expenses were ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1849-12-04'>
