        <section id='meeting-1851-04-09'>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held in the
            Mission Room of the First Baptist Church in the City of Richmond, <time dateTime='1851-04-09'>
              April
              the 9th, 1851
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present, Ro. Ryland, prest.  A. Thomas, J.B. Taylor, Jno. M. Murray, A.
            Snead, Jos. S. Walthall, B. Manly and Thos. J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>
            The president laid before the Trustees several communications in regard
            to the lot of ground in Chicargo [sic] conveyed to Richmond College by
            the Rev. Wm. Southwood, whereupon the following resolution was offered
            and unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Authority to sell Property in Chichargo</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved, That it is expedient to sell the lot in Chicargo [sic]
            Illinois, which was conveyed to Richmond College by the Rev. Wm.
            Southwood, and that the President and Secretary be, and they are hereby
            authorized and directed to<PageNumber num={92} />
            make the necessary arrangements to sell, and to execute any deed or
            deeds to the purchaser or purchasers.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President laid before the board a communication from the Rev. A.M.
            Poindexter declining the appointment of agent of the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of the Rev. J.B. Taylor, Edward T. Finch was appointed agent
            at a salary of $600 per annum and his travelling expenses.
          </p>
          <p>And then the board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1851-06-03' className='annual'>
          <time dateTime="1851-06-03">Richmond June 3rd 1851</time>
          <p>
            At an annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the
            Second Baptist Church in the City of Richmond <time dateTime="1851-06-03">June 3rd 1851</time>.
          </p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols">
            <div>Present:</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, prest.</li>
              <li>Jas. Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell, B. Manly,</li>
              <li>A. Hall,</li>
              <li>Ed. Wortham,</li>
              <li>Jos. S. Walthall,</li>
              <li>A. Snead,</li>
              <li>C.T. Wortham,</li>
              <li>R. Reins,</li>
              <li>Thos. Hume,</li>
              <li>Jno. M. Murray</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>J.B. Taylor,</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter</li>
              <li>E. Kingsford</li>
              <li>Thos. J. Evans</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. Sam'l. Wayt of N.C.</p>
          <p>Minutes of previous meetings read and approved.</p>
          <p>The report of the president was read and received.</p>
          <aside>Trustees Elected. S.G. Mason vis Eli Ball resign<sup>d</sup>.</aside>
          <p>
            Resignation of Eli Ball as Trustee was presented and accepted, and S.G.
            Mason was elected to fill the vacancy occasioned by the resignation of
            Eli Ball.
          </p>
          <aside>W. Goddin vice JB Jeter removed<br /><span className='pencil'>correct</span></aside>
          <p>
            The seat of J.B. Jeter trustee was declared vacated on account of non
            residence in Virginia.  Wellington Goddin was elected to fill his seat.
          </p>
          <aside>B. Grimsley, vice E. Broadus, deced.</aside>
          <p>
            B. Grimsley was elected trustee to fill the seat vacated by the death of
            Edmund Broaddus.
          </p>
          <aside>RH Bagby, vice W. Southerwood, de<sup>d</sup></aside>
          <p>
            R.H. Bagby was elected Trustee to fill the seat vacated by the death of
            Wm. Southwood.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={93} />
          <aside>Commencement of College at night</aside>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the next commencement of the College be
            held at night.
          </p>
          <aside className='pencil'>degree A.M.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the degree of A.M. was ordered to be conferred on E.S. Dulin,
            and J. Lewis Shuck.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from the Virginia Baptist Education Society was
            presented and received and ordered to be filed, and that the
            subscription of $12,750 taken up by that society be accepted.
          </p>
          <aside>A.M. Poindexter appointed Agt.<br /><ins>See Meeting Aug. 6th. 1851</ins></aside>
          <p>
            A.M. Poindexter was unanimously appointed agent of the College, at a
            salary of $1500 per annum.
          </p>
          <p>
            The president was directed to give public notice through the
            <cite>Religious Herald</cite> of the termination of Wm. Pollard's agency for
            the College.
          </p>
          <p>B. Manly offered the following resolutions which were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Resolutions in regard to Endowment</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved,
          </p>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: "inside" }}>
            <li>That this Board feel the necessity of increasing the
              endowment of Richmond College.</li>
            <li>That in view of the suggestions made by the Va. Bap. Education
              Society at its recent sessions in reference to an enlarged endowment, a
              committee be appointed, to whom shall be referred the following subjects
              -
              <ul>
                <li>On the best plan of raising the endowment.</li>
                <li>On organization of the College.</li>
                <li>On scholarships.</li>
                <li>On removal of the College.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>That the President and Treasurer be requested to prepare a statement
              showing the amount collected from the subscriptions made for the
              endowment, the manner in which those sums have been dispersed of or
              invested, the amount now due, together with the amount which may
              probably be collected of the aforesaid subscriptions, and the whole sum
              which now constitutes the endowment fund.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Committee under the second resolution: Manly, Howell, J. Thomas, Jr.,
            Hall, A.G. Wortham, Ryland, and Taylor.
          </p>
          <p>
            C.T. Wortham and A. Snead were appointed a committee to examine the
            Treasurer's accounts.
          </p>
          <p>
            Thos. J. Evans tendered his resignation as Secretary which was accepted.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={94} />
          <aside>Murray Electd Secretary</aside>
          <p>
            Edwin Wortham was elected treasurer, and Jno. M. Murray was elected
            secretary.
          </p>
          <p>
            The president and secretary were directed to execute a bond to John H.
            Stegar conditioned to refund the principal and interest of any amount
            which he may pay under the plan proposed by the V.B.E Society for the
            enlargement of the endowment of the College to $100,000 - provided that
            the sum of $60,000 - shall not have been subscribed under the said plan
            within three years from the <time dateTime="1851-06-02">2nd day of June 1851</time>.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned to meet at the call of the president.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1851-06-21'>
          <div>
            Richmond <time dateTime="1851-06-21">June 21, 1851</time>
          </div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held in the
            Lecture room of the Second Baptist Church, in the City of Richmond <time dateTime="1851-06-21">June
              21, 1851</time>.
          </p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols">
            <div>present</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Robert Ryland</li>
              <li>James Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>Edwin Wortham</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
              <li>Wm. Sands</li>
              <li>A. Hall</li>
              <li>A. Snead</li>
              <li>B. Manly</li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>Jno. M. Murray</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li></li>
              <li>          </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Dr. Howell.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read, corrected and approved.</p>
          <aside>AM. Poindexter accepts agcy</aside>
          <p>
            The President read a communication from the Rev. A.M. Poindexter
            accepting the Agency of the College upon condition named in the
            aforesaid communication which is filed and numbered. -- The conditions
            proposed by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter being considered separately by the
            Board were unanimously agreed to, and the President was requested to
            communicate the same to him and to inform him that the Board desired him
            to enter upon his duties immediately.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={95} />
          <p>
            The committee appointed under the Second Resolution in regard to an
            enlarged endowment of the College, presented their report, which being
            read, on motion was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <aside>Com. to examine Pollard's acts</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Howell the President and Treasurer were appointed a
            committee to examine the accounts of Mr. Wm. Pollard, late Agent of the
            College, and to report to the Board.
          </p>
          <aside>Fees for Diplomas</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of James Thomas, Jr. it was ordered that Five Dollars be
            charged all Graduates upon receiving their Diplomas.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion, permission was granted Prof. Puryear to collect or borrow a
            sum of money, not exceeding $300 for the space of three years, without
            Interest, to be appropriated to the purchase of Chemical Apparatus, and
            for fitting up his lecture room. The Board to be responsible for its
            returns.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1851-07-07'>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College at the 2nd
            Baptist Church, <time dateTime="1851-07-07">July 7, 1851</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present.  Ro. Ryland, pres.  A.G. Wortham, R. Reins, A. Thomas, J.B.
            Taylor, James Thomas, Jr., A. Hall, Wm. Sands, R.B.C. Howell, A. Snead,
            T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor. T.J. Evans, appointed Secy Pro temp.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last called meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Degrees Conferred</aside>
          <p>
            On motion resolved that the degree of 'A.B.' be confered [sic] upon Wm.
            S. Bland, Morton B. Howell, Geo. Wm. Keesee, Geo. B. Taylor, and Wm. D.
            Thomas.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from Samuel Marx was laid before the Trustees in regard
            to the Chesterfield R. Road Company, whereupon Edwin Wortham was
            appointed to represent the Trustees in a meeting of the Directors of the
            Rail Road with instructions to procure the erections of permanent dams
            across the Road wherever [indecipherable, page damaged] bridges are now
            found.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={96} />
          <aside>Professor Geo. E. Dabney Elected</aside>
          <p>
            A proposition of the Faculty of the College to appoint an additional
            professor in the College upon the terms therein contained, was
            submitted, and on motion the plan was adopted and Geo. E. Dabney was
            unanimously elected Professor Latin and French.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was requested to inform Mr. Dabney of his
            appointment and the conditions of the appointment.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1851-08-05'>
          <div>
            <time dateTime="1851-08-05">August 5th, 1851</time>
          </div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            evening at 1/4 past o'clock [sic] at the Second Baptist Church. Opened
            with prayer, C. Tyree.
          </p>
          <div className="presentListThreeCols">
            <div>Present</div>
            <ul>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
              <li>James Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>B. Manly, Jr</li>
              <li>A.G. Wortham</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>Edwin Wortham</li>
              <li>Albert Snead</li>
              <li>William Sands</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter</li>
              <li>and J.M. Murray.</li>

            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>
            The President being absent, on motion Dr. Howell was elected President
            Pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>
            The report of committee appointed in June in regard to an enlarged
            endowment and a reorganization of the College was taken up and after
            mature consideration was amended and adopted as follows.
          </p>
          <aside>Report on Enlarged Endowment &c</aside>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: "inside" }}>
            <li className='first'>—That it is inexpedient at present to remove the the [sic] College,
              and that should the question be hereafter agitated, it will not be
              decided without consulting the friends and patrons throughout the state.</li>
            <li>—As no change in the present organization of the College can be made
              without an increased Endowment, and as the effort now about to be made
              to collect funds cannot be available for the ensuing sessions, we think
              that it is unnecessary at present to recommend any change.  But where
              the condition of the<PageNumber num={97} />
              finances of the College shall justify it, we think the whole system of
              management should be carefully reviewed, and a better organization
              adopted.</li>
            <li>We have not been able to procure accurate information on the subject
              of Scholarships, but we think that unless funds cannot otherwise be
              collected, it is unwise to adopt the Scholarship plan.  It might at
              first, by reducing education below its real cost, give an impulse to our
              operations, but in the end would embarrass the institution.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            On motion of A. Thomas, a committee consisting of Dr. Howell, A.M.
            Poindexter and B. Manly Jr. was appointed to draft a plan for the
            raising of the proposed Endowment and to report to an adjourned meeting
            to be held in this room on Wednesday afternoon at 5 o'clock.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">R.B.C. Howell, Pres't. p. tem.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1851-08-06'>
          <div>
            Richmond <time dateTime="1851-08-06">August 6, 1851</time>
          </div>
          <p>The Trustees met this afternoon pursuant to adjournment. Present.</p>
          <p>
            R.B.C. Howell, A.M. Poindexter, B. Manly Jr., A. Thomas, James Thomas,
            Jr., J.S. Walthall, Jas. B. Taylor, A. Snead, A.G. Wortham, J.M. Murray
            &amp; T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>Opened with prayer by the Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to prepare some plan for raising the proposed Endowment of
            the College made the following report which was unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Plan for Raising Endowmt</aside>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: "inside", listStyleType: "upper-roman" }}>
            <li>That the sum of $85,000 be raised in pledges and donations of not
              less than $100 each.</li>
            <li>That bonds be taken for such pledges, payable in three equal annual
              instalments, the first instalment to be made payable when the amount of
              $60,000 shall have been secured in sums of not less than $100 each and
              notice thereof signed by the President and Secretary<PageNumber num={98} />
              of the Board of Trustees of the College, shall have been published in
              two news-papers published in the city of Richmond, Va., and the whole
              amount said bonds to bear interest from the same date, with the proviso,
              that the aforesaid sum of $60,000 shall have been secured and notice
              thereof duly given, by or on the 1st day of June 1855.</li>
            <li>That whereas some of the contributors may prefer to pay their
              contributions at one payment, and before the completion of the $60,000
              subscription the agents and the Treasurer of the Board of Trustees, or
              either of them, be authorized and empowered to receive such payments,
              and to give refunding bonds on behalf of the Board of Trustees, to
              refund the money thus received provided the condition relating to
              securing $60,000 shall fail of being fulfilled, and provided also that
              application, for refunding of the said money, shall be made within one
              year from and after the first day of June 1855.</li>
            <li>That pledges and donations of amounts less than $100 each also be
              solicited to be paid unconditionally, and to be appropriated to the
              general purposes of the College or to the Endowment fund at the
              discretion of the Board of Trustees.</li>
            <li>That such subscriptions or other obligations now belonging to the
              College, given for endowment or general purposes as are to be collected,
              be placed in the hands of the General Agent, and that he be invested
              with a discretionary power as to their collection or transfer to the
              present Endowment plan.</li>
            <li>That whereas several times the Board has taken action regarding
              plans of Endowment and Scholarships, all such plans be rescinded, except
              so far as any right may have already accrued under their opperation
              [sic] to the College <PageNumber num={99} />
              or the contributors to the College respectively.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            On motion of A.M. Poindexter it was resolved that the Board of Trustees
            will faithfully appropriate the principal of all contributions to the
            Endowment to that purpose forever saving only so much thereof as may be
            necessarily expended in obtaining and collecting the same.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Secretary was directed to have the above plan and
            accompaning [sic] resolution published in the
            <cite>Religious Herald</cite>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary was instructed to correct the minuets [sic] of the last
            annual meeting of the Board, which relates to the appointment of A.M.
            Poindexter Agent, by inserting the word General before Agent, so as to
            read General Agent.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board decided that Mr. E.T. Finch be requested for the
            present to accompany the General Agent and be under his control.
          </p>
          <p>After which on motion the Board adjourned</p>
          <p>John M. Murray, Secy. </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">R.B.C. Howell, Pres't. p. tem.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={100} />
        <section id='meeting-1851-12-02'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1851-12-02">December 2nd, 1851</time></div>
          <p>At a regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church. Present:</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols">
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</li>
              <li>J.B. Taylor,</li>
              <li>A. Thomas,</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter,</li>
              <li>Thos. J. Evans,</li>
              <li>Jos. S. Walthall,</li>
              <li>E. Kingsford,</li>
              <li>B. Manly,</li>
              <li>A.G. Wortham,</li>
              <li>W. Goddin</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>T.J. Evans appointed Secy. pro tem. Opened with prayer by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter. The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The report of the President was read. So much of the report as relates to the leaving of Students was referred to a committee of Manly, Kingsford, Howell and Poindexter.</p>
          <p>On motion, resolved that the hire of the servant mentioned in the president's report, be paid out of the nett [sic] profits of the boarding departments for the current year, if sufficient, if not then the hire to be paid by the professors as mentioned in the president's report.</p>
          <p>On motion, Resolved, That we decline to sell the piece of ground mentioned in the president's report.</p>
          <p>On motion, Trustees Evans, Goddin &amp; E. Wortham were appointed to examine the accounts of the president R. Ryland for the last two years up to the 15th of July 1851.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the report of the president as relates to his residing on the College premises was referred to Kingsford, Manly &amp; A.G. Wortham with instructions to report at the next meeting of the trustees.</p>
          <aside>Resignation of E.T. Finch as Agent</aside>
          <p>The resignation of Mr. Finch as agent was accepted and the Treasurer was directed to pay him for the time of service as agent of the College, and the President was directed to communicate the acceptance of his resignation to Mr. Finch.</p>
          <p>Resolution by Mr. Poindexter was laid on the table -- and then the board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans, Secy. pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={101} />
        <section id="meeting-1852-03-02">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1852-03-02">March 2nd, 1852</time></div>
          <p>At a regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li> Ro. Ryland, Prest.</li>
              <li> W. Goddin</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
              <li>C.T. Wortham</li>
              <li>Edward Kingsford</li>
              <li>E. Wortham</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter</li>
              <li>Dr. A.G. Wortham</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>James Sizer</li>
              <li>James B. Taylor</li>
              <li>Jno. M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Opened with prayer by Rev. E. Kingsford.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President then read his quarterly report, which was received.</p>
          <aside>Provision in regard to students leaving before end of Sessions.</aside>
          <p>The committee to whom was referred so much of the President's report as relates to the leaving of the Students before the close of the sessions, not being prepared to report, on motion of A. Thomas, the subject was taken up and considered and the President was instructed to return to Messrs. Shipp, Dorsett &amp; Bolling the whole amount of money paid in by them for board and tuition, and the President was likewise instructed to have an article inserted in the Catalogues hereafter published, that the board will not refund moneys advanced by Students except for good reasons approved by the Trustees.</p>
          <p>The Committee appointed to examine the President's Account for the last two years, submitted the accompaning [sic] report which was received and the Committee discharged.</p>
          <p>Copy of the Report.</p>
          <aside>Presidents Account for the last 2 years.</aside>
          <p>&quot;The Committee to examine the accounts of Rev. Ro. Ryland, president of Richmond College, report that the duty has been discharged, and we find that he has paid out for the College for the year commencing October 1st, 1849, and ending September 30, 1850 $6,442.21</p>
          <PageNumber num={102} />
          <p>For the year commencing Oct. 1st 1850 and ending September 30th, 1851 <u>6,857.51</u></p>
          <p>Total amount of the payments by him for the 2 yrs $13,299.72</p>
          <p>We find he received for the College in the above mentioned years from Octo. 1849 to Octo. 1850 6,208.59</p>
          <p>For the year from October 1850 to Septr 1851 <u>6,684.22</u></p>
          <p>Total amt of receipts by him for two years <u>12,892.81</u></p>
          <p>1851 Octo 1st Balance due from Richmond College to Ro. Ryland <u>$406.91</u></p>
          <p>The payments by him are all supported by propper [sic] vouchers except as to the sum of 49.97 for the year 1849 &amp; 50 and the sum of $356.19 for the year 1850 &amp; 51. In explanation of this it is to be said that there was no Steward at the College from about the day of ___18 to the 1st day of October 1851, and that most of the payments, for which there are no vouchers, were for marketing and so forth, for which receipts are not usually taken.</p>
          <p>We further report that Ro. Ryland has collected the sum of $519.50 upon accounts due to the College prior to the year 1849, the time to which his accounts were last settled, and that he has credited the said $519.50 on the bond of the College executed to him for the sum of $2,649.08 the amount found due him on the last settlement. The above balance of $406.91 will probably be reduced by the sum of $250 yet to be collected from students; leaving the ultimate deficiency about $156.91.</p>
          <p>Respectfully submitted</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans</div>
            <div className="signature">W. Goddin</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1852-02-04">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1852-02-04">4th Febry 1852</time></div>
          <p>The committee to whom was referred so much of the president's report as regards his residing on the premises, and giving up the boarding department, submitted a report averse to any change being made at present. The report was received and the committee discharged.</p>
          <p>The following preamble and resolution offered by Rev. A.M. Poindexter at the last meeting and <PageNumber num={103} />laid upon the table were taken up and unanimously adopted.</p>
          <aside>Provision to allow J.B. Taylor Scholarships</aside>
          <p>Whereas J.B. Taylor has given his obligation for one thousand dollars to the Trustees of Rich'd. College, upon the plan now being prosecuted for the endowment of said College, and whereas the pledge on account of which said obligation was given, was first made when the said amount would have entitled him to a then existing system of Scholarships, and in consideration also of the liberality of the said obligation therefore, Resolved that the said J.B. Taylor is hereby granted the right of educating his own sons through the collegiate course of Richmond College, upon the following terms and conditions. viz.</p>
          <p>1.  Should he, the said J.B. Taylor, send a son to the College, before the said obligation shall mature, by the raising of the sixty thousand dollars, provided for therein, he shall pay the regular charges until such time, as the said obligation becomes matured and binding, by the fulfilment of conditions aforesaid, but from and after date of such maturity of said obligation the payment thereof and the interest accruing thereon shall be received as a full discharge of all tuition fees, accruing in the subsequent collegiate course of the sons of the said J.B. Taylor at Richmond College.</p>
          <p>On motion resolved that the President be authorized to pay the portion of Prof. Dabney's Salary for which the Trustees are responsible, and to hold the receipt of Prof. Dabney as his Claim upon the Trustees.</p>
          <aside>Alterations in Regulations allowed</aside>
          <p>On motion the faculty were authorized to make such alterations in the rules and regulations of the Institution as were suggested by the President in his report.</p>
          <p>On motion it was resolved that a bond be executed to the President for the balance due him, as shown by the report of the Auditing Committee. And then the board adjourned.</p>
          <PageNumber num={104} />
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secy. pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1852-06-10">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1852-06-10">June 10th, 1852</time></div>
          <p>In consequence of the absence of many of the Trustees the regular annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was postponed till this afternoon. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</li>
              <li>James Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>J.B. Taylor</li>
              <li>B. Manly, Jr.</li>
              <li>C. T. Wortham</li>
              <li>J.C. Spotts</li>
              <li>Dr. A.G. Wortham</li>
              <li>A.J. Crane</li>
              <li>Dr. A. Snead</li>
              <li>E. Wortham</li>
              <li>John M. Murray</li>
              <li>Jos. S. Walthall</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>and A.M. Poindexter</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Opened with prayer by B. Manly.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President presented his quarterly report, which was read and received.</p>
          <p>On motion, J.B. Taylor was appointed President Pro. tempo. for the purpose of signing the Bond which the board ordered to be executed in behalf of Ro. Ryland at its last meeting.</p>
          <p>The General Agent of the Board submitted a report of his operations since he commenced his labours, which was received, adopted, and ordered to be published in the <i>Religious Herald</i>.</p>
          <p>On motion a committee was appointed to examine the Treasurer's account, also the account of the General Agent for Salary and Travelling Expenses.</p>
          <p>The President appointed J.C. Spotts and J.S. Walthall to constitute the Committee.</p>
          <PageNumber num={105} />
          <aside>Treasurer To pay E.T. Finch</aside>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay Mr. E.T. Finch, late agent of the Board, One Hundred and fifty dollars, for Salary and Travelling Expenses. --Present A. Thomas.</p>
          <p>On motion the President and Secretary were appointed a committee to examine the Bonds and Pledges obtained by the General Agent, and also to report the amount of Bonds, Pledges, and Cash in the hands of the General Agent and Treasurer and report to the Board at an adjourned meeting to be held tomorrow afternoon.</p>
          <p>The General Agent was authorized to abate the Bond of Mr. Robert Temple Gwathmey by crediting the same with fifty dollars.</p>
          <p>The Board then proceeded to the Election of a Treasurer and Secretary which resulted as follows:</p>
          <ul style={{ listStyle: "none", textAlign: "center" }}>
            <li>John M. Murray, Secretary</li>
            <li>Edwin Wortham, Treasurer</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The President and Secretary were appointed a committee to have the Treasurer's Bond executed according to the Charter.</p>
          <p>On motion the following resolutions were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Location</aside>
          <p>Ist. Resolved that J.B. Taylor, James Thomas, &amp; A. Snead be a committee to make inquiry relative to removing the College from its present location into the City of Richmond.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Course of Instruction</aside>
          <p>IInd. Resolved that R. Ryland, B. Manly, Jr., &amp; R.B.C. Howell be a committee to obtain information by correspondence or otherwise, in regard to the best methods of organizing the course of instruction and the Boarding Department of a College, and that the said Committee, be empowered to purchase any Books which may be needed on the subject (such books to be deposited in the College Library) and to draw upon the Treasurer, for the amount needed for this purpose and on motion A.J. Crane and J.S. Walthall were added to the Committee.</p>
          <PageNumber num={106} />
          <p>On motion Jas. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, and B. Manly were appointed a committee to confer with the General Agent upon the propriety of appointing an additional Agent and to report to the adjourned meeting to be held tomorrow.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board then adjourned to meet tomorrow afternoon at 4 o'clock.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1852-06-11">
