        <section id="meeting-1852-07-21">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1852-07-21">July 21st, 1852</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Board held this afternoon. Present. Ro. Ryland, Pres., R.B.C. Howell, A.G. Wortham, B. Manly Jr., A.M. Poindexter, A. Snead, Wm. Sands, C.T. Wortham, Richard Reins, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <aside>Ro. Ryland appt to collect Subscription</aside>
          <p>On motion Ro. Ryland was appointed Agent to collect the Subscriptions obtained by the General Agent in the City of Richmond, whose salary to be at the rate of $1000 per annum.</p>
          <p>On motion the Clerk was ordered to inform the Rev. R.H. Bagby, Rev. S.G. Mason &amp; Rev. B. Grimsley that they had been elected Trustees of Richmond College at a former meeting of the Board.</p>
          <p style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>Adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secty.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1852-12-07">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1852-12-07">December 7, 1852</time></div>
          <p>The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was this evening;</p>
          <p style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>Present Ro. Ryland, President</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li>B. Manly, Jr.</li>
              <li>James Thomas Jr.</li>
              <li>Thomas J. Evans</li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>Jas. Sizer</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell &amp;</li>
              <li>J.M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>Prayer by Rev. J.S. Walthall</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last two meetings were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President presented his quarterly report, which was read and received.</p>
          <aside>Resolution concerning Property in Chicago</aside>
          <p>The Presented [sic] presented two communications <PageNumber num={116} />in regard to the lot of ground in Chigago [sic], belonging to College. Whereupon the following resolution was offered by James Thomas, and unanimously adopted, viz.  Resolved that the President be requested to write Messrs. Ogden, Jones, etc., the College Agents in Chicago, to inquire their opinion in regard to the probable value of the property for the next 8 or 10 years, and what will be the probable increase in value, and also to intimate to them that the Board was not desirous to sell the property if it would be advantageous to hold it longer.</p>
          <aside>W.I. Moorfield</aside>
          <p>The President likewise presented a communication from Mr. P.B. Sydnor of Halifax, Administrator of Miss Amanda Crews, informing the Board that she had bequeathed to the Trustees of Richmond College about $900 upon condition that the Board would receive under their charge, and educate in the College her half Brother, Wm. Leonard Moorfield, and he also informed the Board that the said Moorfield was in Georgia, and that it would be necessary for the Board to furnish the necessary means for the young man to be clothed and to pay his travelling expenses. Whereupon the Board made the following order.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the Trustees accept the Conditions of the <u>bequest</u>, and that the President be requested to inform the Administrator of the fact, and to instruct him to furnish an amount of money not exceeding fifty Dollars for clothing and defraying the young man's travelling expenses.</p>
          <aside>Money refunded Bidgood</aside>
          <p>On motion the following order was passed. Resolved that the Treasurer be authorized to refund to Mr. Nathaniel Bidgood, Executor of James Bidgood $25, who had given the College $100 upon condition that it should be refunded, if called for.
          </p>
          <p>A communication from Prof. Geo. E. Dabney was read, and the President was requested to confer with Mr. Dabney in regard to it.</p>
          <PageNumber num={117} />
          <aside>1100 Dollars</aside>
          <p>On motion it was ordered that ($1100) Eleven hundred Dollars, out of the Interest of the Endowment Fund, should be distributed among the Professors, to be divided in proportion to their Salaries.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
          <aside>Omitted in the above Proceedings</aside>
          <p>On motion Wellington Goddin &amp; Thomas J. Evans were appointed a committee to audit the President's account.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>
        
        <section id="meeting-1853-03-07">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-03-07">March 7th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>In consequence of the inclemency the [sic] weather, the regular quarterly meeting which should have been held, was not held till this afternoon.</p>
          <p>Present.  Ro. Ryland, President.</p>
          <p>R.B.C. Howell, B. Manly, J.S. Walthall, J.B. Taylor, Richard Reins, J.C. Spotts, T.J. Evans, William Sands, W. Goddin, A.G. Wortham &amp; J.M. Murray &amp; A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Death of Dr. Hudgins</aside>
          <p>The President presented his quarterly report which was received, in which he informed the Board of the Death of Dr. Hudgins, late Steward at the College, and requested the Board to take some action in regard to the vacancy thus occasioned, whereupon the following resolution was offered by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter and adopted.</p>
          <aside>Committee to settle his acts</aside>
          <p>Resolved that a committee consisting of R. Ryland, J.B. Taylor, B. Manly &amp; T.J. Evans, be appointed to settle the accounts of the late Steward; and to take such measures regarding the Boarding Departments as they may deem advisable; and report at an early day to the Board for its adoption or rejection.</p>
          <p>The committee to examine the accounts of the President presented their report which was ordered to be recorded in the minutes…</p>
          <PageNumber num={118} />
          <aside>Report on Ryland Accounts</aside>
          <p>The committee appointed to examine the accounts of Ro. Ryland with Richmond College, for the year 1851 &amp; 52 beg leave to report, that we have carefully discharged that duty, and find that there was a balance of $67.77 in his hands, of monies collected by him on account of board for previous sessions, which balance he has credited on a bond of the Trustees for the College for $406.91 held by him.</p>
          <p>We report further that he received on account of <u>board</u> and <u>tuition</u>, for the period commencing October 1st 1851 and ending the 30th of September 1852 $9,402.76</p>
          <p>and that he paid for the same period
            <u>9,370.99</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            Leaving a balance on his hands due College
            of                                              $     31.77
          </p>
          <p>All his payments are supported by proper vouchers except as to the sum of $511.35 made up of items for which he could not well take receipts; such as marketing, etc.</p>
          <p>We have also to report that since his accounts were last examined he has received the sum of $58.62 collected by him for board, for previous sessions, which he credited on the bond of the Trustees for $2,649.08 held by him.</p>
          <p>The Rev. Ro. Ryland holds now the bonds of the College, one dated the 18th of March 1850 with interest from the 1st of January 1850 for $2,649.08 on which are the following credits</p>
          <p>1851 Jany   1st $357.12</p>
          <p>&quot;        &quot; 22nd            21.50</p>
          <p>July    5 40.00</p>
          <p>1852 Jany   8 162.38</p>
          <p>&quot;        &quot; 13                59.82</p>
          <p>&quot;      July 2                142.30</p>
          <p>1853 Jany   1 58.62</p>
          <p>
            <u>Febry 2                400.00</u>
          </p>
          <p>$1241.74</p>
          <p>And another bond dated 10th June 1852 and carrying interest from the 1st day of October 1851 for $406.91 on which there is a credit of Jany. 16 1853 of $67.77.</p>
          <p>At the request of the Board by resolution he advanced to Prof. Geo . E. Dabney on the…</p>
          <PageNumber num={119} />
          <p>15th day of July 1852                                $392.01</p>
          <p>21st &quot;&nbsp;&quot;  Feby 1853 <u>65.32</u></p>
          <p>for which he has Professor Dabney's receipts. </p>
          <p>There is due the College from Students for the last session a sum of money, about $100, which may be regarded as collectable.</p>
          <p>Respectfully submitted</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Signed</div>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans<br/><u>W. Goddin</u></div>
          </footer>
          <p>On motion the President was ordered to credit the $67.77 in hands on the smallest bond he held against the Trustees.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer ordered to pay Dabney's Salary</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board made the following order.</p>
          <p>That the Treasurer be authorized to pay to Prof. Geo. E. Dabney, out of the <u>interest</u>of the endowment fund, the portion of his Salary for which the Board was bound.</p>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly the following resolution was adopted. Resolved that the committee on <u>location</u>of the College; appointed last June, be instructed to address a circular to the friends of the College throughout the state, asking their opinion in regard to the location of the College.</p>
          <p>On motion the Rev. J.B. Jeter was elected a Trustee of Richmond College to supply the vacancy occasioned by the death of Samuel Taylor, Esqr.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Plans for Building</aside>
          <p>On motion a committee consisting of R. Reins, W. Goddin, &amp; Jas. Thomas Jr. were appointed to select plans for the college building, and ascertain the means of raising by borrowing, the necessary amount, for building purposes.</p>
          <p>After which on motion the Board adjourned to meet at the call of the President.</p>
          <p>John M. Murray, Secretary. Ro. Ryland, Prest.</p>
          <PageNumber num={120} />
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held in the Mission Rooms at the 1st Baptist Church, March 16th, 1853. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, President</li>
              <li>B. Manly</li>
              <li>J.B. Taylor</li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
              <li>R. Reins</li>
              <li>T.J. Evans</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>J.M. Murray</li>
              <li>and</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President stated the object of the meeting was to hear the report of the committee appointed at the last Meeting in regard to the Stewardship -- thereupon the Chairman presented the report, which being considered till a late hour, on motion of A. Thomas the Board adjourned to meet on Friday evening half past 7 o'clock at the Second Baptist Church.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-03-18">
          <div><time dateTime="1852-03-18">March 18th.</time></div>
          <p>The Board met according to adjournment. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li>Ro. Ryland, Pres.</li>
              <li>B. Manly</li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>Wm. Sands</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>J.C. Spotts</li>
              <li>T.J. Evans</li>
              <li>C.T. Wortham</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>R.B.C. Howell &amp; John M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>The Rev. J.B. Jeter having qualified as Trustee appeared and took his seat.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from Rev. Jas. B. Taylor, chairman of the committee appointed to forward circulars to the friends of the College (inquiring their opinions in regard to location) requesting to be released from the duty in consequence of the difficulty of ascertaining their post offices. -- The request was rejected, and Wm. Sands and T.J. Evans were added to the committee.</p>
          <p>The report of the committee on the Stewardship was now taken up and <PageNumber num={121} />on motion the following resolutions were substituted and adopted.</p>
          <aside>Dr. Hudgins</aside>
          <p>Resolved 1st. That the Trustees of Richmond College have heard with sorrow of the death of Dr. Albert G. Hudgins, late Steward of the College, and hereby tender their heartfelt sympathy to the widow and family of the disceased [sic].</p>
          <p>2nd. That the Trustees take pleasure in expressing their firm conviction that the connection of Dr. Hudgins with the College was marked with the honesty and fidelity becoming a high minded and honourable man.</p>
          <p>3thd. That the Secretary spread these resolutions upon the Records of the College, and furnish a copy of them to Mrs. Hudgins.</p>
          <p>4th. That Mrs. Hudgins be appointed Stewardess for the remainder of the session -- on the same terms that Dr. Hudgins was appointed.</p>
          <p>On motion Richard Reins &amp; R.B.C. Howell were appointed a committee to inform Mrs. Hudgins of her appointment.</p>
          <aside>Secty ordered to have Charter Printed</aside>
          <p>On motion of T.J. Evans, the Secretary was instructed to have 250 copies of the Charter and By Laws printed for the use of the Board.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={122} />
        <section id="meeting-1853-03-21">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-03-21">March 21, 1853</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>Ro. Ryland, President</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell </li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>B. Manly, Jr.</li>
              <li>R. Reins</li>
              <li>Jas. Sizer</li>
              <li>A. Snead</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>T.J. Evans &amp; J.M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <aside>&#10003;<br/>Dr. Hudgins declines</aside>
          <p>A communication was received from J.C. Spotts informing the Board that Mrs. Hudgins would not remain at the College, and that she desired a committee should be appointed to settle the accounts of the late Steward.</p>
          <aside>Auditing his Accounts</aside>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly, a committee was appointed to audit the accounts of Dr. Hudgins and take an inventory of the Stock in hand. The President appointed W. Goddin, T.J. Evans and Jas. C. Spotts the committee.</p>
          <p>On motion a committee, consisting of R. Reins and J.S. Walthall, was appointed to look out and recommend a suitable steward and to report to a called meeting of the Board.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned to meet at the call of the President.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-03-23">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-03-23">March 23, 1853</time></div>
          <p>The Board met this afternoon at the call of the President. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>Ro. Ryland, President</li>
              <li>B. Manly, Jr.</li>
              <li>J.B. Jeter</li>
              <li>W. Goddin</li>
              <li>Jas. C. Spotts</li>
              <li>J.S. Walthall</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>A. Snead</li>
              <li>Edwin Wortham</li>
              <li>R. Reins</li>
              <li>Wm. Sands</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>A.J. Crane &amp; J.M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <aside>Prof. Turner Steward</aside>
          <p>The committee appointed in regard to the Stewardship, reported that they had <PageNumber num={123} />conferred with Prof. Tuner in relation to the matter, and all circumstances being considered, they had agreed to recommend him. And then on motion of Richard Reins, Prof. Lewis Turner was appointed Steward for the remainder of the session, with permission to employ necessary assistance.</p>
          <aside>R.H. Bagby's Accounts.</aside>
          <p>An account of Rev. Richard H. Bagby for services rendered as Agent was presented, and on motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay the same.</p>
          <aside>By Laws</aside>
          <p>On motion a committee, consisting of B. Manly, E. Wortham, and J.M. Murray were appointed to examine the By Laws and have them modified and arranged in order to be printed.</p>
          <p>Then the board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-06-08">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-06-08">June 8th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>The annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this afternoon. Present</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>Ro. Ryland, President</li>
              <li>J.B. Jeter</li>
              <li>J.C. Spotts</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter</li>
              <li>Thomas Hume</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li>E. Wortham</li>
              <li>Jas. Thomas </li>
              <li>R. Reins</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>B. Manly, Jr. &amp; J.M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President presented no quarterly report.</p>
          <p>The committee on the By Laws were continued. </p>
          <PageNumber num={124} />
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas, a committee consisting of J.S. Walthall &amp; J.C. Spotts were appointed to audit the Treasurer's account for the past year.</p>
          <aside>Auditing Committee</aside>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly Jr., the same were appointed an auditing committee for the next 12 months.</p>
          <aside>Bellville Property of Committee</aside>
          <p>On motion of J. Thomas, W. Goddin and A. Thomas were appointed a committee to purchase the Bellville property at a price not to exceed $20,000.</p>
          <aside>Dr. Hudgins Accounts</aside>
          <p>The committee to examine Dr. Hudgins (late Steward's) account, reported that they had discharged the duty assigned them, and they found the accounts correct and a balance due his estate of $151.91/100.</p>
          <p>On motion, Prof. Lewis Turner, Acting Steward, was requested to pay the said balance out of the funds of the Boarding Department.</p>
          <p>The Board now proceeded to election of Treasurer and Secretary for the present year, whereupon</p>
          <p>Edwin Wortham was elected Treasurer</p>
          <p>&amp; J.M. Murray Secretary.</p>
          <p>The Secretary was requested to have the Treasurer's bond executed with the same <u>Security</u>and <u>penalty</u>as last year.</p>
          <p>The General Agent of the Board now presented his annual report, which was read, accepted, and ordered to be filed among the papers of the Board.</p>
          <aside>Resolutions about Building Funds</aside>
          <p>The following Preamble &amp; resolutions were offered by B. Manly, and adopted by the Board.</p>
          <p>Whereas the proposed endowment of $100,000 is reported by the General Agent as nearly completed.</p>
          <p>1. Resolved that the Board are deeply sensible of the efficient services rendered by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter, General Agent of the College…</p>
          <PageNumber num={125} />
          <p>2. Resolved that he be requested to continue his labors, with the view of prosecuting an effort to raise $50,000 for building purposes.</p>
          <p>The General Agent presented his account for the past year, which was referred to the auditing committee.</p>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter the President was requested to continue his agency in collecting Subscriptions, on the same terms that he was appointed last June.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Sub. Agents</aside>
          <p>On motion of the same, the President and Thomas Hume, were appointed a committee to look out and recommend a suitable agent for collecting subscriptions that are due, and to obtain new ones.</p>
          <p>On motion the General Agent was requested to publish in the <i>Religious Herald</i>that Subscribers could forward the instalments [sic] which are due on the Subscriptions, by Mail to the Treasurer, at the risk of the College his receipt for the same to be valid.</p>
          <p>The committee to audit the Treasurer's account, presented their report which was accepted.</p>
          <aside>Chesterfield R. Road Stock</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board authorized the Treasurer to deduct $1000 from his Books being the Chesterfield Rail Road Stock which is worthless.</p>
          <p>On motion B. Manly &amp; J.S. Walthall were appointed a committee to consider the propriety of appointing an assistant for Prof. Dabney.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={126} />
        <section id="meeting-1853-06-29">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-06-29">June 29th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this evening,</p>
          <p>Present Ro. Ryland, President, Jas. Sizer, R.B.C. Howell, J.C. Spotts and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>A quorum not being present the board adjourned to meet to morrow evening at 6 o'clock.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-06-30">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-06-30">June 30th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>An adjourned meeting of the Trustees of the College was held this afternoon. Present.</p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols" style={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
            <ul>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>Ro. Ryland, President</li>
              <li>R.B.C. Howell</li>
              <li>Jas. Sizer</li>
              <li>B. Manly</li>
              <li>J.C. Spotts</li>
              <li>C.T. Wortham</li>
              <li>A. Thomas</li>
              <li style={{ gridColumn: "1 / span 2" }}>&amp; J.M. Murray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Howell.</p>
          <aside>Report on Agents Account</aside>
          <p>The committee to audit the General Agent's account presented their report, which was received and ordered to be spread upon the minutes of the Board. (See opposite.)</p>
          <aside>Z.J. George Graduates</aside>
          <p>The faculty of the College having recommended Z.J. George as qualified for graduation on motion it was ordered that the degree of A.B. be conferred upon him at the approaching annual commencement.</p>
          <p>A communication was read from the Students of the College expressing entire satisfaction at the manner in which Prof. Turner had discharged the duties of Steward and requesting his reappointment.</p>
          <aside>Stewards Salary</aside>
          <p>On motion of C.T. Wortham, it was ordered that the Salary of Prof. Turner for services rendered as Steward should be the same as that allowed Dr. Hudgins.</p>
          <p>(pg. 126a)</p>
          <p>
            [Insert front]  We have examined the account of A.M. Poindexter Gen'l Agent of Richmond College up to 7th June 1853 &amp; find vouchers for disbursement so far as practicable for him to secure them &amp; the additions of his acct to be correct, showing a balance in his hands of $2016.43/100.</p>
          <p>Given under our hand 9th June 1853</p>
          <p>J.S. Walthall</p>
          <p>Jas. C. Spotts</p>
          <p>auditing committee</p>
          <p>(pg. 126b)</p>
          <p>[Insert back, blank]</p>
          <PageNumber num={127} />
          <p>On motion Prof. Turner was appointed Steward for the next session, and Richard Reins and J.C. Spotts were appointed a committee to wait upon him, and ascertain upon what terms he would accept the appointment.</p>
          <p>The committee upon the Belleville property reported, that it could not be purchased for less than $30,000. The report was received and the committee continued.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed at a previous meeting, to consider the propriety of appointing an assistant teacher to Professor Dabney, reported that the request had been withdrawn, thereupon the committee was discharged.</p>
          <p>The committee on the By-Laws, presented the annexed report, which was received and adopted, and committee discharged.</p>
          <p>Report of Committee on Revision of By-Laws</p>
          <aside>Report on the By Laws</aside>
          <p>1.   We recommend that the last sentence in the clause defining the duties of the Treasurer be stricken out, commencing with the words, &quot;countersigned by the Secretary&quot; --</p>
          <p>2.   We recommend that the Article on the Meetings of the Board be so amended as to have the quarterly meetings held on the Tuesday after the first Sunday in September, December and March --</p>
          <p>3.   We propose the adoption of the following -- to succeed immediately the words -- &quot;in the City of Richmond&quot; in the article on meeting of the Board -- At each annual meeting the Records of the preceeding [sic] year shall be read, an auditing committee, consisting of two members, shall be appointed, and a ful [sic] report of the condition of the College shall be presented by the Faculty.</p>
          <p>B. Manly, Jr.</p>
          <p>J.M. Murray</p>
          <p>Committee</p>
          <p>The committee appointed to select a suitable individual to collect subscriptions now due and to <PageNumber num={128} />obtain new ones, reported verbally in favor of Josiah Ryland. After which, on motion the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-08-06">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-08-06">Augist 6th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees was held this morning at the house of Jas. Thomas, Jr.</p>
          <p>Present Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, A.M. Poindexter, B. Manly Jr., Jas. Thomas Jr., James Sizer, Edwin Wortham, R.B.C. Howell, R. Reins, A. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>Rev. A.M. Poindexter offered the following resolution which on motion was adopted.</p>
          <aside>S.A. Creath Appointed Collector</aside>
          <p>Resolved, that the President of the Board be requested to secure the Services of the Rev. S.A. Creath as agent for the collection of bonds due the College, to obtain other funds at a Salary not exceeding $350 per annum, the Board paying all his travelling expenses, or of $400, and he paying his own expenses.</p>
          <p>On motion Josiah Ryland was appointed Agent to collect the Bonds due the College during his vacation at a Salary of 400$ per anm.</p>
          <aside>Poindexters Resolutions Building</aside>
          <p>The following preamble and Resolutions were offered by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter and adopted.</p>
          <p>Where as [sic] the interests of the College demand that additional buildings be erected as soon as practicable and whereas to postpone building until a sufficient amount of funds shall have been collected for the specific object would cause injurious delay, Therefore</p>
          <p>Resolved 1st.  That the Treasurer be and is hereby authorized and instructed to negotiate <u>a loan of not exceeding fifteen thousand dollars</u>to be appropriated to building.</p>
          <p>Resolved 2nd. That the committee to procure <PageNumber num={129} />a plan of building be instructed to secure a plan so arranged, that it can be executed at different periods without injury to the ultimate appearance, the Expense of erecting the whole to be not <u>less than thirty nor more than forty five thousand dollars</u>.</p>
          <p>3thd. [sic] That the interest of the endowment now in hand and what may be hereafter collected, be and the same is hereby subjected to the following appropriations.</p>
          <aside>Professors Salaries</aside>
          <p>The Sum of <u>Sixteen hundred dollars</u>annually to the Salaries of the Faculty.</p>
          <p>All the remainder after providing for the debt now due by the Board and contingencies, to the liquidation of the loan contracted for building.</p>
          <p>This arrangement to continue till the condition of the building fund, or the liquidation of all debts which may be contracted for building shall justify a change.</p>
          <aside>Dabneys Salary</aside>
          <p>Resolved, the Salary of Prof. Dabney be and is hereby placed upon the same basis with those of the other Professors, <u>the Sixteen hundred dollars</u>designated above, being directed between all the Professors according to the practice now established, and the Board assuming no other responsibility to him or them.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr., the committee on the Bellville property was instructed to ascertain from Mr. Marx upon what terms he would be willing to sell from 5 to 8 acres of the said property -- and to make the purchase if it could be done upon [reasonable] terms.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={130} />
        <section id="meeting-1853-10-15">
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the house of Jas. Thomas Jr. --</p>
          <p><time dateTime="1853-10-15">October 15, 1853</time> -- Present Ro. Ryland, President, A.M. Poindexter, R.B.C. Howell, S. Walthall, J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, A.J. Crane, B. Manly Jr., A. Snead, A.G. Wortham and Jno. M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <aside>Mr Mayo's Proposition <br/>See File.</aside>
          <p>The President laid before the Board, a communication from Mr. Edward Mayo stating upon what terms he would dispose of such portion of the Bellville property as might be desired by the Board, after which</p>
          <p>The following resolution was offered by the Rev. J.B. Jeter, and after considerable discussion was laid upon the table. Viz - Resolved that the Trustees decline the proposition of Mr. Mayo.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was also offered by the Rev. J.B. Jeter and adopted by the Board.</p>
          <aside>Ro. Ryland and B Manly added to Building Committee</aside>
          <p>Resolved that the President, &amp; B. Manly, be added to the building committee for the purpose of consulting the Architect Mr. Teft [sic] [T.A. Tefft, Esq.], on the style of the College buildings and all other questions pertaining to their construction.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-12-06">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-12-06">December 6th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this evening at the Second Baptist Church.</p>
          <p>Present Robert Ryland, President, Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Thomas, R.B.C. Howell, J.S. Walthall, R. Reins, W. Goddin, James Sizer, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. J.S. Walthall</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and adopted.</p>
          <p>Communications from the Faculty &amp; Steward together with the Presidents Quarterly report were read and laid upon the table.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was instructed to invest the Moorfield Fund, as he invests other funds <PageNumber num={131} />and also to open a separate account with Mr. L. Moorfield charging him with such funds as he may draw out from time to time, to pay such bills as are certified to by the President -- which shall be a sufficient voucher for the Treasurer.</p>
          <p>On motion Wellington Goddin and J.S. Walthall were appointed a committee to audit the Steward's accounts.</p>
          <p>On motion the communication of the Faculty was laid upon the table for action, at the next meeting.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay Mr. H.K. Ellyson's bill of 7.85/100 Dollars for Printing Charter &amp; By-Laws.</p>
          <p>On motion it was resolved that when the Board should adjourn, it would adjourn to meet on Saturday afternoon at 3 o'clock, and that special notice be given to all the Trustees in the City who are absent from this meeting.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Scty.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1853-12-10">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1853-12-10">December 10th, 1853</time></div>
          <p>An adjourned meeting of Richmond College was held this afternoon at 4 o'clock. Present Ro. Ryland, President, Wm. Sands, Arch'd. Thomas, J.B. Jeter, Thos. J. Evans, Ed. Wortham, Rich'd. Reins, A.G. Wortham, R.B.C. Howell, Jas. Thomas Jr., B. Manly Jr. &amp; J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>In the absence of the Rec. Secy. J.S. Walthall was appointed Secretary pro tem. Last minutes approved.</p>
          <p>Prayer was offered by J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <aside>M.D. Smith appointed agent to collect bonds</aside>
          <p>Mr. A. Thomas read a letter from Rev. Ro. Burton, asking the appointment of Mr. M.D. Smith, an agent of the Trustees, to collect bonds due the College in the bounds of the Concord Association. On motion Mr. Smith was appointed such an agent &amp; also authorised [sic] to obtain new subscribers, &amp; he was allowed a commission of three per cent in collections &amp; new subscriptions.</p>
          <PageNumber num={132} />
          <aside>&#10003;<br/>Josiah Ryland appointed agent</aside>
          <p>On motion Mr. Josiah Ryland was appointed to collect bonds &amp; obtain new subscriptions at a salary of five hundred dollars per annum, &amp; to commence his labors in the bound of the Portsmouth Association.</p>
          <p>The President was requested to inform Mr. J. Ryland of his appointment, &amp; Mr. A. Thomas to inform Mr. M.D. Smith of his appointment.</p>
          <p>On motion the Trustees then proceeded to consider the place of the College Edifice, as reported by the Building Committee, being the pencil sketch presented by Mr. Tefft to said committee. After considerable time spent on the motion to adopt said plan, the motion was withdrawn, &amp; then it was moved &amp; carried that the building committee be instructed to request Messrs. Neirnsee &amp; Neilson of Baltimore to furnish a pencil sketch of a Building.</p>
          <aside>&#10003;<br/>Building Committee to contract with Mr. Mayo for part of his Belville property</aside>
          <p>On motion the Building Committee was authorised &amp; instructed to contract with Mr. Mayo, the owner of the Bellville property, as follows:</p>
          <p>1st. To purchase of Mr. Mayo a portion of said property not exceeding three acres for the College.</p>
          <p>2d. To obtain from Mr. Mayo a legal guarantee that he will open Grace Street &amp; Franklin Street through his said property to the Eastern line of the College property as that line will run after the purchase of the property hereby authorised to be purchased.</p>
          <p>3d. To arrange with Mr. Mayo to have a street opened on the eastern line of the College property &amp; extending at right angles from Broad to Franklin Street, -- the College &amp; Mr. Mayo each granting half the necessary ground.</p>
          <p>On motion Thos. J. Evans was added to the <PageNumber num={133} />Building Committee for the purposes hereby contemplated.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was directed to pay the taxes on the lots in Chicago belonging to Richmond College.</p>
          <p>Also to refund to Mr. Manly one dollar the amount paid by him as postage in the Drawings forwarded by Mr. Tefft the architect.</p>
          <p>On motion the memorial of the Faculty rec'd at the last meeting &amp; then laid on the table, was taken up, &amp; then on further motion it was referred to a committee consisting of Albert Snead &amp; A.G. Wortham.</p>
          <p>On motion adjourned with benediction by the President</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.S. Walthall, Secretary <u>pro</u></div>
            <div className="signature"><u>tem</u>. Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-01-23">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-01-23">January 23d, 1854</time></div>
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this evening at 4 o'clock at the 2d. Baptist Church. Present</p>
          <p>Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, R.B.C. Howell, Arch'd Thomas, James Thomas Jr., W. Goddin, J.B. Taylor, A.G. Wortham, &amp; J.S. Walthall. Prayer by R.B.C. Howell.</p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent J.S. Walthall was appointed Secretary <u>pro tem</u>.  Last minutes approved.</p>
          <p>Mr. Reins of the Building Committee, presented the sketch furnished by Messrs. Niernsee &amp; Neilson, as requested by the Trustees 10 Decr.</p>
          <aside>Teft's Place of College Edifice adopted</aside>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter, the plan sketched by Mr. Tefft was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Comm. to apply to Legislature for appropriation</aside>
          <p>On motion of J. Thomas Jr., a committee, consisting of J.B. Jeter, J. Thomas Jr., &amp; R. Ryland, was appointed to apply to the Va. Legislature for an appropriation for the benefit of Richmond College.</p>
          <p>Adjourned with benediction by the President.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.S. Walthall, Secretary <u>pro</u></div>
            <div className="signature"><u>tem</u>. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={134} />
        <section id="meeting-1854-03-07">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-03-07">March 7th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At a regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held at the Second Baptist this evening,</p>
          <p>Present. Ro. Ryland President, B. Manly, J.B. Jeter, J.S. Walthall, A. Thomas, James Sizer, James Thomas Jr., R.B.C. Howell, Thomas J. Evans, and J. M. Murray.</p>
          <aside>T.J. Evans</aside>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by the Rev. Mr. Manly.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting having been read, were corrected and then adopted.</p>
          <p>The committee to audit the Steward's accounts presented the following report.</p>
          <aside>Report on Steward Act.</aside>
          <p>The committee appointed on the 1st of Dec. last to examine the accounts of the Boarding Department of Richmond College, presented by Prof. Lewis Turner, have performed the duty assigned them, and beg leave to present their report. We find the accounts correctly added, and the expenditures generally supported by propper [sic] vouchers, where vouchers could reasonably be expected. In a few instances such vouchers are wanting, but under such circumstances as to satisfy us that the items of disbursements are correct.</p>
          <p>Receipts $2,551.83</p>
          <p>Disbursements 2,577.13</p>
          <p>The committee appointed to consider a memorial of the Faculty presented at the last meeting, being absent was continued and the Rev. J.S. Walthall added to the same.</p>
          <aside>Josiah Ryland declines Agency</aside>
          <p>The President stated to the meeting that he had informed Mr. Josiah Ryland that he had been appointed Agent to collect Subscriptions due the College, but he had refused to accept the appointment.</p>
          <p>The committee on the Bellville property not being prepared to make a report was continued.</p>
          <aside>Report Committee to petition Legislation</aside>
          <p>The committee appointed to petition the Legislature for an appriation [sic] <PageNumber num={135} />reported the duty performed, and the proposition had failed by a tie vote in the committee to which it had been referred.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from the Faculty and referred to a committee consisting of A. Snead, A.G. Wortham and J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>On motion of Rev. J.B. Jeter, the following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Committee ap. on duties of the Faculty</aside>
          <p>Resolved that a committee of 3 members be appointed to report a system for defining more particularly the duties of the President and other members of the Faculty, and conducting the Studies and religious exercises at the College. The President appointed Rev. J.B. Jeter, B. Manly Jr., and R.B.C. Howell.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Scty.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-06-13">
          <div>Richmond, <time dateTime="1854-06-13">June 13, 1854</time></div>
          <p>As the annual meeting of Trustees of Richmond College was held at the Second Baptist Church this afternoon at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M. Present Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Taylor, E. Wortham, J.S. Walthall, T.J. Evans, J.B. Jeter, J.C. Spotts, Jas. Thomas Jr., A.M. Poindexter, R.B.C. Howell, A. Thomas, R. Reins, Thomas Hume, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor</p>
          <p>The minutes of all the meetings since the last Annual Meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Trustees J.B. Stovall &amp; L.M. Coleman Elected Trustees.</aside>
          <p>Mr. Jas. Thomas now arose and nominated Messrs. J.B. Stovall, and Lewis Minor Colman as Trustees of the College, the vote being taken they were unanimously elected.</p>
          <p>The auditing committee presented their report on the Treasurer's account, which was received and adopted, and the thanks of the <PageNumber num={136} />Board were tendered the committee for the very lucid and faithful manner in which it was drawn up, and also to the Treasurer for the faithful and satisfactory manner in which he had discharged his duties.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed at a former meeting to consider a memorial of the Faculty not being prepared to report on motion was continued, and J.S. Walthall appointed Chairman of the same.</p>
          <p>On motion of J. Thomas Jr., the Treasurer was requested to publish in the City Papers that the last Instalment [sic] on Bonds for the Endowment of Richmond College would be due the 17th of June, and also to state where the Treasurer could be found.</p>
          <aside>&#10003;<br/>Presidents Report</aside>
          <p>The President now presented his annual report, also the report of the Steward, and a communication from Prof. Puryear. All of which having been read, were laid upon the table for consideration.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter the report of the President was taken up, and in accordance with the recommendation of the Faculty the Degree of A.B. was authorized to be conferred <aside>Degrees ordered to be Conferred</aside>upon the following young men at the next commencement of Richmond College, viz., <u>A.J. Burness</u>, <u>J.O. Ferrell</u>, <u>L.J. Haley</u>, <u>Ro. McDonald</u>, <u>F.M McMullen</u>, <u>Ro. Williamsen</u>,<u>and Wm. G. Woodfin</u>.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter the funds arising from the fees paid by the Graduates for Diplomas were appropriated to the purchase of books by the President for the use of the College Library.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the report of the President as related to the small boys attending the College was referred to a committee, consisting of J.B. Taylor, A. Thomas, and A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <PageNumber num={137} />
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter all the evidences of debt held by the President against the Board, were referred to the auditing committee to have them united into one, for the purpose of issuing a new Bond.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the President's report as related to an increase of the Salaries of the Professors was entrusted to a committee, consisting of J.B. Taylor, James Thomas Jr. and A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The General Agent now presented his Annual Report together with that of the Sub. Agent Mr. Creath, which were referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter a Salary of <u>Two hundred Dollars</u>($200) per annum was allowed the Treasurer.</p>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter, the following resolutions were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Appropriation for Laboratory</aside>
          <p>Resolved that an appropriation of <u>fifty</u>dollars per session, be and is hereby made to defray the incidental expenses of the Laboratory and the Treasurer be and he is hereby authorized to pay to the order of Prof. Puryear from any unappropriated contingent funds, in his hands, the said amount from time to time as he may draw for it.</p>
          <p>Resolved that Prof. Puryear be respectfully requested to renew his efforts to collect funds for the enlargement of the Laboratory.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer &amp; Secretary</aside>
          <p>The Board now proceeded to the election of Treasurer and Secretary for the next 12 months, whereupon Edwin Wortham was reelected Treasurer, and J.M. Murray Secretary.</p>
          <p>On motion the President was appointed a committee to have the Treasurer's Bond executed.</p>
          <p>On motion the accounts of Professor Puryear for money borrowed for the use of the Laboratory upon the responsibility of the Board, was referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <PageNumber num={138} />
          <aside>Turner reappointed Steward.</aside>
          <p>On motion Prof. Turner was reappointed Steward for the next session at the Salary heretofore given him.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned to meet this day week at the usual place at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-06-20">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-06-20">June 20th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held at the Second Baptist Church, this afternoon pursuant to adjournment Present, Ro. Ryland, President.  J.B. Taylor, A.G. Wortham, J.S. Walthall, S.G. Mason, T.J. Evans, Wm. Sands, R.B.C. Howell, B. Manly Jr., Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Thomas, &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by the Rev. S.G. Mason.</p>
          <p>A communication from the President in relation to Legacies reported to have been left to the College.</p>
          <p>The committee on the Professors Salaries presented a report which after considerable discussion was recommitted to the committee.</p>
          <aside>Report on the Agents Acct.</aside>
          <p>The Auditing Committee now presented their report on the General Agent's account which was received an [sic] ordered to be filed.</p>
          <aside>President reappointed Agent.</aside>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter the President was reappointed agent to collect debts due the College upon Bonds now due the College, at a Salary the sum he heretofore received.</p>
          <aside>S.A. Creath reappointed</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas, the Rev. S.A. Create was reappointed agent for the College for 12 months from the 1st of September next at a Salary of $500 per annum and travelling expenses.</p>
          <aside>Puryears Bill.</aside>
          <p>The auditing committee also reported upon Professors [sic] Puryear's accounts for money expended for the use of the Laboratory, which was received <PageNumber num={139} />and the Treasurer ordered to pay the same.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Legacies</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas, the communication of the President in relation to legacies was referred to a committee of T.J. Evans &amp; R. Reins.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas, the Treasurer was requested to have circulars addressed to all those indebted to the College by bond, requesting them to send in their dues.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Taylor the following Resolution was unanimously adopted.</p>
          <aside>Complementary Resolutions favor of A.M. Poindexter</aside>
          <p>Resolved that in accepting the resignation of the Rev. A.M. Poindexter as General Agent of Richmond College, the Trustees hereby express their high sense of the self denial, industry and eminent success with which he has prosecuted his arduous work for the last 3 years.</p>
          <aside>Committee to Correspond with Colleges</aside>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas the following resolution was adopted. Resolved that J.S. Walthall, A.M. Poindexter, and A.G. Wortham be appointed a committee to correspond with the President and other officers of Colleges in the United States to elicit such facts as may aid this Board in permanently deciding the location of the College.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the Board adjourned to meet this day 3 weeks at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>
              
        <PageNumber num={140} />
        <section id="meeting-1854-06-28">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-06-28">June 28th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church this afternoon. Present Ro. Ryland, President, A.M. Poindexter, J.B. Jeter, J.B. Taylor, J. Thomas, J.S. Walthall, T.J. Evans, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, A. Thomas, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>P.P. Henderson degree of M.M.</aside>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr. the Trustees authorized the Faculty to confer upon Mr. Poindexter P. Henson of N.C. the Second Degree in the Arts, i.e., A.M.</p>
          <p>The President reported that the Treasurer's Bond for the present year commencing the 1st inst, had been executed with the requisite Security.</p>
          <aside>Salaries of the Professors</aside>
          <p>The committee to whom had been referred the propriety of having the Professors Salaries increased, presented an amended report which was received and unanimously adopted. (See file.)</p>
          <p>The following resolution offered by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter was adopted.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the President requested to communicate to the Faculty the action of the Board, and express the hope that it may be found satisfactory to them.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr., the board decided that when it adjourned, it would adjourn to meet on the 18th of July instead of the 4th as ordered at a former meeting.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={141} />
        <section id="meeting-1854-09-05">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-09-05">September 5th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>In consequence of so many of the Trustees being absent from the city the regular quarterly meeting was not held.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secty.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-10-16">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-10-16">October 16, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this evening at the Second Baptist Church. Present. Ro. Ryland, President, J.S. Walthall, J.B. Jeter, R.B.C. Howell, Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Snead, E. Wortham, A. Thomas, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Dr. Howell.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President laid before the Board the Annual report of of [sic] Mr. Creath the Agent of the College, which was referred to the Auditing Committee with all the accompanying papers.</p>
          <aside>Chicago Property</aside>
          <p>The President also read to the Board, a letter, which he had received from Messrs. Ogden, Jones, &amp; Co. of Chicago, stating that the property in that place, owned by the Trustees was worth about $3000.</p>
          <aside>$100 Allowed S.A. Creath</aside>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, the Board allowed Mr. Creath, the sum of $100, as compensation for a horse, which he had lost in the service of the Board.</p>
          <p>The committee upon Legacies appointed in June last, not being present, was continued.</p>
          <p>The committee to correspond with President and other officers of Colleges in regard to Location, etc., presented a synopsis of the letters which had been received, the report was received and the committee discharged, with the understanding that they <PageNumber num={142} />would prepare a condensed Analysis for preservation. </p>
          <p>After considerable discussion among the members of the Board in relation to the subject of Location &amp; Buildings, the Board, decided that when it adjourned, it would meet again on Friday Evening at 7 1/2 o'clock, at the house of James Thomas Jr., for the purpose of further considering the matter, after which the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-10-20">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-10-20">October 20th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the house of James Thomas Jr., this evening pursuant to adjournment. Present</p>
          <p>Ro. Ryland, Pres. W. Goddin, Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Thomas, J.B. Jeter, A.G. Wortham, Jas. Sizer Sen'r., Edwin Wortham, B. Manly Jr., A. Snead, T.J. Evans, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the President</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>$50 Allowed Laboratory</aside>
          <p>The President presented a communication from Prof. Puryear in which he stated he had received $50 from the Steward of the College, being a surplus of the Boarding Department, which he designed appropriating to purchase necessaries for the Laboratory, if if [sic] it met the appropriation of the Board.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board allowed the appropriation.</p>
          <p>The following communication from Sam J. Rutherford and others, was received and laid upon the Table for the present.</p>
          <PageNumber num={143} />
          <p>Copy</p>
          <aside>Communication from S.J. Rutherford &amp; Others.</aside>
          <p>We the undersigned hereby covenant, promise and agree to open Franklin Street, from Laurel Street to the Street separating the property of Wm. C. Allen from that owned by the Richmond College, of the width of sixty feet, provided all the owners of property bordering on the same, shall in writing agree to such opening within sixty days, and that the said Street when so opened, shall be dedicated to the use of the public for a street.</p>
          <p>Signed, Sam'l J. Rutherford</p>
          <p>Jno. C. Shafer</p>
          <p>Edw. Mayo.</p>
          <aside>Location of College Decided</aside>
          <p>The Rev. Dr. Jeter offered the following resolution which was adopted (6 voting in the affirmative and 3 in the negative)  Resolved that the Location of Richmond College be retained on its present site.</p>
          <p>Messrs. James Thomas Jr. &amp; W. Goddin offered their resignation of members of the Building Committee, which were received.</p>
          <aside>President added to Building Conf.</aside>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, the President was added to Building Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion of W. Goddin the communication laid upon the table, was taken up, and the Board decided to accede to proposition, and the President was authorized to sign the same in behalf of the Trustees.</p>
          <aside>Board decide to modify Building Plan</aside>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter the Building Committee was instructed to inquire into the expediency of modifying the plan of the Building made by Mr. Teft, and report to the Board.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={144} />
        <section id="meeting-1854-07-28">
          <div>Richmond, <time dateTime="1854-07-28">July 28th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held at the Second Baptist Church, this afternoon, Present Ro. Ryland, President, R.B.C. Howell, J.S. Walthall, Jas. Sizer Sen'r., A. Thomas, Richard Reins, Wm. Sands, J.B. Jeter, J.B. Taylor, A.G. Wortham, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Dr. Jeter.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Moorfield Expenses</aside>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Howell it was ordered that the whole amount to be expended for Board, Tuition, and Incidental Expenses, of Wm. Moorfield shall not exceed $250 per annum, according to a schedule exhibited by the President.</p>
          <p>A communication from the Faculty requesting the Trustees to reconsider an action taken on the 28th of June in relation to their Salaries, was read and duly considered, after they determined unanimously to adhere to their former decision.</p>
          <aside>Board Owes President 2193.24</aside>
          <p>The auditing committee having been requested at a former meeting to examine all the evidences of debt, held by Ro. Ryland against the Board in order to have them consolidated into one, now presented their report showing a balance due the President amounting to $2,193.24. The report was adopted and the Treasurer was authorized to issue a new bond accordingly.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed to correspond with the President of Colleges presented a partial report, and was then continued till the next meeting with instructions to write again to those from whom no answer had been received.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed to consider a communication from the…</p>
          <PageNumber num={145} />
          <p>…Faculty in March, now presented their report, which was adverse to taking any action in regard thereto, the report was received and the committee discharged.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned,</p>
          <p>Jno. M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1854-12-05">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-12-05">December 5th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at the Second Baptist Church this evening.</p>
          <p>Present Ro. Ryland, President, Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Snead, A.M. Poindexter, A.G. Wortham, J.B. Taylor, J.S. Walthall, B. Manly Jr., &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.S. Walthall</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President presented his quarterly report and laid upon the table for the present.</p>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas the Board adopted the following Resolution, --</p>
          <aside>Motion Concerning S.J. Rutherford and others.</aside>
          <p>Resolved that the action taken by the Board on the 16th of October, in relation to a communication from S. J. Rutherford and others be reconsidered, and then on motion of A.M. Poindexter, the whole subject was referred to a committee consisting of J.S. Walthall, W. Goddin, and R. Reins, to report to an adjourned meeting to be held this day week.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Taylor, so much of the President's report as referred to a loan of $33,000, was laid upon the table till the next meeting.</p>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas, a committee consisting of James Thomas Jr. and Jas. Sizer Sen'r. was appointed to investigate and report…</p>
          <PageNumber num={146} />
          <p>…upon the nature of all the investments made for the endowment fund of Richmond College.</p>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly, so much of the President's report as related to the Steward's account, was referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Taylor the Treasurer was instructed to pay the Salary of the President for services of 20 days as collecting Agent.</p>
          <p>Then on motion the Board adjourned to meet this day week.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={147} />
        <section id="meeting-1854-12-12">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1854-12-12">December 12th, 1854</time></div>
          <p>At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this evening at the Second Baptist Church, Present Robert Ryland, President, R. Reins, A. Snead, A.G. Wortham, A. Thomas, J.S. Walthall, James Sizer Sen., Wm. Sands, E. Wortham, B. Manly, J.B. Taylor, and John M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by William Sands.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the previous meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Report Committee on S.J. Rutherford Communication</aside>
          <p>The Committee appointed at the last meeting to consider the propriety of reconsidering the action in regard to the communication of S.J. Rutherford and others, in relation to extension of Franklin Street, reported in favor of adhering to the former decision of the Board. The report was adopted.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed to report upon the nature of the Endowment Fund, not being prepared was continued.</p>
          <p>The committee to audit the Steward's account was also continued.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was offered by R. Reins and adopted.</p>
          <aside>$33,000 to be borrowed</aside>
          <p>Resolved that the Building Committee be requested to proceed at once with the arrangements for erecting a College Edifice, and to do this, that they be authorized to borrow Thirty-three Thousand ($33,000) Dollars, to be returned in instalments [sic] not to exceed Five Thousand ($5,000) Dollars per annum.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned. </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secry.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={148} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-01-16">
          <div>Richmond, <time dateTime="1855-01-16">January 16, 1855</time></div>
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at the Second Baptist Church at 3 1/2 o'clock on the 16th of January, 1855. Present Robert Ryland, R. Reins, A.M. Poindexter, R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Jeter, B. Manly Jr., J.B. Taylor, E. Wortham, A.G. Wortham, James Thomas, A. Snead, and J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>Prayer was offered by Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The Rec. Secty. being absent, on motion J.S. Walthall was appointed Secty. pro tem.</p>
          <p>The President stated that the object of the meeting was to receive the report of the Building Committee. Mr. R. Reins, the chairman, reported that the architect, Mr. T.A. Tefft, was present with the drawings of the plan with certain modifications on the plan formerly presented, which having been explained, on motion of Mr. Reins, the following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Building Com. authorized to advertise for Building</aside>
          <p>Resolved that the Building Committee be directed to advertise at once for proposals to erect the northern wing of buildings for Richmond College, according to the plans and specifications submitted this day by T.A. Tefft, Esq., which estimates, when made, shall be submitted to the Trustees for their approval.</p>
          <p>On motion of Rev. J.B. Jeter, Dr. Albert Snead was added to the Building Committee.</p>
          <aside>Mr. Tefft paid 300</aside>
          <p>On motion of Mr. Reins, the Treasurer was directed to pay to Mr. T.A. Tefft, Three Hundred ($300) Dollars on account of drawings, etc., made by him of College Buildings.</p>
          <p>And then on motion the meeting adjourned with the benediction by the President.</p>
          <p>Signed</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.S. Walthall, Sec. pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={149} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-02-03">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-02-03">Feby 3, 1855</time></div>
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this evening at 7 1/2 o'clock, at the Second Baptist Church.</p>
          <p>Present.  R. Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, W. Goddin, James Sizer, R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Taylor, and J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor. In the absence of the Secretary, J.S. Walthall was appointed Secty. pro tem.</p>
          <aside>S.A. Creaths Report</aside>
          <p>The auditing committee presented their report upon the account of S.A. Creath, agent of the College, for the year ending 5th Sept. 1854, showing that the said agent had paid over to the Treasurer Five 53/100 Dollars more than he had received according to the showing of the Book of Receipts presented to the Committee by said Agent. The report was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Steward requests to Build Fence</aside>
          <p>On motion the Steward was authorized and requested to build a fence on the Southern line of the College property fronting on the north side of Franklin Street out of materials now on that portion of the College property which lies South of Franklin Street.</p>
          <p>The Building Committee reported the estimates placed in their hands in response to notice for proposals in the public prints issued in pursuance of the action of the Trustees at their last meeting. Present J.M. Murray.</p>
          <aside>Wm Boshner</aside>
          <p>After a protracted discussion, the recommendation contained in the report was adopted, and the Committee instructed to contract with William Bosher accordingly.</p>
          <p>On motion, adjourned with benediction by the President.</p>
          <p>Signed</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.S. Walthall, Sec. pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={150} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-02-19">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-02-19">February 19, 1855</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church this evening at 7 o'clock.  Present, Robert Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, B. Manly, W. Goddin, Richard Reins, A. Snead, R.B.C. Howell, J.S. Walthall, A.J. Crane, A.M. Poindexter, James Sizer, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. B. Manly.</p>
          <p>The Building Committee having stated that Mr. Wm. P. Bosher had declined accepting the work offered to him at the last meeting in accordance with his proposal, Thereupon Resolved that W.P. Bosher be released from his obligation.</p>
          <aside>Woodward &amp; Minter authorized to Build Col Edifice</aside>
          <p>Resolved That the Building Committee be authorized to contract with Messrs. Woodward &amp; Minter to erect the building on the terms specified in their bid i.e. for $17,359.80. Present T.J. Evans.</p>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly Jr., the following resolution was adopted:</p>
          <aside>Building Com. authorized to make alterations</aside>
          <p>Resolved, That the Building Committee be authorized to make such modifications in the plan as may seem expedient to them after consultation with the architect.</p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned with the benediction.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-04-03">
          <div>Richmond, <time dateTime="1855-04-03">April 3, 1855.</time></div>
          <p>The Quarterly meeting on the 1st Tuesday in March having failed on account of bad weather, a meeting was called for this evening at 7 1/2 o'clock.</p>
          <p>Ro. Ryland, J. Thomas, Jas. Sizer, J.S. Walthall, A.G. Wortham, and J.B. Taylor met, and not having a quorum, adjourned to meet next Tuesday evening at the same place and hour.</p>
          <p>(pg. 150a)</p>
          <p>[Insert on Richmond College Secretary's Office stationery]</p>
          <p><u>College Notes</u>:</p>
          <p>Phillip Snoddy, of Fluvanna Co. made <u>steward</u>in 1855 (July).</p>
          <p>Architect T.A. Tafft's plans for Main Edifice let to contract (Woodward &amp; Minter at $17,359.80) (Feb 1855) (Northern Wing) December (12?) 1854</p>
          <p>A College Edifice -- authorized to borrow $33,000</p>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={151} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-04-10">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-04-10">April 10, 1855</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon, according to adjournment.</p>
          <p>Present.  Robert Ryland, President, J.B. Taylor, R.B.C. Howell, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.S. Walthall, E. Wortham, A.G. Wortham, Wm. Sands, Jas. Sizer, &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Meeting was opened with pray [sic] by the Rev. Dr. Howell.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>On motion the Committee appointed at a previous meeting to report upon he nature of the Endowment Funds, was discharged as their [sic] was now no necessity for such report as was designed when appointed.</p>
          <aside>Auditing Com. Report</aside>
          <p>The Auditing Committee presented their Report on the Steward's accounts for the last year, showing a balance in favor of the Boarding Department of two hundred and sixty four 98/100 dollars ($264.98/100) at the close of the last session. The report was adopted and the committee discharged and</p>
          <aside>Steward to pay over</aside>
          <p>On motion of the Rev. Jas. B. Taylor, the Steward was requested to pay over to the Treasurer the above Sum.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay to J.S. Walthall $15 for services rendered and expenses of corresponding with the Officers of Colleges in regard to location, etc.</p>
          <p>The President's Quarterly Report was now presented, and referred to a committee consisting of J.B. Jeter, J.S. Walthall, B. Manly, J.B. Taylor and R. Ryland, to report at another meeting.  After which the Board adjourned with the Benediction.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M Murray, Secry.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={152} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-04-24">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-04-24">April 24, 1855</time></div>
          <p>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at the 2nd Baptist Church this afternoon at 4 1/2 o'clock.  Present,</p>
          <p>Robert Ryland, Pres., E. Wortham, J.B. Taylor, Jas. Thomas Jr., A.G.  Wortham, A. Snead, W. Sands, R.B.C. Howell &amp; J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent J.S. Walthall was appointed Secretary Pro. tem.</p>
          <p>The committee to whom was referred at the last meeting the President's Report to the Trustees, presented their report. The President also read a communication from Prof. B. Puryear, suggesting some changes in respect to the Academic Department as proposed by the Committee.</p>
          <p>Present J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <aside>Report on the Academic Depart.</aside>
          <p>The Committee's report as presented is as follows, The Committee to whom were refferred [sic] the various subjects embraced in the President's last quarterly report, beg leave to offer as their report the following resolutions.</p>
          <p>1.  Resolved that it is inexpedient to dispense with the Academic Department of the College, but instead of devolving its duties on the Professors, a teacher be appointed to take the entire control of that department.</p>
          <p>2.  That the Trustees guarantee to him a Salary of $750, but allow him all the proceeds of his pupils up to $1000, giving the excess of that Sum to the College Professors.</p>
          <p>3.  That the white frame building now used for a laboratory, be appropriated to the use of the Academic department.</p>
          <p>4.  That instead of enlarging the present dining hall, a change be affected…</p>
          <PageNumber num={153} />
          <p>…in the long building now occupied by Students so as to throw four of its rooms on the 1st floor into a dining hall, and to render the upper rooms suitable to the occupancy of a Steward,</p>
          <aside>Stewards Salary</aside>
          <p>5.  That a Steward be appointed at a Sallary [sic] of $300 per annum and his familys [sic] Board,</p>
          <p>6.  That $5 more be charged for Room Rent in the New Building than in the Old.</p>
          <p>7.  That the Subject of furnishing the new dormitories be referred back to the Board.</p>
          <p>The report was taken up seriatim and adopted as follows.</p>
          <p>1.  The 1st Resolution was amended by Striking the words &quot;entire Control&quot;, and inserting in lieu thereof the word &quot;charge&quot;.</p>
          <p>2.  The 2nd Resolution was recommitted to the Committee with instructions to consider the question in connection with Prof. Puryear's communication.</p>
          <p>3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5, 6.  The 3 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 were respectively adopted.</p>
          <p>7.  The 7th Resolution was recommitted to the committee.</p>
          <p>On motion the propriety of raising the Board was referred to the same Committee.</p>
          <aside>Alterations &amp; Repairs</aside>
          <p>On motion the Building Committee was instructed to have the proposed alterations made in the long Building. The Sketch of the plan and estimate (about 257$) were also referred to that committee.</p>
          <p>On motion the expediency of requiring one of the Professors to reside in the College premises, was referred to the committee on the President's report.</p>
          <p>On motion the President of the Trustees was requested to look out for a Steward and <PageNumber num={154} />report to the Board, and in this connection the President read the Summary of the duties he had drawn up at the request of the committee, setting forth the Steward's duties to be incorporated into the Contract;</p>
          <aside>Sizer appointed Auditing Com.</aside>
          <p>J.S. Walthall, of the Auditing Committee having stated that he would robably be absent at the time when the Treasurer's accounts should be examined and on motion James Sizer was added to that Committee, then on motion the Board adjourned, with the benediction of the President.</p>
          <p>(Signed)</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.S. Walthall, Sec. pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-05-01">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-05-01">May 1st, 1855</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church this afternoon, at the call of the President.</p>
          <p>Present. Rob. Ryland, President, R.B.C. Howell, B. Manly, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, A. Thomas, J.C. Spotts, J.B. Taylor, and William Sands.</p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent, W. Sands was appointed Secretary pro tem.</p>
          <p>The committee appointed at the last meeting to take into consideration the propriety of appointing an Academic Tutor, which being Amended was adopted as follows.</p>
          <p>The Committee to whom was referred the Subject of the Academic Tutor in Connection with Mr. Puryear's letter and other matters ask leave to report the following resolutions.</p>
          <PageNumber num={155} />
          <aside>Tutorship</aside>
          <p>1.  Resolved, that the tutorship established at the College shall be under the general supervision of the Faculty -- that the Tutor shall have Charge of such students -- teach such branches -- &amp; use such text books as they may direct.</p>
          <p>2.  That the Tutor shall be considered a member of the Faculty.</p>
          <aside>Professors Salaries increased</aside>
          <p>3.  That of the $2,400.00 arising from the Endowment $720 be paid to the President of the College and $420 to each of the other Professors; and that the whole amount arising from <u>tuition</u> fees, be equally divided among the several Professors and the Tutor -- provided however, that the Tutor shall not receive less than $600.</p>
          <aside>Tuition Fees $50</aside>
          <p>4.  That the Tuition fee, both in the Collegiate and Academic department be $50 payable semi annually in advance.</p>
          <p>[5.]  That the dormitories in the new Edifice be furnished by the Students at their own Expense.</p>
          <aside>President to live on Premises</aside>
          <p>[6.]  That the President of the College be requested to live on the premises, and that the dwelling house be thoroughly repaired and assigned to him for his occupancy.</p>
          <p>On motion the order of the Board passed at its last meeting requiring Students who should occupy rooms in the New Building to pay 5$ additional was rescinded.</p>
          <p>On motion the [sic] a Resolution to proceed at the Annual Meeting in June to reorganize College was laid upon the Table till next meeting.</p>
          <p>Signed</p>
          <p>W. Sands, Sec. pro tem Ro. Ryland, Prest.</p>
          <PageNumber num={156} />
          <p>A a [sic] meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church June 30, pursuant to adjournment. Present</p>
          <p>Ro. Ryland, Pres.  J.B. Jeter, A.M. Poindexter, Jas. Thomas Jr., Chas. T. Wortham, E. Wortham, Richard Reins, A. Snead, Wm. Sand [sic], J.C. Spotts, &amp; W. Goddin.</p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent W. Goddin was appointed Secretary pro. tem.</p>
          <p>Present T.J. Evans &amp; A.J. Crane.</p>
          <aside>Gas to be introduced</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Snead it was resolved that the building Committee be authorized to introduce Gas Pipes into the new building, now being erected provided the cost thereof shall not exceed $250.</p>
          <p>A communication from Thomas M. Teller in regard to the erection of Lightning rods to the New Building was laid before the Board and referred to the Building Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr., Resolved that the Building Committee be authorized to cause areas to be dug around the building, and the Same be properly drained.</p>
          <p>Present A.G. Wortham &amp; A. Thomas.</p>
          <p>A communication from Prof. B. Puryear was received, read and laid upon the table till next meeting.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned to meet Saturday July 7th at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <p>Signed</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">W. Goddin, Sec. pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-07-07">
          <p><time dateTime="1855-07-07">July 7th, 1855.</time>  R. Ryland, A. Thomas, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.C. Spotts, T.J. Evans, and R. Reins met, and not having a quorum, adjourned to meet July 11th at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={157} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-07-11">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-07-11">July 11, 1855</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon according to adjournment, present Rob. Ryland, Pres., A. Thomas, T.J. Evans, Jas. Thomas Jr., A.G. Wortham, J.B. Jeter, Edwin Wortham, Chas. T. Wortham, Wm. Sands and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting being read were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Fitting up Puryears room</aside>
          <p>A communication from Prof. Puryear which was laid upon the table at the last meeting in regard to fitting up his Lecture Room, was now taken up, and on motion A. Thomas, $500 were appropriated for the purpose of fitting up the room, and the purchase of apparatus as proposed in his communication read to the Board this afternoon.</p>
          <p>Present R. Reins, J.C. Spotts, J.B. Taylor, and A. Snead.</p>
          <aside>Lightning Rods</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Snead the Board authorized the Building Committee to have Lightning Rods put up to the College Building now being erected.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter, the Board now proceeded to elect an Academic Tutor according to a resolution adopted at a <aside>Tutor</aside>former meeting, whereupon Mr. Robert Hall was elected by ballot.</p>
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter, the Board <aside>Snoddy Steward</aside>proceeded now to elect a Steward, and a number of applications and Recommendations being read, Mr. Philip Snoddy of Fluvanna was duly elected to the office.</p>
          <p>On motion the Building Committee was instructed to sell all the Beds and <PageNumber num={158} />and furniture belonging to the Old <aside>Building</aside>excepting so much as may be necessary to furnish such of the old rooms, as shall be occupied by Students.</p>
          <aside>Secretarys Salary</aside>
          <p>On motion the Secretary was allowed a Salary of twenty five dollars per annum commencing January 1st, 1855.</p>
          <p>On motion the President was authorized to employ some one [sic] to take care of the College premises during the present vacation. Adjourned by Benediction,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={159} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-06-19" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-06-19">June 19th, 1855</time></div>
          <aside>Annual Meeting</aside>
          <p>In consequence of so many of the members of the Board being absent from the City, the regular annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was not held till this afternoon. Present, Ro. Ryland, Pres., R.B.C. Howell, Jas. B. Taylor, E. Wortham, T.J. Evans, Jas. Thomas Jr., A.G. Wortham, A. Snead, J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, A.M. Poindexter, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Legacies Continued</aside>
          <p>The Committees on Legacies and on the duties of the President not being prepared to report were continued.</p>
          <p>The Annual report of the Treasurer accompanied by that of the Auditing Committee was presented and accepted.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer Secretary</aside>
          <p>The Board now proceeded to elect a Treasurer and Secretary for the next 12 months, whereupon</p>
          <p>Edwin Wortham was elected Treasurer and John M. Murray, Secretary.</p>
          <p>On motion the President was appointed a committee to have the Treasurer's Bond properly executed for the next twelve months.</p>
          <p>The Annual Report of the President was now presented and laid upon the Table for future consideration.</p>
          <aside>Auditing Committee<br/>Jas. Sizer<br/>J.C. Spotts.</aside>
          <p>The following individuals were appointed the Auditing Committee for the next 12 months., viz.</p>
          <p>Jas. Sizer Sen'r. and Jas. C. Spotts.</p>
          <PageNumber num={160} />
          <p>On motion of Rev. A.M. Poindexter the following Resolutions were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Building Com. authorized to Draw on Treasurer</aside>
          <p>Resolved that the building committee be hereby authorized to draw on the Treasurer for such amounts as may from time to time be required to meet the payments upon the Building now in process of erection, on the College Campus, and that the Treasurer be authorized to meet such drafts, out of any funds in his hands.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the Rev. Ro. Ryland be reappointed Agent to Collect Bonds due the College, at the same Salary heretofore allowed him for that service.</p>
          <aside>Alterations &amp; Repairs</aside>
          <p>On motion of R.B.C. Howell, the Building Committee was instructed to have such alterations and repairs made in the Buildings and on the premises as they may deem necessary and present their bill to the Board.</p>
          <aside>Graduates 1855</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board ordered the Degree of A.B. to be conferred on the following young men at the College viz. P.W. Ferrell, Thomas Hume Jr. and Wm. S. Ryland Jr.</p>
          <aside>Building to Report Monies Borrowed</aside>
          <p>On motion of James Thomas Jr. the Building Committee was requested to report to the Treasurer a list of all the Sums borrowed, for Building purposes and a memorandum of all Bonds given for Said Sums.</p>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas the name of Jas. B. Turner was stricken from <PageNumber num={161} /><aside>J.B. Turner no longer Trustee<br/>J.L. Burrows Elected Trustee</aside>the list of Trustees, as he has never attended any of the meetings of the Board, and then on motion the Rev. J.L. Burrow was elected Trustee to fill the vacancy.</p>
          <p>The Resolution laid upon the Table at the last meeting, in regard to <aside>Reorganizing College</aside>reoganizing [sic] the College, was taken up and amended by striking out the the [sic] words annual meeting in June, and inserting will now proceed, and was then referred to a Committee of A.M. Poindexter, Jas. Thomas &amp; J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas the Trustees decided that when the meeting adjourn it would adjourn to meet this day week at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <p>The subject of requiring the President to reside on the College Premises, was referred to the Committee on Organization. Then on motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>
        
        <section id="meeting-1855-06-26">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-06-26">June 26, 1855</time></div>
          <p>The Trustees met this afternoon pursuant to adjournment. Present Ro. Ryland, Pres., A.M. Poindexter, E. Wortham, Daniel Witt, A.G. Wortham, J.C. Spotts, Jas. Thomas, A. Snead and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer Bond</aside>
          <p>The Committee on the Treasurer's Bond reported that the same had been properly executed, &amp; the committee discharged.</p>
          <PageNumber num={162} />
          <aside>Treasurer to pay Interest on money for Building</aside>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas the Treasurer was authorized to pay the Interest on the Bond, given for money borrowed for building purposes, whenever it became due.</p>
          <p>The Subject of Gas, being brought before the Meeting, the whole subject was referred to the Building Committee to report to a meeting of the Board to be held at the call of the President.</p>
          <aside>Reorganization Adopted</aside>
          <p>The Committee on the reorganization of the College presented their report which having been amended was adopted as follows.</p>
          <p>The Committee to whom was referred the propriety of reorganizing the College respectfully report, while they deem it important that various changes should be made, they do not think the present state of the Endowment, and of the building and fixtures of the College will justify such a reorganization, as under other circumstances they would recommend. They therefore recommend that the subject be postponed to some future period. They would however recommend the appointment of a Committee to revise the By Laws of the the [sic] College, and also a Committee to revise the Charter.</p>
          <p>Your Committee regard instruction by Lectures as of great importance, to completeness and efficiency of Collegiate training.  They are pleased to learn upon inquiry, that to some extent the Faculty have adopted this Course of Instruction, But they consider the subject of sufficient magnitude to justify the adoption by the Board of the <PageNumber num={163} />following Resolution.</p>
          <aside>Lectures Recommended</aside>
          <p>Resolved that each professor be required to incorporate, as far as may be practicable, instruction by Lectures with the Course of Recitation. (The Resolution was adopted.)</p>
          <p>Examinations whether for admission to the Several College Classes or for Graduation, should be extensive and thorough. The true interests of the pupils, and graduates and of the Institution itself demand this.</p>
          <p>The Committee in accordance therefore the [sic] recommended, the following resolution which was adopted, viz.,</p>
          <p>That written Examinations for Degrees be required by every professor, and that the Examinations, oral and written, be so extensive and thorough as to demand a high Standard of Scholarship in every Graduate.</p>
          <aside>President to live at College</aside>
          <p>On motion the Recommendation of the Committee being amended, it was Resolved that the President be requested to live on the College Premises.</p>
          <aside>Charter Revision By-Laws Committee</aside>
          <p>The following individuals were appointed a Committee to revise the Charter and by Bye Laws, in accordance with the recommendation of the Committee on reorganization. Viz. A.M. Poindexter, B. Manly Jr., A.G. Wortham &amp; Ro. Ryland.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board decided that when it adjourned, it would adjourn to meet next Saturday at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M. and that the Secretary be requested to give notice…</p>
          <PageNumber num={164} />
          <p>…of the same to all members of the Board living in Richmond.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned with the Benediction.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-07-31">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-07-31">July 31, 1855</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon, at the call of the President.  Present Robert Ryland President, J.B. Jeter, A.M. Poindexter, B. Manly, Jas. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, T.J. Evans, R.B.C. Howell, A.J. Crane, Jas. Sizer, A. Thomas, A. Snead, Richard Reins and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. B. Manly Jr.</p>
          <p>Minutes of several previous meetings being read were approved.</p>
          <aside>Election of Steward Reconsidered</aside>
          <p>Rev. B. Manly, in consequence of the Election of Steward having been made prematurely at the last, offered the following Resolution, which was adopted. Resolved that the election of Steward be reconsidered, the motion was carried.</p>
          <aside>J.L. Burrows Trustee</aside>
          <p>Rev. J.L. Burrows having qualified as a Trustee, now appeard [sic] and took his seat.</p>
          <aside>Steward<br/>C.A. Mayo</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board now proceeded to the election of a Steward, and a large number of applications and recommendations having been read, Mr. C.A. Mayo was elected having received 10 votes out of 13.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from the Board of the Education Society, requesting the <PageNumber num={165} /><aside>Return Beds</aside>Trustees to return to that Society 15 Beds and other necessary furniture, for the use of the Beneficiaries of the Society, on motion the request was granted.</p>
          <aside>Gas works ordered.</aside>
          <p>The Building Committee now presented their report in relation to the Erection of Gas Buildings at the College, the report was accepted and on motion of James Thomas Jr. the Committee <aside>Kind of Gas to be made</aside>was authorized to have the works constructed, using their own discretion as to the kind of Gas to be manufactured.</p>
          <p>On motion the Same Committee was authorized <aside>Committee to obtain information</aside> to procure all necessary information in regard to the manufacture and use of Gas, at the expense of the Board.</p>
          <p>Leave of absence was granted Dr. A.G. Wortham and R. Reins.</p>
          <p>On motion the Secretary was requested to write to Ro. Hall, informing him of his appointment as Academic Professor, and to solicit an immediate answer in regard to his accepting the Same.</p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned with the Benediction by the President.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-09-04" className="noquorum">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-09-04">September 4, 1855</time></div>
          <aside>no quorum</aside>
          <p>This being the time for the regular quarterly meeting of The Trustees, the President, J.L. Burrows, Jas. Sizer and the Secretary met, a quorum not being present on motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray,<br/>Secretary</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={166} />
        <section id="meeting-1855-12" className="noquorum">
          <aside>no quorum</aside>
          <p>The Quarterly meeting for December was not held, in consequence of their [sic] being no business of importance to demand the action of the Board.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature"><time dateTime="1855-12">December 1855 </time></div>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray,<br/>Secretary</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1855-10-20">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1855-10-20">October 20th, 1855</time></div>
          <p>A a [sic] called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this evening.</p>
          <p>Present. Ro. Ryland, President, R.B.C. Howell, B. Manly, W. Goddin, Edwin Wortham, J.B. Jeter, Jas. Sizer, A.M. Poindexter, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.L. Burrows, &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by R.B.C. Howell</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>R.A. Garretts Bond action in regard thereto.</aside>
          <p>The President read a communication from the Agent, S.A. Creath, in regard to the Bond of R.R. Garrett, deceased, whose Executor refuses to pay the amount due unless by course of law.</p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, the following Resolution was adopted. Resolved that a committee be appointed to obtain the best legal advice in regard to the practicality of collecting the Bonds due the College. The President appointed Dr. Jeter &amp; Wm. Goddin the committee.</p>
          <p>The following Resolution was offered by A.M. Poindexter and adopted, That in the event the said committee deem it expedient to do so after advice had, the proper officers of the Board, are empowered to bring suit against the executors of R.A. [sic] Garrett deceased.</p>
          <p>The President presented the Annual Statement of S.A. Creath, Agent, for the past year which was referred to the auditing committee.</p>
          <PageNumber num={167} />
          <aside>Creath Reappointed Agent</aside>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter the Rev. S.A. Creath was reappointed Agent at a salary of $600 per annum commencing 1st September 1855.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from Mr. Stuart of Randolph Macon College -- asking the Trustees to appoint a committee to confer with a committee of R.M.C. in regard to petitioning the next Legislature for an appropriation, the request was not acceded to, but on motion a committee was appointed to ask an appropriation, but to act independently. The President appointed Dr. Jeter, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.B. Stovall &amp; A.J. Crane the committee for the purpose.</p>
          <aside>Bills for Extra Work</aside>
          <p>On motion of W. Goddin, the Building Committee was authorized to examine the bills for Extra Work and repairs, and settle them at their discretion.</p>
          <aside>Bills for Dabney &amp; Chris Rooms,</aside>
          <p>Bills were presented for fitting up the Lecture Rooms of Professors Dabney &amp; Christian and the Treasurer was authorized to pay the same.</p>
          <aside>Stewards Account</aside>
          <p>On motion the auditing committee was instructed to call upon Prof. Turner, late Steward of Richmond College, for his bills for Settlement.</p>
          <p>After which on motion, the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={168} />
        <section id="meeting-1856-03-04">
          <div>Richmond, <time dateTime="1856-03-04">March 4th, 1856</time></div>
          <p>The regular Quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this evening at the Second Baptist Church. Present</p>
          <p>Robert Ryland, President. J.B. Jeter, W. Goddin, J.L. Burrows, A.G. Wortham, A. Thomas, James Thomas Jr. &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. J.L. Burrows</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Mr. Conway Robinson's opinion of the Bonds</aside>
          <p>The Committee on Bonds appointed at the last meeting reported that they had consulted Mr. Conway Robinson in regard to the same, and that he had given his opinion that they were perfectly good and collectable. The report was received and the Committee discharged.</p>
          <aside>Report of Committee to Legislature</aside>
          <p>The Committee to apply to the Legislature for an appropriation reported that they had discharged the duty and that the petition had failed. On motion the Committee was discharged.</p>
          <p>The Committee on revision of the Charter and By Laws, not being prepared to make their report was continued, as also the Committee on Legacies.</p>
          <aside>President allowed to complete Gas Work</aside>
          <p>On motion of the Rev. J.L. Burrows the President was authorized to spend a sum not exceeding ($300) three hundred dollars including the Patent Right, for the purpose of completing the Gas Works at the College.</p>
          <p>A Communication was received from the late Steward in regard to his accounts, which on motion, was referred to the Auditing Committee and the Clerk was instructed to furnish the Committee with a copy of a resolution in regard to his accounts adopted at a former meeting.</p>
          <p>On motion W. Goddin was added to the Committee with reference to the same.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from Doct. Snead resigning his seat as Trustee of the…</p>
          <PageNumber num={169} />
          <p>… College. </p>
          <p>On motion the communication was laid upon the table for the purpose of some of the Board to have an interview with him in regard thereto.</p>
          <p>A communication was laid before the meeting from the Faculty asking that they might be allowed to make certain alterations in the rules of the College.</p>
          <p>On motion the meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1856-06-17">
          <p>Second Baptist Church</p>
          <div><time dateTime="1856-06-17">June 17th, 1856</time></div>
          <p>The annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this afternoon.</p>
          <p>Present Robert Ryland, President. R.B.C. Howell, Edwin Wortham, Jas.
            Thomas, A.G. Wortham, T.J. Evans, B. Manly Jr., J.B. Taylor, J.C.
            Spotts, J.L. Burrows, A. Thomas, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by the Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The Committee on revision of the Charter and By Laws reported progress and on motion was continued.</p>
          <p>The Committee on Legacies presented a partial report and on motion was also continued.</p>
          <p>The letter of Doct. A. Snead presented at a former meeting resigning his seat as a Trustee was withdrawn.</p>
          <PageNumber num={170} />
          <p>The Auditing Committee presented their reports on the accounts of the Agent, the Treasurer, and the late Steward (Mr. Turner) all of which were received and ordered to be filed away.</p>
          <p>Present Rev. J.B. Jeter</p>
          <aside>Treasurer</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board now proceeded to ballot for a Treasurer and Secretary for the next twelve months, whereupon Edwin Wortham <aside>Secretary Elected</aside>was unanimously elected a Treasurer and John M. Murray, Secretary.</p>
          <p>On motion J.C. Spotts, W. Goddin, <aside>Auditing Committee</aside>and James Sizer Sen'r were appointed the Auditing Committee for the next twelve months.</p>
          <p>On motion of B. Manly Jr. it was ordered that Prof. B. Puryear be requested to <aside>Puryear requsted to Report Expenditures</aside>present to the Board a statement of the manner in which he expended the $500 which were appropriated last year by the Board for the purchase of apparatus and Chemicals for the Laboratory.</p>
          <p>On motion the Rev. J.L. Burrows was <aside>Burrows added to Revising Committee</aside>added to the Committee for revising Charter and By Laws, and on motion was appointed Chairman of the same.</p>
          <p>The following resolutions were presented from the Faculty, and on motion were referred <aside>Defining Duties</aside>to the Committee on Revision.</p>
          <aside>Facutly in Relation of Stewards Dept.</aside>
          <p>Resolved. That the Trustees be requested at their next meeting to define the duties and powers of the Faculty in regard to the Steward's department.</p>
          <aside>Deposite Fee for damages</aside>
          <p>That the Trustees be requested to require hereafter at the commencement of each session a deposit fee of two dollars from each student to meet damages, and appoint some person to assess and collect damages.</p>
          <aside>Students Leaving before end of Session</aside>
          <p>That they also be requested to require that any student who shall hereafter go away before the end of the session, shall pay one dollar <PageNumber num={171} />per month more than the regular price of board. </p>
          <p>Absent:  A.G. Wortham</p>
          <p>On motion the propriety of conferring <aside>Degree of A.M.</aside>the Second Degree in Course was referred to the Committee of Revision.</p>
          <p>On motion the Faculty was requested to furnish the Board with the names of such Individuals as they deemed worthy of the Second Degree in Course.</p>
          <p>On motion the action taken by the Education Society at the late meeting of the General Association in regard to applying to the next <aside>Theological Department</aside>Legislature for a change in the Charter so as to allow the establishment of a Theological Department at the College, was referred to the Committee on Revision.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized <aside>Capt Haskins Bond to be Credited</aside>to credit on the bond of Capt. Ed. Haskins $35, being the amount which the Rev. Robert Burton is under the impression he sent by Mail on account of Capt. Edward Haskins, to the Treasurer or some one [sic] else, but never reached the hands of the Treasurer.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was offered by A.M. Poindexter: --</p>
          <aside>To purchase Lot in Hollywood Cemetery</aside>
          <p>Resolved that W. Goddin and James Thomas Jr. be appointed a Committee to purchase a lot in Hollywood Cemetery as a College Burying Ground, to have the same suitably enclosed and to cause to be removed to said lot the remains of those burried [sic] in the present College Ground together with the head stones attached to their graves.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was laid on the Table:</p>
          <p>Resolved that the price of Board at the College be raised to fifteen dollars per month.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned to meet this day week at 4 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={172} />
        <section id="meeting-1856-06-24">
          <p>Second Baptist Church</p>
          <div><time dateTime="1856-06-24">June 24, 1856</time></div>
          <p>At a meeting of the Trustees held this afternoon according to adjournment. Present. Ro. Ryland president, R.B.C. Howell, James Thomas Jr., J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, J.L. Burrows &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Dr. Burrows</p>
          <p>The reading of the minutes was dispensed with at this meeting.</p>
          <p>The faculty unanimously recommended the following young Gentlemen as worthy of the Degree of A.B. which was authorized to be conferred by the Board,</p>
          <aside>Graduates</aside>
          <ul>
            <li>Wm. F. Fox of King William,</li>
            <li>H.H. Harris of Louisa,</li>
            <li>Jno. C. Long of Amherst</li>
            <li>Wm. Bernard Meredith, Richmond,</li>
            <li>Geo. W. Morris, Princes [sic] Ann.</li>
          </ul>
          <aside><u>D.D.</u><br/>Thornton Stringfellow.</aside>
          <p>On motion, the Board authorized the Title of D.D. to be conferred on the Rev. Thornton Stringfellow.</p>
          <p>The account of Prof. B. Puryear, stating how the appropriation of the $500 made for the use of the Laboratory had been expended on motion the account was referred to the auditing committee.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the auditing committee was instructed to examine the Steward's accounts at the end of the present session and the Clerk was requested to inform him of the fact, so that he may have them ready for the committee.</p>
          <p>Ordered that when the Board should adjourn it would adjourn Wednesday next at 4 1/2 o'clock.</p>
          <p>On motion the meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={173} />
        <section id="meeting-1856-07-02">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-07-02">July 2, 1856</time></div>
          <p>At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second Baptist Church this afternoon present Ro. Ryland, president. J.B. Taylor, Wm. Sands, R.B.C. Howell, Jas.C. Spotts, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.B. Jeter, B. Manly Jr., A. Thomas and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by the Rev. B. Manly Jr.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meetings were read and adopted.</p>
          <aside>Tutor Hall Resigns</aside>
          <p>The resignation of Mr. Ro. Hall, Tutor in the Academic department was presented to the Board, and accepted by them.</p>
          <p>On motion the president was instructed to advertise in the <i>Richmond Whig, Enquirer, Dispatch</i>and <i>Religious Herald</i>the vacancy in the Academic dept till the 25th day of July, when the Board would elect a Tutor to fill the vacancy.</p>
          <aside>Boarding Houses</aside>
          <p>On motion the following resolution was adopted, &quot;Resolved that a Committee of 3 be appointed to inquire into the expediency of establishing Boarding Houses at the College, as well as the propriety of erecting an additional building for that purpose, and that they submit a plan and estimate for the same at the next meeting of the Board. The president appointed B. Manly Jr., James Thomas Jr. &amp; J.B. Taylor the committee and on motion the president was added.</p>
          <aside>Gymnastic Apparatus</aside>
          <p>On motion the subject of appropriation a sum of money for the purpose of erecting Gymnastic Apparatus on the College Campus, was referred to same Committee.</p>
          <aside>Making Change in Professors</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas, a committee was appointed to consider expediency of making changes in any of the Professors, at the College, the following…</p>
          <PageNumber num={174} />
          <p>…were appointed the committee, James Thomas Jr., J.B. Jeter and R.B.C. Howell.</p>
          <p>Absent Jas. C. Spotts and James Thomas Jr.</p>
          <p>On motion it was ordered that when the meeting should adjourn, it would meet this day week at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <p>On motion the meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest</u>.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1856-07-09">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-07-09">July 9th, 1856</time></div>
          <p>The Board met this evening pursuant to adjournment. Present Ro. Ryland, president, R.B.C. Howell, J.L. Burrows, B. Manly Jr., J.B. Jeter, J.C. Spotts, James Thomas Jr., A.J. Crane, Jas. B. Taylor and J.M. Murray</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Dr. Burrows.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the previous meeting were read, amended and adopted.</p>
          <aside>Repost on Board Houses</aside>
          <p>The committee to consider the expediency of of [sic] establishing Boarding Houses at the College and of erecting an additional house for that purpose, reported that they considered it expedient to do so, and resented estimates and a plan for the house.</p>
          <p>Present A. Snead</p>
          <aside>Trustees Give up <u>Board</u> Department</aside>
          <p>On motion the Board decided to discontinue furnishing Board for the students in future.</p>
          <p>On motion the following Resolution was referred to <aside>Building Committee in Boarding Houses</aside>a committee consisting of J.B. Stovall, Jas. B. Taylor, James Thomas Jr. and Jas. C. Spotts. Wher as [sic] it is expedient to establish at the College, two <u>boarding houses</u>for the accommodation of the Students, Therefore, Resolved that arrangements be made for the…</p>
          <PageNumber num={175} />
          <p>…new building with the one already on the premises for that purpose.</p>
          <p>The committee to consider the propriety of making any change in the Professors, reported that the committee could not agree upon any report. On motion the committee was discharged.</p>
          <p>On motion Resolved that the Committee of Revision be instructed to consider the expediency of inserting in the <u>By Laws</u>, an article, stating that the Professors shall be elected during the pleasure of the Board.</p>
          <p>Absent A.J. Crane, Jas. Thomas Jr. &amp; J.C. Spotts</p>
          <p>The Committee on Revision presented the following report which was adopted, &quot;The committee to whom was referred the resion [sic] of the By Laws &amp;c beg leave to offer the following report on such <aside>$2. Desposite for Damages</aside>of those subjects as seem to require immediate action. -- Resolved that each student be required at the beginning of the session, to deposite [sic] with the Treasurer of the Faculty <u>two dollars</u>to be appropriated to the repairs done to the premises.</p>
          <aside>Forfeit damages</aside>
          <p>Resolved that students leaving for any cause before the close of the session shall forfeit the deposite [sic] for damages.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the Faculty after surveying the premises at the close of each session shall decide what proportion of the deposite [sic] shall be returned to each pupil.</p>
          <p>On motion it was decided that when the Board should adjourn, it would meet this day week.</p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jno. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={176} />
        <section id="meeting-1856-07-16">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-07-16">July 16th, 1856</time></div>
          <p>At an adjournment meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College this afternoon present, Robert Ryland, President, J.B. Taylor, J. Thomas Jr., R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, J.L. Burrows and B. Manly Jr.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor </p>
          <p>The Secretary being absent, B. Manly Jr. was requested to act as Secretary pro tem.</p>
          <aside>Report on Prof. Puryears Accts.</aside>
          <p>The Auditing Committee reported that they had examined the accounts of Prof. Puryear as to funds expended by him for Apparatus etc. and found hem correct, and a balance in his hands of $19.93 due the College.
          </p>
          <aside>Report of Committee on New Hotel</aside>
          <p>The committee on Boarding Houses reported through Rev. J.B. Taylor as follows, -- The committee to consider the question of erecting buildings for an additional boarding house beg leave to report--</p>
          <p>Estimates have been obtained for the erection of a building according to the annexed plan; the lowest of which by Mr. R.B. Woodward for $2,577.00 -- one third cash, the balance in twelve and twenty four months, interest added, is regarded by the committee as most favorable and is hereby recommended to the Trustees. It is supposed that the necessary additional improvements will not exceed $423.</p>
          <p>Making a total of                                     ... $3,000.00</p>
          <p>Interest on 1st year of Woodward's note ... 51.54</p>
          <p>
            &quot;            &quot;    2nd &quot;     &quot;
            &quot;                   &quot;    ...          103.08
          </p>
          <p>
            Add discount on notes renewed…          ...
            <u>15.00</u>
          </p>
          <p>$3,219.62</p>
          <p>To meet this expenditure the committee propose to sell the cows, furniture, etc. belonging to…</p>
          <PageNumber num={177} />
          <p>Amt Brot [sic] forward  $3219.62</p>
          <p>…the Trustees, worth say                                    $  300</p>
          <p>Rent of 80 Students rooms, 3 years                       1200</p>
          <p>Boarding houses, say $240 each 3 years
            <u>1500                                  3000.00</u>
          </p>
          <p>Balance to be provided for $  219.62</p>
          <p>Or the Trustees may order the Treasurer to pay the notes as they become due leaving the Rents to reimburse for the whole expenditure which will be fully done in three years, from October 1856.
          </p>
          <p>With the above calculation before them, the Committee do not hesitate to recommend as a wise arrangement.
          </p>
          <p>1. That from the beginning of the next session two boarding houses be opened at the College, each to be rented to a suitable person or persons, who shall be bound to furnish good board according to a general bill of fare, here after to be named.
          </p>
          <p>2. That the propositions of Mr. Woodward to build a new boarding house, be accepted, and that a building committee be appointed to superintend the erection of the building on the unenclosed lot owned by the Trustees, lying south of Franklin Street -- and that this committee be authorized to have the whole or a part of the lot enclosed, a well dug, and other necessary improvements made at a nett [sic] cost not exceeding $3000.
          </p>
          <p>3. That the dormitories be equally divided between the keepers of the boarding houses, and that arrangements be made to divide between them the responsibility of making the fires.
          </p>
          <p>4. In order to complete the whole arrangement, the committee recommend a change in the price of board as follows.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={178} />
          <p>For Board for 9 months          $100.</p>
          <p>&quot;Fuel do <u>10.</u> <u>$110</u></p>
          <p>The committee also recommend the appropriation of $50 to be applied under the direction of the President of the College, for the use of the students in their gymnastic exercises.</p>
          <p>All which is respectfully submitted.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Building New Hotel</aside>
          <p>On motion the report was adopted and Jas. B. Taylor, Jas. Thomas Jr., and J.C. Spotts were appointed a building committee to carry out the plan, and to dide [sic] all details arising out of the plan.</p>
          <p>The same committee was also authorized to advertise for 2 Boarding house keepers, and report the applications received to the Board.</p>
          <p>The President having stated that the plank floors in the furnace rooms were objectionable; the subject was referred to the same building committee with power to act.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was adopted.  Resolved that the hire of the Servant William, for the session of 1854 &amp; 5, ought to have been paid out of the proceeds of the boarding department, as the Trustees assumed the payment of his hire, only on condition that the Boarding department should not involve them in loss.</p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Burrows, Resolved that the subject of lodging the Professors in the College building, be referred to the Building Committee --</p>
          <aside>Repairs</aside>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, Resolved that <PageNumber num={179} />the repairs needed on the premises be referred to the President of the College to have them executed.</p>
          <p>The accounts of Mr. Mayo, as Steward of the College were referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion the board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <p>(Signed)</p>
            <div className="signature">B. Manly Jr.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1856-07-25">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-07-25">July 25th, 1856</time></div>
          <p>At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon. Present, Robert Ryland, President, James Thomas, R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Jeter, J.B. Taylor, A. Snead, A. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, W. Goddin, B. Manly Jr. &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>JC Long Elected Tutor.</aside>
          <p>The object of the meeting this afternoon being the election of a Tutor for the Academic Department of Richmond College and all the letters and recommendations of the different applicants having been read and considered, the board proceeded to ballot and Mr. J.C. Long, having received 6 votes out of 10 cast, was declared duly elected, and the Secretary was instructed to inform him of his appointment.</p>
          <p>The Chairman of the Building Committee having stated that Mr. Woodward, the…</p>
          <p>(p. 180)</p>
          <p>…builder of the New Hotel, had informed the committee, that in making out his estimates, he had omitted the item of painting. On motion the committee was authorized to allow the additional Charge.</p>
          <p>On motion the Building Committee was instructed to reconsider the subject of location of the new Boarding House and if they think proper, make any change.</p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, the Building Committee was authorized to rent the Boarding Houses out to Hotel Keepers.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, <u>Sec</u></div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland</u>, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={181} />
        <section id="meeting-1851-11-07">
          <div>A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held at the Second Baptist Church on <time dateTime="1851-11-07">Saturday November the 7th, 1851.</time></div>
          <p>Present R. Ryland, President, R.B.C. Howell, Wm. Sands, A. Thomas, J. Thomas Jr., A.G. Wortham, E. Wortham, J.B. Jeter, J.L. Burrows, B. Manly Jr., and Jas. B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Jas. B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>On motion, Jas. B. Taylor was appointed Secretary pro. tempore.</p>
          <p>The Building Committee charged with the duty of erecting a Hotel for the use of the College, reported through their Chairman, that it had with all the necessary outhouses been completed, the enclosure around the open lot yet to be put up.</p>
          <aside>Bill ordered to be paid</aside>
          <p>The following bills were ordered to be settled when certified to be correct by the Chair of the Building Committee, viz. --</p>
          <p>One third of Mr. R.B. Woodward's bill amount to $3,540.60 to be paid by the Treasurer for the balance, notes for One and two years; with interest added, were directed to be executed in accordance with the provisions of the Charter.</p>
          <p>The bill for digging and bricking well amounting to $28.50 was ordered to be paid by the Treasurer.</p>
          <p>The bill for pump amounting to $34 was ordered to be paid.</p>
          <p>Letters from Thos. A. Teft Architect <aside>Board Refused to pay balance to T.A. Teft - before Building Completed</aside>were read in which he requested payment of the balance for plans &amp; Specifications of College buildings, although the buildings are not yet erected, Whereupon Resolved that the Board decline any payment until in accordance with the contract, the buildings shall been [sic] completed.</p>
          <PageNumber num={182} />
          <p>A letter from the President read, whereupon resolved, that in accordance with his recommendation, the President be requested to obtain Mr. Mayo's accounts and have them laid before the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>2. Resolved that whole arrangements for securing gas at Richmond College be referred to the building committee with power to act.</p>
          <p>The regulations for renting and Keeping the Boarding houses at Richmond College as prepared by the Building were presented by Chairman (see file).</p>
          <p>On motion adjourned</p>
          <p>(Copy. Signed)</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">B. Taylor<br/>Sec. Pro tempore.</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1856-12-02" className="noquorum">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-12-02">December 2, 1856</time></div>
          <aside>No quorum</aside>
          <p>The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was not held in consequence of the inclemency of the weather.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray<br/>Secretary.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={183} />
        <section id="meeting-1856-12-12">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1856-12-12">December 12, 1856</time></div>
          <p>The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College which had been postponed on account of the weather was held this afternoon. Present R. Ryland, Prisedent [sic], R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Taylor, Edwin Wortham, W. Goddin, A. Thomas, A.G. Wortham &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The Committee to examine the accounts of Mr. C.A. Mayo, late Steward presented their report which was received.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer to pay account of Steward</aside>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay all unsettld [sic] accounts of the laste Stewards, Messrs. Turner &amp; Mayo, when the accounts shall have been certified to by the President.</p>
          <p>On motion the President was <aside>President to Collect debt due by Students</aside>requested to collect as far as possible all debts due the College by students for Board, etc., and pay the same over to the Treasurer.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to credit on the Bond of <aside>Credit to George Bell's Bond</aside>Mr. George Bell twenty dollars, being amount deducted from the Board of his son on account of ill health.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from the &quot;Mu Sigma Rho&quot; Society of the College requesting the Trustees to prepare some room for the use of the society. On motion the Building Committee was instructed was instructed [sic] to examine the premises in regard thereto and report to the Trustees.</p>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter the Building Committee was instructed <PageNumber num={184} />to inquire into the propriety of taking measures for erecting the additional College buildings.</p>
          <aside>Gas to be turned off 11 Oclock</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas the Board decided that the Gas should be turned off from the rooms of the Students at 11 o'clock every night.</p>
          <p>On motion it was ordered that the $2.00/100 paid by day Scholars should be handed over to the Treasurer, and that the sum of $25 Should be allowed to pay the hire of a servant to attend to Prof. Puryear's room and assist him in preparing for his Lectures.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the President was requested to collect the Rent from the Hotel Keepers. One half on the first of February and the Other on the first of July.</p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Howell it was ordered that a committee be appointed to examine into the discipline at the College and report to the Trustees. The Chair appointed A.M. Poindexter, J.B. Jeter, B. Manly Jr., R.B.C. Howell &amp; J.B. Taylor the Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br/>Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland,<br/><u>Prest</u>.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={185} />
        <section id="meeting-1857-06-09">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1857-06-09">June 9th, 1857</time></div>
          <p>The Annual Meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this afternoon. Present, Robert Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, Jas. Thomas Jr., Edwin Wortham, B. Manly Jr., A.G. Wortham, Jas. B. Taylor, A. Thomas &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. B. Manly.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the meetings held since the last Annual Meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Death J.C. Spotts Resolutions.</aside>
          <p>The following Resolution was offered by the Rev. J.B. Jeter and unanimously adopted.  <u>Resolved</u>, That the Trustees of Richmond College have heard with deep regret of the death of James C. Spotts, Esqr., for several years a faithful and efficient Trustee of the College, that they cherish a sincere and high respect for his pure and elevated character, as a man and a Christian; that we cordially sympathize with his bereaved and effectionate [sic] widow, and that the Secretary be requested to communicate to her a copy of the resolution.</p>
          <aside>L.R Spilman Elected Trustee</aside>
          <p>On motion of A. Thomas, Mr. L.R. Spilman, was elected a Trustee to fill the vacancy created by the death of Jas. C. Spotts Esqr.</p>
          <p>On motion Jas. B. Taylor and A. Thomas were <aside>Committee on Trustees</aside>appointed a committee to examine the list and report all vacancies and those Trustees who had forfeited their seats by continued absence from the Meetings of the Board.</p>
          <p>The President now presented his Annual Report which was read and laid upon the table to be considered…</p>
          <PageNumber num={186} />
          <p>On motion of J.B. Jeter, a standing committee, <aside>Committee on Premises</aside>consisting of three were ordered to be appointed whose duty shall have a general superintendance [sic] of the College Premises. Whereupon J.B. Taylor, A. Snead, and Edwin Wortham were appointed.</p>
          <aside>J.C. Long resigns</aside>
          <p>A communication was read from J.C. Long resigning his situation as Tutor of the Academic department.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Academic Department.</aside>
          <p>A communication was received from the Faculty of the College recommending the abolition of the Academic departments, which on motion of A.G. Wortham was referred to a committee consisting of J.B. Jeter, B. Manly Jr., James Thomas Jr., A.M. Poindexter &amp; J.L. Burrows.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the President's <aside>Moorfield's Account</aside>report as related to the accounts Wm. L. Moorfield was referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the report of the President and Faculty as related the College buildings and grounds was referred to the committee on the <u>Premises</u>.</p>
          <p>On motion of Rev. J.B. Jeter, so <aside>Committee on Rent of Hotels</aside>much of the President's report as relates to the rent due by the Hotel Keepers was referred to the same committee.</p>
          <p>A communication was received from the Agent, S.A. Creath, stating that <aside>EN. Robert's Bond.</aside>Mr. Ellett N. Roberts of Nelson, had given his obligation to the College for fifty dollars but had since died, and that his administrator refuses to pay the Bond, whereupon the Board instructed the Agent to have the Bond placed in the hands of an attorney for collection.</p>
          <p>The report of the Agent was presented and referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <PageNumber num={187} />
          <aside>Agents Salary raised to $800.</aside>
          <p>A communication was received from the Agent stating that his salary was inadequate to his support and asked that it might be increased, whereupon it was ordered that it should be raised to Eight hundred dollars ($800) per annum and travelling expenses, to take effect from this date.</p>
          <p>The Treasurer now presented his Annual Report, which was referred to the Auditing Committee.</p>
          <aside>Treasurer to Collect City Stock</aside>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was instructed to collect all the Bonds for city stock falling due during the current year, and reinvest the proceeds at his discretion.</p>
          <p>On motion so much of the Treasurer's <aside>Collection of Bonds</aside>report as related to the collection of Bonds due the College was referred to a committee consisting of the President, Treasurer, and A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The Board now proceeded <aside>Treasurer &amp; Secretary</aside>to elect a Treasurer and Secretary for the present year, whereupon Edwin Wortham was elected Treasurer and J.M. Murray Secretary.</p>
          <aside>Auditing Committee</aside>
          <p>On motion L.R. Spilman, W. Goddin and James Sizer Sen'r. were appointed the Auditing Committee for the current year.</p>
          <aside>Committee on Legacies.</aside>
          <p>On motion L.R. Spilman was added to the committee on Legacies.</p>
          <p>On motion adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={188} />
        <section id="meeting-1857-06-21">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1857-06-21">June 21, 1857</time></div>
          <p>At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon, present. Ro. Ryland, President, A.M. Poindexter, J.B. Jeter, R.B.C. Howell, J.B. Taylor, Daniel Witt, A. Thomas, Jas. Thomas, J.L. Burrows, E. Wortham, A.G. Wortham, L.R. Spilman, B. Manly Jr., &amp; J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Opened with prayer by Rev. D. Witt.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>In accordance with a recommendation from the Faculty, the Trustees ordered the degree of A.B. to be conferred upon the following you [sic] men, now students of the College, viz.,</p>
          <aside>Graduates 1857</aside>
          <p>Edward Epps, Wm. F.G. Garnett</p>
          <p>A.T. Goodwin, J.W. McCown,</p>
          <p>J.T. Wallace                                        J.M. Gregory Jr.
          </p>
          <p>&amp; Stephen E. Morgan,            and</p>
          <p>also the degree of A.M. upon the following young men former students, viz.,</p>
          <p>Morton B. Howell, A.J. Burrows, and Wm. G. Woodfin.</p>
          <p>The President reported to the Board that Mr. Lindsay one of the Hotel Keepers intended to resign his situation at the end of the present session. On motion the subject of the Hotels was referred to the committee on the Premises.</p>
          <aside>Lot in the Hollywood Cemetary</aside>
          <p>The committee to purchase a lot in the Hollywood Cemetery, reported that they had purchased a lot and ordered the remains of those students burried [sic] on the College Premises to be removed, the report was received and the committee continued to see the work completed.</p>
          <PageNumber num={189} />
          <aside>$25. Gas used by President Mr. Lindsay</aside>
          <p>The committee on the Premises reported that they had assessed the value of Gas used by the President and Mr. Lindsay for the present session at $25. each, the report of committee was adopted.</p>
          <p>Rev. J.B. Jeter Chairman of the committee on the expediency of abolishing the Academic department in the College, reported that the committee had considered the subject, but had not agreed upon a report, and therefore referred the subject back to the Trustees. -- Thereupon after some discussion, on motion of A. Thomas the Board decided that it was <u>inexpedient</u>to <u>abolish the department</u>.</p>
          <p>Absent A.G. Wortham.</p>
          <aside>Committee Academics Department</aside>
          <p>On motion a committee consisting of J.L. Burrows, B. Manly, Jas. Thomas Jr., J.B. Taylor &amp; J.B. Jeter, was appointed to take the subject into consideration and report to another meeting of the Board.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was offered by Rev. J.B. Taylor and adopted.</p>
          <p>Resolved that a committee consisting <aside>Enlarging Library</aside>of J.L. Burrows, A.M. Poindexter, and Jas. Thomas be appointed to consider and report a plan for enlarging the Library of Richmond College.</p>
          <aside>Discipline</aside>
          <p>The committee appointed on discipline made a verbal report, and was discharged.</p>
          <p>On motion of Jas. Thomas, the <aside>Room for Debating Society</aside>committee on the Premises was instructed to have a room fitted up in the small brick building at the College for the use of the Mu Sigma Rho Society Debating Society.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned to meet Wednesday 1st of July 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={190} />
        <section id="meeting-1857-07-01">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1857-07-01">July 1st, 1857</time></div>
          <p>The Trustees of Richmond College, met this afternoon, pursuant to adjournment, present, Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Taylor, J.B. Jeter, L.R. Spilman, Edwin Wortham, A.M. Poindexter, B. Manly Jr., R.B.C. Howell &amp; Jno. M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>The committee on the Academic Department presented the following report which was adopted.</p>
          <aside>Report on the Academic Department</aside>
          <p>Resolved that it is inexpedient to remove this department into the city.</p>
          <p>That while we deem it desirable to build a house for this department on the lot South Side of Franklin Street, yet in view of the funds, and the importance of erectining [sic] as soon as practicable, the South Wing of the Main College building, we recommend that for the present there be no change in the location of the school.</p>
          <p>On motion of A.M. Poindexter the <aside>Advertise for Tutor.</aside>President was authorized to advertise for an Academic Tutor, and that the 24th day of July, the Selection be made.</p>
          <p>Present James Thomas Jr.</p>
          <p>The Committee on the Premises presented a report on the price of Board &amp;c which was recommitted to the committee, to report at another meeting.</p>
          <p>The Treasurer laid before the <aside>Letter from Mr Bowden</aside>Board a letter from Mr. Bowden the Attorney of the College to prosecute the claim against the Estate of R.R. Garrett deceased, asking instructions.  On on [sic] motion the Board decided not to interfere in the matter. --</p>
          <p>The auditing committee presented their report on the Treasurer's account which was received, stating that the account was correct, a copy of which is herewith annexed.</p>
          <PageNumber num={191} />
          <aside>Treasurer to pay Bonds when due.</aside>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was instructed to pay, the Bonds of the Trustees given for money borrowed for building purposes, when the [sic] fell due when in funds.</p>
          <aside>Dr Howell resigns</aside>
          <p>Rev. R.B.C. Howell now presented his resignation of his situation as Trustee which was accepted.</p>
          <p>On motion now adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, <u>Prest</u>.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1857-06-09">
          <aside>Treasurers Report.</aside>
          <div><b><u>Treasurer's Report presented <time dateTime="1857-06-09">June 9th, 1857</time></u></b></div>
          <p>To the Trustees</p>
          <p>of Richmond College</p>
          <p>Gent.,</p>
          <p>Your Treasurer respectfully reports the condition of his accounts to be as follows.</p>
          <p>
            <u>Endowment Account</u>
          </p>
          <p>Shows a balance against him</p>
          <p>29 May 1857 of … $21,779.02</p>
          <p>
            <u>Bond Account</u>
          </p>
          <p>Shows a balance again on</p>
          <p>
            the 29 May of …<u>9,165___</u>
          </p>
          <p>Both of which amounts to $30,944.02</p>
          <p>
            <u>College Building Account</u>
          </p>
          <p>Shows a balance in his favor 29 May 1857 of … $28,642.92</p>
          <p>
            <u>Contingent Fund Account</u>
          </p>
          <p>Shows a balance in favor</p>
          <p>
            29 May 1857 of …<u>$634.87           $29,277.79</u>
          </p>
          <p>Balance due Edwin Wortham Treasurer</p>
          <p>
            on the 29 May 1857
            <u>$31,666.23</u>
          </p>
          <p>In explanation of these accounts, he would say that the Contingent Fund Account is credited by all payments of dividends on investment -- by interest paid on bonds, and…</p>
          <PageNumber num={192} />
          <p>…by any moneys received other than the collection for Endowment fund, -- thus he has received since the 29 May 1856, (when his account was last settled) for</p>
          <p>Dividends &amp; Interest investment        $4,392.23</p>
          <p>Interest on bonds -- 150.--</p>
          <p>do. Allowed by R.H. Maury &amp; Co.</p>
          <p>for deposites [sic] -- 51.17                    $4,593.40</p>
          <p>Received of Goddin &amp; Approven for nett [sic]</p>
          <p>proceeds of sales of Personal effects</p>
          <p>
            at the College
            <u>572.72</u>
          </p>
          <p>$5,169.12</p>
          <p>that he has paid out and charged to this account (Contingent Fund) all appropriations made by the Board, -- such as Professors Salaries -- payment in full to R. Ryland, expenses of Wm. L. Moorfield, interest on money ($9165) borrowed, -- indebtedness of the boarding departments all of which amounts to -- $6,865.84</p>
          <p>Bond Account shows of whom and the amounts of money borrowed for erecting College buildings -- amounting to $9165.--</p>
          <p>The interest of which has been paid to January 1857 except in the bond to Jno. Hollins for $1000 -- he has never applied for it.</p>
          <p>
            <u>College Building Account</u>
          </p>
          <p>Shows the amount paid for erecting the buildings, etc., etc.</p>
          <p>
            Amount paid 29 May 1856 …
            $25,422.79
          </p>
          <p>
            Amount paid since
            <u>3,220.13</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            <u>$28.642.92</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            <u>Endowment Fund</u>
          </p>
          <p>is for moneys received for the College Endowment</p>
          <p>
            Balance due on this account 29 May 1856
            $15,909.31
          </p>
          <p>
            Amount received since
            <u>6,544.11</u>
          </p>
          <p>$22,453.42</p>
          <p>from which deduct amount of</p>
          <p>
            Agent's Salary paid him
            <u>674.40</u>
          </p>
          <p>$21,779.02</p>
          <PageNumber num={193} />
          <p>The Investment which has not been in any way changed since last report, amounts to $72,642.-- and consist of</p>
          <p>$9,600 of bonds of the James River &amp; Kanawha Co. with the States guarrantee [sic],</p>
          <p>44,200 of Richmond City Stock,</p>
          <p>2,982 of Virginia State Stock,</p>
          <aside>Stocks</aside>
          <p>500 of Farmers Bank Stock,</p>
          <p>500 of Bond of the Town of Portsmouth,</p>
          <p>500 of Bond of Town of Petersburg with State guarrantee [sic],</p>
          <p>20 of the Fire Association Stock</p>
          <p>8,500 of the Bonds of the Town of Petersburg</p>
          <p>140 of the Stock of the Bank of Virginia</p>
          <p>600 of the Bond of the Central R.R. Co. state guarrantee [sic]</p>
          <p>3600 of the Bonds of the Corporation Lynchburg,</p>
          <p>500 of the Bond of the Ches &amp; Ohio C. Co. State guarrantee [sic]</p>
          <p>1000 of the Bond of the Lynchburg &amp; Tennessee Rail R. Co.</p>
          <p>Of the city stock $6,300 is due July 1st 1857 and $200 November 1857. I would recommend the collection of this, and reinvested in the same kind of Stock, which can be done for about 93 to 95 -- thereby making several hundred dollars.</p>
          <p>Your Treasurer also reports that he has made out a list (which is hereby submitted as apart [sic] of this report) of balances due the College by bonds and Subscriptions, the amount due is about $19,473.24. It is impossible to say how much of this amount is <u>good</u>and collectable -- a very large amount is known to be perfectly worthless, and a large amount will soon be in the same condition unless active and rigid measures are adopted for its collection. He would therefore recommend not only in regard to these but to all the debts due the College the adoption of such steps as will ensure…</p>
          <PageNumber num={194} />
          <p>…there [sic] speedy collection of them, even if resort is had to the law. -- He understands that the suit vs. R.R. Garrett's Estate has been decided in favor of the College and that the money will soon be paid over.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">(Copy) Signed</div>
            <div className="signature">Edwin Wortham Tr. R.C.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>
        
        <section id="meeting-1857-07-10">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1857-07-10">July 10, 1857</time></div>
          <p>A called Meeting of the Trustees was held this afternoon, at the Second Baptist Church. Present, Robert Ryland, President, J.L. Burrows, James Thomas Jr., Richard Reins, E. Wortham, J.B. Taylor, L.R. Spilman, and J.M. Murray.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.L. Burrows.</p>
