          <p>
            <u></u>
          </p>
          <p>July 7, 1857  We have examined the Treasurer's books and find he has paid Ro. Ryland on account of the Moorfield fund nine hundred and twenty three dollars and 61 cents and have examined Ro. Ryland's account and find he has expended for Wm. L. Moorfield exactly that sum ($923.61) -- sustained by proper vouchers.</p>
          <p>A copy signed, W. Goddin</p>
          <p>L.R. Spilman, Committee</p>
          <PageNumber num={196} />
          <p>The same committee also reported on the President's account for the Gas showing the amount expended to be $433.26 and cash received for the same to $321.54.</p>
          <p>On motion the subject of the Gas -- was referred to the President to report at the next meeting.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was authorized to pay the President the excess expended by him as reported in his statements of account.</p>
          <p>The auditing committee reported the bill for Gymnastics fixtures, which the Treasurer was authorized to pay.</p>
          <p>On motion the Treasurer was <aside>Treasurer authorized to pay Yale's bill</aside>authorized to pay Messrs. Charles Yale &amp; Co.'s bill for repairs to the Furnaces, when it shall have been audited by the committee.</p>
          <p>Prof. Puryear presented his account for Chemicals, etc. used in his department which was also referred to the auditing committee. </p>
          <p>The committee to examine the <aside>Bonds to be placed in the hands Spilman</aside>Bonds presented a report, and on motion of James Thomas Jr., the Treasurer was authorized to hand over to Mr. L.R. Spilman all the Bonds in his hands for collection, and a commission of 5 per cent was allowed him for all monies collected.</p>
          <p>The following Resolutions were offered by Rev. J.L. Burrows, and laid upon the table to a called meeting to be held this day week at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the President be authorized and requested to inform Professors Christian and Turner that their resignation as…</p>
          <PageNumber num={197} />
          <p>…professors would be acceptable to the Trustees.</p>
          <p>Resolved that the President be authorized to advertise that the Professorships of Greek and Mathematics in Richmond College will be filled on ______ the day of August 1857.</p>
          <p>The subject of the Furnaces was referred <aside>Repairs Furnaces</aside>to the committee on the premises with instructions to have them repaired.
          </p>
          <p>The committee on the Premises made <aside>Board raised to $120.</aside>the following report which was adopted as to the change in Board. They recommend a change in the price of Board from $100 to $120 for the session of nine months. --
          </p>
          <p>With reference to so much of the recommendation of the Faculty as relates to a well on the Premises they recommend that the preparation of a well and good pump be ordered by the Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>Signed, Jas. B. Taylor, Chairman</p>
          <aside>Well</aside>
          <p>On motion so much of the report of the committee as related to the Well was referred back to the committee with discretion to act.</p>
          <p>The subject of the Rent was laid upon the table till the next meeting.</p>
          <aside>Time for Elections</aside>
          <p>The President was requested to advertise that the election of two Hotel Keepers for the ensuing collegiate <aside>Hotel Keepers</aside>year would be had on the 17th inst.</p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned to meet on the 17th instant at 4 1/2 o'clock P.M.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, <u>Prest</u>.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

