        <section id="meeting-1857-12-08">
          <header>Richmond <time dateTime="1857-12-08">December 8th, 1857</time></header>
          <p>
            The regular quarterly meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was
            held  this afternoon. Meeting opened with prayer by A.M. Poindexter.
            Present
          </p>
          <p>
            Ro. Ryland, president.  A.M. Poindexter, A. Thomas, L.R. Spilman, Wm.
            Sands, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, B. Manly Jr., and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Minutes of the last meeting were received and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Chairman of the Committee on the revision of the Charter and By
            Laws <PageNumber num={206} /> made a partial report, which was recommitted, and the Committee
            enlarged by the addition of L.R. Spilman and T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President presented a petition from Prof. Puryear, asking for a
            special appropriations [sic] to the Laboratory. On motion <aside>$50 additional allowed laboratory</aside> fifty dollars
            were allowed and the Treasurer directed to pay the same.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President also presented a communication from the Faculty asking
            that the Treasurer be instructed to pay the <aside>Commitee on Tuition fees J.B. Taylor's sons</aside> <u>tuition</u>fees of the
            sons of Rev. J.B. Taylor who had been allowed by a special act of the
            Board to educate his sons free of tuition, on account of his liberal
            donation to the permanent endowment of the College. On motion the
            subject was referred to a committee, consisting of B. Manly, L.R.
            Spilman, and E. Wortham.
          </p>
          <aside>Auditing Com Report Gen Agent act year ending Sept 1857</aside>
          <p>
            The auditing committee presented the report on the Accounts of S.A.
            Creath, General Agent, for the year ending Sept 10th 1857, showing that
            he had collected since Sept 5 1857 [sic] to that date $4,393.12
          </p>
          <p>From which deduct amt paid Treas. 4,401.71</p>
          <p>
            From former balance due him                         _
            <u>193.05           $4,594.71</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            Leaving balance due
            Agent                                                        $201.64
          </p>
          <p>
            The seat in the Board of Rev. R.B.C. Howell having become vacant by
            resignation and removal from this state, on motion the <aside>L.W. Seeley Elected Trustee</aside> Rev. L.W. Seeley
            was elected to fill his place.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Rev. A.M. Poindexter informed the Board that he had received from
            <aside>Donation from Mrs Hollins</aside> Mrs. Hollins of Lynchburg, as a donation to the College, the Bond of the
            Trustees to Jno. Hollins for $1000, which she wished to be transferred
            to the permanent endowment fund of the College. On motion it was
            received, and the Treasurer <PageNumber num={207} /> was authorized and instructed to act, accordingly, and to inform Mrs.
            Hollins that it had been done as she desired.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mr. L.R. Spilman collector of the Bonds due the College asked
            instructions in regard to a suit which had been brought against a Mr.
            Johnston of Petersburg, whereupon, he was authorized to act according to
            his own discretion.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1857-12-15">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1857-12-15"> December 15th, 1857</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon. Present, Ro. Ryland. Pres.  J.B. Jeter, Wm. Sands, A.M.
            Poindexter, J.B. Taylor, James Thomas Jr., A. Thomas, C.T. Wortham, B.
            Manly Jr., L.R. Spilman, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, A. Snead and J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prayer by Rev. L.W. Seeley, who was invited to assist in the
            deliberations of this meeting, as he had not yet qualified to act as a
            Trustee, not having taken the necessary oath of office.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President called the Rev. J.B. Jeter to the Chair, when Rev. A.M.
            Poindexter stated that the meeting had been called to take some action
            in regard to an article <aside>charges preferred against Pres</aside> which appeared in &quot;<u>The South</u>&quot;,
            a newspaper published of the 12 inst, -- over the signature &quot;
            <u>Amicus Doulcias</u>&quot;. Whereupon he presented the following
            preamble and resolutions, which were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>Preamble &amp; Resolutions</p>
          <p>
            <b></b>Whereas an article was published in <u>The South</u> of the 12
            inst, over the signature &quot;<u>Amicus Doulcias</u>&quot;, charging
            that the <PageNumber num={208} /> President of Richmond College, &quot;has dared and still dares to use
            his most strenous [sic] exertions for the overthrow of Slavery -- for
            sowing the seeds of Abolitionism and implanting a spirit of Northern
            fanatacism [sic] in the minds of those intrusted [sic] to his
            care&quot;, That, &quot;with a zeal that would be truly laudable in a
            more glorious enterprise, he devotes all his time and talents to the
            accomplishment of his fiendish purposes&quot;, That &quot;there are
            young men of undoubted talents and of wisdom fit to adorn much older
            heads, who have by his villanous [sic] labors alone, become so
            thoroughly imbued with his abolition principles that they do not
            hesitate to openly avow and advocate his sentiments,&quot; and whereas
            we, as the legal guardians of the College are responsible to the Public
            for the Character of the instruction imparted by its faculty,
          </p>
          <p>
            And whereas Mr. Roger A. Pryor, the Editor of The South, having been
            called upon, has refused to give the name of the author, and assumed the
            responsibility of the charges himself, Therefore Resolved 1. That from
            our long and intimate acquaintance with President Ryland, the facts that
            he is a Virginian and a slave holder, our Knowledge of his views on the
            subject of Slavary [sic] as publickly [sic] &amp; privately expressed,
            and such investigation as the brief period which has transpired since
            the said publication has permitted us to make, we unhesitatingly declare
            our belief that the said charges are wholly false.
          </p>
          <p>
            2. That for the entire satisfaction of the Public Mind we will continue <PageNumber num={209} /> our investigation, until we have arrived at as full a Knowledge of the
            grounds of these charges as we can attain, and that when said
            investigation is ended we will, without reserve, publish the result,
          </p>
          <p>
            3. That A.M. Poindexter, Jas. Thomas, and L.R. Spilman, be and they are
            hereby appointed a committee to conduct this investigation, and to
            report as soon as a thorough investigation can be made.
          </p>
          <p>
            4. That said committee are hereby instructed, to call upon the Editor of
            The South, and request him to aid them in their labor, by furnishing
            them a statement in full, of the facts and evidence upon which he bases
            the allegations of the article aforesaid.
          </p>
          <p>
            5. That the Secretary be instructed to secure the insertion of this
            preamble and resolution in The South, Whig, and Enquirer of this city.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution offered by A.M. Poindexter was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the committee of investigation be and they are hereby
            empowered to assure Mr. R.A. Pryor, should it be necessary, that no use
            shall be made of any disclosures he may make, for legal purposes, -- The
            President resuming the Chair. On motion the Board adjourned to meet at
            the call of the President.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={210} />

        <section id="meeting-1857-12-22">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1857-12-22"> December 22nd, 1857</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon, present, J.B. Taylor, A.M. Poindexter, James Thomas, A.
            Snead, A.J. Crane, A. Thomas, B. Manly, L.W. Seeley, Wm. Sands, T.J.
            Evans, L.R. Spilman, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Rev. J.B. Taylor was called to the chair.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Wm. Sands.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last two meetings were read and approved.</p>

          <p>
            The committee appointed at the last meeting to investigate charges
            prefered [sic] against the President of the College <aside>Report of Committee to investigate charges against the President</aside> mentioned in the
            preamble &amp; resolutions of the last meeting, presented their report
            which being amended was unanimously adopted and is herein inserted, and
            the Secretary was instructed to have it published. Absent A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Secretary was instructed to retain an article styled a
            Defence [sic] placed in the hands of the investigating committee by the
            Editor of The South, and to furnish him with a copy should he desire it.
          </p>
          <p>The following report was presented by the appropriate committee,</p>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was refered [sic] the question of a <aside>Report of Committee on well</aside> new well on
            the College premises, have in view of its necessity, had the well dug,
            and a pump prepared.
          </p>
          <p>
            The bills for digging and bricking the well $38.32/100 and for pump
            $42.50/100 are hereby presented; also a bill of Glenn &amp; Davis for
            various repairs amounting to $54.
          </p>
          <p>Respectfully submitted,</p>
          <p>Signed Jas. B. Taylor</p>
          <p>Chairman</p>
          <p>
            On motion the report was received and the Treasurer instructed to pay
            the bills.
          </p>

          <PageNumber num={211} />

          <p>
            Report of the Investigating Committee, to investigate charges preferred
            against Rev. Ro. Ryland, being quite lengthy is not copied but filed
            away among the Documents of the College.  The following resolution was
            offered by the Committee and unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved; That the charges made against Rev. Robert Ryland and the
            Students of Richmond College, are without foundation, and are <aside>Charges against President decided false</aside> proved to
            be false.
          </p>
          <p>Adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary President</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1857-01-02">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1857-01-02"> January 2nd, 1858,</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this
            afternoon, present Ro. Ryland, Edwin Wortham, R. Reins, L.W. Seeley,
            L.R. Spilman, J.B. Jeter, T.J. Evans, A.J. Crane, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Richard Reins.</p>
          <p>
            Mr. Evans stated that the object of the meeting being called, was to
            consider what steps ought to be taken by the Board in relation to the
            affairs of Mr. Hyde, one of the Hotel Keepers at the College, whose
            Hotel property some of his creditors had levied upon, and if sold the
            College would be incommoded, and after consultation he offered the
            following resolution which was adopted,
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved; That L.R. Spilman and Ed. Wortham be authorized and empowered
            to take any steps, legal or otherwise, that may be necessary to protect
            the College from any loss or inconvenience that may result from the levy
            of an execution on property which the plaintiff in the execution claims <PageNumber num={212} /> to be the property of W.F.B. Hyde <aside>Commitee no cause of Hyde's Hotel property</aside>, one of the Hotel Keepers at the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>Present Rev. J.L. Burrows.</p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed September 4, 1857 to prepare some plan for the
            appointment of a <aside>Report of Committee on Receiver</aside> Receiver of Monies from the Students at the College,
            presented their report which was laid upon the table and the committee
            discharged.
          </p>
          <p>Absent Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee to revise the Charter and By Laws <aside>Commitee on charter reported</aside> presented their report
            which being discussed, was recommitted to the committee, to be presented
            at an adjourned meeting to be held next Thursday the 7th inst, at 7
            o'clock, P.M.
          </p>
          <p>Now adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1857-01-07">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1857-01-07"> January 7th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this
            day, present, Ro. Ryland, W. Goddin, J.B. Taylor, E. Wortham, C.T.
            Wortham, J.L. Burrows, Wm. Sands, L.W. Seeley, A. Snead, L.R. Spilman
            &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Wm. Sands.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved. Present B.
            Manly.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee to revise the Charter and By-Laws presented their report <aside>Report on charter and By-Laws</aside>,
            which was received and adopted, and on motion L.R. Spilman was appointed
            a committee to lay the same before the Legislature for the purposes of
            having it granted.
          </p>
          <p>Absent A. Snead.</p>
          <p>
            The committee on the communication of the Faculty respecting the <aside>Tuition of J.B. Taylor's sons (see file)</aside> tuition
            of Mr. Taylor's sons presented their report recommending the <PageNumber num={213} /> following resolution, which was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            <u>Resolved</u>, That the claims of the Faculty against this Board, for
            the tuition of Mr. J.B. Taylor's sons from 1853 to 1858 amounting to
            $232.50 be not allowed.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1857-04-20">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1857-4-20"> April 20th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon,
            present, Ro. Ryland, J.B. Jeter, A.M. Poindexter, Edwin Wortham, Jas.
            Thomas, L.W. Seeley, L.R. Spilman, B. Manly and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. L.W. Seeley.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved. Present A.G.
            Wortham.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the suit which had been instituted by the
            Trustees against a _____ Johnson of Petersburg to recover the amount of
            his bond in favor of the endowment fund, <aside>Suit against Johnson dismissed</aside> be dismissed, the Trustees
            being informed of the insolvency of the said Johnson and his wife having
            assured the President that she would pay the debt.
          </p>
          <p>Present A. Thomas.</p>
          <p>
            A petition was presented to Board from Mrs. Hines <aside>Mrs Hines' appreciation</aside> to be released from
            the payment of the bond of her husband, now desceased [sic], given in
            behalf of the endowment fund, on the plea of inability. On motion L.R.
            Spilman and E. Wortham, were appointed a committee to ascertain if it
            was so and report to the Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>Present Wm. Sands.</p>
          <p>
            On motion L.R. Spilman and B. Manly were appointed a committee to
            enquire if it was incumbent on the Board to return to the Executor of
            Miss <PageNumber num={214} /> Amanda Crews Estate any balance of the Legacy left by her to be applied
            to the education of Wm. L. Moorfield, in consequence of his not availing
            himself of the privilege of remaining at the College till the whole was
            expended.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was presented to the Board from the Tutor F.W. Reinhart,
            asking an increase of his Salary. On motion the same was refered [sic]
            to a committee consisting of L.R. Spilman and L.W. Seeley.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was presented from Prof. Owens tendering his
            resignation, which on motion was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President now presented the Charter of the College as amended by the
            last Legislature, which was accepted by the Board and ordered to be
            spread upon the Records of the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The By Laws as reported by the Committee were also adopted, which are
            herewith recorded.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the subject of the casting vote of the President was refered
            [sic] to a committee consisting of L.W. Seeley and L.R. Spilman.
          </p>
          <p>
            The term office of the Officers appointed under the old Charter having
            expired by the acceptance of the new, the Board now now [sic] proceed to
            elect its officers under the new. Whereupon        Robert Ryland was
            elected President
          </p>
          <p>Jno. M. Murray, Secretary</p>
          <p>Edwin Wortham, Treasurer.</p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was requested to have the bond of the Treasurer
            executed.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that all other committees and persons appointed
            under the former organization be continued in office to which they were
            appointed.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned,</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>

          <PageNumber num={215} />

          <p>
            <b>
              <u>Amended Charter</u>
            </b>
          </p>
          <p>
            A bill to amend an act, passed <div><time dateTime="1846-03-04"> March 4th 1846,</time></div> entitled &quot;An act to
            incorporate the Trustees of Richmond College.&quot;
          </p>
          <p>
            Be it enacted by the General Assembly, that the act passed March 4th
            1840, entitled an act to incorporate &quot;The Trustees of Richmond
            College&quot;, be, and the same is, hereby so amended as to read as
            follows: --
          </p>
          <aside>location and name</aside>
          <p>
            1.         That there be and is hereby established, at or near the city
            of Richmond, a Seminary of learning for the instruction of youth in the
            various branches of Science and literature, which shall be Known by the
            name, Richmond College.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustees</aside>
          <p>
            2.         That Archibald Thomas, J.B. Jeter, Alexander Fleet, Barnett
            Grimsley, William Sands, Daniel Witt, Robert Ryland, James B. Taylor,
            Edwin Wortham, John M. Murray, Samuel G. Mason, Thomas Hume, A.M.
            Poindexter, Thomas N. Welch, Addison Hall, L.W. Allen, W.A. Baynham,
            L.W. Seeley, Basil Manly Jr., A.G. Wortham, Albert Snead, James Thomas
            Jr., Richard Reins, A. Judson Crane, Charles T. Wortham, C.F. Fisher,
            L.R. Spilman, Thomas J. Evans, Wellington Goddin, Thomas Wallace, J.B.
            Stovall, L.M. Coleman, R.H. Bagby, A.J. Coons, J. Lansing Burrows,
            Edward J. Willis, Jno. A. Broadus, Roscoe B. Heath, and J.R. Chambliss
            be and are hereby constituted Trustees of said College, who and their
            successors shall be a body corporate under the name and style  <aside>Style</aside> &quot;
            <u>Richmond College</u>&quot;, who shall have perpetual succession and a
            common seal; may receive and hold property for the benefit of said
            College, and may sue and be sued, implead and be impleaded,
          </p>

          <p>They shall have power to appoint <aside>Rights</aside> and <PageNumber num={216} />
            <aside>appointed of faculty and removal</aside>
            remove officers for their own body, and a Faculty of instruction for
            the College, and to regulate all fees and salaries. They shall also have
            power to make By-Laws and regulations, not contrary to the laws of the
            land. Any seven Trustees shall form a <aside>quorum</aside> quorum, and a less number may
            adjourn from time to time, till a quorum be had.
          </p>
          <p>
            3.         The said Trustees, or any seven of them, are hereby
            authorized and empowered to confer literary degrees <aside>Power to confer degrees</aside> upon such persons as
            in their opinion shall merit the same, in as ample a manner as any other
            College in this State, and under the corporate seal to grant
            testimonials thereof.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurer duties</aside>
          <p>
            4.         The said Trustees shall elect a Treasurer who shall give bond
            with approved security, payable to said College, conditioned faithfully
            to discharge the duties of his office, and, on failure; so to do he may
            be proceeded against by motion, upon ten days notice, before the Circuit
            or Hustings Court of the City of Richmond.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustees how removed from office and vacancies filled number trustees</aside>
          <p>
            5.         The said Trustees shall have power, at any annual meeting,
            ten of them being present and concurring, to remove any trustee, and at
            any time to supply any vacancy. The number of Trustees shall never be
            less than twenty four, nor more than forty. There shall be annual and
            other stated meetings of the Trustees at such time and place as their
            By-Laws shall prescribe. There may be special meetings at the call of
            the presiding officer, or of any three Trustees, due Notice of all such
            meetings being given.
          </p>
          <aside>meetings</aside>
          <p>
            6.         The said Trustees are hereby authorized to admit
            gratuitously, such students they may think proper.
          </p>
          <aside>special meetings now called</aside>

          <PageNumber num={217} />

          <p>
            7.         All rights, claims, privileges and appurtenances now
            belonging, or in any wise appertaining to &quot;The Trustees of Richmond
            College&quot;, as heretofore incorporated by act of this General
            Assembly, passed March 4th, 1840, are hereby transfered [sic] to &quot;
            Richmond College&quot;
          </p>
          <p>8.         This act shall be in force from its passage.</p>

          <p>
            <b>
              <u>By Laws</u>
            </b>
          </p>
          <p>
            1.         The officers of the Trustees shall be a President, a
            Secretary and a Treasurer.  <u>These shall be chosen by ballot</u>, at
            each annual meeting of the board, but vacancies may be supplied at any
            other meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>President's Duties</aside>
          <p>
            2.         The President shall preside at all meetings of the Board; but
            in case of his absence a President pro. tem. shall be appointed. He
            shall be guided by the usual rules of deliberative assemblies and in
            case of a tie, shall have the casting vote.
          </p>
          <aside>Duties of Secretary</aside>
          <p>
            3.         The Secretary shall keep a book, or books, in which he shall
            faithfully record all proceedings of the board. He shall conduct the
            correspondence, file and safely keep all documents entrusted to his
            care, subject at all times, to the inspection of the members of the
            board, but shall not deliver the same to any other, than to an agent of
            the board appointed to receive them.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurer Duties of</aside>
          <p>
            4.         The Treasurer shall give a receipt for all moneys received by
            him, on account of Richmond College. He shall pay no money until the
            same <PageNumber num={218} /> <aside>Treasurer Bond</aside> shall have been ordered by a vote of the board. He shall keep an
            account of all moneys, stocks, bonds and other effects in his hands, of
            said College, or subject to his control, which shall be balanced at
            least once a year, and be by him reported in full at the Annual Meeting.
            His bond shall be in the penalty of <u>five thousand Dollars</u>, and it
            shall be deposited with the Secretary. His books shall be open at all
            times to the inspection of the board or its committees.
          </p>
          <aside>Annual meetings quarterly</aside>
          <p>
            5.         The annual meeting of this Board she [sic] be held on the
            tuesday [sic] succeeding the Second Sunday in June in the city of
            Richmond, and their [sic] shall be a semi annual meeting on the tuesday
            [sic] after the Second Sunday in December. At each annual meeting the
            records of the preceeding [sic] year shall be read, and an auditing
            committee consisting of two members, shall be appointed. A full report
            of the condition of the College shall be submitted by the faculty, and
            arrangements shall be made for the annual report to &quot;The Board of
            the Literary Fund&quot;
          </p>
          <aside>Faculty</aside>
          <p>
            6.         The Faculty shall consist of a President, professors and
            teachers who shall have power to make all needful regulations for the
            instruction and discipline of the Students subject to the approval of
            the Trustees.
          </p>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={219} />

        <section id="meeting-1858-04-26">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-04-26"> April 26, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon,
            present Robert Ryland, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, A. Thomas, L.R.
            Spilman, J.L. Burrows, Jas. Thomas, and Jno. M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.L. Burrows.</p>
          <p>
            The president informed the Board that the object of calling this meeting
            was to acquaint them that he had been notified by Mr. Hyde, one of the
            Hotel Keepers, that he was unable longer to keep up the Hotel as he had
            no funds and no credit.     (Present A.J. Coons)
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the whole subject of keeping up the Hotel
            be intrusted [sic] to the President with authority to draw upon the
            Treasurer for an amount not exceeding $8 per day for the purpose of
            supplying Mr. Hyde with funds to enable him to continue the Hotel till
            the end of the present session.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the bills of Messrs. Glinn &amp; Davis for
            brick work and Messrs. Mitchell &amp; Hewlett for Painting be paid by
            the Treasurer.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1858-06-15" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-06-15"> June 15th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At an annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held June 15th,
            1858. Present Robert Ryland, Edwin Wortham, J.B. Jeter, A.J. Coons, Ed.
            J. Willis, L.W. Seeley, A.J. Crane, A. Thomas, A.G. Wortham, Richard
            Reins and Jno. M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last two meetings were read and approved. The reading
            of the minutes of all meetings since the last annual meeting were <PageNumber num={220} /> on motion dispensed with.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to which had been refered [sic] the petitions of Mrs.
            Hines, F.W. Reinhart and the Executor of Amanda Crews Est, not being
            prepared to report, were continued.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolutions offered by Dr. Jeter were adopted.</p>
          <p>
            1.         <u>Resolved</u>--     That we highly appreciate <aside>Compliments to faculty</aside> the ability,
            faithfulness and efficiency with which the Professors of Richmond
            College have performed their official duties.
          </p>
          <p>
            2.         <u>Resolved</u>That in view of the smallness of their
            compensation for their labors for the present session, the sum of <aside>$450 appropriated to the faculty</aside> $450.
            be divided among them in the following proportion. To F.W. Reinhart
            $150, to Geo. E. Dabney $100, and $50 to each of the other Professors.
          </p>
          <p>
            3.         <u>Resolved</u>That the prohibition now existing against  the
            Professors giving instruction out of the College be removed except so
            far as to require application to be made to the Board of Trustees for
            permission to give such instruction.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Resignation of Professor Owens was now taken up and accepted <aside>Owens reelected</aside>, and
            then on motion he was unanimously elected to the Chair of Greek
            Professorship in Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee in case of the casting vote of the President made no
            report and was continued.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Board now proceeded to ballot for a President of the Board, a
            Secretary and Treasurer for the next twelve months, whereupon the former
            officers were unanimously reelected <aside>Annual officers elected</aside>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented his annual report which was received, audited by
            the Committee.
          </p>

          <PageNumber num={221} />

          <p>
            The General Agent, S.A. Creath, offered his resignation <aside>S.A. Creath resigns</aside> to take effect
            by the middle of July next which was accepted. He also presented his
            annual report which was refered [sic] to the Auditing Committee.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion, L.R. Spilman, W. Goddin, and C.T. Wortham were appointed the
            <aside>Auditing committee</aside> auditing committee for the next twelve months.
          </p>

          <p>
            An application was presented to the Board from Mr. ____ Gilliam a former
            Student at the College, asking for a return of a portion of the money
            paid by him for Board, in consequence of his having been compelled to
            leave the College before the close of the Session. The request was
            refused.
          </p>

          <p>
            The President now read his Annual Report, which was received and refered
            [sic] to a committee consisting of A.J. Coons, Jas. Thomas Jr. and L.R.
            Spilman, to consider and report to the Board upon the suggestions made
            therein.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion the Faculty were authozized [sic] to confer the degeree [sic]
            of A.B. upon the following young men, members of the Senior class <aside>Graduates for 1858</aside> in the
            College, viz.
          </p>
          <p>
            Wm. S. Pinnick, Josephus A. Turner, Samuel H. Pulliam, John W. Ryland,
            William E. Hatcher &amp; Harvey Hatcher.
          </p>

          <p>
            The following resolution was offered by Richard Reins to lay on the
            table till the next meeting -- <u>Resolved</u>-- that a committee of
            three be appointed whose <PageNumber num={222} /> duty it shall be to visit the College as often as they may deem proper,
            to inquire into the efficiency of the Professors, the progress and
            deportment of the Students as well as to any other matters or things
            that they may deem promotive of the interest of the Institution.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the meeting now adjourned at the call of the President.</p>
          <p>
            John M. Murray, Secretary
            <u>Ro. Ryland, Prest</u>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <u>Note</u>.  Communications were also received from Professor Puryear
            and Mr. Hyde, Hotel Keeper, and refered [sic] to the committee on the
            President's report.
          </p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1858-07-03">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-07-03"> July 3, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon at the Second Baptist Church. Present, Ro. Ryland, A. Snead,
            J.B. Jeter, A.J. Coons, B. Manly Jr., T.J. Evans, A. Thomas and Jno. M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. B. Manly Jr.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were approved.</p>
          <p>
            The President presented his report of the monies furnished Mr. Hyde
            since the 28th of April to enable him to carry on the Boarding
            department.  The report was received and referred to the auditing
            committee.
          </p>
          <p>Present A. Thomas.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed at the last meeting to consider several
            communications presented to the Board at the said meeting, reported in
            part as follows
          </p>

          <PageNumber num={223} />

          <p>
            <b>Report</b>
          </p>
          <p>
            1st.      The question whether the present rate of board ought to be
            reduced?
          </p>

          <p>
            We deem it very desirable to reduce the board if suitable and
            responsible. Hotel keepers <aside>Hotel keeper to board of beneficiary</aside> can be obtained; but in view of all the
            difficulties, we deem it inexpedient to reduce the board, for the coming
            session.
          </p>
          <p>
            2nd.     We recommend that hereafter in lieu of the rent for the Hotels,
            the proprietors be requested to board two of the beneficiary Students;
            that is, each hotel keeper board one Student, and the treasurer of the
            fund appropriated towards the beneficiaries, be requested to retain this
            amount, and pay it over to the Treasurer of this Board.
          </p>

          <p>
            3.         That One dollar <aside>$1 for fuel</aside>, for fuel be paid to the hotel keepers for
            this session, and also for the last session, out of the $2 paid by each
            of the day scholars in the College proper for room rent.
          </p>
          <p>
            4.         We deem it desirable to increase the income of the faculty,
            and therefore offer the following resolution for your consideration,
            viz. at the earliest practicable period -- when consistent with the
            present obligations of the College, the income of the Professors be
            increased.
          </p>
          <p>
            <u>Signed</u>
            A.J. Coons, <u>Chairman</u>
          </p>

          <p>
            The committee also presented a report on the damage <aside>Damages</aside> done to the premises
            for the present session, as assessed by Messrs. Tyler and Hyde,
            amounting to $68.52/100.
          </p>
          <p>The reports were received and the committee continued.</p>
          <p>Absent A. Thomas and A. Snead.</p>

          <PageNumber num={224} />

          <p>
            A report was received from Prof. Puryear showing the amount of
            expenditures for the presentsession for the Laboraty [sic] which was
            refered to the auditing committee.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion the President was appointed a committee on the appointment of
            hotel keepers, to make inquiries and report to a called meeting.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion Mr. A.H. Sands was appointed agent of the Trustees to secure
            the rent <aside>Sands to coellect rent</aside> of the hotels for the present session, in any manner he may
            think best.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board now adjourned to meet at the call of the President.
          </p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1858-07-12">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-07-12"> July 12th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon. Present, J.L. Burrows, Jas. Thomas Jr., R. Reins, Edwin
            Wortham, L.R. Spilman, W. Goddin, A.J. Coons, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President being absent, J.L. Burrows was elected President pro. tem.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by A.J. Coons.</p>
          <p>
            A communication was presented from Professor B. Puryear, containing a
            resignation of his Professorship in the College, which on motion of L.R.
            Spilman was accepted.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion a committee consisting of the Chairman, Secretary &amp; W.
            Goddin, was appointed to communicate to Prof. Puryear the sentiments of
            respect and esteem which the Board had for him personally and the manner
            he <PageNumber num={225} /> had discharged his duties.</p>
          <p>Present T.J. Evans &amp; L.W. Seeley.</p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the Board would proceed to fill the
            vacancy thus created in the faculty, on the 17th day of August next, and
            that the Secretary be instructed to advertise the same in the usual
            Richmond newspapers.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion Messrs. J.P. Tyler and Wm. T. Lindsey were appointed <aside>Hotel keepers</aside> Hotel
            Keepers for the ensuing session, and the Secretary was requested to
            inform them of the appointment, and ascertain if they would accept in
            the terms proposed by the Board at its last meeting, but if either or
            both did not, he should advertise that the vacancy would be filled this
            day 2 weeks.
          </p>

          <p>
            The auditing committee presented their report on Prof. Puryear's account
            for expense incured [sic] for the Laboratory showing a balance due him
            of $5.66, which the Treasurer was ordered to pay.
          </p>
          <p>Present A.G. Wortham.</p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee was appointed to confer with Treasurer and report
            whether it was expedient or not to appropriate a larger amount of the
            income of the endowment to the Professor's Salaries.  The Chair
            appointed W. Goddin, T.J. Evans, &amp; the Treasurer the committee.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={226} />

        <section id="meeting-1858-07-28">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-07-28"> July 28, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            day. Present Ro. Ryland, J.B. Jeter, A. Thomas, A.M. Poindexter, T.J.
            Evans, W. Goddin, &amp; A.J. Coons.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent from the city, W. Goddin was appointed
            Secretary pro. tem.
          </p>
          <p>
            An account due Ro. Ryland for money advanced to Mr. Hyde for the
            boarding department amounting to $386.05/100 was allowed, and ordered to
            be paid by the Treasurer, also an account due him for money expended for
            Gas furnished at the College, amounting to $275.41 was allowed and
            ordered to be paid by the Treasurer.
          </p>

          <p>
            The Trustees voted $600 <aside>Professors salaries increased</aside> additional to the appropriation to the Faculty,
            to be divided equally between <u>five</u>officers -- the President's
            salary to remain as before -- the tuition fees to be equally divided
            among all the officers.
          </p>
          <p>(Signed)</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">W. Goddin, Secty Pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u></div>
          </footer>
          <p></p>
          <p></p>
          <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1858-08-17">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1858-08-17"> August 17th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this afternoon
            pursuant to adjournment. Present Ro. Ryland, W. Goddin, Ed. Wortham,
            R.B. Heath, L.R. Spilman, C.T. Wortham, Jas. Thomas Jr., A. Thomas, A.
            Snead, A.J. Coons, J.M. Murray, B. Manly, A.M. Poindexter.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Coons.</p>
          <p>
            The object of the meeting being to elect a Professor to fill the Chair
            of Chemistry and Natural Philosophy in Richmond College, and letters of
            applicants accompanied by recommendations being <PageNumber num={227} /> read, on motion it was ordered the election should be made by ballot,
            whereupon Mr. <u>Wm. G. Strange</u>was declared duly elected having
            received a <aside>Professor Strange elected</aside> <u>majority</u>of the votes on the <u>first ballot</u>.
          </p>

          <p>
            The President read a communication from
            <u>Mr. H.W. Reinhart</u>, tutor of the Academic department,
            <u>resigning</u> <aside>Reinhart resigns</aside> his office, which was accepted, and on motion the board
            proceeded to fill the vacancy. Whereupon <u>Josiah Ryland</u>was
            unanimously elected.
          </p>

          <p>
            The Auditing Committee now reported on the accounts of S.A. Creath,
            Agent, showing a balance of $36.84 due him <aside>S.A. Creath's accounts settled</aside>, which was ordered to be paid
            by the Treasurer.
          </p>

          <p>
            An account of C.D. Yale &amp; Co. <aside>Account of C.D. Yale</aside> for repairs amounting to $6.25 was
            ordered to be paid by the Treasurer, when audited by the committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            An application was presented from Rev. Geo. G. (Exall?), asking to be
            released from the payment of apart [sic] of his bond given for the
            endowment of the College. No action was taken.
          </p>
          <p>Absent A. Snead &amp; W. Goddin.</p>

          <p>
            On motion Mr. Woodward was required to have the brick work of the
            College painted in compliance with his <u>original</u>contract, with the
            exception of the windows, which are to be painted <aside>House to painted</aside> <u>white</u>, under
            the superintendence of the President.
          </p>
          <p>The board now adjourned.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u></div>
          </footer>

          <PageNumber num={228} />

          <p>
            (Note: <u>Read</u>the succeeding 2 meetings next)
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1858-11-09">
          <div>Tuesday<time dateTime="1858-11-09"> Nov. 9th, 1858</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College, held this
            afternoon, present Ro. Ryland, J.B. Taylor, Jas. Thomas, A. Thomas, A.G.
            Wortham, A.J. Coons, L.W. Seeley, L.R. Spilman, Wm. Sands, Edwin
            Wortham, &amp; B. Manly.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. L.W. Seeley</p>
          <p>On motion L.R. Spilman was requested to act as Secretary.</p>
          <p>
            On motion of Jas. Thomas, a committee of the Students of the College and
            a Mr. Camden from St. Louis, were invited to take seats with the Board.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion of Jas. Thomas it was resolved than [sic] in accordance with
            the petition of the <aside>Appropriation for 2 Halls for the Liteary [sic] Societies</aside> 2 Liteary [sic] Societies of the College the sum of
            six hundred dollars be appropriated with such additional amounts as may
            be raised by the students of the College by private subscription to be
            expended under the direction of a committee of the board of Trustees on
            the erection of 2 Halls, suitable for the accommodation of said
            societies. On futher [sic] motion, Jas. Thomas, J.B. Taylor and L.W.
            Seeley were appointed members of said committee.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion of A. Thomas it was resolved that the sum of three hundred
            dollars be <aside>Appropriation for ornamenting College grounds</aside> appropriated to be expended under the direction of the same
            committee as above with Dr. Burrows, in laying of the College grounds,
            in planting trees, and otherwise beautifying and adorning the same; The
            said committee were also to erect suitable privy houses, and draw on the
            Treasurer for the cost. On motion it was resolved that the petition of
            Wm. Gwinn, Jos. C. Boxley Jr., and of W.G. Strange to have grates fixed <PageNumber num={229} /> in the 2 end rooms on the second floor of the north side of the main
            College building be referred to the same committee with discretion in
            the premises.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
          <p>
            Signed L.R. Spilman, Sec pro tem
            <u>Ro. Ryland, Prest</u>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <u>Note</u>:  The minutes of the two succeeding meeting [sic] should
            have been recorded previous to the one above. Secretary.
          </p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">L.R. Spilman, Sec pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

