        <PageNumber num={231} />

        <section id="meeting-1859-02-15">
          <div><time dateTime="1859-02-15">Feby 15, 1859</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Grace
            Street Baptist Church, Tuesday evening 15th Febry. 1859, present Ro.
            Ryland, J.B. Jeter, Jas. B. Taylor, J.L. Burrows, A.M. Poindexter,
            Roscoe B. Heath, A. Thomas, L.R. Spilman, A.G. Wortham, A.J. Coons, B.
            Manly Jr., and Wellington Goddin.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary being absent, W. Goddin was appointed Secretary pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. A.J. Coons from the Committee to whom was referred several
            communications from the President, B. Puryear and others, made a report,
            which being amended was adopted as follows.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was referred several communications that had been
            addressed to the Board of Trustees of the College in June 1858, beg
            leave to report further.
          </p>
          <aside>Report on Steward's a/c</aside>
          <p>
            The books and accounts of Prof. Lewis Turner for the two sessions in
            <time dateTime="1859-07">1856-7</time> &amp; <time dateTime="1859-08">1857-8</time> have been carefully examined. We believe Mr.
            Turner's atcs [sic] are correct except in some very small items which we
            will presently specify. Though his manner of keeping his books is not
            clearly intelligible to your committee, and but for the kindly
            assistance of Mr. Turner, we should not have been able to make the
            proper examination.
          </p>
          <p>
            We found vouchers and receipts for all sums paid out and doubt not he
            has faithfully reported all sums collected by him.  Upon proper
            adjustment of his [indecipherable] for<time dateTime="1857-08"> 1857-8</time>  we find a balance of 50
            cents due the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The books also show 8$ in hand yet to be refunded by Mr. Turner to
            students from deposite [sic] money for<time dateTime="1887"> 1857</time> &amp;<time dateTime="1858"> 1858</time>.  It should be
            understood <PageNumber num={232} /> that this report is only up to the <time dateTime="1858-06-29"> 29th of June 1858</time>, and if anything
            has been received or paid out since this date, it is not embraced in
            this report.
          </p>
          <p>
            We would recommend that in the future Mr. Turner keep his books in more
            accountant form.  1st.  Each pupil's account of 1st &amp; 2nd payment
            should be kept on the same page.  2nd.  Students who still owe for
            tuition should appear on the books in a separate from [sic], as
            delinquents and the amount due annexed to each name.
          </p>
          <p>
            We discover that Mr. Turner has been in the habit of paying small bills
            for repairs and other work about the College. We recommend that no one
            pay any bill except our Treasurer. That the Treasurer require every bill
            properly vouched for as correct before paying it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The accounts of the President of the College, were examined by the
            regular auditing committee and hence we are relieved of the necessity of
            reporting upon Mr. Ryland's accounts though by resolution referred to
            us.
          </p>
          <p>
            The time for holding prayers and requiring the attendance of students we
            think had better be left to the judgment of the President &amp; Faculty
            and in case the Faculty cannot enforce proper discipline, it may then be
            proper for the Board of Trustees to take action in the case.
          </p>
          <p>Respectfully submitted,</p>
          <p>(Signed) A.J. Coons,</p>
          <p>Chairman of Com'tee.</p>
          <p>The President and Mr. Spilman were <PageNumber num={233} /> appointed a committee to take such legal steps as they may deem
            expedient to recover the Rent <aside>Commitee to collect Tyler's Rent</aside> in arrears due from J.P. Tyler, as one of
            the Hotel Keepers.
          </p>

          <p>
            A communication from Prof. Geo. E. Dabney being read, was on motion of
            Dr. Jeter referred to a committee of two, to report at an early day, and
            Dr. Jeter and Manly were appointed the committee.
          </p>

          <p>
            The President called attention to the fact that the fence between the
            &quot;Mayo&quot; property and the College grounds was in bad repair, and
            would require replacing <aside>Fence to rebuilt</aside>. On motion the Committee in the College grounds
            were authorized to do what was necessary to accomplish the object.
          </p>

          <p>
            The President brought to the attention of the Board the fact that the
            <aside>Commitee to settle to the suit vs Hyde</aside> suit relative to W.F.B. Hyde had been decided adversely to the College,
            whereupon a committee consisting of Messrs. Spilman &amp; Goddin were
            appointed to compromise or adjust the matter in such terms as to them
            may seem expedient.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned. </p>
          <p>
            <u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u>
          </p>
          <u>
            <br />
          </u>
          <p>
            <u></u>
          </p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A.J. Coons, Chairman of Com'tee</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={234} />

        <section id="meeting-1859-04-28">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1859-04-28"> April 28, 1859</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            evening at the Grace Street Baptist Church.  Present Ro. Ryland, Edwin
            Wortham, B. Manly Jr., A.J. Coons, A.M. Poindexter, J.L. Burrows, A.
            Thomas, A.G. Wortham, W. Goddin, J.B. Jeter, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prayer by Rev.. C.C. Bitting [Charles Carroll Bitting] who was invited
            to a seat during the session of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of previous meetings were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The President presented a bill of Mr. Edward Mayo amounting to $95.26
            being one half of the expenses of putting a new fence between the
            College ground and the &quot;Mayo&quot; property. The bill was allowed
            and ordered to be paid. Also a bill of C.D. Yale &amp; Co. for repairs,
            which was also allowed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Rev. B. Manly Jr. <u>one</u>of the committee on Modern Languages
            appointed at the last meeting presented their report which being
            considered was laid upon the table, and the following resolution
            adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Committee be instructed to confer with The Faculty of
            the College regarding the desirableness of establishing a professorship
            of Modern Languages and to ascertain whether in the event such a
            professorship be established, they would be willing to admit the
            incumbent to an equal pro rata distribution of the tuition fees.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following resolution was also adopted. Resolved that the Treasurer
            be directed to furnish, at the next meeting of the Board, a statement of
            the fiscal <PageNumber num={235} /> condition of the college and also of the contingent expenses for the
            last 3 years.
          </p>

          <p>
            Resolved that a committee be appointed to recommend to the Board the
            exact number of vacations <aside>Commitee on vacations</aside> to be observed during the College sessions.
            Committee J.L. Burrows and A. Thomas.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following resolution was offered by Rev. A.M. Poindexter and adopted
            by the Board.
          </p>

          <p>
            Resolved that the Faculty be instructed to consider and report to the
            Board if in their opinion any suitable plan can be arranged for
            incorporating Modern Languages <aside>mod languages?</aside> into the College Curriculum as an
            optional study in place of some portion of the present studies.
          </p>
          <p>The Board was adjourned to meet at the call of the President.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1859-05-16">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1859-05-16"> May 16, 1859</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of the College held this evening at
            Grace Street Baptist Church.  Present, Ro. Ryland, Edwin Wortham, B.
            Manly Jr., L.R. Spilman, J.B. Jeter, A.J. Coons, J.L. Burrows, and J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Mr. Spilman.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed to confer with the Faculty in relation to the
            appointment of Professor of Modern Languages, presents the following
            report.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed to confer with the Faculty of the College
            regarding <PageNumber num={236} /> the desirableness of establishing a professorship of Modern Languages,
            and to ascertain whether, in the event such a professorship be
            established, they are willing to admit the incumbent to an equal pro
            rata distribution of tuition fees report
          </p>
          <aside>Report of Committee on mod languages</aside>
          <p>
            That after a free and full consultation on the subject it was found that
            one of the Faculty, the professor of Greek, was doubtful of the
            expediency of such appointment because he feared it might lessen the
            attention paid to Classical Studies, one the Mathematical professor was
            neutral, on the subject the other professor favored the appointment.
            After this free explanation of opinion, the Faculty recommend the
            creation of the Professorship.
          </p>
          <p>
            They also expressed their willingness to admit the professor, should one
            be appointed, to an equal participation in the proceeds of tuitions.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Rev. J.L. Burrows the following resolution was adopted.
          </p>

          <p>
            Resolved that a Professorship of Modern Languages and Literature be
            established <aside>Professorship mod languages established</aside>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the sum of $540 per annum be appropriated from the
            endowment fund towards the payment of the Salary of the Professor.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was instructed correspond [sic] with Professors
            (Gammell?), Wood and any others in regard to the qualifications of Mr.
            _____ Chase to <u>fill</u>the chair now created and also to ascertain at
            what Salary he might be employed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Rev. J.L. Burrows presented a communication from Professor Owens
            resigning his professorship.
          </p>

          <PageNumber num={237} />

          <p>
            On motion of Rev. J.B. Jeter the Board instead of accepting the
            resignation granted the Professor leave to spend one session at the
            University of Virginia <aside>Prof Owens leave of absence</aside>, with the understanding that he recommend a
            substitute to fill his place who shall be approved by the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Burrows also presented a petition from Professor Owens, asking the
            Board to authorize him their Agent to raise by Voluntary contribution
            the sum of $10,000 or any part thereof, for special endowment fund of
            the Chair of Greek in the College. The petition was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Faculty in obedience to the instructions of the Board to report upon
            the expediencey [sic] of incorporating Modern Languages in the College
            Curriculum presented their report which was laid upon the Table.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer also presented a statement of the Fiscal Condition of the
            College, as ordered by the Board at its last meeting, which was
            received.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secty.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={238} />

        <section id="meeting-1859-06-07" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1859-06-07"> June 7th, 1859</time></div>
          <p>
            At an annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            evening at Grace Street Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. Jas. B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, A.J. Coons, A.G. Wortham, L.R. Spilman, L.W. Seeley,
            J.B. Taylor, J.B. Jeter, J.L. Burrows, B. Manly Jr., A.M. Poindexter,
            Edwin Wortham and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the reading of all the minutes since the last meeting required
            by the By-Laws was dispensed with.  The minutes of the last meeting were
            read and approved.
          </p>

          <p>
            The report of the Professors recommending the introduction of Modern
            Languages <aside>Commitee on modern languages</aside> into the College Curriculum on motion of Rev. A.M. Poindexter
            was refered [sic] to a committe [sic] consisting of Rev. L.W. Seeley,
            L.R. Spilman, and B. Manly Jr.
          </p>
          <p>
            The proposition of Prof. Owens to raise $10,000 for the endowment of the
            Greek Professorship was laid upon the table. Mr. Manly offered
            resignation -- laid on table.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented his annual report, which was received &amp;
            ordered to be filed with the Auditor's report when presented.
          </p>
          <p>Present R.B. Heath</p>
          <p>
            Bills of Messrs. Glinn &amp; Davis amounting to $81.50 for work done on
            the College premises, and one of Mr. Lindsay's for repairs, amounting to
            $4.44 were reported and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Board now proceed to the Election of its annual officer, as required
            by the By Laws.  Whereupon, Rev. Ro. Ryland was reelected President and <PageNumber num={239} /> Edwin Wortham <u>Treasurer</u>.
          </p>
          <p>J.M. Murray Secretary.</p>
          <p>
            The President here presented the testimonials he had received in
            relation to the qualification of Mr. Wm. S. Chase to fill the Chair of
            Modern Languages and after consultation it was deemed expedient to
            postpone the election one month from this date, and the President was
            requested to advertise the fact in the usual newspapers of this city.
          </p>
          <p>Absent Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>

          <p>
            A Communication was presented from Prof. Dabney asking an additional
            compensation <aside>Extra pay Prof Dabney</aside> of $200 for extra services rendered in teaching the French
            Classes. On motion of Dr. Jeter $100 was allowed.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned to meet at the call of the President.</p>

          <footer>
            <div className="signature">John M. Murray, Secty.</div>
            <div className="signature"><u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u></div>
          </footer>

          <p>
            <time dateTime="1859-06-07">June 7, 1859</time>, Note:  <aside>June 7, 1859 note</aside> Rev. B. Manly offered his resignation as a Trustee
            of the College -- which laid upon the table.
          </p>

          <div><time dateTime="1859-06-27">June 27, 1859</time></div>
          <p>
            At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church.  Present Ro. Ryland,
            Pres., A.J. Coons, A.J. Crane, J.B. Jeter, E. Wortham, L.R. Spilman,
            Wellington Goddin, R.B. Heath, J.L. Burrows, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the recommendation of the Faculty of the College, the Board
            authorized the degree of A.B. to be conferred on the following young
            men, who had passed the necessary examinations during the <PageNumber num={240} /> present Session of the College, viz., </p>

          <p>Wm. H. Agnew                       Hilary E. Hatcher</p>
          <p>Jno. J. Harvey                         D. William Gwin,</p>
          <p>Jas. A. Mundy             &amp;         Geo. B. Smith.</p>
          <p>
            The Trustees also confered [sic] the honouray [sic] title of L.L.D. on
            Prof. Geo. F. Holmes of of [sic] the University of Virginia, and the
            degree of A.M. on the following gentlemen former graduates in the first
            degree at Richmond College, viz.,
          </p>

          <p>Wm. R. McDonald                 Josiah Ryland</p>
          <p>
            Jas. O'Farrell
            <s>M.B.Howell</s>
          </p>
          <p>Rev. Jno. C. Long                   A.R. Courtney</p>
          <p>Rev. Wm. S. Bland,                Fayett McMullen</p>
          <p>Rev. Geo. B. Taylor                Thos. Hume Jr.</p>
          <p>Rev. Wm. D. Thomas             Rev. Alex Eubank</p>
          <p>Rev. Jos. Walker                     Wm. S. Ryland</p>
          <p>A.E. Dickinson                       L.F. Haley,</p>
          <p>
            Ro. Williamson           and the Title of D.D. on Rev. B. Manly Jr. and
            Jno. A. Broadus.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President presented a bill of Mr. Woodward for work done at the
            College amounting to $29.20, which was allowed and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Mr. L.R. Spilman, A.R. Holliday was elected a Trustee of
            the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the resignation of Mr. C.T. Wortham which laid upon the table
            at a meeting held<time dateTime="1858-09-27"> Sep. 27, 1858</time> was taken up and accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Chairman of the Auditing Committee now presented his report on the
            Treasurer's accounts, which was received.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion Messrs. Wellington Goddin and R.B. Heath were appointed the
            Auditing Committee till the next annual meeting.
          </p>
