        <PageNumber num={241} />
        <p>Richmond July 7th, 1859</p>
        <p>
          At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the
          Grace Street Baptist Church this afternoon.  Present. Ro. Ryland, Jas.
          B. Taylor, A.J. Coons, E.J. Willis, L.W. Seely [sic], R.B. Heath, Wm.
          Sands, B. Manly Jr., and J.M. Murray.
        </p>
        <p>Prayer by Rev. Mr. Willis.</p>
        <p>
          The President presented a communication from Mrs. Amanda M. Williamson
          asking to be released from the payment of a bond given for the endowment
          of the College, alleging that her name was signed to it without her
          consent. On motion of Mr. Heath the petition was refered [sic] to a
          committee of L.R. Spilman and A.M. Poindexter to consider the same and
          if they deemed it expedient, to give up the bond.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President presented to the Board his report for Monies received and
          disbursed by him since July 28, 1858 accompanied with report of the
          Auditing Committee. The report was received and ordered to be filed.
          Present A.R. Holladay.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President informed the Meeting that Mr. Tyler declined being a
          candidate for reelection as Hotel Keeper, whereupon the Board proceeded
          to consider the subject of the appointment of a successor, and Mr. A.
          Brock being nominated and the vote taken, was declared elected to the
          position.
        </p>
        <p>Present Rev. J.B. Jeter, Richard Reins, and Wellington Goddin.</p>
        <p>
          The board now proceeded to the business for which this meeting had been
          especially appointed, the election a Professor of Modern…
        </p>

        <PageNumber num={242} />
        <p>[blank]</p>

        <PageNumber num={243} />

        <p>
          …Languages and Literature and applications and testimonials furnished by
          the candidates having been read, the members proceeded to cast their
          ballot, which having been counted by the Secretary, it was found that
          Mr. Wm. S. Chase had received 9 out of 12, the whole number cast,
          wherupon [sic] he was declared duly elected.
        </p>
        <p>
          On motion made by Dr. Jeter it was ordered that his Salary for the first
          year shall be $800, eight hundred dollars, 540 dollars of which are to
          be paid from the Endowment fund and the balance from tuition fees.
        </p>
        <p>Absent E.J. Willis.</p>
        <p>
          After some discussion the Board decided to go into the election of a
          Professor for one year to supply the place of Prof. Owens to whom leave
          of absence had been granted.
        </p>
        <p>
          Dr. Coons presented the name of Prof. E. Adkins of Marietta College Ohio
          as a suitable person to fill the place, accompanied with a statement of
          facts in regard to his eminent qualification to fill the place, after
          which the ballotts [sic] were cast and being counted by the Secretary,
          it was found that 11 votes had been given of which he had received 9 and
          was therefore declared to be duly elected.
        </p>
        <p>After which the Board adjd.</p>
        <p>
          J.M. Murray, Secty.
          <u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u>
        </p>

        <PageNumber num={244} />

        <p>Richmond Aug. 29, 1859</p>
        <p>
          At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at Grace Street
          Baptist Church this evening, present, Ro. Ryland, A. Thomas, Edwin
          Wortham, J.L. Burrows, A.J. Coons, Richd. Reins, T.J. Evans &amp; J.M.
          Murray.
        </p>
        <p>Prayer by Mr. Reins.</p>
        <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and adopted.</p>
        <p>
          The President stated that the object of the meeting was to take into
          consideration the appointment of Mr. Brock as one of the Hotel Keepers,
          made at the last meeting, as various report [sic] had been made as to
          his qualifications &amp; abilty [sic] to discharge the duties
          satisfactorily.  Present J.B. Taylor &amp; A.M. Poindexter.
        </p>
        <p>
          On motion of Rev. A.M. Poindexter the following resolutions were
          adopted.
        </p>
        <p>
          1.  Resolved    That Mr. Brock and hereafter all Stewards shall be
          required to enter into bond with approved Security for the faithful
          performance of their duties, in the amount of ($1500) fifteen hundred
          Dollars.
        </p>
        <p>
          2.  Resolved -- That in making a contract with Mr. Brock and hereafter
          with every Steward the right of occupancy of a hotel and premises shall
          terminate on the 15th day of August.
        </p>
        <p>
          The following gentlemen were appointed a committee to make the
          arrangement with Mr. Brock as contemplated in the above resolutions,
          viz., T.J. Evans, Edwin Wortham, and A.J. Coons.
        </p>
        <p>
          On motion it was resolved that the same committee see Mr. Tyler and
          request him to vacate the hotel occupied by him <PageNumber num={245} /> by the 15th of September, and that they be empowered to make such
          arrangements with him as they may deem expedient to secure his removal
          by that date.
        </p>
        <p>
          The committee to whom was referred the subject of Holy days presented
          their [sic] which was adopted as follows.
        </p>
        <p>
          The committee to whom the subject of Holy days during term time was
          referred beg leave to present the following resolutions.
        </p>
        <p>
          1.         Resolved, That there may be a <u>suspension</u>of studies and
          recitations for <u>two days</u>during the Meeting of the Agricultural
          Fair in Richmond, <u>one week at Christmas</u>and the Monday of Easter
          week, and that the recitation shall not be suspended upon any other
          school days during the term.
        </p>
        <p>
          2.         Resolved that this resolution be communicated to the Faculty
          and Students at the commencement of the next session.
        </p>
        <p>
          The committee appointed to prepare a plan defining the President's
          duties also presented their report which was received and laid upon the
          table be [sic] acted upon at a called meeting to be held before the
          commencement of the next session.
        </p>
        <p>After which Board adjourned.</p>
        <p>
          J.M. Murray, Secy.
          <u>Ro. Ryland, Prest.</u>
        </p>
        <u>
          <br />
        </u>
        <p>
          <u></u>
        </p>
        <PageNumber num={246} />

        <p>Richmond September 19, 1859</p>
        <p>
          A [sic] a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at Grace
          Street Baptist Church this evening.  Present Rev. J.B. Jeter, A.J.
          Coons, A.M. Poindexter, T.J. Evans, Ed. Wortham, J.L. Burrows, L.R.
          Spilman, A.J. Crane, R. Reins, L.W. Seeley &amp; J.M. Murray.
        </p>
        <p>
          The president being absent Rev. J.B. Jeter was appointed President pro.
          tempo.
        </p>
        <p>Prayer by Rev. L.W. Seeley.</p>
        <p>
          The committee appointed at the last meeting in regard to the Hotel
          Keepers, reported that Mr. Brock offered security which they did not
          approve and that Mr. Tyler declined to vacate the Hotel occupied by him
          by the 15th of September. The report was received and the following
          resolution adopted.
        </p>
        <p>
          Resolved that the subject be referred back to the same committee with
          discretionary power to make the best arrangements with Mr. Mr. [sic]
          Brock that they can.
        </p>
        <p>J.M. Murray, Secy.</p>

        <p>Richmond November 11th, 1859</p>
        <p>
          At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this evening
          present Ro. Ryland, A. Thomas, Edwin Wortham, T.J. Evans, A.G. Wortham,
          L.R. Spilman, A.J. Coons, J.B. Taylor and J.M. Murray.
        </p>
        <p>Prayer by T.J. Evans.</p>
        <p>
          The President presented a petition from Messrs. Blair &amp; Coffer
          students at the College asking to be reimbursed the sum of $8.50 being
          the amount expended by them <PageNumber num={247} /> in puting [sic] a grate in their room. On motion the Treasurer was
          authorized to refund the same at the end of the present session.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President having informed the Trustees that a committee from the Mu
          Sigma Rho. Society was at hand, who wished to be heard, in relation to
          the erection of the Literary Halls at the College, on motion they were
          invited into the meeting and having been heard, retired, and the Board
          having considered the subject for a while, on motion the subject was
          laid upon the table.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President read communications which he had received from Revds. B.
          Manly Jr., J.A. Broadus and Prof. Geo. F. Holmes respectfully accepting
          the Honorary Degee's [sic] which had been conferred upon them by the
          Trustees at the last commencement.
        </p>
        <p>The following resolution was adopted.</p>
        <p>
          Resolved That the Treasurer be requested to lay before the Trustees a
          statement of the cost of repairing the furnaces at the College since
          their erection.
        </p>
        <p>
          Petitions were presented by the President from Mr. Brock for blinds to
          the Hotel Windows, and from Mr. Lindsay for another door in his Hotel.
          Both petitions were declined by the Board.
        </p>
        <p>The following resolution offered by A.J. Coons was adopted.</p>
        <p>
          Resolved that the Faculty of R. College be requested to examine into the
          subject of Chapel Service and the propriety of all the Students and the
          Faculty attending such service.
        </p>
        <p>
          On motion of Rev. J.B. Taylor, it was resolved that a committee
          consisting of <PageNumber num={248} /> Rev. J.B. Jeter, J.L. Burrows, A.M. Poindexter and Wellington Goddin
          be appointed to to [sic] take under consideration the whole subject of
          completing the College Edifice, and that the committee be requested to
          report to a meeting of the Trustees to be held the 2nd tuesday [sic]
          evening in December next.
        </p>
        <p>On motion the meeting was adjourned,</p>

        <p>J.M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Prest.</p>

        <p>Richmond, December 15th, 1859</p>
        <p>
          In consequence of not being able to get a quorum the adjourned meeting
          which was to have been held the 2nd tuesday [sic] evening in December
          was held this afternoon at 1st Baptist Church.
        </p>
        <p>
          Present. Rev. Ro. Ryland, A.M. Poindexter, Edwin Wortham, L.R. Spilman,
          Wm. Sands, E.J. Willis, A.R. Holladay, J.B. Taylor, A.J. Crane, &amp;
          J.M. Murray.
        </p>
        <p>Prayer by Rev. E.J. Willis.</p>
        <p>The minutes of the last meeting were approved.</p>
        <p>Absent A.J. Crane.</p>
        <p>
          The Board now proceeded to the consideration of the business for which
          it was convened. The report of the committee appointed at the last
          meeting to consider the subject of completing the College Edifice, 2
          plans were submitted by the committee, and having been discussed by the
          Board on motion of Rev. A.M. Poindexter the following resolutions were
          adopted.
        </p>
        <p>
          Resolved 1.  That the Board will as soon as practicable proceed to build
          upon <PageNumber num={249} /> one of the plans submitted, or to erect one wing of the Main College
          edifice.
        </p>
        <p>
          2.  That the President be instructed to ascertain what the Chicago
          property can be sold for and when it can be made <u>available</u> and as
          soon as he learns; to call a meeting of the Trustees.
        </p>
        <p>Absent Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
        <p>
          On motion a committee composed of Messrs. A.R. Holladay, R.B. Heath and
          L.R. Spilman were appointed a committee to petition the Legislature for
          an appropriation as recommended by the Governor of Va. in his last
          Annual Message.
        </p>
        <p>
          On motion the Treasurer authorized to pay a bill of Mr. Eggeling
          amounting to $300 as per contract entered into with him for ornamenting
          the College Grounds.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President presented a petition from a Mr. Lewis Dart desiring to the
          Trustees to allow him to make such alterations in the Gas Works as to
          greatly to improve them at small cost.  On motion it was refered [sic]
          to the Committee on the Premises to consider and report to the Board.
        </p>
        <p>
          The President also presented the report of the Faculty on Chapel
          Services which was laid upon the table.
        </p>
        <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
        <p>J.M. Murray, Secretary R. Ryland, Prest.</p>

        <PageNumber num={250} />

        <section id="meeting-1860-01-10" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-01-10"> January 10, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            The Semi-Annual Meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held
            this evening at Grace Street Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Rev. J.B. Jeter, J.L. Burrows, Edwin Wortham, Richard Reins,
            A.M. Poindexter, Ro. Ryland, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The report of the President was presented and read.</p>
          <p>Present L.R. Spilman.</p>
          <p>
            On motion Rev. J.B. Jeter was requested to attend a meeting of the
            Committee of the Legislature on Schools and Colleges to be held this
            evening, to represent this College.
          </p>
          <aside>Dr Coons Resigns</aside>
          <p>
            Dr. Coons, through the Rev. J.B. Jeter, offered his resignation as a
            Trustee which was accepted, and motion [sic] A.H. Sands Esq.<aside>A.H Sands Trustee</aside>was
            appointed, Trustee in his stead.
          </p>
          <p>Absent Rev. J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>
            In compliance with recommendation of the President contained in his
            report the following resolution was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved That<aside>President to have grates erected</aside> the President be directed to take such measures as may be
            necessary to warm the rooms comfortably at the smallest expense to the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>Present A.G. Wortham.</p>
          <p>
            So much of the Report of the President as related to future arrangements
            in making of  fires in the Students rooms and of the Board Department
            was laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following bills were ordered to be Settled viz. Jno. B. Glazebrooks
            for making gate, &amp; C.D. Yale &amp; Cos. for repairs of the Furnaces,
            etc.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={251} />
          <p>
            The Committee appointed at the last meeting to make enquiries and to
            report on the expediency of selling now the Chicago property now
            reported, after which the following resolution was adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Chicago property to be sold</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved That the President and W. Goddin be and are hereby appointed a
            Committee to take such measures as are necessary to effect a sale of
            said property as soon as in their judgment it can be done without a
            sacrifice.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Sec'ty</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland<br /> Prest</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1860-03-27">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-03-27"> March 27th, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            evening at the Grace Street Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Rev. Ro. Ryland, A.M. Poindexter, J.B. Taylor, E. Wortham, A.G.
            Wortham, L.W. Seeley, L.R. Spilman, A. Thomas, Richard Reins, J.B.
            Jeter, A.H. Sands &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by  Rev. L.W. Seeley.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The President stated the object of the meeting being to hear the report
            of a committee appointed on Modern Languages, which having been
            submitted through the Chairman Rev. L.W. Seeley and duly considered, was
            adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            <b>Report</b>
          </p>
          <p>
            <b></b>The committe [sic] to whom was referred the report of the Faculty
            of Richmond College, on the subject of incorporating Modern Languages in
            the College Curriculum <PageNumber num={252} /> recommend the adoption of the following Articles regulating the course
            of instruction.
          </p>
          <p>
            1st.      The course of Instruction in the College shall be divided into
            seven Departments, viz., <u>Latin</u>, <u>Greek</u>, <u>Mathematics</u>,
            <u>Natural Science</u>, <u>Moral Science</u>,<u>Modern Languages</u>
            &amp; <u>Hebrew</u>.
          </p>
          <p>
            2nd.     A certificate of Proficiency under the seal of the College
            shall be given to a student who has satisfactorily completed the studies
            of any Department; and in the Department of Modern Languages, to one who
            has completed any <u>one</u>of the languages taught in that Department.
          </p>
          <p>
            3rd.      A Student who has received Certificates of Proficiency in the
            Department of Latin, Greek, Mathematics, Natural Science and Moral
            Science shall be entitled to the degree of A.B.
          </p>
          <p>
            4.         A Student who has received the certificates above mentioned
            as necessary for the degree of A.B. and also certificates of Proficiency
            in two Modern Languages or in Hebrew, shall be entitled to the degree of
            A.M.
          </p>
          <p>
            5th.      A Student who is a candidate for the degree of A.B. shall be
            allowed to substitute one Modern Language or the Hebrew for the
            Calculus; but no such substitution shall be allowed to one who is a
            candidate for the degree of A.M.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following bills were presented and allowed and the Treasurer
            authorized to pay them out of any monies in his hands, not otherwise
            appropriated, G &amp; A Bargamin Jr. $100.75 for grates, &amp;c, Geo
            Minor for fitting up Library room $81.95, Mr. Glinn $62 for brick work <PageNumber num={253} /> W.A. Wyatt $12.00 for painting the same.</p>
          <p>
            On motion of Rev. L.W. Seeley it was ordered that every student entering
            the College shall pay a matriculation fee of $5, and the fund arising
            therefrom shall be appropriated to the increase of the Library.
          </p>
          <aside>Committee on Library</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the President, Rev. L.W. Seeley and A.H. Sands were appointed
            a Committee on the Library, whose duty shall be to select and purchase
            Books and shall report annually to the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following resolutions recommended by the President in his semi
            annual [sic] of<time dateTime="01-06"></time> Jany. 9 were adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            1st.      Resolved that each hotel keeper in future be requested to
            furnish coal to &amp; make fires for his boarders at an advance of 5
            cents a bushel above the price of the coal deliverd [sic] on the 20th of
            September of each year.
          </p>
          <p>
            2d.       That each student be required to deposite [sic] with his
            hotel-keeper $5 for fuel on the 1st of October and $5 on the 1st of
            January, and to settle his bill for fuel in full on the 15th of April.
          </p>
          <p>
            3rd.      Resolved that the rooms now occupied by the furnaces be given
            to each hotel-keeper for keeping his coal.
          </p>
          <p>
            4th.      That each hotel-keeper be required to keep up a fire in three
            of the recitation rooms, on the same terms as those for the students to
            be paid out of the contingent fund.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that Students who are beneficiaries shall be
            required to deposite [sic] the same amount for damages and painting, as
            the other Students.
          </p>
          <p>A communication from Mr. Jno. Kenson <PageNumber num={254} /> of Fluvanna was presented and read and referred to Mr. L.R. Spilman.
          </p>
          <p>After which the Board adjourned,</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Secty</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland<br /> Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1860-04-22">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-04-22"> May 22, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the
            Second Baptist Church this evening, present Ro. Ryland, Edwin Wortham,
            J.B. Jeter, J.L. Burrows, L.R. Spilman, Richd. Reins, A.H. Sands, &amp;
            J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <aside>Prof Owens Resigns.</aside>
          <p>
            The President stated that the meeting was called at the request of Prof.
            Owens who wished to be released by the Trustees, and his resignation
            being presented to the Board on motion of Dr. Burrows it was accepted.
          </p>
          <aside>Tutor Slocum resigns</aside>
          <p>
            The Presedint [sic] also presented the resignation of the Tutor, Mr.
            A.H. Slocum, to take effect from the end of the present session, which
            was accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President presented an account of Mr. Slocumb [sic] amounting to
            $7.30 for sundry necessary repairs, which was ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was received from Mr. Slocumb informing the Board that
            there was a deficit in his Salary for the last session of $34.41, and as
            the Board had guarranteed [sic] that his Salary should not be less than
            $750, it was now ordered the Treasurer should pay the deficit when
            certified by the Treasurer of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the President was requested <PageNumber num={255} /> to have the usual advertisements for a Greek Professor published in the
            City Newspapers, and that the election will take place on the<time dateTime="07-05"></time> 5th of
            July next.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer having informed the Board that he had been called upon by
            the Rev. Samuel Harris for payment of a bond held by him against the
            College, and as no provision had been made for the payment, he asked
            instruction from the Board. On motion the whole matter was left in the
            hands of the Treasurer with instruction to act according to his own
            discretion.
          </p>
          <p>On mow [sic] now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland<br /> Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <div>Annual Meeting<time dateTime="1860-06" className="annual"></time> June 1860,</div>

        <section id="meeting-1860-06-12">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-06-12"> June 12th, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            At an Annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            evening at the Grace Street Baptist Church  Present Ro. Ryland, J.B.
            Taylor, W. Goddin, L.R. Spilman, J.B. Jeter, A.J. Crane, A.H. Sands,
            Edwin Wortham, J.L. Burrows, A.R. Holladay &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter.</p>
          <p>
            On motion of A.J. Crane the reading of the Minutes since the last Annual
            Meeting was dispensed with, those of the last meeting having been read
            were approved.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President presented his Annual report which was read and accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer also presented his report accompanied by the Report of the
            Auditing Committee.  The Report was received, and ordered to be recorded
            with the minutes.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={256} />
          <aside><Link to="../258"> See page 258.</Link></aside>
          <p>
            On motion the Board now proceed to the election of its annual officers,
            whereupon, Rev. Ro. Ryland was reelected Prest.,
          </p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Edwin Wortham, Treasurer</div>
          </footer>
          <p>Wellington Goddin and R.B. Heath Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was instructed to have the usual advertisment
            [sic] made for a Tutor of the Academic Department, the election to take
            [sic] on the 5th of July next, terms same as heretofore.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the Salary of Prof. Chase be made the same
            as the Salary of the other Professors, commencing with the next session.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was authorized to have the College Grounds kept
            in proper order at the expense of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            Th [sic] President presented a communication from Prof. Adkins in regard
            to Salary, &amp;c, upon which the Board declined to act.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Jeter the report of the committee on defining the
            President's duties was called up and having considered was unanimously
            adopted, Mr. A.H. Sands giving notice that at a subsequent meeting he
            would move a reconsideration.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the meeting now adjourned to meet at the call of the
            President.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland<br /> Prest.</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={257} />
