        <section id="meeting-1860-06-11">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-06-11"> June 11, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            The undersigned auditing Committee have examined the accounts of Edwin
            Wortham Treas'r. of Richmond College from the<time dateTime="1859-05-1"></time> 19th May 1859 to the 19th
            May 1860 and find the accounts balanced &amp; properly stated.
          </p>
          <p>The balances on hand are as follows, viz.,</p>
          <p>
            The &quot;Endowment&quot; account shows a balance due by the Treas. of …
            $24,915.66
          </p>
          <p>
            The Bond acct. …<u>8,165.00</u>
          </p>
          <p>33,080.66</p>
          <p>forward,</p>
          <PageNumber num={258} />
          <p>
            (Deduct) Fwd                                              $33,080.66
          </p>
          <p>
            The &quot;Building&quot; acct shows a balance due to the Treas. …
            $31,215.74
          </p>
          <p>
            The &quot;Contingent&quot; acct. …<u>1,495.75      $32,711.49</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            Leaving a balance on all the accts of
            …                                                       $     369.17
          </p>
          <p>
            in the hands of the Treasr., of three hundred and sixty nine dollars and
            seventeen cents.
          </p>
          <p>
            We have examined the &quot;investment&quot; list, and find all the
            stocks and bonds therein referred to, are in the hands of the Treasr.,
            and properly labelled [sic] and safely kept.
          </p>
          <p>All which is respectfully submitted</p>
          <p>(Signed) W. Goddin, Committee</p>
          <p>
            <b>
              <u>Duties of the President</u>
            </b>
          </p>
          <div>Adopted<time dateTime="1860-06-12"> June 12, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            The Committee to whom was referred the subject of defining the
            President's duties beg leave to submit the following:
          </p>
          <p>Report.</p>
          <p>
            Whereas the President of the College is from his office its recognized
            functional head and executive officer, to whom a general superintendence
            is committed, and upon whom a general responsibility as to the Trustees,
            faculty, students and the public devolves; and whereas it is important
            to the efficiency &amp; prosperity of the College that there should be
            unity of administration, a well defined and stable policy of management,
            therefore:
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved I --That the Trustees hereby invest the President with official
            authority to superintend and enforce the general discipline and
            management of the College, in all its departments, and that they will
            sustain him in the judicious exercise of such authority <PageNumber num={259} /> that they regard him as the official organ of communication between
            themselves and the faculty, and the students and that they will give due
            consideration, to the plans and suggestions for promoting the interests
            of the College which he may from time to time present.
          </p>
          <p>
            II.  That his official position requires him to observe and direct and
            by all proper methods promote the efficiency of all the students in all
            the classes and that he be required therefore occasionally to attend
            upon all the recitations of all the classes making such enquiries and
            suggestions as he may deem necessary or profitable.
          </p>
          <p>
            Provided that nothing in this resolution shall be construed as
            interfering with the rights of any professor, in the special control of
            his own department in the selection of text books, methods of
            instruction, standards of merit &amp; proficiency or discipline of the
            classroom.
          </p>
          <p>
            III.  That when occasion shall arise for any extra services, not
            specifically devolving upon any particular member of the faculty, or
            when there shall be difficulty as to adjusting conflicting studies or
            hours of recitation of the several classes after consultation with the
            faculty or with the students or Professors interested the decision of
            the President shall be final.
          </p>
          <p>
            IV.  That the President be requested from time to time to visit the
            hotels and observe that the tables and fare and the conduct of the <PageNumber num={260} /> students are in accordance with the regulations of the College, and
            that he and the Professors, as he may request, shall from time to time
            visit the rooms of the resident students with a view to their neatness
            and good order and to the general behaviour [sic] of their occupants.
          </p>
          <p>
            V.  That all incidental repairs needed on the College premises, during
            term time, be ordered according to his judgment by the President.
          </p>
          <p>
            VI.  That at each annual meeting of the Board of Trustees, the President
            be required to present a report of the Condition and operations of the
            College and to give his views frankly as to the efficiency and
            suitableness of each College officer in his separate department, and
            such other information or suggestions as he may deem important  to the
            prosperity of the School and the effective working of its several
            departments.
          </p>
          <p>
            VIII. [sic]  That a copy of these resolutions be placed in the hands of
            the faculty and of the Hotel Keepers.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={261} />
          <p>
            <u>
              The minutes of this meeting should have been recorded after the next.
            </u>
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1860-07-05">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-07-05"> July 5, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            At an adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon for the purpose of electing a Greek Professor and Tutor of the
            Academic Department.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, A. Thomas, J.B. Jeter, Jas B. Taylor, A.J. Coons, R.
            Reins, A. G. Wortham, L. R. Spilman, J. Burrows, E.J. Willis, T.J.
            Evans, Edwin Wortham, A.R. Holladay, W. Goddin &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. E.J. Willis.</p>
          <p>
            The President presented the applications for professor and testimonials
            of the candidates for Greek Professorship, which being read<aside>Greek Professor</aside> and
            considered, the Board<aside>W.T Lockthan</aside> proceded to cast their ballots, and it was found
            that no one of the Candidates had received a majority of the votes.
            Thereupon the Board proceeded to cast the second ballot, which being
            counted it was found that Mr. Wm.T. Lockthan had received 10 out of 15,
            the whole number cast. He was accordingly declared duly elected to the
            professorship of Greek in the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President now presented the applications and recommendations of the
            Candidates for the Tutorship, which having<aside>Tutor</aside> also been read, and the vote
            taken by ballot, it was found that Mr. Chs S. Yarbrough had received a
            majority of the ballots, he was declared duly elected Tutor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee on Building appointed at the last meeting presented the
            following report which was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>Report</p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed by the Board of Trustees of Richmond College to
            consider and report on the expedience and practicability of immediately
            entering the Centre Building of the College Edifice <PageNumber num={262} /> having given the subject such consideration as they were able, beg
            leave to submit the following report.
          </p>
          <aside>On completing College Edifice</aside>
          <p>
            That the interest and prosperity of the College manifestly require, that
            suitable rooms should be provided for Library, Laboratory - Chapel -
            Society Halls and Recitation Rooms all of which are now either entirely
            wanting or sadly inadequate to the needs of the institution. They
            consider these additional apartments essential to the progressive
            efficiency of the School. The admirable plan of the Center Building
            provides suitable accommodations for all these purposes.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your Committee also report that having conferred with some of the Master
            builders of the City, they are assured that the Buildings can be erected
            during the present season, enclosed by the<time dateTime="10-01"></time> first of October, and
            completed by the<time dateTime="1861-01-01"></time> first of January, 1861.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your Committee therefore recommend that a Building Committee be
            appointed and instructed to advertise for proposals for the erection and
            completion of the Main Central Building of the College Edifice according
            to the plan and specifications of the architect as speedily as may be
            prudently practicable.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your Committee further report that they have reason to believe that the
            building can be erected and completed by giving the notes of the College
            (bearing interest) payable at four, eight, twelve and sixteen months
            from the date of completion of the building.
          </p>
          <p>
            They therefore respectfully recommend that in order to meet such notes
            when <PageNumber num={263} /> matured, the property owned by the College in Chicago be sold by the
            Agent of the Trustees, that the land owned by the College in Henrico,
            lying south of Franklin Street and north of the old Scuffletown road, be
            also sold, and the proceeds applied towards the cost of erecting the
            Central Building, and that whatever additional amount may be needed to
            meet the liabilities incurred, be raised from any uninvested funds in
            the hands of the Treasurer, from such bonds yet unpaid as may be
            collected, or from such invested fund as may be legally appropriated to
            this object or by loan to be replaced at such time as may be prescribed
            by the Board of Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>All of which is respectfully submitted</p>
          <p>(Signed)</p><footer className='rightStacked'><div className="signature">J.L. Burrows</div>
            <div className="signature">Ewd J. Willis</div>
            <div className="signature">Thos. J. Evans</div>
            <div className="signature">W. Goddin</div>
          </footer>
          <aside>Building Committee</aside>
          <p>
            On motion a committee consisting of J.L. Burrows, W. Goddin &amp; L.R.
            Spilman was appointed to carry the foregoing report into effect.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was appointed Agent for the purpose of
            collecting funds during the present vacation for the benefit of the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter the following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That a committee of three members be appointed to report on
            the propriety of establishing a Law Department in connection with
            Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>The President appointed Mr. Crane, Mr. Holladay, AR, the Committee.</p>
          <p>On motion the meeting adjourned.  </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={264} />
          <p>
            <u>
              The minutes of this meeting should have been recorded after the last.
            </u>
          </p>
        </section>

