        <section id="meeting-1860-12-11" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1860-12-11"> December 11, 1860</time></div>
          <p>
            The regular semi-annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was
            held this evening at the house of Mr. James Thomas, Jr.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Rev. Ro. Ryland, Jas. Thomas, Jr., Rev. J.B. Taylor, Rev. J.B.
            Jeter, R.B. Heath, Edwin Wortham, L.R. Spilman, A.H. Sands, J.L. Burrows
            and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President presented his semi-annual report which was received.</p>
          <p>
            The Chairman of the Building Committee, Rev. J.L. Burrows that no
            definite arrangements had been made in regard to the completion of the
            College edifice<aside>Completing College Buildingdeferred state of the country!</aside> owing to the high price of work and the peculiar state
            of affairs of the country, and then on motion of Dr. Jeter committee was
            discharged and the purpose of building was postponed for the present.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President having been appointed agent to collect funds in behalf of
            the College during the last vacation, reported that from physical
            inability, &amp;c. he had done nothing except visiting several
            Associations.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee to consider the proposal of establishing a Law department,
            made a verbal report, and motion was continued and Mr. Heath added to
            the committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer reported to the meeting that he had been notified by Mr.
            H. Sims that he would call for payment of the bond due him by the
            College, during the present month, but that he had not funds enough in
            hand to pay it. On <PageNumber num={267} /> motion, the Treasurer and President were appointed a committee to
            make such arrangements with Mr. Harris as they deem best.
          </p>
          <p>After which the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1861-01-17">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1861-01-17"> January 17, 1861</time></div>
          <p>
            At called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this evening
            at Grace Street Baptist Church, present Ro. Ryland, A. Thomas, A.G.
            Wortham, J.B. Taylor, R. Reins, A.M. Poindexter, J.L. Burrows and J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor</p>
          <p>
            The President presented a communication<aside>Prof Louthan Resigns.</aside> from Prof. Louthan offering his
            resignation of the Professorship of Greek in the College owing to the
            failure of his health.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the following preamble and resolutions offered by Rev. A.M.
            Poindexter were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereas the fracture of his health has caused<aside>Complementary Resolutions</aside> Prof. Louthan to tender
            his resignation as professor of Greek in Richmond College. Therefore,
            Resolved  That the Board regret the cessation of his connection with the
            College, and tender to him their sincere sympathy in his affliction,
            with the hope that he may be soon restored to health.
          </p>
          <p>2.  That his resignation be accepted.</p>
          <p>3.  That the Secretary transmit a copy of these resolutions to him.</p>
          <p>
            He suggested that Mr. Crawford H. Toy would be a suitable person to
            supply the vacancy this created in the faculty, but <PageNumber num={268} /> that he was endeavoring to raise funds for the purpose of being sent
            as a missionary<aside>C.H Toy Elected Professor</aside> to Japan, and it was probable only a conditional
            arrangement could be made with him. On motion he was unanimously
            appointed to supply the vacancy in the Department of Greek with the
            proviso that should he desire at any time during the session to be
            released for the purpose of going to Japan, the Board would comply with
            his request.
          </p>
          <p>Absent A. Thomas &amp; A.G. Wortham.</p>
          <p>
            The President presented a petition from Lindsay (Hotel Keeper)
            requesting the Trustees<aside>to pay</aside> a bill incurred in having closet built in his
            hotel, as the work was done without authority from the Board, and for
            Mr. Lindsay’s own convenience, the Board refused to pay it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following resolutions offered by Rev. A.M. Poindexter were adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            1.  Resolved  That the President of the College be, and he is hereby
            instructed by private correspondence, to look out and recommend to the
            Board one or more persons suitable in his judgment to become a permanent
            Professor of Greek in the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            2.  That it is desirable, if not absolutely necessary, that such
            Professor be a member of a Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution by same, was also adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That the Treasurer of the<aside>Treasurer to pay bills not authenticated</aside> be and is hereby instructed
            hereafter to pay out no money unless upon bills property certified.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={269} />
          <p>
            A communication was presented through Rev. A.M. Poindexter from Dr. A.J.
            Coons relation to Mr. E. Adkins late Professor of Greek in the College,
            and the following action taken.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereas a letter from Dr. A.J. Coons of St. Louis, Mo. to Rev. A.M.
            Poindexter and a statement from Prof. Adkins late Professor in Richmond
            College have been laid before the Board, from which it appears that
            Prof. Adkins claims to have sustained a loss of not less than $200.00 by
            reason of his connection with the College and whereas it is stated in
            the letter of Dr. Coons that Prof. Adkins has some doubt as to the<aside>Adkins appeal</aside>
            feelings of the Board towards him as a reason why it might be proper to
            make an appropriation for his benefit.
          </p>
          <p>
            <u>Therefore</u>
            1st  That the Board cherish the kindest feelings toward Prof. Adkins,
            late Professor of Greek in Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>
            2nd -- That the Board do not recognize any <u>moral,</u>as certainly
            they are under no <u>legal</u>, obligation to refund to Prof. Adkins any
            loss which he may have sustained in consequence of his connection with
            the College since he accepted the apportionment after explicit
            information from the President as to what he would be entitled from the
            endowment fund and what amount had been paid, the previous year from the
            tuition fees to his predecessor.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1861-08-15">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1861-08-15"> August 15, 1861</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of the College was held this evening.
            Present Ro. Ryland, E. Wortham, L.W. Seeley, J.B. Taylor, A.H. Sands, W.
            Goddin, &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={270} />
          <p>
            Prof. Dabney being present, was invited to a seat and to take part in
            its deliberations.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Seeley</p>
          <p>
            The President presented his annual report which was received and laid on
            the table for consideration.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented his annual report, accompanied by the report of
            the Auditing Committee, showing the following stocks to be now held by
            the College, viz.
          </p>
          <p>38,800             Richmond City Stock</p>
          <p>19,882             Virginia State Stock</p>
          <p>500             Farmers Bank Va Stock    (5 shares)</p>
          <p>500              Town of Portsmouth</p>
          <p>500              Town of Petersburg   State Guar &amp; Coupon</p>
          <p>8,500              Town of Petersburg</p>
          <p>20              Fire Association    (1 share)</p>
          <p>140              Bank of Va. Stock</p>
          <p>600              Central Railroad Co.    State guarantee</p>
          <p>3,600              Corporation Lynchburg</p>
          <p>500              Chesapeake &amp; Ohio Canal State guarantee</p>
          <p>
            <u>3,500</u>Virginia &amp; Tennessee bonds
          </p>
          <p>$77,042           Seventy seven thousand and forty two Dollars.</p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer was authorized to collect a bond due by the City of
            Richmond and to invest the same in state stock.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Auditing Committee reported that they had assessed the account of
            Lewis Turner, Treasurer of the Faculty for the sessions of 1858-1859 and
            for 1859-1860 and found them (except in a few small items) sustained by
            proper vouchers.  The accounts for<time dateTime="1858/1859">1858&ndash;1859</time> 1858-1859 show a balance in his favor
            of a few cents, and the accounts for<time dateTime="1859/1860">1859&ndash;1860</time> 1859-1860 are balanced.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President presented a statement of funds received by him for the
            Trustees of the College since<time dateTime="1861-07-09"></time> July 9, 1861. The statement was accepted.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={271} />
          <p>
            A bill of Mr. W.T. Lindsays amounting to $23.17 for fuel furnished was
            allowed and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prof. Wm G. Strange presented his account for monies spent for the
            Laboratory1858-9 which had been examined by the Auditing Committee
            showing a balance due him of $6.32. No report for 1859-1860.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the appropriation heretofore made of $25
            for servants hire to attend the Laboratory be hereafter dispensed with.
          </p>
          <p>
            L. R. Spilman agent apportioned by the Trustees to collect bonds due the
            College reported that had collected      $4303.26
          </p>
          <p>
            By Amount of Compensation &amp;c
            <u>386.03</u>
          </p>
          <p>3917.23</p>
          <p>
            Amt paid Treasurer
            <u>3851.41</u>
          </p>
          <p>Balance due by him $65.82</p>
          <p>The same having been audited by the Committee was received.</p>
          <p>
            A bill of the Messrs Bargamon for repairs was presented which was
            allowed and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board decided that is expedient that the duties of the
            College be resumed on the 1st of October and the President was requested
            to notify the authorities of the Confederate States to that effect, and
            also to have the usual advertisement made in the newspapers, and also to
            have the premises put in proper order.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that when Board adjourned, it would meet again
            at the call of the President.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mr. Lindsay was selected Hotel Keeper and Mr. C.H. Toy was elected
            Professor of Greek and Greek Literature.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={272} />
          <p>
            On motion the Board decided to withhold for the future the guarantee
            $700 as the salary of the Tutor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Board authorized the degree of AB to be conferred on the following
            students,<aside>Graduates</aside> viz on
          </p>
          <p>R.R. Bailey                                         R.S. Lindsay</p>
          <p>C. W. Faruh                                        Geo M. Leftwich</p>
          <p>Geo W. Prince                                    J. M. Pilcher</p>
          <p>W. H. Williams                                   A. B. Woodfin</p>
          <p>&amp; A.P. Woodfin</p>
          <p>Rev. R. Ryland was reelected President of the Board</p>
          <p>Edwin Wortham                     Treasurer</p>
          <p>J.M. Murray                            Secretary</p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that Prof. Toy be requested to give Military
            instruction to the students at such times as he may select during the
            next session.
          </p>
          <p>
            It was decided that it is desirable that the Professors not having
            families should reside on the College premises during the session, and
            the President was requested to inform them of the action of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1862-11-24">
          <div><time dateTime="1862-11-24">November 24, 1862</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond<aside>Selling Stock</aside> College was held this
            afternoon. Present Ro. Ryland, J.B. Jeter, W. Goddin, L.R. Spilman, J.B.
            Taylor, E. Wortham and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter</p>
          <p>
            The President stated the object of the meeting to be to consider the
            propriety of authorizing<aside>Stocks to be sold</aside> the Treasurer to sell certain of the stocks
            belonging to the College, and reinvest the proceeds in 8 percent
            Confederate Bonds. After consultation, the Board determined to postpone,
            action to a fuller meeting to be held <PageNumber num={273} /> next Thursday at 4 Oclock PM. and the Secretary was directed to give
            notice to the absent members of the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was authorized to rent out the premises now
            accepted by Mr. Lindsay provided they were vacated by him. After this,
            the meeting adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1862-11-27">
          <div><time dateTime="1862-11-27">November 27, 1862</time></div>
          <p>
            The Trustees met this evening pursuant to adjournment. Present, Ro.
            Ryland Prest. E. Wortham, L.W. Seeley, A. Snead, W. Sands, T.J. Evans,
            L.R. Spilman &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Seeley</p>
          <aside>Bonds of the College to be sold</aside>
          <p>
            On motion made by L.R. Spilman, the Treasurer was authorized to sell the
            Bonds held by the College, of the City of Richmond, Petersburg and
            Lynchburg and reinvest the proceeds of the sale in 8% confederate Bonds.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President &amp; J.B. Taylor were appointed a committee, to
            have the rent of the College premises increased, and should the present
            occupants refuse to pay the increased rent,the committee was authorized
            to give them legal notice to vacate the same.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={274} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1863-06-15" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1863-06-15"> June 15 1863</time></div>
          <p>
            Annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon. Prayer by Dr. Burrows. Present Ro. Ryland, President, L.W.
            Seeley,  W. Goddin, T.J. Evans, Wm Sands, J.B. Taylor, E. Wortham, L.R.
            Spilman, J.L. Burrows, J.B. Jeter, A.H. Sands &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented his annual report accompanied by that of the
            Auditing Committee certifying its correction. The report was adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>D. Witt Legacy</aside>
          <p>
            The following preamble &amp; resolution were offered by Dr. Jeter, and
            adopted by the meeting. Whereas Rev. Daniel Witt, executor of the will
            of James D. Witt, has paid to the Treasurer of Richmond College the sum
            of two thousand dollars, to be a perpetual investment, the interest of
            which shall be devoted to the education of young men preparing for the
            Ministry in the College, preference to be given to such as may be
            recommended by the Education Board of the Baptist General Association of
            Virginia. Therefore Resolved -- That the Trustees accept the above named
            on the conditions specified, and that the Treasurer be directed to
            invest the same in Confederate bonds, and keep a separate account of it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved -- That the above sum be made the nuclous [sic] of a fund to be
            used for the purpose above stated to be called &quot;The Witt Education
            Fund&quot; and that it shall be the policy of the Trustees to obtain
            contributions to the Fund by bequeath or gifts.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved -- That the Secretary be directed to furnish to Rev D. Witt a
            certified copy of these resolutions.
          </p>
          <p>
            The meeting now proceeded to the election of President, Treasury and
            Secretary of the <PageNumber num={275} /> Board for the next twelve months whereupon Ro. Ryland was elected
            President. Edwin Wortham was elected Treasurer and J.M. Murray,
            Secretary.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee to rent out the College premises reported that they were
            unable to get the desired increase in rent. On motion the Committee was
            increased by adding AH Sands and the following resolution adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Committee be authorized to give absolute notice to the
            tenants to quit or take any other legal step to get possession of the
            property, deemed proper by them, and the Committee be authorized to rent
            out the College buildings to the persons holding the same now or to any
            others, at the best price the[y] can secure.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the President was allowed to continue to occupy the building
            at present occupied by him free of rent.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the holding of the premises by Mr. Lindsay which he now
            occupies was referred to a committee consisting of Jas B. Taylor and
            A.H. Sands.
          </p>
          <p>After this the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <u><div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div></u>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1863-10-20">
          <div><time dateTime="1863-10-20">October 20, 1863</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Mission
            rooms of the first Baptist Church on the <time dateTime="1863-10-20"></time>20th October, 1863.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, President, Jas B. Taylor, J.L. Burrows, W. Sands,
            Wellington Goddin, L.R. Spilman &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President having explained the object of the meeting the following
            preamble and resolutions were adapted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereas the late James C. Crane of the city did by his last will and
            testament, leave to the Trustees of Richmond College in a <PageNumber num={276} /> certain contingency, the sum of $10,000 and whereas Wm. H. Gwaltney
            Exr. of the said Crane has filed a bill in Chancery against this Board
            and others in the Circuit Court of Richmond Va of the object of which
            suit is to have the transactions of the said Executor (affirmed?) by the
            Court and to make a settlement of the estate.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved -- That the President be and is hereby instructed to answer and
            say in behalf of the Board of Trustees, that so far as they have any
            interest or concern in the matters stated in the said bill, they are
            willing to admit the same to be true, and that they have no objection to
            the relief prayed for in the said bill, by the said complainant.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President submitted a letter from J.H.C. Jones one of the executors
            of the late Wm S. Nunn dec'd. announcing his willingness to pay to the
            Trustees of the College the legacy of $2,000 left by the dec'd. to the
            College, on condition that the usual refunding be given to the said
            executor.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereupon it was resolved that on the payment of the said legacy, the
            Treasurer of Richmond College on behalf of the Trustees be authorized to
            execute the refunding bond referred to.
          </p>
          <p>
            On application having been made to the President for the loan of books
            from the Library of the College -- it was resolved that it is
            inexpedient to grant the said request.
          </p>
          <aside>R.B Heath deal</aside>
          <p>
            The death of one of the Trustees, R.B. Heath, was announced by the
            President, whereupon the following resolution was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved -- That we receive with profound regret, the intelligence of
            the death of Roscoe B. Heath, Esq., for sometime [sic] an esteemed
            member of the Board, and that the President be requested to convey to
            his family our high appreciation of his worth and our sincere
            condolences with them in their heavy affliction.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={277} />
          <p>
            The President stated that N.H. Massie on behalf of the Executor of
            [blank space] dec'd. had paid to the Treasurer of the College the legacy
            bequeathed by her to the College amounting to $[blank space]
          </p>
          <p>
            Rev. Jas B. Taylor on behalf of the Committee of the College buildings,
            made a report to the following effect. That the committee had made a
            rental of the College building to the Louisianna [sic] Hospital
            Association for $3,000 per annum, and the Stewards building recently
            occupied by Mr. Lindsay to Mr. Carl Eukes for $400 per annum.
          </p>
          <p>On motion adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1863-11-21">
          <div> <time dateTime="1863-11-21">November 21, 1863</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees was held this afternoon at Grace Street
            Baptist Church. Present, Robert Ryland, Prest., A.H. Sands, E. Wortham,
            L.R. Spilman, J.B. Jeter, T.J. Evans, W. Goddin and J. M. Murray. Prayer
            by A.H. Sands
          </p>
          <p>
            The President stated that the Surgeon General had broken up the hospital
            at the College, and that Mr. Sulley, the Agent of the Association which
            rented the buildings, offered to give them up to the Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee was appointed with full power to act in the matter
            of taking the property back and renting or not as they deemed best, the
            President, W. Goddin &amp; A.H. Sands were appointed to the Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was authorized to invest the funds he has or may
            have in hand belonging to College in Confederate Bonds.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion Col T.J. Evans was appointed to represent the Board, in any
            interest the Board may have in the will of the late Mary Muse, dec'd.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer className='rightStacked'>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={278} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1865-07-24">
          <p>
            A [sic] a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the house
            of A.H. Sands <time dateTime="1865-07-24">July 24, 1865.</time>
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, Prest. J.B. Jeter, E. Wortham, A.H. Sands, W.
            Goddin, J.B. Taylor, L.R. Spilman, Wm Sands, A. Snead &amp; T.J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>T. J. Evans was appointed Secretary pro temp.</p>
          <p>On motion of Wm. Sands, the following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved that a School be opened at the College buildings on the 1st of
            October with two teachers.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Edwin Wortham Rev. Ro. Ryland was appointed one of the
            teachers, and on motion of A.H. Sands, Geo E. Dabney was appointed the
            other, with authority to them to appoint such other teachers as may be
            necessary for the coming year.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Rev. J. B. Taylor.         Resolved that the entire
            premises be placed under the Control of the two teachers for 1 year from
            <time dateTime="1865-10-01">October the 1st 1865</time>, with the understanding that they appropriate the
            proceeds of the rents to the repairs of the College premises, the
            payment of <u>insurance</u>and incidental expenses.
          </p>
          <p>Signed T.J. Evans, Sec. pro tem. Ro. Ryland, Prest.</p>
          <PageNumber num={279} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-03-26">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1866-03-26"> March 26, 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at Grace Street
            Baptist Church this afternoon, present Ro. Ryland, President., J.B.
            Jeter, L.R. Spilman, J.L. Burrows, W. Goddin, Jas B. Taylor and J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer was offered by Rev. J.B. Jeter</p>
          <p>
            The President laid before the Board a communication from Messrs. Ogden
            &amp; Co. Agents of the College at Chicago proposing the sale of a small
            strip of the lot belonging to the College, which had detached by the
            extension of a street.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board sanctioned the sale and the President was authorized
            to communicate this decision to the agents and also to instructed them
            to defer the sale of the remaining land till further advice from the
            Trustees.
          </p>
          <aside>Pr Ryland offer to Resign</aside>
          <p>
            The President presented a communication resigning whatever connection he
            might have with the College which having been read, was laid upon the
            table to be considered.  Meeting to be held this day 2 weeks.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secy</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={280} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-04-09">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-04-09" > April 9, 1866 </time></div>
          <p>
            An adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at the house of A.H. Sands.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present. W. Goddin, James Thomas, Jr., Jas B. Taylor, A.G. Wortham,
            Edwin Wortham, L.R. Spilman, A. Snead and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer was made by Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            The President being absent, W. Goddin, was called to the Chair as
            President pro tem.  The minutes of the last meeting were read and
            approved.
          </p>
          <p>
            The object of the meeting being to consider the communication of the
            President presented at the last meeting of the Board resigning his
            connection with the College. On motion the communication was taken up
            and having been considered was laid upon the table till the next annual
            meeting for final action.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that<aside>Ryland to Remain till<time dateTime="1866-10" > Oct. 1866</time></aside> Dr. Ryland be requested to remain and have
            charge of the College premises, free of all charge till the 1st day of
            October next, and the Secretary be requested to inform him officially of
            this action. After which the meeting adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="pencil signature">To be signed by W. Goddin</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={281} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-06-12" className="annual">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1866-06-12">June 12, 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            The regular annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held
            this afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church.  Prayers by Rev. T.
            Hume.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, Pres., A.M. Poindexter, A. Snead, James Thomas, I.L.
            Burrows, T.J. Evans, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, Thomas Hume, Wm.
            Sands, T.J. Evans, L.R. Spilman, R. Reins, J.B. Taylor &amp; J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following gentlemen friends of the College, being present, were
            invited to seats and participation in the meeting. Viz. Rev. C.C.
            Chaplin,<aside>Rev ?</aside> Rev. J. C. Long, Rev. Harvey Hatcher and Messrs. A.M. Bailey
            and J.P. Ballard.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and adopted.</p>
          <aside>Death of Trustees announced</aside>
          <p>
            The president announced the deaths of the following members of the Board
            of Trustees.  Viz. Archibald Thomas, C.F. Fisher, Lewis Minor Coleman.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Ryland vacated the chair having called upon Dr. Snead to act as
            Chairman and retired from the meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>Rylands Resignation accepted</aside>
          <p>The following resolutions offered by Dr. Burrows were adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved the resignation of Rev. Ro. Ryland, D.D. as President of
            Richmond College be accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that Dr. Ryland be affectionately requested to retain his
            position as Trustee of the College.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={282} />
          <p>
            Resolved  That Rev. Drs. Taylor and Jeter be requested to prepare a
            paper expressive of the gratitude of the Trustees for the faithfulness
            and devotion which Dr. Rylan has manifested in promoting the interest of
            College to be inserted in the minutes and published in the Religious
            Herald and the daily papers of this City.
          </p>
          <p>The following offered by A.M. Poindexter were adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the use of the house<aside>Use of house & granted Dr Ryland</aside> and lot on the corner of Franklin
            Street and College Avenue be tendered to President Ryland for the
            occupancy of his family free of rent until the first day of September
            1867 with expression of the earnest wish of the Board that he may find
            it convenient to accept it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Secretary transmit to President Ryland a copy of these
            Resolutions.
          </p>
          <aside>Annual Election</aside>
          <p>
            The Board now proceeded to ballot for its annual officers which being
            counted, Rev. Ro. Ryland was declared elected President of the Board,
            Edwin Wortham, Treasurer and J.M. Murray, Secretary.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurer Annual Report</aside>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented his annual rept which being read was received
            and ordered to be filled [sic]
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Thos. J. Evans the Treasurer was authorized to change the
            balance which being in Confederate money to <PageNumber num={283} /> account of profit and loss.</p>
          <aside>Trustees Elected Ballard Ryland Long Jones</aside>
          <p>
            Messrs. John P. Ballard, Josiah Ryland, Revs. John C. Long and T.G.
            Jones were unanimously elected Trustees to fill some of the vacancies in
            the Board of Trustees.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustees Droped</aside>
          <p>
            The following gentlemen were nominated to fill other vacancies, which
            was laid upon the table till next meeting. Viz. Dr. R.T. Coleman, A.M.
            Bailey, C.T. Wortham, A.R. Courtney, H. K. Ellyson, J.B. Watkins, David
            Shaver.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following names were dropped from the list of Trustees, in
            accordance with authority granted by the Charter, on account of
            neglecting to attend the meeting of the Trustees, or removable [sic]
            from the state. Samuel G. Mason, Thos. N. Welch, Rev. L.W. Seeley, Rev.
            Basil Manly, A. Judson Crane, Rev. Jno A. Broadus.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary, the President and T.J. Evans were appointed a committee
            to report at the next meeting on the vacancies in the Board and
            nominations to fill the same.
          </p>
          <aside>Committee on New organization</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows, a committee was ordered to be appointed to
            recommend a plan for a new organization of the College. The President
            appointed Dr. Burrows, James Thomas and J.B. Jeter the Committee.
          </p>
          <p>Absent Dr. Snead and E. Wortham.</p>
          <p>
            The attention of the Board was called to the following action taken by
            the General Association at its last annual meeting.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={284} />
          <p>
            &quot;Resolved, that in the opinion of this body&quot;,<aside>Motion of General Association</aside> the exercises of
            Richmond College sought to be assumed at the beginning of the next
            session.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that this should be done in such a way and under such auspices
            as to give a reasonable assurance that the institution is to be one
            worthy of the character and suitable to the wants of the Baptist
            denomination.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the General Association tender to the Board of Trustees of
            Richmond College the subscription just made, and request the Board to
            take immediate steps to increase it to a sum not less than one hundred
            thousand ($100,000) dollars.
          </p>
          <aside>A.M Poindexter appointed General Agent</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows Rev. A.M. Poindexter was appointed Agent to
            raise our endowment of one hundred thousand dollars at a salary of
            twenty-five hundred dollars and travelling expenses.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of James Thomas, the further sum of twenty-five hundred
            dollars appropriated to be used by the agent in employing aid in raising
            the endowment provided he could find suitable aid.
          </p>
          <p>Absent Dr. Burrows</p>
          <p>
            Resolutions in regard to the manner of raising the endowment were read
            and committed to a committee consisting of L.R. Spilman, T. J. Evans and
            A.R. Holladay to report at the next meeting.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned to meet call President [sic].</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Jas. B. Taylor, Secy.</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">Dr Snead</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={285} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-06-20">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-06-20"> June 20<sup>th</sup>1866</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church. Present Ro. Ryland,
            President, Jas Thomas, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, Wm. Sands, A. Snead,
            James B. Taylor, J.B. Jeter, J.M. Murray, W. Goddin.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The following communication from Rev. A.M. Poindexter was laid before
            the meeting.
          </p>
          <div>Halifax C.H. Va.,<time dateTime="1866-06-18"> June 18, 1866</time></div>
          <p>To the Trustees of Richmond College, Richmond, Va</p>
          <p>Gentlemen</p>
          <p>
            Although I have not<aside>Poindexter Accepts Agency</aside> received official notification of my election as
            agent for the College, yet having been present when the election was
            made and as another Board has requested my services and is anxious for
            an early decision I address you this, trusting it will not be regarded
            as premature or indelicate.
          </p>
          <p>
            While I would prefer other service which is offered me, yet the
            necessity for prompt in [sic] vigorous in behalf of the College decides
            me to accept the agency for it provided the Board meet necessary
            expenses and the conditions which I now specify are acceptable.
          </p>
          <p>
            1st, I must be supplied by the Board with whatever funds are needed <PageNumber num={286} /> for outfit and traveling expenses and such portions of salary as I
            may need from time to time.
          </p>
          <p>
            2nd, I am to be allowed full discretion as to expenses, and also as to
            the time which I may spend with my family -- No part of the expenses are
            to be deducted from my Salary.
          </p>
          <p>
            3rd, I am to have full authority to engage at the cost of the Board such
            assistance as I may find necessary to the speedy and successful
            consummation of the objects of the agency.
          </p>
          <p>
            I am thus explicit, because I cannot myself advance the money necessary
            for outfit &amp;c and unless the Board can do so, shall thereby be
            estopped from engaging the work and because regarding the other matters
            an explicit understanding now will prevent liability to misunderstanding
            hereafter.
          </p>
          <p>
            Should the appointment under the above condition be confirmed, I shall
            be willing to enter upon active services as soon as I can arrange my
            private affairs for that purpose.
          </p>
          <p>An immediate reply is respectfully requested.</p>
          <p>Yours respectfully,</p>
          <p>A.M. Poindexter</p>
          <p>
            On motion the Secretary was instructed to inform A.M. Poindexter the
            Board accepted the conditions as set forth in his letter above, and
            confirmed the apportionment.
          </p>
          <p>The following Resolutions offered by W. Goddin were adopted.</p>
          <PageNumber num={287} />
          <p>
            Resolved that the Treasurer of the College be instructed to borrow from
            one<aside>Treasurer to borrow $1000.</aside> of the Banks in this City or from some other source, the sum of
            $1,000 and to hypothecate enough of the Va. State Stock held by the
            College as shall be sufficient to secure the same.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that W. Goddin be requested<aside>Chicago Property</aside> to open a correspondence with our
            agents in Chicago, Ogden Fleetwood &amp;c relative to the expediency of
            selling at an early day, the lots in that City belonging to the College
            -- and that said agents be instructed to sell said lots at auction
            without delay unless in their opinion a sale at this time would be
            injurious.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that W. Goddin be requested to call upon the
            proper officers of the different Rail Road companies in this State and
            request them to furnish free tickets to the Agents of the College whilst
            in the prosecution of their labors.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed for the purpose presented the following paper
            which was unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereas the resignation of Rev. Ro. Ryland as President of Richmond
            College tendered on the 25th March, and after due consideration it
            having been accepted,
          </p>
          <p>Therefore as the sense of the Trustees be it Resolved</p>
          <p>
            I.  That the unselfish devotion of President Ryland to the interest of
            the College from its foundation to the present time meets the gratitude
            of its friends and <PageNumber num={288} /> all the friends of education in Virginia amid all the struggles, he
            has pursued<aside>Complimentary Resolution to Dr. Ryland</aside> the same undeviating course seeking only to promote its
            elevation and to extend its influence. The large numbers of its alumni
            filling various positions of usefulness in this state and in other
            states are witnesses of the sound, liberal education secured within its
            walls under his administration. The Baptist Churches of the South are
            especially indebted to him for the judicious training through which many
            of their most esteemed and efficient Ministers have passed while
            identified with the College. These Ministers in common with other
            classes of students, have not ceased to bear towards him, as their
            faithful instructor, feelings of unfeigned respect and reverence.
          </p>
          <p>
            II.  In sundering the relation which has so long and so pleasantly
            subsisted, the Trustees hereby express their sincere and unabated
            personal esteem for the many excellencies of character uniting in their
            late President. They will not cease to follow him with their best wishes
            for the prosperity of himself and family and to pray that he may yet see
            many years of usefulness and happiness in his endeavors to promote the
            cause of education and the interests of religion.
          </p>
          <p>
            III.  That the Secretary be instructed to transmit to President Ryland a
            copy of the above preamble and resolutions.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That the above be published in the Religious Herald and other
            papers of the City --
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={289} />
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was instructed to pay out of any funds in hand
            not<aside>Treasurer to Pay Insurance</aside> otherwise appropriated, one hundred dollars due for insurance on the
            College Building and one hundred dollars for renewal of the insurance.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-07-05">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-07-05"> July 5, 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church. Present, Ro. Ryland, Rev.
            A.M. Poindexter, Wm. Sands, A.G. Wortham, A. Snead, Edwin Wortham, J.B.
            Taylor, J.B. Jeter, L.R. Spilman, J.L. Burrows, James Thomas, Jr.,
            Josiah Ryland, R. Reins and J.M. Murray. (Josiah Ryland having
            qualified)
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and adopted.</p>
          <p>
            The committee on the plan of raising the endowment presented their
            referral which<aside>Have The Endowment to be raised</aside> was adopted as follows.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved I.      That the Board accept the subscriptions tendered by the
            General Association of the Baptists of Virginia and will proceed at once
            to take measures to obtain the sum of one hundred thousand dollars, as
            an endorsement for the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            II.        That the said sum of one hundred thousand dollars be sought
            in subscriptions of $100 or over, but that subscriptions of smaller
            amounts may at the option of the Board, be counted as part of said
            amount of one hundred thousand dollars.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={290} />
          <p></p>
          <p>
            III.       That bonds be taken with interest at 6 per cent per annum,
            payable in five annual installments -- the interest to commence from the
            1st day of June 1866. The first installment to be payable on the 1st day
            of June 1867 provided that the agents of the College may vary the terms
            of payment and the number of installments to suit the wishes of the
            subscribers.
          </p>
          <p>
            IV.       That any person paying the interest on his or her bond
            promptly and without cost to the College, the Board will not enforce
            payment of principal on any part thereof.
          </p>
          <p></p>
          <aside>Bond</aside>
          <p>
            L.R. Spilman and A.M. Poindexter were appointed committee to prepare the
            form of bond to be used.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee on Organization now<aside>Report Committee on Organization</aside> presented their report which having
            been amended was adopted as follows.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee on organization of Richmond College recommend to the
            Trustees, the names of the following gentlemen for election as Faculty
            of the College. Viz.
          </p>
          <p>General J.B. Gordon, President</p>
          <p>
            <u>Professors</u>
          </p>
          <p>John Heart                   A.M.</p>
          <p>Crawford Toy             A.M.</p>
          <p>H. H. Harris                A.M.</p>
          <p>Bennett Puryear          A.M.</p>
          <p>
            They recommend that Mr. Toy be elected to fill such chair as may be
            decided upon when he shall have returned from Germany, whither he has
            gone to prosecute further studies preparatory to the great work to which
            he has devoted his life --
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={291} />
          <p>
            The committee further recommend that as soon as a Faculty shall have<aside>Professor to student plan for studies graduation. <Link to="../302"><span className="pencil">See 302</span></Link></aside>
            been secured, they be requested to submit to the Board a plan of studies
            and graduation for the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee further recommend that the Salary of the President be
            $2,000 and the salaries of the Professors $1,000 each to be supplemented
            by the addition of $300 to each Professor the first year and an equal
            division of the fees received from the students for tuition.
          </p>
          <p>
            They also recommend that all the buildings and grounds except the house
            and ground reserved for Dr. Ryland be placed at the disposition and
            control of the Faculty, they keeping them in repair and making such
            arrangements for residences and for boarding students as they may deem
            best.
          </p>
          <div
            style={{
              display: 'flex',
              justifyContent: "flex-end"
            }}
          >
            <div>Signed</div>
            <ul
              style={{
                margin: 0,
                listStyle: 'none',
              }}
            >
              <li>J.L. Burrows</li>
              <li>Jas Thomas, Jr.</li>
              <li>J.B. Jeter</li>
            </ul>
            <div className='tripledSize'>{'}'}</div>
            <div className='tripledLineHeight'>Committee</div>
          </div>
          <p>
            The following communication from the Treasurer was received and ordered
            to be spread on the Minutes with the thanks of the Board.
          </p>
          <div>&quot;Richmond<time dateTime="1866-07-23"> 23 June 1866</time></div>
          <p>To the Trustees of Richmond College </p>
          <p>Gent.</p>
          <p>
            I wish it understood that since the last entry on the Book of the
            Treasurer of Richmond College, I have made no charge or claim for Salary
            as Treasurer from the Board of Trustees, and will not for the future
            until the labors of the office become so onerous and troublesome as to
            require me <PageNumber num={292} /> to do so for which I will give due notice to the Board.</p>
          <p>(Signed) Respectfully,</p>
          <p>Edwin Wortham</p>
          <p>
            Application from Mrs. Farly to be released from the payment of a portion
            of the rent due by her to the Trustees, was referred to the President
            for settlement.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee on organization was instructed to communicate to the
            Professors about the fact of their appointment.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer was authorized to pay the bill for printing of Blanks used
            by the Secretary.
          </p>
          <aside>RT Coleman Trustee</aside>
          <p>
            On motion made by J.L. Burrows, Dr. R.T. Coleman was elected a Trustee
            of Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>There being no other business the Board adjourned.</p>
          <p>J. M. Murray, Secretary Ro. Ryland, Pres't.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-07-24">
          <div>Tuesday<time dateTime="1866-07-24"> July 24 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present -- James Thomas, Jr., Edwin Wortham, Richard Reins Wellington
            Goddin, Wm. Sands, Josiah Ryland, A. Snead, J.B. Jeter, A.G. Wortham and
            J.M. Murray
          </p>
          <p>Dr. J.L. Burrows was appointed President pro tem.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Burrows</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <PageNumber num={293} />
          <p>
            The committee of correspondence presented communications from Genl Jno.
            B. Gordon and John Hart, AM, declining to accept the appointments as
            part of the Faculty of the College. Also a communication from Prof.
            Puryear accepting the appointment tendered him.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of A.G. Wortham, Rev.<aside>JA Broaddus appointed President</aside> John A. Broaddus D.D. was unanimously
            appointed President of the College at a Salary of $2,000 per annum and
            an equal division of the fees received of the students for tuition.
          </p>
          <p>
            The appointment of another Professor in place of Mr. Hart was referred
            to the committee on organization to make a selection of a suitable
            person to be recommended to the Board at its next meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee on organizations was instructed to publish immediately
            that the College will be opened on the 1st of October next.
          </p>
          <aside>Committee on Premises after <Link to="../297">page 297</Link></aside>
          <p>
            On motion the President of the Board together with A.G. Wortham and R.
            Reins were appointed a committee on the premises whose duty is to have
            the premises cleansed and put in proper condition for the opening of the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>After which the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <p>J. M. Murray, Secretary</p>
          <PageNumber num={294} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-08-04">
          <div>Saturday<time dateTime="1866-08-04"> August 4 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at 6 o'clock at the residence of A.M. Bailey.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present W. Goddin, Edwin Wortham, Wm. Sands, Rev. J.L. Burrows, Richard
            Reins, R.T. Coleman and Thomas J. Evans.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion W. Goddin was called to the chair and Thomas I. Evans,
            appointed Secretary pro tem.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Burrows</p>
          <p>
            The committee (through Dr. Burrows) reported prospectus &amp;c for
            advertisement in the Richmond newspapers of the opening of the College
            on the 1st of October next, which was adopted and the Secretary was
            instructed to publish the same.
          </p>
          <aside>Professor Smith & Harrison Elected</aside>
          <p>
            Messrs. Edward B. Smith and Edmund Harrison were now elected by the
            Board to Professorships in the College. Salaries to be one thousand
            dollars, supplemented by three hundred dollars and an equal division of
            the fees received from students for tuition for the present year.
          </p>
          <p>
            The meeting now adjourned to meet Thursday afternoon next at 6 o’clock
            p.m.
          </p>
          <p>T.J. Evans, Secretary pro tempo</p>
          <PageNumber num={295} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-08-06">
