        <section id="meeting-1866-08-09">
          <div><time dateTime="1866-08-09">August 9 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            An adjourned meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at the Grace Street Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, President, A.G. Wortham, Wm. Sands, W. Goddin, R.
            Reins, Edwin Wortham &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>

          <p>
            On motion the sum of $600 and<aside>Appropriation for Laboratory</aside> traveling expenses to and from New York
            were appropriated for the purpose of purchasing chemical apparatus and
            chemicals, by Prof. Puryear before the oppening [sic] of the College.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Trustees was authorized to borrow an additional <PageNumber num={296} /> thousand dollars by hypothecating a sufficient amount of Stock
            belonging to the College.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.  </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-08-24">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-08-24"> August 24, 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            At a  meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Grace
            Street Baptist Church this afternoon, present
          </p>
          <p>
            J.L. Burrows, J.B. Jeter, Edwin Wortham, Wm. Sands, Jno P. Ballard, R.
            Reins, A. Snead, T.J. Evans, R.T. Coleman, A.R. Halladay &amp; J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Dr. Burrows was appointed Chairman.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Jeter</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            Professors Smith, Harrison and Thomas being present were invited to
            seats and to participate in the [deliberations]. Rev. T.G. Jones, D.D.
            also having come in was likewise invited.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustees Elected Member Bailey</aside>
          <p>
            The following individuals were unanimously elected Trustees of the
            College Viz. Charles H. Winston, Rev. David Shaver, A.R. Courtney, H.K.
            Ellyson, Harvey Hatcher and A.M. Bailey.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the committee on premises was authorized and instructed to
            have done whatever was necessary to put the College premises in complete
            order.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee consisting of Rev. J.L. Burrows, R.T. Coleman and
            John P. Ballard was appointed whose duty <PageNumber num={297} /> is to cooperate with the Faculty in perfecting the organization of
            the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of A. Snead the building on the College premises known as the
            President’s house was set apart as the residence of the President.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board now proceeded to the election of a President of the
            College, whereupon Rev. T.G. Jonas, D.D. of Norfolk, Virginia was
            unanimously elected President of Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned.</p>
          <p>J. M. Murray, Secretary</p>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-11-01">
          <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-11-01"> November 1, 1866</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at Grace Street Baptist Church. Prest. Ro. Ryland, A.H. Sands,
            L.R. Spilman, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, Josiah Ryland, J.B. Taylor,
            Richard Reins, W. Goddin, J.P. Ballard, A.M. Bailey, Jas Thomas Jr.,
            J.M. Murray and J.B. Jeter.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by President Jones</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            President Jones and Prof. Harris being present were invited to seats and
            to participate in the deliberations of the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee on the premises reported what progress had been made in
            repairs
          </p>
          <p>
            President Ryland presented report of what monies had been received by
            him for rents which was referred to the Auditing Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was authorized to borrow an amount not to exceed
            $2,000 should he find it necessary by hypothecating State Stock
            belonging to the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows it was ordered that the beneficiary students be
            required to pay the matriculation fees and room rent.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that an additional appropriation $350 be made
            for purchasing chemicals and apparatus for the Laboratory.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was instructed to pay the President $500 and
            each of the Professors $300 on account salaries for the present session.
          </p>
          <p>
            Chas. T. Northam was unanimously elected a Trustee in place of H.K.
            Ellyson who declines to accept.
          </p>
          <p>Jno P. Ballard was added to the committee on the premises.</p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was authorized to borrow $600 in gold a year for
            two years to be advanced to Prof. Toy now in Europe on these conditions,
            that he returns in two years and refunds the money in salary. President
            Jones was requested to inform him of this action.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.  </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
          <PageNumber num={298} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-11-20">
          <p>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-11-20"> November 20, 1866</time></p>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon. Present Edwin Wortham, Josiah Ryland, A.G. Wortham, R. Reins,
            T.J. Evans, A.M. Bailey, Harvey Hatcher, L.R. Spilman, A.M. Poindexter,
            J.L. Burrows, A.R. Courtney and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr.  Poindexter stated that the object for the call of the meeting was
            to consult them as to the expediency of making efforts at the present
            time in the City of Richmond toward the endowment.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the meeting decided that the General Agent should proceed at
            once towards the accomplishment of the object.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Poindexter, A.M. Bailey and D. Shaver were appointed a
            committee to call attention of the public to this object through the
            papers of this City.
          </p>
          <p>Meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <p>J.M. Murray, Secy.</p>
          <PageNumber num={299} />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1866-12-13">
          <p>Richmond<time dateTime="1866-12-13"> December 13, 1866</time></p>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held today at
            the Study of Rev. Dr. Jeter.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.L. Burrows, A.M. Bailey, R. Reins, A.M. Poindexter, J.B.
            Jeter, Jas. Thomas, Jr., A.G. Wortham, T.J. Evans, A.G. Wortham, R.T.
            Coleman, Harvey Hatcher, Josiah Ryland &amp; J.M. Murray and Ro. Ryland,
            President.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Poindexter stated that object for which the was called to take the
            necessary to memoralize [sic] the Legislature in behalf of the College
            in order to obtain the donation of land scrip appropriated by Congress
            to the State for certain educational purposes.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee consisting of A.H. Sands, T.J. Evans &amp; A.M.
            Poindexter were appointed to prepare the Memorial and present it to the
            Legislature.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. J.B. Jeter, A.R. Holladay and Thomas Wallace were appointed a
            Committee to represent the College before the Committee of Schools and
            Colleges.
          </p>
          <aside>Beneficiaries Not to Pay Room rents</aside>
          <p>
            It was resolved that the order requiring Beneficiaries to pay room rent
            and matriculation fees be rescinded.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee was appointed to arrange for holding a meeting in
            the City during the month of January to advance the interest of the
            College. Jas Thomas, Jr. was appointed Chair man [sic] of the committee
            with the privilege of selecting the other members of the committee. Dr.
            R.T. Coleman and A.M. Bailey were selected by him.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={300} />
          <p>
            The President presented his final account on account of rents &amp;c
            which was received and ordered to [be] filed by the Clerk.
          </p>
          <p>After which the adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <div>Richmond<time dateTime="1867-01-21"> January 21, 1867</time></div>
        <p>
          A meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this afternoon.
        </p>
        <p>
          Present Robt. Ryland, J.L. Burrows, J.B. Jeter, A.G. Wortham, A.M.
          Poindexter, R. Reins, Wm. Sands, Jas Thomas, Jr., A.M. Bailey and Josiah
          Ryland.
        </p>
        <p>President Jones was present by invitation, who offered prayer.</p>
        <p>Josiah Ryland was appointed Secretary pro tempo.</p>
        <p>
          A communication was received from Mr. C.S. Maupin of Albemarle Co., Va.
          stating that he had given his Bond for $300 towards the endowment of
          Richd. College upon some misunderstanding of his ability to pay; he
          being a minor at the time &amp; requesting that the Board receive in
          lieu of his Bond, a $300 bond of the state of Virginia (state stock)
          next May when he shall have become of age. Whereupon it was resolved
          that the Genl. Agent be authorized to receive the state stock offered by
          Mr. Maupin in lieu of his bond.
        </p>
        <p>
          Genl. Henry A. Wise being present, was invited to take a seat, who
          proceeded to lay before the Board a plan drawn up by him for the purpose
          of securing to the College the fund offered by the General Goverment
          [sic] to the State <PageNumber num={301} /> of Virginia for educational purposes.</p>
        <p>
          On motion General Wise, A.R. Holladay and Dr. Jones were appointed a
          committee to present the papers read by General Wise to the Committee of
          the Legislature as the proposal of the College to accept the fund of
          General Goverment [sic].
        </p>
        <p>
          A petition was received, signed by Professors Harris, Harrison, Smith
          and Puryear of the College respectfully requesting the Board to take
          steps to pay the portion of their salaries due 1st day of January of
          which they are very much in want. The Board decided that the plans
          already set in motion for this purpose would be sufficient.
        </p>
        <p>On motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
        <p>
          Josiah Ryland, Secretary pro.
          tem.                                                                 Ro.
          Ryland, Pres’t.
        </p>

