        <section id='meeting-1867-03-25'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1867-04-25">April 25, 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon.
            Present Rev. Ro. Ryland, President, A.G. Wortham, Edwin Wortham, W.
            Sands, L.R. Spilman, Chas H. Winston, A. Snead, A.M. Bailey, Josiah
            Ryland, R. Reins &amp; J.M. Murray &amp; James Thomas, Jr., and Dr.
            Jones, President of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Mr. Wm. Sands</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            Dr. Jones on behalf of the Committee to petition the Legislature in
            regard to the appropriation made by the General Government for
            Educational purposes, stated that the Committee <PageNumber num={302} />
            had discharged the duty as far as practicable but in consequence of
            subsequent action taken by the Federal Government, the Committee of the
            Legislature had dismissed the subject for the present. The committee was
            continued.
          </p>
          <aside className='pencil'>Catalogue</aside>
          <p>
            Dr. Jones read a portion of the Catalogue prepared by the Faculty
            designed as an introduction as proceeding from the Trustees. The same
            was adopted. The Faculty also asked that the two Schools of Languages
            might be dived [sic] into three. Viz.<aside>3 Departments Languages</aside>  Depart of Greek, Latin &amp;
            Modern Languages which was agreed to. The Faculty likewise asked that
            committee be appointed to confer with Faculty <aside>Commitee Commercial Department</aside> in regard to the
            propriety of establishing a commercial department in the College agreed
            to, and the Chair appointed A.M. Bailey, Josiah Ryland and Chas H.
            Winston, the committee.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Rylant, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1867-06-24'>
          <div><time dateTime="1867-06-24">June 24, 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon in
            the Study of Dr. Jeter.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, President, J.B. Jeter, A.G. Wortham, A.R. Courtney,
            T.J. Evans, A.H. Sands, A.M. Bailey, A. Snead, C.H. Winston, Josiah
            Ryland, L.R. Spilman, Wm. Sands and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by A.M. Bailey</p>
          <PageNumber num={303} />
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were ready and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed at the last meeting to confer with the Faculty
            on the expediency of establishing a Commercial department reported
            progress and was continued.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from Prof. Smith was read, asking for an appropriation
            of funds by the Board for the purpose of purchasing Mathematical and
            Astronomical instruments. The Secretary was instructed to inform Prof.
            Smith that the Board would comply with the request as soon as they
            should have the means to do so.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolutions offered by Dr. Jeter were adopted.</p>
          <aside className="pencil">Law</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved  That in the opinion of the Trustees it is desirable to
            establish with Richmond College a first class Law and Commercial Schools
            provided it can be done without additional cost to the Institution.
          </p>
          <aside>Law School</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved that a committee of five be authorized to inquire into the
            practicability of establishing a Law School on the above basis and
            report to an early meeting of the Trustees. The Chair appointed the
            following members to constitute the committee A.H. Sands, T.J. Evans,
            L.R. Spilman, A.R. Holladay &amp; J.L. Burrows.
          </p>
          <p>
            Rev. J.L. Burrows offered the following resolution.  Whereas the Board
            of <PageNumber num={304} />
            Trustees by the resolutions of <time dateTime="1866-07-05">July 5</time> and <time dateTime="1866-08-24">August 24, 1866</time> intended to
            put the Faculty upon equal grounds as to the use and occupation of the
            residences upon the College premises, and whereas two Professors have
            been compelled to use dwellings outside the premises and the same number
            at least in the future will be compelled to do so. Therefore resolved
            that the professors occupying residences on the College premises shall
            pay to the Faculty a sum not exceeding rental for similar buildings, the
            sums accruing to be equally divided between all the Professors.  The
            Chair appointed A.G. Wortham, A.R. Courtney and L.R. Spilman, the
            committee.
          </p>
          <aside>Beneficiary not to pay Marticulation fee</aside>
          <p>
            A motion of Jas Thomas, Jr. &quot;that students for the ministry
            hereafter be required to pay the matriculation fee and room rent was
            rejected.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President of the Faculty presented the Annual Report which was
            received and ordered to be filed. He also presented a report of Prof.
            Harris, Treasurer of the Faculty, and of Prof. Puryear for expenditures
            for apparatus which were received and referred to the Auditing
            Committee.
          </p>
          <aside>Commitee onf Presidents Report.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Jeter, the suggestions contained in the President’s
            report were referred to a committee consisting of C.H. Winston, Wm.
            Sands &amp; Josiah Ryland.
          </p>
          <aside>Ho Degrs</aside>
          <p>
            On recommendation of the Faculty the honorary degree of AM Master of
            Arts was conferred on Ro. E. Binford of Franklen [sic], Tennessee, a
            former graduate of Richmond College
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={305} />
          <aside>Trustee JA Chambliss</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Wm. Sands, Rev. J.A. Chambliss was appointed in the place
            of Rev. D. Shaver who has removed from the State, a Trustees of Richmond
            College.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from Mr. C.T. Bailey was referred to the Faculty for
            consideration, after which the Board adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J. M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Rylant, Pres't.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1867-07-01'>
          <div><time dateTime="1867-07-01">July 1st 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon at
            Grace Street Church
          </p>
          <p>
            Present  Ro. Ryland, President, A.M. Poindexter, J.B. Taylor, Dr. Robert
            T. Coleman, James Thomas, Jr., Charles H. Winston, Dr. A.G. Wortham,
            Edwin Wortham, J.A. Chambliss, Josiah Ryland, A.H. Sands, L.R. Spilman,
            and A.R. Courtney.  Trustees and Dr. T.G. Jones, President of Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.A. Chambliss</p>
          <p>
            On motion of Josiah Ryland, A.R. Courtney was appointed Secretary
            <u>pro tem</u>in absence of J.M. Murray, Secretary.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and corrected.</p>
          <p>
            Rev. A.M. Poindexter read a report of his transactions as agent for the
            College up to the <time dateTime="1867-06-17">17th ultimo</time>, the end of the first year of his agency
            and followed with some remarks upon the same.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={306} />
          <p>
            Before acting upon the report of Mr. Poindexter, the report of the
            committee appointed at the last meeting of the Board consisting of A.R.
            Courtney, A. Wortham and L.R. Spilman, on the subject of the residences
            of Professors &amp;c was called for and thereupon A.R. Courtney as
            Chairman of said committee submitted their report with accompanying
            papers.
          </p>
          <aside>Action on Subject of Professors Residency</aside>
          <p>
            After some discussion, the following resolutions offered by A.M.
            Poindexter were adopted.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li className='first'>
              Resolved that the Board will pay to Professors Puryear, Harris,
              Harrison and Smith the sum of three hundred and forty dollars as part
              rent of the President’s house for the past year in consideration of the
              vote of the Board of <time dateTime="1866-08-24">August 24, 1866</time>, appropriating the said house to
              the President.
            </li>
            <li className="second">
              Resolved that the future disposition of the houses, together with
              the report of the agent, be committed to a committee of five with
              directions to confer with the Faculty upon the whole subject of future
              arrangements and report as soon as practicable.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            The committee appointed under the above resolution consists of James B.
            Taylor, Dr. R. T. Coleman, James Thomas, Jr., Josiah Ryland and A.M.
            Poindexter
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. T.G. Jones, President of the Faculty, presented two communications
            from the Faculty on the subject of an assistant Instructor and providing
            a larger room for the Latin School.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of James B. Taylor the communications of the Faculty were
            referred to the same committee <PageNumber num={307} />
            appointed under the resolutions of A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>On motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A.R. Courtney, Secretary pro
              tem. </div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1867-07-09'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1867-07-09">July 9, 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon at
            Grace Street Baptist Church
          </p>
          <p>
            Present  Ro. Ryland, Prest., James Thomas, Jr., James B. Taylor, Edwin
            Wortham, Josiah Ryland, J.B. Jeter, C.H. Winston, A.G. Wortham, J.A.
            Chambliss, L.R. Spilman and A.R. Courtney, Trustees, and T.G. Jones and
            H.H. Harris of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor</p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed at the last meeting to consider and report upon
            the subject of future arrangements with the Faculty as to residences,
            salaries &amp;c and other subjects -- presented the following report.
          </p>
          <aside>Report on Residences Faculty</aside>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was referred the question of a proper disposition
            of the Buildings &amp; lots connected with College premises - the report
            of the General Agent and sundry other matters beg leave to report.
          </p>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: 'outside' }}>
            <li>
              In relation to the dwellings the committee recommend that the house now
              occupied by the President with grounds attached to it be appropriated to
              the sole use of the President, and that in view of the claim which <PageNumber num={308} />
              which the other members of the Faculty have upon this building and
              grounds. The committee recommend that the Trustees grant <u>rent fee</u> the
              house and lot occupied by Professor Puryear in place
              thereof and that this house and lot, with the house and lot now occupied
              by Professor Harrison be assigned to the Professors to be so jointly
              occupied &amp; arranged as to them may be most agreeable. This plan of
              adjustment though not in perfect accordance with understanding of the
              Professor as to their proper claim still meets with their concurrence.
              They express a willingness to submit to the arrangement.
            </li>
            <li>
              In reference to the Agent’s report, the committee beg leave to state
              that they have given serious and prolonged attention to the facts
              involved, especially to the threatened embarrassment of the College by
              the deficiency of funds to meet the expenses of the year just closed and
              the probable recurrence of a similar deficiency in the year to come.
              They were satisfied that the obligations under which the Trustees have
              placed themselves to the President and Professors could not be met
              without involving the College in a heavy debt which could be constantly
              augmenting and which would seriously impede the work of filling up the
              endowment if it did not imperil the actual continuance of the
              Institution. They saw no escape in the present condition <PageNumber num={309} />
              of the times, but in an appeal to the President and Professors
              themselves asking them to consider the expediency of so far abating
              their claim upon the Trustees for the coming year as to bearing the
              current expenses within limits easily controlled. In deciding upon this
              course, while they confided in the magnanimity of the President &amp;
              Professors, they believed that a present sacrifice on their part would
              be ultimately promotive of their interest well as to the interest of
              the College.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <aside>Salaries Faculty.</aside>
          <p>
            The committee are happy to report that their consultation with the
            Faculty was free and pleasant. The President &amp; Professors seemed to
            apprehend the present &amp; prospective exegencies [sic] of the College
            and expressed a willingness to yield to a proper abatement of their
            claims. It was finally proposed by them to diminish on the part of the
            President the sum of $300 and on the part of the Professor each $250,
            making a sum total of $1300 which the Faculty agree to relinquish, so
            that instead of $2,000, the President will receive seventeen hundred
            dollars as the stipulated salary for the coming year, and instead of
            $1,000 to be paid as salary to each of the Professors, they will receive
            each the sum $750. The whole of the tuition fees are to be as heretofore
            equally divided between the President &amp; Professors. The committee
            recommend that the Trustees concur in the arrangement. If it shall be
            carried out and the Chicago property be advantageously <PageNumber num={310} />
            sold, the hope may be reasonably entertained, that any remaining
            indebtedness will be entirely under the control of the Board. It is
            however of the utmost importance that with a cautious regard to the
            solvency of the Institution and its final success, no liabilities be
            incurred which may not be met from the income of the endowment and
            incidental fund. An encroachment upon the endowment itself, excepting
            under circumstances of extreme necessity must not be allowed.
          </p>
          <p>
            It will be understood that the arrangement this proposed is to be valid
            only for the ensuing scholastic year and that notice shall hereby be
            given to the President and Professors of Richmond College, that before
            the close of the session, other propositions will be presented for their
            acceptance -- propositions as liberal as the finances of the Institution
            will justify and which we hope will be commensurate with the eminent
            qualifications of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee have also had under consideration the paper addressed to
            the Trustees by the Faculty in relation to the imployment [sic] of
            assistant instructors for the primary classes in connection with any of
            the schools which may need this assistance. The Faculty propose to
            select such instructors subject to the appointment of the Board. They
            also expect to sustain the entire expense of these instructors and to
            hold them amenable to themselves.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={311} />
          <aside>Assistant Instructors</aside>
          <p>
            The committee recommend that in any case when the more efficient
            instruction in any school shall seem to require it the Faculty may
            nominate for appointment an assisted instructor and that the Trustees
            should in such case be prepaired [sic] to consider the application with
            respect, and if deemed appropriate, should confer the appointment with
            the understanding that the expense of such instruction is to be borne by
            the Faculty, and that the instructor is to be responsible to them for
            the faithful discharge of his duty.
          </p>
          <p>
            Another paper presented by the Faculty, asking for authority to throw
            two of the rooms on the second floor of the College building <u>into one</u> by
            removing a partition, has been considered by the
            committee. In view of having a larger room for the Latin School, the
            committee recommend that the desired authority be given, provided that
            the change can be made without injuring the building.
          </p>
          <p>All of which is respectfully submitted.</p>
          <div>Signed, James B. Taylor, Chairman</div>
          <p>On motion of L.R. Spilman, the report was approved and adopted.</p>
          <p>
            A letter from W. Goddin in reference to the sale of the real estate of
            the College in Chicago, and also a letter from the agent in Chicago were
            read and on motion the President of the Board was directed to renew the
            Note for $1100 in the Planters National Bank in order to give further
            time for its payment from the sale of that property and on motion of <PageNumber num={312} />
            James Thomas, Jr., Rev. Jas B. Taylor was requested to go by Chicago
            on his visit to the West and look after the property of the College in
            that City and have it sold if possible.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Jas B. Taylor, it was resolved that a committee of five be
            appointed to consider the expediency of constituting an <u>“Executive Committee”</u> from the Board of Trustees for the
            transaction of the ordinary business of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            A.R. Courtney, J.A. Chambliss, Josiah Ryland, R.T. Coleman and A.G.
            Wortham were appointed the committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Jones in behalf of the Faculty, reported adversely to the
            application of C.T. Bailey for honorary degree of the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            Upon an inquiry of the Faculty, whether they or the Board should pay the
            bill of the Religious Herald for advertising for the last year, it was
            ordered that the Board should pay for the advertising up to the
            beginning of last session in October 1866 after which the Board
            adjourned.
          </p>
          <div>(signed)</div>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A.R. Courtney, Secretary pro
              tem. </div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Pres’t</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={313} />

        <section id='meeting-1867-09-23'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1867-09-23">September 23 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland, President, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, James
            Thomas, Jr., Wm. Sands, A. Snead, Josiah Ryland, J.B. Jeter, L.R.
            Spilman and J.M. Murray of the Trustees, and Dr. Jones and Professor
            Smith of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by James Thomas, Jr.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The following Resolution offered by Mr. Edwin Wortham was unanimously
            adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurer may use funds for Contingent [illegible]</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved.  If a resolution has been passed restricting the Treasurer from
            using any funds collected for the endowment, in the necessary
            expenditures of the College that the same be cancelled, and the
            Treasurer is hereby authorized to use whatever funds coming into his
            control, whether for interest, endorsement or contingent purposes in the
            actual expenditures of the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            In pursuance of a communication from Prof. Smith in which he proposes to
            establish a Commercial Course in connection with the School of
            Mathematics - embracing Commercial Arithmetic &amp; Bookkeeping it was
            on motion of Dr. Burrows
          </p>
          <aside>Canges Commercial Department</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved:  That an extra charge of 12 dollars per session may be
            required of each student in the School of Mathematics, who desires to
            attend also the Commercial Course, the money thus received to be
            expended <PageNumber num={314} />
            by the Professor of Mathematics for instruments, models &amp;c -- to
            illustrate the subjects of Surveying, Levelling, Astronomy &amp;c in
            this School -- for students not in the Mathematical Course, the charge
            to be the same as for a separate school.
          </p>
          <p>
            It is understood that this arrangement is temporary and intended to
            furthur [sic] the introduction of a full Commercial Department at the
            College.
          </p>
          <aside>C Toy declines</aside>
          <p>
            A communication was received from Professor Toy declining to accept the
            position to which he had been elected in the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion Dr. Burrows in connection with President Jones were appointed
            a committee to have a conference with the City Council with a view to
            have the streets leading to College put in a better condition and have
            the marshes near the College drained.
          </p>
          <aside>Appropriate Apparatus</aside>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that an appropriation not exceeding $300 be
            made to purchase apparatus for the Department of Mathematics and Natural
            Science to be divided between them as may be agreed upon by the
            Professors.
          </p>
          <p>
            A proposition was presented from Professor Heinrich asking the
            privilege of establishing and [sic] independent School of Applied
            Science if he should find it desirable. On motion the application and
            papers in relation thereto were referred to the Faculty, with the
            intimation that the Board would acquiesce in their decision.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={315} />
          <p>
            On motion Dr. James was authorized to take subscriptions to raise funds
            for necessary repairs &amp;c about the College premises.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following resolution offerred [sic] by Dr. Jeter was unanimously
            adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved:  That the Trustees have heard with sorrow of the bereavement
            of Dr. A.M. Poindexter and tender to him our sincere sympathy in the
            loss of his esteemed wife, and that the Secretary be requested to
            transmit him a copy of this resolution.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1867-10-14'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1867-10-14">October 14 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro. Ryland President, J.B. Jeter, A. Snead, Josiah Ryland, A.G.
            Wortham, Wm. Sands &amp; J.M. Murray, James Thomas Jr., L.R. Spilman
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter.</p>
          <p>The following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved: That the Board ratify and confirm the sale of the seven lots
            in Chicago to George C. Tollman at the price of five thousand dollars in
            cash, and that the President and Secretary be and they are hereby
            authorized and instructed to execute to the purchaser thereof the proper
            deed conveying the said lots.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={316} />

        <section id='meeting-1867-10-25'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1867-10-25">October 25, 1867</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon, Present Robt. Ryland, President, R.T. Coleman, AG Wortham,
            J.A. Chambliss, Josiah Ryland, A.R. Holladay, Chaz H. Winston, L.R.
            Spilman, &amp; J.M. Murray Trustees and Dr. Jones of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jones.</p>
          <p>The minutes of <time dateTime="1867-09-23">September 23rd 1867</time> were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The following Resolution offered by Dr. R.T. Coleman and seconded by
            C.H. Winston was unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Rev. M. Curry Elected Prof</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved:  That the Rev. J.L.M. Curry be elected Professor of English
            Literature and History in Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Coleman stated in view of the present depressed financial Condition
            of the College he would hold himself responsible for a Salary to Mr.
            Curry equal to that received by the other professors for the present
            year. For subsequent years Mr. Curry would come in on the same terms as
            those proferred for Mr. Toy that is on the same footing with the other
            professors in the Institution.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={317} />

        <section id='meeting-1867-11-09'>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the Second
            Baptist Church, Saturday <time dateTime="1867-11-09">November 9th 1867</time>. Present, Rev. J.B. Jeter, W.
            Goddin, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, R. Reins, J.A. Chambliss, Josiah
            Ryland, J.B. Taylor, C.H. Winston
          </p>
          <p>Dr. Jeter was called to the Chair.</p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Rev. J.A. Chambliss.</p>
          <p>Josiah Ryland was appointed Secretary Pro tem.</p>
          <p>
            Mr. Goddin made a statement in regard to the sale of the lots in Chicago
            to the effect that the supposed sale had proved abortive, the party
            purchasing declining to take them, whereupon it was Resolved.  That the
            Board deem it inexpedient to prosecute the matter, and request the
            Agents in Chicago to dispossess the parties who have squatted on the
            lots and proceed to sell them if possible.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the order of the Board dated <time dateTime="1867-10-14">October 14th 1867</time> ratifying a
            sale of the property to George C Tollman an[d] ordering a deed to be
            made to him be and the same is hereby rescinded.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer stated that a Note of the College held by the Planters
            Bank of this, to the amount of $1100 had matured, and the Bank
            wished it paid without further delay, it was Resolved That the
            Treasurer of the College be authorized to employ a suitable Collector to
            wait on delinquent Subscribers in Richmond.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={318} />
          <p>
            The Treasurer was authorized to refund to Starke &amp; Ryland the sum of
            $136.65 paid by them for freight on Dr. Owens Library presented to the
            College.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Treasurer and W. Goddin be authorized to procure an
            extension of the Note now held by Planters Bank on whole or in part, and
            if it should be found necessary, to sell any of the State Stock which
            had been held by the Bank as Collateral, that this amount Amount [sic]
            be replaced by the first funds accruing from the Sale of the Chicago
            lots.
          </p>
          <aside>Helbach</aside>
          <p>
            On motion resolved that E.W. Helbach of Charlottesville be permitted to
            change his bond to the College from $100 to $30.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board now adjourned. </p>
          <aside>Signed.</aside>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Josiah Ryland, Sec. pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-01-10'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-01-10">January 10 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the
            Office of Dr. Geo. B. Steel
          </p>
          <p>
            Present, Robert Ryland President. J.B. Jeter, Edwin Wortham, C.H.
            Winston, A.G. Wortham, Josiah Ryland, J.B. Taylor, J.L. Burrows, A.R.
            Courtney, Jas. Thomas Jr., A.M. Poindexter and J.M. Murray
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter</p>
          <p>
            A communication was presented from the Faculty in relation to amount <PageNumber num={319} />
            due them by the Board on account of Salaries.</p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Jeter a committee consisting of Rev. J.B. Taylor, A.G.
            Wortham and Dr. Poindexter was appointed to ascertain and report upon
            the Financial condition of the College and report to any adjourned
            meeting to be held at the office of Jas. Thomas Jr on Monday January
            13th at 7 1/2 o’clock P.M.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the meeting then adjourned.</p>
