        <section id='meeting-1868-01-13'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-01-13">January 13. 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            A meeting of the Trustees Richmond College was held this evening at the
            Office of James Thomas Jr. pursuant to adjournment.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Jas. Thomas Jr., J.L. Burrows, A.G. Wortham, Jas. B. Taylor,
            Josiah Ryland, A.M. Poindexter, Edwin Wortham, C.H. Winston, J.B. Jeter,
            Ro. Ryland in the chair, and Josiah Ryland Secretary pro. tem. Prayer by
            Rev A.M. Poindexter.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed to look into the financial Condition of the
            College reported in writing.
          </p>
          <p>
            It was resolved that the Treasurer be authorized to effect a loan of
            ($2500) twenty five hundred Dollars, hypothecating as much of the State
            Stock owned by the College as may be necessary as Security.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={320} />
          <p>
            On motion it was resolved that Rev. J.B. Taylor be appointed Special
            Agent of the Board to sell the Chicago lots, and be authorized to act
            according to his discretion in the matter.
          </p>
          <aside>see below.</aside>
          <p>
            It was resolved that the Report of the Committee be adopted and that a
            Committee of Drs. Poindexter and Burrows be appointed to communicate it
            to the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            It was resolved that ($150) One hundred and fifty Dollars per Annum be
            appropriated to paying the Treasurer for his services.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting there adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">Josiah Ryland, Sec. pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro. Ryland, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
          <p>Report</p>
          <aside>Financial Condition</aside>
          <p>
            The Committee to whom was referred the Financial Condition of the
            College respectfully report
          </p>
          <table id='financialreport18680113'>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Debt due in Bank</td>
                <td>$1700.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Faculty for 1866-7 </td>
                <td>1375.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>House Rent</td>
                <td>340.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Agent Salary to 18 January 1868 &amp; Expenses</td>
                <td>681.77</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Faculty Salaries July, 1868. </td>
                <td>4700.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>Agent. 18 June 1868 say</td>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>1200.</td>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>$9996.77</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th colSpan={3}>Cr.</th>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>By Cash on hand</td>
                <td>376.18</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Interest now due on Bond</td>
                <td>1089.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <aside>June</aside>
              <tr>
                <td>To become due June 1868</td>
                <td>4500.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>&quot;        July 1868</td>
                <td>600.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Prof. Harrison for Rent</td>
                <td>100.</td>
                <td></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>To balance</td>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>3341.59</td>
                <td style={{ borderBottom: '1px solid black' }}>$9996.77</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p>
            This shows a balance of $3341.59 against the College <time dateTime="1868-07-01">1st July 1868</time> should all the interested be collected: but it would not be safe to
            depend upon the collection by  <PageNumber num={321} />
            that time of more than two thirds of it. It is probable however that
            bonds may be obtained by the Agent increasing somewhat the amount then
            to become due.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Agent has secured bonds amounting to $73447 and annual pledges for
            five years equal to the interest on $2583 and for life equal to the
            interest on $1600 -- in all $77630. -- But there has been paid of
            principal of the bonds a considerable amount, so that not more than
            $75000 can be now at interest. In addition to this the College owns
            about $25000 of Va. State and other bonds, of which the Va. bonds pay
            interest regularly.
          </p>
          <aside>Authority to borrow $4000.</aside>
          <p>
            In view of the necessity for paying the bank debt, and meeting as far as
            practical the wants of the Faculty your committee recommend that an
            effort be made to borrow the sum of $4000, and that the Va. State bonds
            or so much thereof as may me [sic] be requisite, be pledged as security
            for the loan.
          </p>
          <p>
            It should however be distinctly made known to the parties from whom it
            is proposed to make such loan, that the College will not expect to repay
            the money until it can realize from the sale of the Chicago lots.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your Committee further recommend that a Special Agent be appointed to
            proceed to Chicago and endeavor to effect a sale of the lots there
            located.
          </p>
          <p>
            It seems useless longer to depend upon the Chicago Agents to effect a
            sale.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={322} />
          <p>
            Another point to which your committee would call the special attention
            of of [sic] the Board is that at the rate of Salaries as now fixed, the
            College cannot be expected to have for some years, an income sufficient
            to prevent the accumulation of debt.
          </p>
          <p>
            The rate is, to the President $2000 per Annum and house rent, to each
            Professor $1000 per annum and a portion of the rent of the other
            dwellings. Now with present Faculty this requires $6000 per Annum,
            exclusive of incidentals and Expenses of Agency.
          </p>
          <p>
            It would in the judgement of your Committee, be unwise to expect more
            than $4500, the interest on $75,000 from the present Endowment; and any
            increase that can reasonably [be] hoped for will not be greater than
            will be needed to Constitute a sinking fund on which means to
            sustain the agency in the first place, and when that necessity shall
            cease, to replace the amount of principal used in Current expenses may
            be obtained.
          </p>
          <aside>Professors Salaries.</aside>
          <p>
            Until both these demands shall have been met it would be unsafe to
            pledge more than the amount indicated ($4500.) per annum to the support
            of Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            The College should not be allowed to go on accumulating debt, thus
            cripling [sic] it for an indefinite period and risking in fact its ruin.
          </p>
          <p>
            Should the idea once take hold of the public mind that such a course is
            being pursued, it would stop all chance of increased Endowment.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={323} />
          <p>
            Already the use of a portion of the principal for current Expenses,
            although only in the shape of a loan, to be replaced from income (as the
            Agent has represented it to be) has had an injurious effect. Looking at
            the interest of the Faculty alone, it would be better for them that the
            Board pledge only $4500 and pay it than that it should pledge a larger
            sum and not pay it. Especially, as by the former course it is to be
            hoped it will sooner be in the power of the College to pay increased
            Salaries.
          </p>
          <aside>Professors Salaries</aside>
          <p>
            The sum proposed would give to each Professor $750 and to the President
            $1500. per Annum divided at the rates as now fixed by the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            This would be within two hundred dollars of which the Faculty
            voluntarily agreed to accept the present term.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your Committee beg leave to state that while they think the Board
            should, as we are sure they are disposed to do, use every effort for the
            prompt payment of Salaries, yet should it be found impracticable to
            effect this, the Faculty should not feel aggrieved, as they knew at the
            time of accepting their appointments, that the Board was without
            resources and that the attempt to secure them was an experiment -- an
            experiment far more successful that [sic] could have been expected had
            it been known that the Condition of the Country would be as it is. Nor
            do your Committee anticipate any unpleasant feeling <PageNumber num={324} />
            on this account, or as the result of such measures herein recommended
            as are necessary to the more speedy and efficient establishment of the
            College on a firm foundation. The Gentlemen of the Faculty have shown a
            high appreciation of the important trust Committed to them and a general
            Concurrence with the Board and Agent in efforts to secure endowment, and
            to lessen expenses, especially by the voluntary relinquishment of $1300
            Salaries for present term.
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'space-between' }}>
            <div>Signed</div>
            <ul style={{ marginTop: 0 }}>
              <li>Jas. B. Taylor. Ch</li>
              <li>A.M. Poindexter.</li>
              <li>A.G. Wortham.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-03-28'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-03-28">April 28. 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon in the Pastors Study at the Second Baptist Church
          </p>
          <p>
            Present Ro Ryland, President of the Board, J.B. Taylor, A. Snead, A.G.
            Wortham, Wellington Goddin, A.R. Courtney, J.A. Chambliss, Josiah
            Ryland, Thos. J, Evans, C.H. Winston, J.S. Watlhall [sic], J.B. Jeter,
            Wm. Sands, R.B. Coleman and J. M. Murray. and Dr. Jones &amp; Harris of
            the Faculty.
          </p>
          <aside>Faculty</aside>
          <p>Dr. Ryland in the chair.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.S. Walthall.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            Dr. Jones, President of the Faculty presented and read Communication from
            the Faculty in regard to the expediency of establishing a Preparatory
            Department connected with the <PageNumber num={325} /> College. Dr. Jeter then offered the following preamble and resolution
            which were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Preperatory Department</aside>
          <p>
            “The Faculty of Richmond College having submitted a document proposing
            the establishment of a Preparatory Department, Therefore
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved. That the Faculty be authorized to establish such a Department
            on such terms as they may deem proper, provided that it shall involve
            the Treasurer in no additionall [sic] expenses.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution offered by Dr. Jeter was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved. That the Librarian be authorized to make any exchange of of
            [sic] duplicate volumes or other books in the Library under the
            direction of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            Thos. J. Evans offered the following resolution which was unanimously
            adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Dr Owen</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved that Committee of three be appointed to prepare a suitable
            Notice (to be spread upon Records of the Trustees) of the Donation of
            the Library to the College by Dr. Owen.
          </p>
          <p>
            The President appointed T.J. Evans, J.B. Jeter and A.R. Courtney the
            Committee.
          </p>
          <p>On motion of Dr. Jeter, it was</p>
          <p>
            Resolved.  That the Mu Sigma Rho society be authorized to throw two of
            the dormitories of the College into one room for its accommodation and
            at their own expense and under the direction of the Faculty.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={326} />
          <p>
            A bill was presented to the Board by Prof. Puryear for repairs on the
            premises amounting to $111.57 and the following order was made in
            relation thereto.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ordered. That the Treasurer of Richmond College be and he is hereby
            instructed to pay to B. Puryear on or before the <time dateTime="1869-04-27">27th April, 1869</time> without
            further action of the Board One hundred and eleven 57/100
            Dollars to cover all expenses incurred by him for repairs on his house
            and premises since <time dateTime="1866-10-01">Oct. 1, 1866</time> to <time dateTime="1868-04-27">April 27, 1868</time>.  Dr. Jones also
            presented a bill for sundry repairs amounting to $26.75 which was
            allowed and ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Mr. Wellington Goddin the Board accepted the following
            order
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Committee on the Premises of Richmond College be
            instructed to examine the buildings occupied by the President and other
            Professors and report the cost  necessary to put the premises in
            comfortable order—having a due regard to the present financial
            Condition of the College.
          </p>
          <p>Dr. Jeter offered the following resolution which was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved.  That the Faculty with the concurrence of the Committee
            heretofore appointed to consider and report in regard to the subject be
            authorized to establish a Mercantile Department of the College, provided
            it can be done without additional expense to the Trustees.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={327} />
          <aside>referred</aside>
          <p>
            Dr. Taylor the special agent to sell the lots in Chicago belonging to
            the College reported progress and referred the subject to the Board for
            advice it was ordered that the whole subject be committed to him, to
            act according to his own discretion.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed at a former meeting to report on the expediency
            of appointing an executive Committee to transact the ordinary business
            of the Board was presented and read and laid on the table to be acted on
            at the next Annual meeting.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">JM Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature">Ro Ryland, Pres't</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-05-22'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-05-22">May 22, 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            evening at the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present  W. Goddin, Edwin Wortham, R.T. Coleman, Josiah Ryland, T. J.
            Evans, Chas H. Winston, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>
            T.J. Evans was called to the Chair and the meeting was opened with
            prayer by C.H. Winston.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mr. Goddin having explained the object for the call of the meeting the
            following action was taken.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Board ratify and confirm the Sale of the Seven lots in
            Chicago to Chalkly J. Hambleton, at the price of five thousand Dollars <PageNumber num={328} />
            in cash; and that the President and Secretary, be and they are hereby
            authorized and instructed to execute to the purchaser thereof the proper
            deed conveying the said lots.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">JM Murray, Secretary </div>
            <div className="signature">T.J. Evans P P tem</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-05-25'>
          <div><time dateTime="1868-05-25">Monday May 25, 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held this
            afternoon at the Second Baptist Church.  Present. Ro Ryland, President,
            Josiah Ryland, J. A. Chambliss, A. Snead, A.R. Holladay, Chas. H.
            Winston, Edwin Wortham, A.R. Courtney, J.L. Burrows, J.M. Murray and
            T.G. Jones.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jones</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last two meetings were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            Dr. Jones presented a communication from the Faculty which was read and
            considered and the following action was taken in relation hereto.
          </p>
          <aside>Incidental Expenses. of all students $5.</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved.  hat the Faculty be authorized to estimate the probable cost
            of Fuel and incidental expenses for each Student and to require this
            amount of the Ministerial Students as well as of the rest,
            <u>the amount fixed at $5.</u>
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved.  That the incidental expenses for advertising, Catalogues
            &amp;c should not be a charge upon the Treasury of the Board, but should
            be met out of the tuition and other fees.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={329} />
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows it was Resolved that the Treasurer of the Board
            is hereby authorized to pay to the Faculty from time to time, on account
            of Salaries the funds he may then have in hand.
          </p>
          <p>The President of the Board presented the following Communication.</p>
          <div style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-05-28">May 28, 1868</time></div>
          <div>To the Trustees of Richmond College</div>
          <div>Gentlemen</div>
          <aside>Ro Ryland Resigns</aside>
          <p>
            Expecting to remove to Kentucky, I hereby offer my resignation as a
            trustee of Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>
            In dissolving a connexion which has continued so long, I will only say
            that I have no other feelings than those of kindness to you as
            individuals and a corporation.
          </p>
          <div style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>Very Respectfully</div>
          <div className='signature' style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>Ro. Ryland.</div>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows the Communication was deferred to a committee
            consisting of C.H. Winston, J.A. Chambliss and A.R. Courtney to report
            at the next meeting of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">Ryland.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-06-16' className='annual noquorum'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-06-16">June 16, 1868</time></div>
          <aside>Annual Meeting No Quorum</aside>
          <p>
            This being the time for holding the 28th Annual Meeting of the Trustees,
            but in consequence of the inclemency of the weather, only the following
            Trustees met. Viz. Rev. J. B. Jeter, Rev. J. B. Taylor, <PageNumber num={330} />
            Edwin Wortham, Chas. H. Winston, J.M. Murray &amp; Rev. T. G. Jones.
            there being no quorum, they adjourned to meet Thursday afternoon the
            18th inst. at 5 Oclock at the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <div className='signature' style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-06-18'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-06-18">June 18, 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            The following Trustees of Richmond College met this afternoon, according
            to adjournment. Viz. Jas. B. Taylor, A.M. Bailey, T.J. Evans, J.A.
            Chambliss, T.G. Jones, William Sands and J.M. Murray.  and it being
            deemed expedient to have a fuller meeting of the Board, they adjourned
            to meet <time dateTime="1868-06-23 17:00:00">Tuesday the 23rd instead at 5 O’clock PM</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <div className='signature' style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-06-23' className='annual'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-06-23">June 23, 1868</time></div>
          <aside>28<sup>th</sup> Annual Meeting</aside>
          <p>
            The 28th Annual Meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held
            this afternoon at the Second Baptist Church according to adjournment.
            Present Edwin Wortham, J.A. Chambliss, Josiah Ryland, Jas. B. Taylor, T.G.
            Jones, J.B. Jeter, C.H. Winston, J.L. Burrows, A.G. Wortham, A.R.
            Holladay, A.R. Courtney, R.T. Coleman, A.M. Bailey, T.J. Evans and J. M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Rev. J B. Jeter was appointed President pro. tem.</p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J. A. Chambliss.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of all the meetings held during the last 12 months were
            read, and the minutes of the last two meetings were corrected and then
            approved.
          </p>
          <p>Dr. Jones President of the College now <PageNumber num={331} />
            presented his Annual Report showing the Condition of the College as
            required by the By Laws, his report was also accompanied by a statement
            of the Treasurer of the Faculty. The Reports were received and ordered
            to be filed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prof. Smith presented a very encouraging report on the Condition of the
            Commercial Course which was inaugurated at the opening of the present
            session notwithstanding inadequate public notice had been given of the
            establishment of this department.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from Prof. Harris was read asking that an appropriation
            be made by the Trustees for the purchase of two Guyot's Wall Maps. One
            of Ancient Greece and one of Ancient “Italy” and the “Roman Empire” for
            the use of the Greek and Latin Schools. It was ordered that the
            necessary appropriation be made, when the Treasurer shall have funds in
            hand, not otherwise appropriated.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented now his annual Report, accompanied by the report
            of the Auditory Committee. The report was received and filed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Rev. Jas. B. Taylor, special Agent to sell the Chicago property
            presented his final report stating that the property had been sold
            through his Agency for $5000 in cash, and that a satisfactory deed of
            Conveyance had been given to the purchaser, and the transaction closed.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustee Ro. Ryland Resigns</aside>
          <p>
            The Communication of Ro. Ryland, presented at the last meeting,
            tendering his resignation as a trustee <PageNumber num={332} />
            of Richmond College was taken up and accepted, and the Committee to
            whom was referred duty of drawing up a paper expressive of the feelings
            of the Board towards Dr. Ryland, was continued, they not being ready to
            present the report at this meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>Auditing Committee</aside>
          <p>
            The Chairman appointed Wellington Goddin &amp; T.J. Evans the Auditing
            Committee for the Current year.
          </p>
          <p>
            The meeting now proceeded to elect A [sic] President, Treasurer and
            Secretary of the Board as required by the By-Laws. [T]he Chairman
            appointed Dr. Coleman and A.R. Courtney Tellers, who reported that
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'grid', gridTemplateColumns: 'repeat(3, minmax(10px, 1fr))', columnGap: '1em' }}>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>Rev. J. B. Jeter D.D.</div>
            <div>was chosen </div>
            <div>President.</div>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>Mr. Edwin Wortham</div>
            <div><span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span> <span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span></div>
            <div>Treasurer</div>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>J. M. Murray</div>
            <div><span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span> <span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span></div>
            <div>Secretary.</div>
          </div>
          <aside>Premises Committee</aside>
          <p>
            The President appointed the following Trustees to Constitute the
            Committee on the Premises, A. Snead &amp; A.R. Courtney.
          </p>
          <p>
            The report of the Committee on the expediency of appointing an
            <u>Executive Committee</u>which was laid on the table at a former
            meeting was taken up and considered, and then indefinitely postponed.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee to prepare a suitable notice of the Donation of Dr. Owen
            of his Library to the College not being ready to report was continued.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed under the resolution of Mr. Goddin in April last
            to report the necessary repairs that were needed to the buildings on the
            College Premises was also continued.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={333} />
          <aside>Degree Confd. DW. Gwin A.M.</aside>
          <p>
            At the recommendation of the Faculty, the Trustees, authorized the
            degree of Master of Arts, (A.M.) to be conferred on D.W. Gwin, of
            Griffin Georgia, a former graduate of the College under the old
            organization.
          </p>
          <p>
            An Invitation was received from the Mu, Sigma, Rho, and Philologian
            Societies of the College, inviting the Trustees to attend the first
            Celebration of the two Societies <time dateTime="1868-06-29 20:00:00">June 29</time> &amp; <time dateTime="1868-06-29 20:00:00">30th at 8 P.M.</time> The
            invitation was respectfully accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Rev J. B. Taylor it was ordered that when this meeting
            adjourned, it would adjourn to meet on <time dateTime="1868-07-07 17:00:00">
              Tuesday the 7th July 1868 at 5
              P.M.
            </time> and that the Secretary be requested to inform the General Agent,
            Dr. Poindexter of it and request his presence.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary </div>
            <div className="signature">J. B. Jeter, Prest.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id='meeting-1868-06-30'>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-06-30">June 30, 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees was held this afternoon at the Second
            Baptist Church.  Prest. J.B. Jeter President, Edwin Wortham, A.M.
            Poindexter, L.W. Allen, Wm. Sands, J. A. Chambliss, R. Reins, Jas.
            Thomas Jr, R.T. Coleman, J.B. Taylor, W. Goddin, T.G. Jones, J.L.
            Burrows, Josiah Ryland, A.R. Courtney and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Rev C.C. Bitting being present was invited to a seat.</p>
          <PageNumber num={334} />
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by the Rev. Mr. Bitting.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>The President explained the reason for the call of the meeting.</p>
          <p>
            Thos. J Evans then offered the accompanying Preamble and resolution
            which were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustee Tho<sup>s</sup> Wallace Death.</aside>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College have heard with deep regret of the
            death of Thomas Wallace, lately a member of this body—and deem it
            proper to add their testimony to his worth as a Christian gentleman and
            public spirited citizen. We therefore adopt the following resolutions.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              Resolved.—That in the death of Thomas Wallace, Richmond College
              has lost a friend, and the Trustees have lost a Colaborer [sic], with
              whom it was always pleasant and profitable to cooperate.
            </li>
            <li>
              —That we tender to the family of the deceased our sincere sympathy
              in their affliction and that the Secretary be requested to forward a
              copy to the family of the deceased.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Rev. A.M. Poindexter presented now his Annual Report for the second year
            of his Agency ending <time dateTime="1868-06-18">June 18, 1868</time>. The Report was received and ordered
            to be filed with the College documents.
          </p>
          <p>
            The General Agent in the above report having stated that some of the
            Bonds and a greater part of the subscriptions have become valueless,
            accompanied with a request that the <PageNumber num={335} />
            Board should decide what steps should be taken in relation to
            Bankrupts. <aside>Bankrupts Committee</aside> It was ordered that the subject be committed to a committee,
            Consisting of the General Agent, the Treasurer, and T.J. Evans to act in
            the matter as they may deem most expedient.
          </p>
          <p>The following Resolutions offered by Dr. Burrows were adopted.</p>
          <aside>Principal of Bonds to be funded</aside>
          <p>
            <u>Resolved 1st</u>. That from and after this date, any amount
            collected upon the principal of bonds for the endowment of Richmond
            College, shall not be appropriated to current expenses or to the payment
            of debts, but shall be funded from time to time, at the discretion of
            the Treasurer.
          </p>
          <aside>Interest on Bonds to <time dateTime="1868-06">June 1868</time></aside>
          <p>
            <u>Resolved 2nd.</u>That the interest due on bonds to the <time dateTime="1868-06-01">
              first day of
              June 1868
            </time> as the same is collected be applied to the liquidation of
            debts due the Faculty of the College, and accruing interest on bonds now
            held to the amount of $4500 per annum be and is hereby set apart for the
            Salaries of the Faculty and shall not be appropriated to any other
            purpose.
          </p>
          <aside>Edowment [sic] how ot be appropriated</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved 3rd.  That Rev A.M. Poindexter D.D. be requested to continue
            his Agency in the College, and that any surplus of interest accruing on
            bonds in hand above the $4500 appropriated to the Faculty of the College
            and all donations, and interest on bonds obtained after this date, be
            and hereby are appropriated to the payment of said Agent’s Salary and
            expenses <PageNumber num={336} />
            and provided that the amount thus accruing be not sufficient to pay <aside>Provision for Agents Salary</aside> his
            salary and expenses, any balance due him shall be secured by a bond of
            the College bearing interest at six per cent per annum, payable
            semi-annually, and provided further that nothing in these resolutions
            shall be so construed as to prevent or delay the payment of necessary
            expenses and Salaries of Treasurer &amp; Secretary.
          </p>
          <aside>Agents Salaray Reduced.</aside>
          <p>
            At the request of the General Agent the Board reduced his Salary from
            $2500 to $1500 per annum commencing with the current year.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Rev. J.B. Taylor then offered the following resolution which was
            unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Complimentary Resolution Genl Agt</aside>
          <p>
            <u>Resolved</u>. That the Trustees hereby express their deep sense of
            the earnest and successful labors of the General Agent Rev. A.M.
            Poindexter thus far in securing the sum of $100,000 as a permanent
            endowment—and especially do they express their thanks for the
            voluntary offer to reduce his Salary by the sum of $1000.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Poindexter offered the following resolution which was unanimously
            adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Dr Curry</aside>
          <p>
            <u>Resolved.</u>That the Board hereby renew the tender of a
            professorship in Richmond College to Rev J.L.M. Curry with the
            understanding that the duties of his Chair shall be fixed by himself and
            the gentlemen of the Faculty. Should he accept the appointment and
            provided, that in the event of acceptance the appropriation from the<PageNumber num={337} />
            from the [sic] interest to accrue on endowment <aside>Professors Salaries</aside> for the support of the
            Faculty be increased to $5250 of which he shall be entitled to $750 and
            a pro-rata share with the other professors, of tuition fees and
            perquisites.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Chair, appointed Edwin Wortham, Thos. J Evans and Dr. Coleman a
            committee to wait on Mr. Curry and urge his acceptance of the
            appointment.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was received from a Committee of the students at the
            College asking the approval of the Board of a plan in which they propose
            to build a Chapel on the College Grounds, the location to be selected by
            a Committee of the Board. thereupon the following resolution was
            adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That the petition of the students be granted and that the
            selection of location be referred to the Committee on the Premises with
            instructions to report to the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Burrows the Trustees were requested to take seats in
            the stand, on the evening of the closing exercises of the College on the
            <time dateTime="07-01">1st day of July</time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The order passed at the last meeting to hold an adjourned meeting on the
            <time dateTime="07-07">7th of July</time> was rescined [sic], the purpose having been accomplished by
            this meeting.
          </p>
          <p>The Board now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J. B. Jeter, Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={338} />

        <section id='meeting-1868-07-01'>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held at the
            Second Baptist Church <time dateTime="1868-07-01">July 1, 1868</time>
          </p>
          <p>
            Present.  J.B. Jeter President, Wm. Sands, Edwin Wortham, A.M.
            Poindexter, J.L. Burrows, Josiah Ryland, A.M. Bailey, L.R. Spilman, Jas.
            B. Taylor, T.G. Jones, C.H. Winston, J.A Chambliss &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Rev A.M. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The President stated the object of the meeting.</p>
          <aside>Conway Robinson LLD.<br /> A. B. Brown D.D.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of Wm. Sands the Board by a unanimous vote conferred the
            honorary degree of L.L.D. on Conway Robinson Esqr. of Washington D.C.
            The Board also conferred the honorary title of D.D. on Rev. A.B. Brown
            Pittsylvania Va. and Rev Daniel Witt of Prince Edward Va.
          </p>
          <aside>Trustee HK Ellyson</aside>
          <p>
            C.H. Winston nominated H.K Ellyson as a Trustee to supply the vacancy on
            the Board occasioned by the death of Thomas Wallace Esqr. of Petersburg.
            He was duly elected.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting now adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J. B. Jeter, Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>


        <PageNumber num={339} />

        <section id="meeting-1868-08-17">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-08-17">August 17, 1868</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon. Present W. Goddin, T. J. Evans, Josiah Ryland, R. Reins, A.
            Snead, A.M. Bailey, H.K. Ellyson, and J.B. Jeter.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Dr. Wm. H. Gwathmey.</p>
          <aside>DM Francisco</aside>
          <p>
            Wellington Goddin was called to the Chair, who stated the object of the
            meeting was to consider a proposition from W. L. Francisco in behalf of
            the estate of the late Dr. B.M. Francisco one of the subscribers to the
            endowment of the College, who proposed to Compromise the claim by paying
            $850.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Board refused to accept the proposition, but agreed to
            accept $1000 and the Cost of the suit, abating accrued interest.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">W. Goddin, president pro tem<br /><span className='pencil'>Goddin</span></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={340} />

        <section id="meeting-1868-12-10">
          <p>Richmond <time dateTime="1868-12-10">December 10, 1868</time></p>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this day in the
            Lecture Room of the Second Baptist Church, present J.B. Jeter President,
            A.M. Bailey, J.B. Taylor, Edward Wortham, Josiah Ryland, J.A. Chambliss,
            C.H. Winston, James Thomas, H.K. Ellyson, T.J. Evans, T.G. Jones and
            J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting opened was with prayer by Rev JB Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            The meeting was called at the request of the President who stated the
            object of the meeting was to consider and take action in relation to the
            establishment of a Law School in the City of Richmond in connection with
            the College. HK Ellyson then offered the following resolutions, which
            having been discussed were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Law School</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved—That if arrangements can be made we will at the Commencement
            of the next Session of Richmond College or sooner, establish a Law
            School in connection with it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved—That a committee of 5 be appointed, charged with the duty of
            recommending to the Board for appointment, suitable Professors for such
            a School, and making other necessary arrangements for putting the School
            into operation subject to the approval of the Board.
          </p>
          <aside>Law School Committee</aside>
          <p>
            The Chair appointed H.K. Ellyson, T.J. Evans, T.G. Jones, A.R. Holladay
            and Dr. R.T. Coleman, the Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Chairman of the Committee of the Premises presented several small
            bills for necessary repairs, which were ordered to be paid.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={341} />
          <aside>RE Binford</aside>
          <p>
            On motion the Faculty of the College was authorized to issue a duplicate
            Diploma to Ro. E Binford of Franklin Tennessee the original said to be
            lost or destroyed.
          </p>
          <aside>Death of W Sands</aside>
          <p>
            The death of Wm Sands, a member of the Board being announced, a
            Committee was appointed consisting of the President of the Board and the
            President of the College to draw up and report suitable resolutions
            commemorative of the deceased to be spread on the minutes of the Board.
            -- The meeting then adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-01-15">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-01-15">January 15, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of the College held this afternoon,
            present A.M. Poindexter, J.L. Burrows, A Snead, Edwin Wortham, T.G.
            Jones, Josiah Ryland, C.H. Winston, J.A. Chambliss, R.T. Coleman &amp;
            J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting was opened with prayer by Dr. Jones.</p>
          <p>Dr. Burrows was appointed Chairman.</p>
          <p>
            Dr. Poindexter stated that the meeting had been called at his request,
            in order that he might consult with the Board in regard to the
            expediency of continuing his Agency—the subjecting having been
            considered, Dr. Burrows offered the following Resolution, which was
            adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved; That the Rev. Dr. Poindexter be requested to continue his
            Agency for Richmond College, and that <PageNumber num={342} />
            he is hereby authorized and requested to give attention to the
            Collection of the interest accruing on the bonds and also such general
            superintendence of the fiscal affairs of the College as to him may seem
            wise and effective.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature pencil"><u>Burrows</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-04-13">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-04-13">April 13, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon,
            present J.B. Jeter, President, R.T. Coleman, A.G. Wortham, Josiah
            Ryland, Jas. Thomas Jr, L.R. Spilman, H.K. Ellyson, Jas. P. Ballard,
            Edwin Wortham, T.J. Evans, T.G. Jones, A.R. Holladay, J.L. Burrows, A.H.
            Sands, C.H. Winston, A. Snead, W. Goddin, A.R. Courtney &amp; J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jones.</p>
          <p>
            The minutes of all the previous meetings that had not been read, were
            now read and approved.
          </p>
          <p>
            A Communication was presented from the Faculty asking that some action
            should be taken by the Board for the payment of their Salaries falling
            due at the end of the present session, in response thereto the following
            Resolution was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That the Treasurer be authorized to borrow the sum of $2500
            pledging a sufficient amount of State Stock as collateral security to be
            applied towards the payment of Salaries of the present session.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={343} />
          <p>
            The Treasurer presented a report on the Finances of the College for the
            information of the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>On motion of W. Goddin the following resolution was adopted.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved That the Salaries of the Professors be paid half yearly, on
            the <time dateTime="01-01">1st of January</time> and <time dateTime="07-01">1st of July</time>—and if necessary to raise funds
            for that purpose, that the Treasurer be authorized to pledge the stock
            of the College as collateral security.
          </p>
          <aside className='bottomToTop'>Repealed <time dateTime="1869-06-19">June 17 1869</time>.</aside>
          <p>The Committee on the Law School contemplated, reported progress.</p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was authorized to accept an individual bond well
            secured, for an amount exceeding $100 and to credit the bond of L.J.
            Hailey by the same.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of A.R. Courtney the Committee on the Premises was requested
            to report what repairs are needed by the College buildings and
            improvements to the College grounds and the probable cost of the same.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following action of the Faculty was communicated to the meeting.
          </p>
          <aside>Change System proposed</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved 1. That we request the Board of Trustees to appoint a
            Committee to examine into the workings of our somewhat anomalous
            organization and to recommend any changes that may seem to them
            desirable.
          </p>
          <p>
            2. That we respectfully urge speedy action if any be taken, so that it
            may appear in our forthcoming catalogues.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that a Committee consisting of 5 members be
            appointed to consider the subject and report to the next meeting of the
            Board, the <PageNumber num={344} />
            following individuals were appointed the Committee, J.B. Jeter,
            (Chairman) Josiah Ryland, J.B. Taylor, J.L. Burrows, and A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>
            The meeting then adjourned to meet this day week at 4 1/2 Oclock P.M.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-03-20">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-03-20">April 20, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this afternoon
            according to adjournment.  Present
          </p>
          <p>
            J.B. Jeter, Pres't., A.M. Poindexter; A.M. Bailey, A. Snead, H.K.
            Ellyson, R.T. Coleman, A.G. Wortham, James Thomas Jr., Edwin Wortham,
            Josiah Ryland, T.J. Evans, A.R. Courtney, L.R. Spilman, A.H. Sands, J.L.
            Burrows, C.H. Winston, J.B. Taylor, W. Goddin and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Poindexter.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed at the last meeting of the Board to consider the
            communication from the Faculty, made the following report, which was
            discussed and adopted.
          </p>
          <hr />
          <p>
            The Committee to whom was referred the Communication of the Faculty of
            Richmond College in regard to the present organization of the College
          </p>
          <p>Report.</p>
          <ol>
            <li className='1st'>
              “1st.  We recommend that the office of President be abolished at the end
              of the present Session.
            </li>
            <li className='2nd'>
              <PageNumber num={345} /> That President Jones be continued in his present Professorship,
              with the same Salary and emoluments which he now receives; and that in
              consideration thereof; it shall be his duty to endeavor to promote the
              interests of the College by public addresses in different localities, so
              far as may be compatible with his professional duties.
            </li>
            <li className='3rd'>
              3rd  That a committee be appointed to consist of three members of the
              Board and one of the Faculty to draft a plan upon which the foregoing
              recommendations may be fully carried out; the said plan to be subject to
              the approval of the Board.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            This plan has been submitted to the Faculty and approved as judicious by
            all of them, except the President who reserves his decision.
          </p>
          <p>We recommend the adoption of the following resolutions.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved -- That Dr. Jones be earnestly requested to continue his
            connection with College as Professor.”
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of W. Goddin the Secretary was requested to forward a copy of
            the report to the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Chair appointed Dr. R.T. Coleman, C.H. Winston and A.M. Poindexter
            the Committee on the part of the Board in compliance with the
            recommendation of the above report.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned to meet at the Call of the President.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature pencil"><u>Jeter</u></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={346} />
        <section id="meeting-1869-06-15" className='annual'>
          <aside>29<sup>th</sup>. Annual Meeting.</aside>
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-06-15">June 15th 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            The 29th Annual meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held
            this afternoon.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.B. Jeter, Pres. T.G Jones, J.B. Taylor, A.M. Poindexter, W.
            Goddin, T.J. Evans, A.R. Holladay, R.T. Coleman, J.L. Burrows, James
            Thomas Jr., A.M. Bailey, L.R. Spilman, J.A. Chambliss, A.R. Courtney,
            C.H. Winston, A.G. Wortham, E. Wortham, A.H. Sands, J.C. Long &amp; J.M.
            Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Burrows,</p>
          <p>
            On motion the By Laws requiring all the minutes of the last year to be
            read at each Annual Meeting was suspended—and the reading omitted.
          </p>
          <p>The proceedings of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The President of the College read his Annual Report on the condition of
            the College, which was received and referred to a committee consisting
            of Jas. B. Taylor, T.J. Evans, and L.R. Spilman to consider the
            suggestions therein made, and to report to a subsequent meeting of the
            Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            The report of the Treasurer of the Faculty was suspended and then
            referred to the Auditing Committee.
          </p>
          <p>The following resolution offered by Dr. Poindexter was adopted</p>
          <p>
            Resolved That hereafter the Treasurer of the Faculty shall present a
            detailed account of the expenditures of the general fund.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Report of the Treasurer of the College was submitted, accompanied by
            the report <PageNumber num={347} /> of the Auditor. The Report was received and filed.</p>
          <p>
            The Report of the Agent was presented and accepted, and the Treasurer
            was instructed to settle the balance due him on account of Salary by
            giving the bond of the College for the amount.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Board proceeded to ballot for the following Officers of the Board
            for the current year, as required by the By-Laws. C.H. Winston &amp;
            J.A. Chambliss were appointed tellers who reported
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'grid', gridTemplateColumns: 'repeat(3, minmax(10px, 1fr))', columnGap: '1em' }}>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>J.B. Jeter,</div>
            <div>elected</div>
            <div>President.</div>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>Edward Wortham</div>
            <div><span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span></div>
            <div>Treasurer</div>
            <div style={{ justifySelf: 'end' }}>J.M. Murray</div>
            <div><span style={{ padding: '0 20px' }}>"</span></div>
            <div>Secretary</div>
          </div>
          <aside>✓ Auditing Committee</aside>
          <p>W. Goddin and T.J. Evans were re-elected Auditing Committee.</p>
          <p>The Committee on the Law School presented the following report.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee charged with the duty of recommending to the Board for
            appointment suitable Professors for a Law School, beg leave to report
            that we have been unable to find anyone willing to accept the position
            with the uncertain and inadequate Compensation offered.
          </p>
          <div style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>T.J. Evans, Chair'n. pro tem</div>
          <p>
            On motion the committee was continued and Dr. Curry was added to the
            Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Committees on the Donation of Dr. Owen, and on the death of Wm.
            Sands Trustee were continued.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={348} />
          <p>
            On motion T.J. Evans was appointed a Committee to represent whatever
            interest the College may have in the estate of the late Mrs. Muse.
          </p>
          <aside>✓ Dr. Jones resigns</aside>
          <p>
            A communication was received from President Jones, resigning his
            position at the College to take effect at the end of the present
            session. Dr. Poindexter then offered the following resolution which was
            adopted,
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved  That the resignation of President Jones of his professorship
            in the College be accepted.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that a committee of three be appointed to
            prepare suitable resolutions in relation to the resignation of Dr.
            Jones, to be submitted to the Board for adoption. The Chair appointed
            A.H. Sands, J.B. Taylor and C.H. Winston the committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Board then adjourned to meet <time dateTime="1869-06-16 17:00:00">tomorrow afternoon at 5 o’clock P</time> to
            consider the report of the Committee on New Organization.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-06-16">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-06-16">June 16, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            The Trustees of Richmond College met this afternoon according to
            adjournment. Present J.B. Jeter President, J.B. Taylor, A.H. Sands,
            James Thomas, C.H. Winston, A.M. Poindexter, A.G. Wortham, A.M. Bailey,
            J.L. Burrows, J.A. Chambliss, J.C. Long, A.R. Courtney, T.G. Jones &amp;
            J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by A.H. Sands.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read approved.</p>
          <PageNumber num={349} />
          <p>
            A bill of the Religious Herald for advertising for the College from
            <time dateTime="1867-08-16">August 16th</time> to <time dateTime="1867-01-01">January 1st, 1867,</time> amounting to $56 was presented and
            referred to the Auditor for adjustment and settlement.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee on Resolutions in regard to the Resignation of Dr. Jones
            presented their report which was adopted and the Secretary was
            instructed to furnish a copy to Dr. Jones, and also to have them
            published in the Newspapers of the city of Richmond.  (report recorded
            below)
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion a committee was appointed consisting of James Thomas Jr., A.M.
            Poindexter, and J.L. Burrows to nominate four suitable persons to supply
            vacancies in the Board of Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was committed the duty of submitting a plan for
            the reorganization of the Faculty of the College presented their report
            which was considered and amended and adopted. (recorded below)
          </p>
          <p>
            Professor Harris on behalf of the Faculty presented the rules and
            regulations which they had adopted for the internal government of the
            College—they asked the approval of the Trustees which was agreed to.
          </p>
          <p>Dr. Poindexter offered the following resolution.</p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Faculty be requested to make provision for the
            discharge of the duties of the Professorship vacated by the resignation
            Dr. Jones, until a Professor shall have been appointed.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={350} />
          <p>
            On motion the subject was referred to a committee consisting of C.H.
            Winston, J.B. Taylor, and A.M. Poindexter.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned to meet <time dateTime="1869-06-17 16:30:00">tomorrow afternoon 4 1/2 O’clock</time>.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="report-1869-06-16">
          <hr />
          <h3>
            Report of the Committee on resignation of Dr. Jones adopted June 16,
            1869.
          </h3>
          <ol>
            <li className='resolved1'>
              That we deeply regret this resignation of his professorship
              by Rev. Tiberius G. Jones D.D, who has, for three years, presided over
              this College and filled one of its most important Chairs.
            </li>
            <li>
              That high as was our estimate of his capacity as a Professor of the
              Moral Course at the time of his appointment, our expectations have been
              fully realized and we take pleasure in bearing testimony to the great
              zeal and distinguished ability he has brought to the discharge of the
              duties of this office.
            </li>
            <li className='third'>
              3.  That President Jones’s devotion to the interests of this institution
              over which he was called to preside at a dark hour in its history and
              which he now leaves in a prosperous condition -- a devotion signalized
              alike by public speech and private effort -- calls for the expression of
              our sincere approval and that we feel it due to him and to ourselves to
              place on record this public acknowledgement of the fact.
            </li>
            <li>
              That we will follow him in new field of labor upon which he is about
              to enter, with our sincerest wishes <PageNumber num={351} />
              for his eminent prosperity and success.</li>
            <li>
              That a copy of these resolutions be furnished to President Jones and
              that they be published in the newspaper of the City of Richmond.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <section id="bylaws-1869-06-16">
          <hr />
          <h2>New Organization</h2>
          <h3>Adopted <time dateTime="1869-06-16">June 16, 1869</time></h3>
          <h2><span style={{ textDecorationLine: 'underline', textDecorationStyle: 'double' }}>By-Laws</span> (for Trustees)</h2>
          <h3>1 .Officers</h3>
          <p>
            The officers of the Trustees shall be a President; a Secretary and a
            Treasurer. They shall be chosen at each annual meeting of the Board, but
            vacancies may be filled at any other meeting. Each of them will hold
            office until relieved by his successor.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>2. President’s Duties</h3>
          <p>
            The President shall discharge the duties commonly pertaining to a
            presiding officer, being guided by the usual rules of deliberative
            bodies. In case of his absence from any meeting President <span style={{ textDecorationLine: 'underline', textDecorationStyle: 'double' }}>pro</span>.
            <span style={{ textDecorationLine: 'underline', textDecorationStyle: 'double' }}>tem</span>. shall be appointed.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>3. Secretary’s Duties</h3>
          <p>
            The secretary shall keep a faithful record of all proceedings of the
            Board conduct correspondence, duly notify Trustees of the time and place
            for holding each meeting regular or called file and safely keep all
            documents entrusted to his care. The books and papers kept by him shall
            be subject at all times to the inspection of the Trustees but shall be
            surrendered only to an <PageNumber num={352} />
            agent or officer of the Board appointed to receive them.</p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>4. Treasurer’s Duties</h3>
          <p>
            The Treasurer shall give receipts for all monies paid him on account of
            Richmond College, shall safely keep the same, or shall pay them out on
            proper vouchers and in accordance with instructions previously given by
            a vote of the Board. He shall keep accounts of all receipts and
            disbursements, and of all Stock Bonds and other effects of the College
            in his hands or subject to his control, which accounts shall be open at
            all times to the inspection of the Board, and shall be balanced and
            audited at least once a year and reported in full to the annual meeting.
            His bond (required by Art. 4 of Charter) shall be in the penalty of
            <u>five thousand Dollars</u> and shall be deposited with the Secretary.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>5. Meetings</h3>
          <p>
            The annual meetings shall be held in the City of Richmond commencing on
            the <time dateTime="06-28">28th of June</time> or if that be Sunday then on the <time dateTime="06-29">29th</time>. A semi annual
            meeting shall be held on Tuesday after the second Sunday in December,
            other meetings may be called as provided in Art. 5 of Charter. At each
            annual meeting the records of the preceeding year shall be read, reports
            received from Treasurer and Faculty; officers and Auditing Committee
            appointed; and arrangements made for the Annual report to the “Board of
            the Literary Fund.”
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={353} />
          <p>
            All meetings shall be with closed doors except that any member of the
            Faculty or other friend of the College may be present upon special
            invitation of the Board.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>6. Faculty</h3>
          <p>
            The Faculty of instruction and government appointed under Article 2 of
            Charter shall consist of Coequal Professors, one of whom shall be chosen
            annually as their Chairman. To them as a body shall be committed all
            that pertains to the discipline and interior management of the College.
            In the exercise of these functions they shall be guided by the laws and
            resolutions of the Trustees and by established precedents; a majority of
            the whole body shall be required to decide any questions, and such
            decision shall be binding unless reversed by the Board of Trustees.
          </p>
          <p>
            They shall report promptly to the Trustees any matters that seem to
            require their attention, and shall make to the Annual Meeting a full
            report of the condition of the College, so far as committed to their
            hands with such recommendations as they may desire to submit.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>7. Chairman of the Faculty</h3>
          <p>
            The Chairman of the Faculty shall be appointed annually by the Trustees,
            on nomination by the Faculty. He shall preside in all Faculty meetings,
            on Commencement and other public occasions and shall be the Chief
            executive officer of the Faculty. He shall receive all applications for
            admission to the College, keep a record of Matriculates, assign them to
            rooms <PageNumber num={354} /> and transmit monthly to their parents or guardians a report of their
            absences and class standing, keeping also a copy of the same. He shall
            reside on or near the College premises, superintend such of the grounds
            and buildings as are not assigned for residences to other Professors,
            exercise a general supervision over the conduct of students, when not in
            recitation and report to the Faculty all such matters as seem to require
            their attention.
          </p>
          <p>
            He shall keep a copy of all rules and regulations communicated by the
            Trustees or adopted by the Faculty and enforce due observance thereof
            and shall prepare subject to approval by the Faculty the Annual Report.
            At his request the Faculty may assign to another Professor for a
            specified time any of the duties above mentioned and in case of his
            absence for disability they may select a chairman <u>pro</u>
            <u>tem</u>to supply his place.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>8. Professors Duties</h3>
          <p>
            Each Professor shall hereafter be elected at first for one year, but if
            at or before the expiration of that time, he be reelected then his chair
            can be vacated only by his death or resignation or by a vote of the
            Trustees. He shall be responsible directly and only to the Trustees, for
            the efficient conduct of his school and shall submit along with each
            annual report a tabular statement showing the number of lectures
            required of him under the schedule adopted by the Faculty, and the
            number actually delivered, adding such explanations as may seem
            desirable.
          </p>
          <p>He shall engage in no occupation that <PageNumber num={355} />
            conflicts with his professional duties and as an Officer of the
            Institution shall use whatever influence he can exert to enforce its
            disciplinary regulations and to promote its general interest.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>9. Assistants</h3>
          <p>
            The Faculty may appoint assistants and Teachers of Special Classes,
            provided that such appointments shall be subject to approval by the
            Trustees, and shall not in any way increase their pecuniary liabilities.
          </p>
          <hr className='short' />
          <h3>10. Amendments</h3>
          <p>
            These By-Laws may be altered or amended at any Annual Meeting of the
            Board.
          </p>
          <hr />
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-06-17">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-06-17">June 17, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the trustees, held this afternoon pursuant to
            adjournment,
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.B. Jeter, President, A.M. Poindexter, A.H. Sands, C.H.
            Winston, A.M. Bailey, E. Wortham, A.G. Wortham, L.R. Spilman, J.B.
            Taylor, J.M. Murray, J.A. Chambliss, T.G. Jones, and James Thomas Jr.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Taylor</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The committee to consider certain recommendations and suggestions
            contained in the President’s Annual Report submitted the following
            report which was adopted.
          </p>
          <h4>Report.</h4>
          <ol>
            <li className='first'>
              In reference for the arrangements for messing the students, your
              committee recommend, that the whole system, both with <PageNumber num={356} />
              respect to the beneficiaries of the Education Society, and the other
              students, be subjected to the Scrutiny of the Faculty and that they be
              empowered to adopt such measures as will best promote the comfort of all
              concerned.
            </li>
            <li className='second'>
              In regard to the improvements and repairs needed at the College, it
              is recommended that the Treasurer be authorized to pay out of the
              permanent fund, a sum not exceeding One thousand Dollars for repairs and
              improvements under the direction of the Committee on the premises it
              being understood that the sum thus expended, be returned to the
              endowment fund, out of monies hereafter to be collected for this
              purpose, or out of the incidental fund.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: "center", justifyContent: 'flex-end' }}>
            <div>
              Jas. B. Taylor<br />L.R. Spilman
            </div>
            <div style={{ fontSize: '2em', lineHeight: 2 }}>{'}'}</div>
            <div>Committee</div>
          </div>
          <p>
            The Board now proceeded to appoint the committee on the premises. The
            names of James Thomas, A.R. Courtney and Jas. B. Taylor were proposed to
            constitute the Committee, and they were unanimously elected, with the
            request that Prof. Puryear should act with the Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Poindexter the following committee was appointed to
            confer with the Faculty in regard to the subject of Messing of the
            Students. Viz. A.M. Bailey, C.H. Winston &amp; J.L. Burrows.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prof Harris was invited to a seat and to participate in the meeting.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={357} />
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Poindexter the resolution adopted by the Board on the
            <time dateTime="1869-04-13">13th April 1869</time> requiring the Salaries of the Professors to be paid half
            yearly in advance, and also authorizing the Treasurer to borrow money
            for this purpose if necessary, by pledging Stock of the College, was
            rescinded.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee on the vacancy in the Chair of Moral Science occasioned by
            the resignation of Dr. Jones, now made their report which being amended
            was adopted as follows,
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was referred the subject of the vacancy in the
            Chair of Moral Science in the College, occasioned by the resignation of
            Prof T.G. Jones respectfully submit the following resolution for the
            adoption of the Board.
          </p>
          <li>
            Resolved  That in view of the present straitened condition of our
            finances it is inexpedient now to elect a Professor.
          </li>
          <li>
            Resolved—That the Faculty are hereby requested to arrange among
            themselves for the instruction of the Classes in Moral Science until a
            Professor shall be elected.
          </li>
          <p>
            On motion of James Thomas it was resolved that a Committee consisting of
            the Agent of the College and C.H. Winston in connection with the Faculty
            of the College be appointed to arrange for the holding of a mass meeting
            sometime in <time dateTime="1869-09">September</time> next in behalf of education and to promote the
            interest of Richmond College.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={358} />
          <aside><u>Chairman</u> <time dateTime="1869-06-17"><u>June 17.</u> '69</time></aside>
          <p>
            A communication was received from the Faculty, nominating Prof. Puryear
            as Chairman of the Faculty for the Session of 1869-79. The Board
            approved the appointment.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Agent &amp; L.R. Spilman were appointed a committee to
            inquire what compensation shall be given the Chairman of the Faculty for
            services and what disposition shall be made of the buildings on the
            College premises.
          </p>
          <aside>EK Murray Elected Tutor</aside>
          <p>
            Prof Harris in behalf of the Faculty stated that they had selected E.K.
            Murray, a student at the College who was expected to graduate, as Tutor
            for the next Session, they asked the approval of the Board, which was
            unanimously granted.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned to meet at the Call of the President.</p>
          <p>J.M. Murray J.B. Jeter</p>
          <p>Secretary. Prest. of Trustees</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-06-30">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-06-30">June 30, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.B. Jeter, Pres't. A.M. Poindexter, T.G. Jones, Edwin Wortham,
            A.G. Wortham, A.M. Bailey, W. Goddin, J.L. Burrows, Josiah Ryland, H.K.
            Ellyson &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Jeter</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee on the compensation of the Chairman of the Faculty, and
            the disposition of the buildings on the College premises made the
            following report which was adopted.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={359} />
          <h3>Report</h3>
          <p>
            The committee to whom was referred the consideration of the disposition
            of the Presidents house and the Salary of the Chairman of the Faculty
            respectfully report:
          </p>
          <p>
            It having been suggested that it might conduce to the advantage of the
            College to appropriate the President’s house for Lecture rooms, and the
            use of Students, until the College can enlarge its buildings, and in
            view of the facts, that the Chairman should be compensated for the
            discharge of the duties of his office; and the limited revenue of the
            Board, we recommend the adoption of the following resolutions viz.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved 1st -- That the President’s house be temporarily subjected to
            the control of the Faculty from the <time dateTime="1869-10-01">1st of October 1869</time> on the same
            terms and conditions as specified in regard to the other houses placed
            at their disposal, to be used as they may deem for the interests of the
            College.
          </p>
          <aside>Salary of Chairman Faculty</aside>
          <p>
            2nd—That the Faculty be required to adjust and pay the Salary of the
            Chairman in such manner as they judge best, provided that in no event
            shall the Board be held responsible for any part thereof; and provided
            further that neither the President’s house nor any other of the College
            buildings subject to the control of the Faculty shall be rented by them
            to any person not connected with the College.
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: "center", justifyContent: 'flex-end' }}>
            <div>
              A.M. Poindexter<br />L.R. Spilman
            </div>
            <div style={{ fontSize: '2em', lineHeight: 2 }}>{'}'}</div>
            <div>Committee</div>
          </div>
          <p>The following resolution offered by Dr. Burrows was adopted -</p>
          <PageNumber num={360} />
          <p>
            Resolved—That the Treasurer be authorized to make such arrangements
            as he may deem best, by renewing the Note due in <time dateTime="1869-08">August</time>, or in any other
            way for paying the arrearages due the Professors <time dateTime="1869-07-01">July 1, 1869</time>.
          </p>
          <aside>EK. Murray Graduates M.A.</aside>
          <p>
            On recommendation of the Faculty, the Trustees authorized the Degree of
            &quot;Master of Arts,&quot; to be conferred on Edward K. Murray, a
            student of the college the last three sessions, he having complied with
            all the requirements, which are imposed, to entitle him to this
            distinction.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion H.K. Ellyson was added to the committee on the Mass Meeting.
            after this meeting adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-07-01">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-07-01">July 1, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees held this evening at Grace Street Baptist
            Church,
          </p>
          <p>
            Present J.B. Jeter, Pres't., Jas. Thomas Jr., W. Goddin, T.G. Jones,
            Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, A.M. Poindexter, J.L. Burrows, Josiah
            Ryland, J.A. Chambliss, J.B. Taylor, T.J. Evans &amp; J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <aside>H.H Levy Graduates A.B.</aside>
          <p>
            The Faculty recommended the Degree of Bachelor of Arts to be conferred
            on Henry H. Levy, of Richmond, a student of the college the present
            session who had passed all the examinations necessary to entitle him to
            this honor, the Board authorized the degree to be conferred, then
            adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter Pres't. of Trustees</div>
