        <PageNumber num={361} />
        <section id="meeting-1869-09-07">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-09-07">September 7th 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon at the Second Baptist Church, Present
          </p>
          <p>
            J.B. Jeter, President, Jas. Thomas Jr., W. Goddin, L.R. Spilman, J.B.
            Taylor, W.A. Baynham, H.K. Ellyson, J.M. Murray, T.J. Evans, Josiah
            Ryland and R.T. Coleman
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Dr. Baynham.</p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The Committee on the premises presented a report in regard to the recent
            repairs done to the grounds and buildings, which were authorized by the
            Board at Meeting held in June last, which was received and referred to
            the Auditing Committee.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that a Committee consisting of three members of
            the Board be appointed, to raise by subscription the sum of $500 for
            further repairs and improvements, the Chair appointed the following
            Members the Committee. T.J. Evans, A.R. Courtney &amp; A. Snead.
          </p>
          <p>
            It having been brought to the notice of the Trustees that there was in
            the hands of the Sheriff of Richmond an Execution in favor of John
            Boisseau, on account of M. Hyde once a Hotel Keeper at the College, on
            motion L.R. Spilman was appointed to represent the interests of the
            College in this cause.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of James Thomas Jr. the following gentlemen were unanimously
            appointed additional Trustees of the College to supply the vacancies in
            the <PageNumber num={362} /> Board. Viz.  Barnas Sears. LLD, Staunton</p>
          <aside>Trustees appointed</aside>
          <div style={{ display: 'grid', gridTemplateColumns: '1fr 1fr 1fr' }}>
            <div>Judge</div>
            <div>Jno. A. Meredith,</div>
            <div>Richmond</div>
            <div>"</div>
            <div>Joseph Christian</div>
            <div>"</div>
            <div></div>
            <div>Jas. Alfred Jones Esq.</div>
            <div>"</div>
          </div>
          <p>The Board then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-09-24">
          <time dateTime="1869-09-24">
            <div>Richmond September 24, 1869</div>
          </time>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees Richmond College held this afternoon
            at the Second Baptist Church, present. James Thomas Jr., J.L. Burrows,
            Jas. B. Taylor, H.K. Ellyson, Josiah Ryland, James Alfred Jones, J.M.
            Murray. J.A. Chambliss and A.R. Courtney.
          </p>
          <p>
            The meeting was opened with prayer by Dr. Burrows. Jas. Thomas Jr. was
            called to the Chair. The minutes of the past meeting were read and
            approved.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following preamble and resolutions were offered by Dr. Burrows and
            unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>West. V<sup>a</sup></aside>
          <p>
            Whereas the Baptists of Va. both Eastern and Western have for
            generations been one people and in all ecclesiastical and educational
            sympathies and interests and one people still, and whereas no
            Institution of Collegiate grade has yet been established in West
            Virginia therefore
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved: That the Trustees of Richmond College cordially invite the
            Baptists of West Virginia to make such use of the facilities furnished
            by the College for importing a thorough education, as they may deem
            desirable for their sons, and especially for their young men approved by
            their Churches as candidates for the Gospel Ministry. The Trustees
            pledge themselves to receive students from <PageNumber num={363} />
            West Va. whether preparing for the Ministry or other liberal
            professions, upon precisely the same conditions, with the same
            privileges and to furnish them the same aids and facilities as their own
            sons.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved, that Rev. A.E. Dickinson be requested to convey and make known
            this action of the Trustees of Richmond College to the Baptist General
            Association of West Virginia.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray<br />Secretary</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">Thomas.</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p>
            Judge Jno. A. Meredith, Joseph Christian, Jas. Alfred Jones, and Barnas
            Sears, having formally accepted the appointments are now Trustees of
            Richmond College.
          </p>
          <footer style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>J.M. Murray<br />Secretary</footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-10-12">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1869-10-12">Oct. 12 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this
            afternoon at the Second Baptist Church. Present J.B. Jeter, President.
            A.M. Poindexter, Edwin Wortham, A.G. Wortham, Thos .J. Evans, C.H.
            Winston, Jas. B. Taylor, Jas. Thomas Jr., Josiah Ryland, R. Reins, L.R.
            Spilman, J.A. Chambliss and A.M. Bailey
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.A. Chambliss</p>
          <p>A.M. Bailey was appointed Secretary pro. tem.</p>
          <p>
            The President laid before the meeting a communication from the Sheriff
            of the City of Richmond, with a copy of an Execution in favor of John
            Boisseau against the College amounting to $870.64 and stated that the
            object of the meeting to be to devise <PageNumber num={364} />
            means to enlarge accommodations for students at Richmond College.
            Prof Puryear was invited to take a seat with the Board and to take part
            in its proceedings. Information being asked for Prof. Puryear submitted
            a statement of the number of students and the number of rooms at the
            College and explained the present arrangements for this accommodation.
            He showed the want of more room.
          </p>
          <aside>Stocks to Sold</aside>
          <p>
            Whereupon Jas. Thomas Jr. stated that the Treasurer held bonds of Va.
            and Tenn. R.R. and the Corporation of Portsmouth, which had paid no
            interest for several years and which he learned might possibly be
            disposed of at reasonable rates.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr. it was Resolved That the Treasurer be
            instructed to sell the Va. and Tenn bonds amounting to $3,500 and the
            Portsmouth Corporation stock of $500.
          </p>
          <aside>Cottages to be built</aside>
          <p>On motion of the same—it was</p>
          <p>
            Resolved—that the Treasurer be instructed after the payment of the
            execution out of the proceeds of the sale of the bonds to pay over the
            balance to the Committee on the premises to be expended by them in the
            erection of Cottages.
          </p>
          <p>On motion of T.J. Evans, it was</p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Committee on the Premises be instructed to proceed at
            once in the erection of at least two Brick four room Cottages, on the
            lawn at such places as they may select.
          </p>
          <p>
            The General Agent stated that he was doubtful about his retaining the
            General Agency as the College could not be much benefitted in money and
            wished candidly to know the opinion of the Board.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={365} />
          <p>
            After an interchange of views and full deliberation, on Motion T.J.
            Evans the following resolution was adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that in the opinion of the Trustees, although we may not look
            to any immediate considerable receipt of money from the efforts of the
            agency, it is expedient that Dr. Poindexter be continued as the Agent,
            and that he be instructed to direct his attention and efforts to the
            raising of a fund for building purposes, in such manners as he may deem
            wise and prudent for the present and the future interest of the College.
          </p>
          <p>On motion the Board adjourned.</p>
          <aside>Signed</aside>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">A.M. Bailey<br />Sec. pro. tem.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter <span className='pencil'>Jeter</span></div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1869-12-14" className='annual'>
          <div><time dateTime="1869-12-14">December 14, 1869</time></div>
          <p>
            The 29th Annual Meeting was held this afternoon, present
            <br />
            Rev. J.B. Jeter, President. Edwin Wortham, James Thomas Jr., Charles H.
            Winston, J.L. Burrows, Jas. A Meredith, J.A. Chambliss, W. Goddin, L.R.
            Spilman and J.M. Murray
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.A. Chambliss</p>
          <p>
            Prof. Puryear being present was invited to a seat and to participate in
            the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            James Thomas Jr. stated that the bonds which the last meeting authorized
            to be sold had been disposed of at a price which he considered as very
            satisfactory, about $2600.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prof. Puryear made a statement in regard to the improvements which had
            been made under the management of the committee of the premises and
            final report on the expenditure for the same, which was referred to the
            auditory committee.
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={366} />
          <p>
            The Professor also made an interesting and encouraging statement of the
            Condition and prospects of the College for the present session, and
            after a free conversation between the members in regard to the College,
            and there being no business requiring action of the Board, the meeting
            adjourned.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray<br />Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1870-03-10">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1870-03-10">March 10, 1870</time></div>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this day at the
            Second Baptist Church. Present. J.B. Jeter, President. A.M. Poindexter,
            A.M. Bailey, Edwin Wortham, J.L. Burrows, A.G. Wortham, A. Snead, L.R.
            Spilman, W. Goddin, Josiah Ryland, J.A. Chambliss, C.H. Winston, J.M.
            Murray. Dr. Curry and Rev. C.C. Bitting were invited to seats. Prayer by Rev.
            C.C. Bitting.
          </p>
          <aside>Brookly Meeting</aside>
          <p>The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved.</p>
          <p>
            The President stated that object of calling the meeting was to consider
            the propriety of appointing representatives from this Board to attend an
            educational meeting to be held in the City of Brooklyn, New York in
            April next.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion, Dr. Curry of the Faculty and Dr. Jeter of the Board were
            unanimously chosen to represent Richmond College.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Dr. Goddin, the Treasurer was authorized and instructed to
            pay their travelling expenses incurred by them in attending the meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was instructed to pay over to the Education
            Board $200—<PageNumber num={367} />
            which had been erroneously paid to the Treasurer of the College on
            account of W.B. Langridge a beneficiary student some years since.
          </p>
          <p>
            Upon a Statement made by the Agent, the Board authorized the Treasurer
            to receive $24, amount of interest due on the bond of Mr. Gilbert of [sic]
            and on the payment of the said interest to relinquish the bond.</p>
          <aside>Col Fleet</aside>
          <p>
            It having been mentioned to the Board that it is probable that a claim
            will be made by Col. Alex Fleet, for the privileges of a
            Scholarship in the College, it was ordered that the Agent and Secretary
            make an investigation of the subject to see if he is entitled to these
            privileges.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of L.R. Spilman it was
            <br />
            Resolved - That the Treasurer and Agent be authorized to settle any
            bonds taken from [indecipherable] due the College upon such terms as in
            their judgment seem best to the interest of the College and report their
            proceedings to the Board of Trustees.
          </p>
          <aside>Diplomas</aside>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that an appropriation of $120 be made for the
            purpose of procuring plates for the printing of Diplomas should there be
            funds in the Treasury not otherwise appropriated.
          </p>
          <p>On motion of C.H. Winston it was</p>
          <p>
            Resolved - That the Faculty are hereby authorized so to modify the
            elective system provided in the College as to retain a direct control in
            the choice of studies by students who enter college hereon to attaining
            some definite age to be fixed by the Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>The Secretary was requested to tender the thanks of the Board to [sic] <PageNumber num={368} />
            to those Publishers of Books who have made donations to the College
            library through the Agency of Rev. J.B. Taylor Jr.
          </p>
          <aside>W<sup>m</sup>. Sands</aside>
          <p>
            The committees to whom was assigned the duty of preparing suitable
            Memorials of William Sands and E.J. Owen presented the following reports
            which were unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            “William Sands was from the Organization of Richmond College to the time
            of his death a member of its Board of Trustees. He cherished a lively
            interest in its welfare, punctually attended the meetings of its Board,
            and faithfully discharge all his duties as trustee. The College and the
            cause of education in general are indebted to him for his long continued
            and earnest advocacy of their interest. His position as editor of the
            Religious Herald, which he occupied for more than thirty years, gave
            advantages for promoting those interests of which he zealously and
            disinterestedly availed himself. He was by birth and education an
            Englishman but coming in early life to Virginia, he identified himself
            with her people, especially with the Baptists of the State and became a
            useful and respected citizen. His death which occurred very suddenly,
            left a vacuum in his family, in the Church of which he was a Member, and
            in the Board of Trustees of Richmond College not easy to be filled. He
            was an intelligent, modest, pious, energetic man, and the Trustees of
            the College deem it due to his memory to place upon record this
            testament of their appreciation of his character and services.”
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={369} />
          <aside>Dr. Owen</aside>
          <p>
            "Edward Jarworth Owen was a native of Wales. He came to this country in
            his youth and completed his education at the theological seminary in
            Campton, Kentucky. About the year 1850 he settled in his first pastorate
            with a new Church in St. Louis. After remaining there some years, he was
            transferred to the Presidency of William Jewell College, in Clay Count,
            Missouri. Of his labors in this position we have no information. About
            the close of the war, his health failed. After lingering sometime with
            pulmonary disease, he died.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Owen was a man of astute mind, varied learning, considerable
            research and great energy. He died comparatively young. Had he lived to
            old age, he would have distinguished himself by his attainments and
            labors. As it was, he had secured the title L.L.D. a distinction he
            doubtless merited. He laid Richmond College under lasting obligations by
            bequeathing to it his library containing 2597 volumes and estimated to
            be worth $5,000.
          </p>
          <p>
            The gift was the more valuable as it was received soon after the close
            of the war, during which the College library had been greatly scattered
            and reduced. The bequest should be the more highly estimated because it
            was made by a stranger, who sympathized with us in our poverty and
            embarrassments. Your committee  suggest that it would be a proper and
            becoming memorial of the magnificent and timely gift of Dr. Owen to
            separate the library and call it by his
            <br /><span style={{ display: 'block', textAlign: 'right', textDecoration: 'underline' }}>over</span>
            <PageNumber num={370} /> name. Such a measure would not only be a just honor to his memory but
            might an incentive to others to imitate his noble example.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Secretary was requested to provide copy of the report for
            publication in the Religious Herald.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray, Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1870-05-17">
          <p>Richmond <time dateTime="1870-05-17">May 17th 1870</time></p>
          <p>
            At a called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held this day at
            the Second Baptist Church. Present -
          </p>
          <div className="presentListTwoCols">
            <ul>
              <li>James B. Taylor,</li>
              <li>Cha. H. Winston,</li>
              <li>James Thomas Jr.</li>
              <li>L.R. Spilman,</li>
              <li>Wellington Coddin,</li>
              <li>Edwin Wortham,</li>
              <li>J.L. Burrows,</li>
              <li>A.G. Wortham,</li>
              <li>Josiah Ryland,</li>
              <li>R.I. Coleman,</li>
              <li>Joseph Christian,</li>
              <li>T.J. Evans</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>
            On motion James B. Taylor was called to the Chair, and T.J. Evans was
            appointed Secretary pro tem. Prayer by Dr. Burrows -
          </p>
          <p>
            The minutes of the last meeting were read and approved. Professors
            Puryear and Harris, being present, were invited to take seats and
            participate in the deliberations of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            J.L. Burrows offered the following preamble and resolution which were
            adopted -
          </p>
          <aside>AE Dickinson</aside>
          <p>
            Whereas the Students of Richmond College have proposed to erect two
            stalls for the Literary Societies at the College, and that the Rev. A.E.
            Dickinson, who has volunteered to act as agent to raise the funds for
            that purpose, shall act as such agents. Therefore,
          </p>
          <PageNumber num={371} />
          <p>
            Resolved, that the Trustees approve the plan proposed and concur in the
            appointment of A.E. Dickinson to that agency.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication from Professor Curry in regard to the establishment of a
            Law school in connexion with the College was presented and read.
          </p>
          <aside>Committee on Law School</aside>
          <p>
            On motion a Committee consisting of Professor Curry, James Alfred Jones,
            John A. Meredith and Joseph Christian, was appointed for the purpose of
            putting into operation by the <time dateTime="1870-10-01">1st of October</time> next if possible a law
            school in connexion with the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was received from the Faculty of the College,
            recommending the appointment of a professor of moral philosophy in
            regard to which James Thomas Jr. offered the following resolution which
            was adopted.
          </p>
          <aside>Chair of Moral Science</aside>
          <p>
            Resolved, that the recommendation of the Faculty of the appointment of a
            Professor of Moral Philosophy, be referred to a committee of five, with
            instructions to report thereon at an adjourned meeting of the Trustees
            to be held at the Second Baptist Church on the <time dateTime="1870-05-24 16:30:00">
              24th of May 1870 at 4 ½
              o’clock P.M.
            </time> and if the Committee approves of the appointment of the new
            professor, to recommend the names of two or more persons from whom one
            shall be elected to fill the place, if the Trustees shall concur with
            the Committee in approving the recommendation of the Faculty—and that
            the Secretary of the Board inform Rev. A.M. Poindexter the General Agent
            of the Board of said adjourned meeting—
          </p>
          <div style={{ display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'flex-end' }}>
            <div>Committee</div>
            <ul style={{ marginTop: 0 }}>
              <li>James Thomas Jr.</li>
              <li>R.I. Coleman,</li>
              <li>Chal H. Winston,</li>
              <li>Josiah Ryland,</li>
              <li>Thd. J. Evans,</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}><u>over</u>.</div>
          <br />
          <PageNumber num={372} />
          <p>
            A communication from Thomas Rambant, President of William Jewell College
            addressed to Professor Puryear chairman of the Faculty, asking that the
            Trustees would confer the degree of A.M. on Professors A.F. Fleet and
            R.B. Semple of Wm. Jewell College, was laid before the College Trustees,
            and Professor Puryear was instructed to reply to the said communication
            giving the reasons why the Trustees respectfully declined to confer the
            degree.
          </p>
          <p>
            And then the Board adjourned to the <time dateTime="1870-05-24 16:30:00">24th May 1870 at 4 ½ o’clock P.M.</time> at
            the Second Baptist Church.
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature pencil">Evans</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">Taylor</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1870-05-24">
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held <time dateTime="1870-05-24">24th May 1870</time>.
            Present
          </p>
          <p>
            J.L. Burrows, Pres. pro. tem. A.M. Poindexter, W. Goddin, J.A. Meredith,
            J. Thomas Jr., Jas. Thomas Jr., L.R. Spilman, A. Snead, Edwin Wortham,
            J.A. Chambliss, R.J. Coleman, A.M. Bailey, T.J. Evans, C.H. Winston,
            Josiah Ryland.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. A.M. Poindexter</p>
          <p>
            The Committee appointed at the last meeting of the Board to report on
            the expediency of appointing a Professor to the Chair of Moral Science
            reported in favor of such an appointment, as soon as a suitable man can
            be found. After some discussion the report of the Committee was adopted,
            and the same Committee was continued with instructions to nominate a
            suitable person to fill such Chair.
          </p>
          <p>At the request of C.H. Winston, he was excused from serving on <PageNumber num={373} />
            the Committee and on motion Judge J.A. Meredith was appointed in his
            place.      adjourned
          </p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature pencil">Goddin<br />Sec pro tem</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">JB Burrows<br />Pres pro tem</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1870-05-30">
          <div>Richmond <time dateTime="1870-05-30">May 30, 1870</time></div>
          <p>
            A called meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College was held <time dateTime="1870-05-30 16:30:00">
              this
              afternoon at 4 ½ o’clock
            </time>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Present. J.B. Jeter, President. A.M. Poindexter, J.L. Burrows,
            J.B. Taylor, J.A. Chambliss, T.J. Evans, L.R. Spilman, E. Wortham, A.G.
            Wortham, A.M. Bailey, A.R. Courtney, Josiah Ryland, Jas. Thomas Jr., and
            C.H. Winston.
          </p>
          <p>Prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor</p>
          <p>
            In the absence of the Secretary, C.H. Winston was appointed Secretary
            pro. tem.
          </p>
          <p>The minutes of the last two meetings were read and approved.</p>
          <aside>Judge D.B. DeLands Donation</aside>
          <p>
            The President read a private letter from Judge D.B. DeLand of Fairfield,
            N.Y. offering to create a cottage at Richmond College for the
            accommodation of students at a cost of $2,500. Whereupon it was
            unanimously resolved
          </p>
          <ol style={{ listStylePosition: 'outside' }}>
            <li>
              That the generous proposal be accepted, and that the Committee on the
              premises be authorized to proceed at once to contract for the erection
              of the building, in such form and on such part of the College ground as
              they may deem proper.
            </li>
            <div style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>over</div>
            <li>
              <PageNumber num={374} />That the Cottage be called “DeLand Cottage,” and that its name be
              inscribed on a block of Marble, to be placed in a conspicuous position
              on the wall of the building.
            </li>
            <li>
              That the thanks of the Trustees are due, and are hereby tendered to
              Judge DeLand for his timely gift, in addition to a liberal contribution
              heretofore received at his hands.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            That a copy of these resolutions signed by the President and Secretary
            be forwarded to Judge DeLand and that they be published in the Religious
            Herald.
          </p>
          <p>Prof. Curry was invited to sit with the Board.</p>
          <p>
            The Report of the Committee to examine the Claim of Col. A. Fleet to the
            benefits of a Scholarship in the College was read together with letters
            from A. Fleet and R. Ryland. On motion of T.J. Evans the Report was
            recommitted, with instructions to examine the whole subject more fully
            and to submit a recommendation to the Board, and on motion J.B. Taylor
            was added to the Committee.
          </p>
          <aside>JS. Walthall Death.</aside>
          <p>
            On motion of J.L. Burrows the President and J.B. Taylor were appointed a
            committee to prepare a suitable minute in reference to the death of Rev.
            J.S. Walthall, a Trustee of the College—to be presented to the next
            meeting of the Board.
            ß</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature pencil">Winston</div>
            <div className="signature pencil">Jeter</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <PageNumber num={375} />
        <section id="meeting-1870-06-28" className='annual'>
          <aside>Annual Meeting</aside>
          <h3>30<sup>th</sup> Annual Meeting</h3>
          <p><time dateTime="1870-06-28">June 28th, 1870</time>.</p>
          <p>
            Present, J.B. Jeter, President. A.R. Holladay, Edwin Wortham, A.G.
            Wortham, Jos. Ryland, A.M. Bailey, Jas. B. Taylor, L.R. Spilman, J.L.
            Burrows, A.M. Poindexter, Jos. Christian, James Thomas Jr., A.R.
            Courtney, J.A. Meredith, Daniel Witt. J.A. Chambliss, Jo. P. Ballard, A.
            Snead, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p>Opened with prayer by Rev. J.B. Taylor.</p>
          <p>
            Prof. Puryear, Chairman of the Faculty was invited to sit in the
            meeting.
          </p>
          <p>
            The minutes of all the meetings held since the last Annual Meeting were
            read as required by the by-laws.
          </p>
          <aside>Treasurers Reports</aside>
          <p>
            The Annual Report of the Treasurer of the College, accompanied by the
            Report of the Auditing Committee, was presented, which was accepted and
            ordered to be filed.
          </p>
          <aside>Report Faculty</aside>
          <p>
            The Annual Report of the Faculty was now presented by the Chairman,
            which was also ordered to be filed. The report was very satisfactory to
            the Trustees in regard to the management and success of the session now
            ending—it was ordered that so much of the report as related to the
            long building on the college grounds, be referred to the Committee on
            the Premises, and the Chairman of the Faculty be requested to prepare an
            abstract of his report to be published.
          </p>
          <aside>Graduates</aside>
          <p>
            On the recommendation of the Faculty, the Board authorized the degree of
            Bachelor of Arts to be conferred on C.J. James, of Loudon Co., Va. and
            the degree of Master of Arts on
          </p>
          <ul style={{ textAlign: 'right' }}>
            <li>Lewis J. Gwathmey. Hanover, Va.</li>
            <li>E. Carrington Cabell. Richmond, Va.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            The General Agent presented his Annual Report, also his resignation as
            Agent of the College, the report was received <PageNumber num={376} />
            and the resignation accepted. The Treasurer was instructed to settle his
            Salary by Bond or otherwise.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dr. Burrows offered the following preamble and resolution, which were
            unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whereas the Agent of the College, Rev. A.M. Poindexter has tendered his
            resignation in view of the present difficulties of collecting funds, on
            account of the depressed financial condition of the country, therefore
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved—That in accepting his resignation the Board express to Rev.
            Dr. Poindexter their high appreciation of the value of his services in
            adding to the endowment of the College, and in promoting its general
            interests, and that the thanks of the Board of Trustees be hereby voted
            to Dr. Poindexter.
          </p>
          <p>The following officers were then elected for the current year.</p>
          <div style={{ display: 'grid', gridTemplateColumns: '1fr 1fr 1fr' }}>
            <div>Rev.</div>
            <div>J.B. Jeter. </div>
            <div>President.</div>
            <div></div>
            <div>Edwin Wortham.</div>
            <div>Treasurer</div>
            <div></div>
            <div>J.M. Murray. </div>
            <div>Secretary.</div>
          </div>
          <h5>Auditory Committee</h5>
          <div style={{ textAlign: 'center' }}>W. Goddin, and T.J. Evans.</div>
          <aside>Committee on Premises</aside>
          <h5>Committee on the Premises</h5>
          <p>
            Jas. Thomas Jr., A.R. Courtney, Jas. B. Taylor and Prof. Puryear of the
            Faculty.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Treasurer was instructed to pay a bill presented by H.M. Smith for
            repairs to a well in October 1868, amounting to $14.
          </p>
          <p>
            A request of W.L. Montague asking permission to pay off his bond by
            painting, was referred to the Committee on the Premises.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion of Jas. Thomas Jr. the Board referred the questions of
            deciding on the expediency of converting the individual Bonds belonging
            to the College into certain other securities to a committee. The
            President app-<PageNumber num={377} />-pointed Ja. Thomas Jr. A.R. Holladay, Jos. Ryland and the Treasurer of
            the Committee.
          </p>
          <aside>Committee on Prof Moral Science Continued</aside>
          <p>
            The committee to nominate a suitable person for the Vacant Chair of
            Moral Science, reported progress, and asked for more time, the request
            was granted.
          </p>
          <p>
            A communication was received from Dr. Curry in request to conferring
            honorary degrees of D.D. on certain persons, laid upon the table.
          </p>
          <aside>Chairman of the Faculty</aside>
          <p>
            At the request of the Faculty, Prof. Puryear was unanimously reappointed
            Chairman of the Faculty for the year 1870-81.
          </p>
          <aside>W<sup>m</sup>E Hatcher Elected Trustee</aside>
          <p>
            Rev. W<sup>m</sup>.E. Hatcher of Petersburg Va. was unanimously elected a Trustee of
            the College to fill the vacancy occasioned by the death of Rev J.S.
            Walthall.
          </p>
          <p>The Board then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter<br />President</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

        <section id="meeting-1870-07-01">
          <time dateTime="1870-07-01">
            <div>Richmond July 1, 1870</div>
          </time>
          <p>
            At a meeting of the Trustees of Richmond College held today. Present
          </p>
          <p>
            J.B. Jeter, President. Jas. Thomas Jr. J.B. Taylor, J.A. Chambliss, A.M.
            Bailey, J.A. Meredith, J.L. Burrows, W. Goddin, Jas. Alfred Jones, Jos.
            Christian, C.H Winston, Edwin Wortham, and J.M. Murray.
          </p>
          <p style={{ textAlign: 'center' }}>Prayer by Dr. Burrows.</p>
          <p>
            Jas Thomas Jr. then offered the following resolution which was
            unanimously adopted.
          </p>
          <p>
            Resolved that the Board do hereby withdraw their acceptance of the
            resignation of Rev. A.M. Poindexter, and earnestly request him to
            withdraw his resignation of the office of Genl. Agent of Richmond
            College and beg him to continue his efforts and devote as much of his
            time as he finds will be to the <PageNumber num={378} />
            interests of the College—charging for the time so devoted at the
            present rate of Salary.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion Jas. Thomas Jr. was requested to inform Dr. Poindexter of this
            action and earnestly urge his acceptance of the request of the Board.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer, the General Agent, W. Goddin and Jas. Thomas
            Jr. were appointed a committee with authority to convert the Bonds of
            the College into such other securities as they may deem desirable and
            expedient for the interests of the College.
          </p>
          <p>
            The committee appointed on the same subject at the last meeting was
            discharged.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion the Treasurer was instructed to make any arrangements he may
            deem desirable to pay the Salaries of the Faculty now due.
          </p>
          <p>
            On motion it was ordered that the claim of Col. A. Fleet of
            King & Queen for the privileges of a Scholarship, which would allow
            him to educate one son at the College free of charge for tuition, be
            allowed.
          </p>
          <p>The meeting then adjourned.</p>
          <footer>
            <div className="signature">J.M. Murray,<br /> Secretary.</div>
            <div className="signature">J.B. Jeter<br />President</div>
          </footer>
        </section>

